window.SB_CONCEPTS={"version":6,"count":121,"chapters":[{"title":"The Champion's Routine — say, spell, say","category":"Spelling Bee Basics","difficulty":"easy","concept":"Every champion spells the same way: SAY the word, SPELL it letter by letter, then SAY it again. Saying it first proves your ears heard right; saying it after proves your letters match the sound.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>REMEMBER</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> rih-MEM-ber\n<b>Spell it.</b> R · E · M · E · M · B · E · R\n<b>Say it again.</b> rih-MEM-ber\n<b>Syllables.</b> re · mem · ber\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [rih=RE] [MEM=MEM] [ber=BER]\n<b>Exception.</b> none — every sound is spelled just as you hear it\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin re- = again + memor = mindful","cards":[{"title":"The Core","body":"Champions never blurt letters. The routine is always the same three beats: SAY the word out loud, SPELL it at a steady pace, SAY it again. Say–spell–say. It works for a 4-letter word and a 14-letter word."},{"title":"Why say it first?","body":"You cannot spell a word you heard wrong. Saying it back checks your ears: if the judge says 'remember' and you say 'remender', you just caught a mistake before it cost you. Your mouth is your first spell-checker."},{"title":"Spell it steady","body":"Letters come out at a drumbeat — R…E…M…E…M…B…E…R — never in a rush. A steady beat keeps your place in the word, and at a real bee it lets the judges hear every letter clearly."},{"title":"Why say it again?","body":"The final say seals the word. You just heard yourself spell it; saying the whole word confirms the letters you gave add up to the word you meant. If it feels wrong in your mouth, something was off."},{"title":"Make it automatic","body":"Use the routine on every practice word in this app — easy ones too. When say–spell–say is a habit, your brain saves all its energy for the hard part: the letters."}],"words":[{"w":"remember","def":"to keep something in your mind; to not forget","ex":"I remember the first word I ever spelled on stage.","say":"rih-MEM-ber","hook":"re + MEM + ber — the MEM in the middle comes from memory."},{"w":"practice","def":"to do something again and again to get better at it","ex":"She spends ten minutes on spelling practice every morning.","say":"PRAK-tis","hook":"PRACT + ICE — practice makes the tricky parts feel like smooth ice."},{"w":"together","def":"with each other; joined as one group","ex":"The team spelled the word together on the bus ride home.","say":"tuh-GEH-ther","hook":"to + get + her — three little words hiding inside one."},{"w":"important","def":"mattering a lot; having great value","ex":"Saying the word before you spell it is the most important step.","say":"im-POR-tunt","hook":"im + PORT + ant — ends in -ANT, like an important ant carrying the word."},{"w":"champion","def":"the winner of a competition; the very best","ex":"The champion said every word clearly before spelling it.","say":"CHAM-pee-un","hook":"CHAMP + ION — a CHAMP never skips the routine."},{"w":"microphone","def":"a device that makes your voice louder","ex":"Step up to the microphone and say the word first.","say":"MY-kruh-fohn","hook":"micro (small) + phone (sound) — a small-sound helper. PH says /f/."},{"w":"routine","def":"a set of steps done the same way every time","ex":"Her routine never changes: say it, spell it, say it again.","say":"roo-TEEN","hook":"rout + INE — the machine-like -INE ending, like engine."},{"w":"steady","def":"even and regular; not shaky or rushed","ex":"He spelled the letters at a slow, steady beat.","say":"STEH-dee","hook":"STEAD + Y — EA makes the short e sound, like in bread."},{"w":"clearly","def":"in a way that is easy to hear or see","ex":"Say every syllable clearly before you begin.","say":"KLEER-lee","hook":"CLEAR + LY — just add -ly to clear; no letters change."},{"w":"confirm","def":"to check that something is true or correct","ex":"Saying the word again helps you confirm your spelling.","say":"kun-FURM","hook":"con + FIRM — make the word FIRM by saying it one more time."}]},{"title":"Alphabet Sounds — cat, city, goat, giant","category":"Spelling Bee Basics","difficulty":"easy","concept":"Letters are not their names: B says /b/, not 'bee'. Most letters keep one sound, but c and g each have two — hard before a, o, u and soft before e, i, y. Know what each letter SAYS and you can catch its sound in any word.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>CIRCUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> SUR-kus\n<b>Spell it.</b> C · I · R · C · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> SUR-kus\n<b>Syllables.</b> cir · cus\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [sur=CIR] [kus=CUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> one word, both c sounds — soft c before i (cir = /s/), hard c before u (cus = /k/)\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin circus = ring, circle","cards":[{"title":"The Core","body":"A letter's name and a letter's sound are different things. The letter B is named 'bee' but it says /b/, as in bat. When you spell by sound, always think about what the letter SAYS, never what it is called."},{"title":"Two faces of c","body":"C is a copycat with two voices. Before a, o, u it is HARD and says /k/: cat, coat, cup. Before e, i, y it is SOFT and says /s/: city, cent, cycle. The next letter decides — look one letter ahead."},{"title":"Two faces of g","body":"G plays the same game. Hard g before a, o, u: goat, game, gum. Soft g before e, i, y: giant, gentle, gym — it says /j/. (English keeps a few rebels like 'give' and 'girl', so listen first.)"},{"title":"The team players","body":"Q never works alone — it always brings u, and qu says /kw/: queen, quick, quiet. X is two sounds in one letter: /ks/, as in fox and exact. Spot them and you will never write 'qeen' or 'foks'."},{"title":"Use it at the mic","body":"When you hear /s/, ask: is it S, or a soft C? (city, not sity). When you hear /j/, ask: is it J, or a soft G? (giant, not jiant). The word's origin often decides — and you can ask for it at the bee!"}],"words":[{"w":"circus","def":"a traveling show with acrobats, clowns, and animals","ex":"The circus came to town with a big striped tent.","say":"SUR-kus","hook":"Both c sounds in one word: soft CIR /s/, hard CUS /k/."},{"w":"city","def":"a large town where many people live","ex":"The spelling bee finals were held in a big city.","say":"SIH-tee","hook":"Soft c before i — CITY starts with /s/ but is spelled with C."},{"w":"cycle","def":"a set of events that repeats in the same order","ex":"The seasons follow the same cycle every year.","say":"SY-kul","hook":"Soft c before y, hard c before l — C-Y-C-L-E, one c soft, one hard."},{"w":"giant","def":"a huge imaginary person; anything very large","ex":"A giant sequoia tree can grow taller than a building.","say":"JY-unt","hook":"Soft g before i — sounds like J but spelled GI."},{"w":"gentle","def":"kind and soft; not rough","ex":"Be gentle when you turn the old book’s pages.","say":"JEN-tul","hook":"Soft g before e — GEN, not JEN."},{"w":"garden","def":"a piece of ground where flowers or vegetables grow","ex":"Grandma grows tomatoes in her back garden.","say":"GAR-dun","hook":"Hard g before a — g keeps its true /g/ voice."},{"w":"guitar","def":"a musical instrument with six strings","ex":"He practiced guitar after finishing his spelling words.","say":"gih-TAR","hook":"The u after g is a bodyguard keeping g hard — GUI, not GI."},{"w":"quick","def":"fast; done in a short time","ex":"She gave a quick smile and spelled the word perfectly.","say":"KWIK","hook":"Q always brings U — QU says /kw/."},{"w":"queen","def":"a woman who rules a country","ex":"The queen bee is the mother of the whole hive.","say":"KWEEN","hook":"QU + EEN — never write q without its friend u."},{"w":"expect","def":"to think something will happen","ex":"I expect the next word will be harder than the last.","say":"ek-SPEKT","hook":"X = /ks/ — one letter, two sounds: e/ks/pect."}]},{"title":"Vowels & Magic E — cap, cape","category":"Spelling Bee Basics","difficulty":"easy","concept":"A, e, i, o, u each have a short voice (cap, pet, sit, hop, cub) and a long voice that says the letter's own name (cape, Pete, kite, hope, cube). A silent e at the end is the magic switch that turns the short voice long.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>MISTAKE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> mih-STAYK\n<b>Spell it.</b> M · I · S · T · A · K · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> mih-STAYK\n<b>Syllables.</b> mis · take\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [mih=MI] [STAYK=STAKE]\n<b>Exception.</b> the final e is silent — its whole job is making the a say its name: tak → TAKE\n<b>Origin.</b> Old Norse\n<b>Root.</b> mis- = wrongly + taka = to take","cards":[{"title":"The Core","body":"Every vowel has two voices. The SHORT voice is quick: a as in cap, e as in pet, i as in sit, o as in hop, u as in cub. The LONG voice simply says the letter's name: cape, Pete, kite, hope, cube."},{"title":"The magic e","body":"Add a silent e to the end and the vowel before it goes long: cap→cape, kit→kite, hop→hope, cub→cube, plan→plane. The e itself says nothing — it reaches back over one consonant and flips the switch."},{"title":"Closed = short","body":"When a consonant closes in a vowel with no magic e, the vowel stays short: cat, bed, fish, pond, drum. One vowel, shut in by consonants — expect the short sound. This is the most common syllable in English."},{"title":"Open = long","body":"When a syllable ENDS on its vowel, the vowel is free to say its name: go, me, hi, ba·by, mu·sic, pa·per. Spot where the syllable ends and you can predict the vowel sound before you spell it."},{"title":"Y the substitute","body":"Y jumps in as a vowel when a, e, i, o, u are missing: gym (short i sound), sky (long i), happy (long e). If you hear a vowel sound but see no vowel, look for y doing the job."}],"words":[{"w":"mistake","def":"something done wrong; an error","ex":"One small mistake taught her to slow down and say the word first.","say":"mih-STAYK","hook":"Magic e turns TAK into TAKE — the a says its name."},{"w":"escape","def":"to get away from a place or danger","ex":"The hamster tried to escape from its cage again.","say":"eh-SKAYP","hook":"ES + CAPE — magic e makes cap into cape."},{"w":"invite","def":"to ask someone to come somewhere","ex":"Did you invite your cousins to the party?","say":"in-VYT","hook":"Magic e stretches VIT into VITE — long i."},{"w":"alone","def":"without anyone else; by yourself","ex":"He likes to practice alone in his quiet room.","say":"uh-LOHN","hook":"A + LONE — magic e makes the o say its name."},{"w":"complete","def":"having every part; finished","ex":"Complete the whole list before dinner.","say":"kum-PLEET","hook":"Magic e makes the middle e long — comPLETE."},{"w":"costume","def":"clothes worn to look like someone or something else","ex":"She wore a bee costume to the school parade.","say":"KOS-toom","hook":"Magic e turns the u long: cos + TUME."},{"w":"baby","def":"a very young child","ex":"The baby clapped every time someone spelled a word.","say":"BAY-bee","hook":"Open syllable BA — the a is free, so it says its name."},{"w":"music","def":"sounds arranged to be beautiful to hear","ex":"Soft music helps him focus while studying.","say":"MYOO-zik","hook":"Open MU = long u; closed SIC = short i."},{"w":"gym","def":"a room or building for exercise and sports","ex":"The spelling bee was set up in the school gym.","say":"JIM","hook":"No a-e-i-o-u in sight — Y is the vowel, saying short i."},{"w":"sky","def":"the space above the earth where clouds and stars appear","ex":"Not a single cloud crossed the summer sky.","say":"SKY","hook":"Y at the end of a little word says long i — s + k + y."}]},{"title":"Syllables — re, mem, ber","category":"Spelling Bee Basics","difficulty":"easy","concept":"A syllable is one beat of a word, and every beat has exactly one vowel sound. Long words are just short words holding hands: re·mem·ber is three easy pieces, not one scary one. Break the word into beats and spell one beat at a time.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>FANTASTIC</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> fan-TAS-tik\n<b>Spell it.</b> F · A · N · T · A · S · T · I · C\n<b>Say it again.</b> fan-TAS-tik\n<b>Syllables.</b> fan · tas · tic\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [fan=FAN] [TAS=TAS] [tik=TIC]\n<b>Exception.</b> the /k/ at the end is spelled C, the usual ending after a short vowel in longer words\n<b>Origin.</b> Greek\n<b>Root.</b> Greek phantastikos = able to imagine","cards":[{"title":"The Core","body":"Say 'remember' and clap: re–mem–ber. Three claps, three syllables, three small spelling jobs. A syllable is one push of your voice, and each push carries exactly one vowel sound."},{"title":"Find the beats","body":"Three easy ways to count beats: clap them, hum the word (each hum-bump is a beat), or rest your hand under your chin — your jaw drops once per syllable. Try 'umbrella': um–brel–la. Three drops."},{"title":"Twin consonants split","body":"When two of the same consonant sit in the middle, the syllables split between them: rab·bit, sum·mer, les·son. That's why the word keeps both letters — each syllable owns one. Hear rab + bit, write both b's."},{"title":"Spell beat by beat","body":"Never spell a long word in one gulp. Say the first syllable, spell it. Say the next, spell it. cal·en·dar = CAL + EN + DAR. Each piece is kid-sized, and the word spells itself."},{"title":"Every beat needs a vowel","body":"No syllable exists without a vowel sound — so if you spelled a syllable with no vowel letter, you dropped something. This one check catches missing-letter mistakes: cas-tle, lit-tle — the -le hides its vowel but always writes one."}],"words":[{"w":"fantastic","def":"wonderful; extremely good","ex":"Spelling all ten words right feels fantastic.","say":"fan-TAS-tik","hook":"Three beats: fan + tas + tic — spell them one at a time."},{"w":"rabbit","def":"a small animal with long ears that hops","ex":"A rabbit hopped across the garden path.","say":"RAB-it","hook":"Twin b’s split the beats: rab + bit — each syllable keeps one b."},{"w":"summer","def":"the warmest season of the year","ex":"They practice spelling on the porch every summer evening.","say":"SUM-er","hook":"sum + mer — the twin m’s mark where the beats split."},{"w":"basket","def":"a container woven from strips, with a handle","ex":"She carried the word cards in a little basket.","say":"BAS-kit","hook":"bas + ket — two closed beats, both vowels short."},{"w":"monster","def":"a large frightening imaginary creature","ex":"Long words look like monsters until you break them into beats.","say":"MON-ster","hook":"mon + ster — two beats tame the monster."},{"w":"umbrella","def":"a folding cover that keeps rain off you","ex":"Keep an umbrella by the door in April.","say":"um-BREL-uh","hook":"um + brel + la — three beats, twin l’s at the split."},{"w":"wonderful","def":"amazing; very good","ex":"The judges said her steady spelling was wonderful.","say":"WUN-der-ful","hook":"won + der + ful — full loses an l when it becomes -ful."},{"w":"hospital","def":"a place where sick or hurt people are cared for","ex":"The hospital is two blocks from the school.","say":"HOS-pih-tul","hook":"hos + pi + tal — three beats, spell each one alone."},{"w":"calendar","def":"a chart of the days, weeks, and months of a year","ex":"Circle the bee date on the kitchen calendar.","say":"KAL-un-der","hook":"cal + en + dar — the last beat is DAR with an a, not der."},{"w":"celebrate","def":"to do something fun for a special occasion","ex":"We celebrate every level she finishes with pancakes.","say":"SEL-uh-brayt","hook":"cel + e + brate — soft c starts it, magic e ends it."}]},{"title":"Sounds to Letters — stretch, spell","category":"Spelling Bee Basics","difficulty":"easy","concept":"Inside each syllable live single sounds. Stretch the syllable like a rubber band — /s/…/t/…/a/…/m/…/p/ — and write each sound in the order you hear it. Nothing skipped, nothing guessed: that is spelling by sound.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>SPLASH</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> SPLASH\n<b>Spell it.</b> S · P · L · A · S · H\n<b>Say it again.</b> SPLASH\n<b>Syllables.</b> splash (one beat)\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [s=S] [p=P] [l=L] [a=A] [sh=SH]\n<b>Exception.</b> the last sound /sh/ needs two letters working as one team\n<b>Origin.</b> English\n<b>Root.</b> imitative — the word sounds like the thing it means","cards":[{"title":"The Core","body":"Take one syllable and stretch it slowly: 'stamp' becomes sss–t–aaa–mmm–p. Five sounds. Now write them in order: S, T, A, M, P. Every sound gets a letter; every letter earns its place."},{"title":"Stretch like a band","body":"Say the word in slow motion, as if your voice were a rubber band being pulled. Sounds you rush past at normal speed — the n in 'plant', the r in 'crisp' — pop out clearly when stretched. What you can hear, you can spell."},{"title":"Count first, then write","body":"Before writing, count the sounds on your fingers: /t/ /r/ /u/ /s/ /t/ — five. If your spelling has fewer letters than sounds, you dropped one. 'Trust' with four letters is missing something."},{"title":"The order is the spelling","body":"Sounds come out in a line, and letters follow the same line. If you hear /d/ /r/ /i/ /f/ /t/, you write d-r-i-f-t. Swapping the order — 'dirft' — is the #1 slip, so touch a finger per sound as you write."},{"title":"When teams join in","body":"Some sounds need two letters (sh, ch, th — next concept!), and some vowel sounds need teams too. But the stretch-and-spell habit stays the same: one sound at a time, in order, every sound accounted for."}],"words":[{"w":"splash","def":"to hit water so it flies around","ex":"The dog made a huge splash jumping into the pool.","say":"SPLASH","hook":"Stretch it: s-p-l-a-sh — five sounds, six letters."},{"w":"stamp","def":"a small paper square stuck on mail; to press your foot down","ex":"Put a stamp on the envelope before mailing it.","say":"STAMP","hook":"s-t-a-m-p — do not lose the quiet m before p."},{"w":"blend","def":"to mix things together smoothly","ex":"Blend the letters together and read the word.","say":"BLEND","hook":"b-l-e-n-d — the n hides before d; stretch to hear it."},{"w":"crisp","def":"firm and fresh; making a snapping sound","ex":"The crisp autumn air smelled like leaves.","say":"KRISP","hook":"c-r-i-s-p — four consonants, one short i in the middle."},{"w":"plant","def":"a living thing that grows in soil","ex":"Water the plant twice a week.","say":"PLANT","hook":"p-l-a-n-t — stretch it or the n vanishes."},{"w":"drift","def":"to be carried slowly by water or air","ex":"The paper boat began to drift downstream.","say":"DRIFT","hook":"d-r-i-f-t — keep the order; dirft is the classic slip."},{"w":"trust","def":"to believe someone is honest and reliable","ex":"Trust your ears — they heard every sound.","say":"TRUST","hook":"t-r-u-s-t — five sounds on five fingers."},{"w":"twist","def":"to turn something around and around","ex":"Twist the cap to open the bottle.","say":"TWIST","hook":"t-w-i-s-t — the w is a real sound, not a decoration."},{"w":"grasp","def":"to grab firmly; to understand","ex":"Once you grasp the method, long words feel easy.","say":"GRASP","hook":"g-r-a-s-p — stretch the end: sss then p."},{"w":"strap","def":"a strip of material used to fasten or hold things","ex":"Buckle the strap on your backpack.","say":"STRAP","hook":"s-t-r-a-p — three consonants launch one short a."}]},{"title":"Letter Teams — sh, ch, th, ph","category":"Spelling Bee Basics","difficulty":"easy","concept":"Some sounds are spelled by two letters working as one team: sh in shark, ch in chest, th in thumb, wh in whale, ph in phone, ck in duck, ng in ring. One sound, two letters — spot the team and spell it as a unit.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>WHISPER</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> WIS-per\n<b>Spell it.</b> W · H · I · S · P · E · R\n<b>Say it again.</b> WIS-per\n<b>Syllables.</b> whis · per\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [wis=WHIS] [per=PER]\n<b>Exception.</b> the opening /w/ is the team WH — many question-and-wind words start with wh: what, when, whisper, whale\n<b>Origin.</b> Old English\n<b>Root.</b> Old English hwisprian = to murmur","cards":[{"title":"The Core","body":"Stretch 'shark': /sh/–/ar/–/k/. That first sound is ONE sound, but no single letter says it — S and H team up. English is full of these letter teams; treat each team as a single spelling piece."},{"title":"The big four","body":"SH as in shine and brush. CH as in chest and lunch. TH as in thumb and bath. WH as in whale and whisper. When you hear these sounds, your pencil writes two letters but your mind counts one."},{"title":"Two kinds of th","body":"TH whispers in thin, thumb, math — and buzzes in this, that, brother. Put your fingers on your throat: the buzzing kind vibrates. Both are spelled the same way — T-H — so this trap costs nothing once you know it."},{"title":"ch wears costumes","body":"CH usually says /ch/ (chest, lunch), but in Greek words it says /k/ — chorus, echo, school — and in French words it says /sh/ — chef, machine. If /k/ or /sh/ shows up in a fancy word, suspect CH and ask about the origin."},{"title":"End-of-word teams","body":"CK ends short-vowel words: duck, clock, stick — never 'duk'. NG holds the ringing sound in ring, king, strong. PH is the Greek team for /f/: phone, graph, dolphin. Hear /f/ in a science-y word? Think PH."}],"words":[{"w":"whisper","def":"to speak very softly and quietly","ex":"She whispered the syllables to herself before spelling aloud.","say":"WIS-per","hook":"WH team starts it — whisper, whale, what."},{"w":"shark","def":"a large ocean fish with sharp teeth","ex":"A shark can grow new teeth its whole life.","say":"SHARK","hook":"SH is one sound, one team — sh + ark."},{"w":"chest","def":"the front of your body between neck and stomach; a big box","ex":"The pirate’s chest was full of gold coins.","say":"CHEST","hook":"CH team + est — four sounds, five letters."},{"w":"thumb","def":"the short thick finger on the side of your hand","ex":"He gave a thumbs-up after spelling the word.","say":"THUM","hook":"TH team starts it, silent b ends it — thum(b)."},{"w":"whale","def":"a huge animal that lives in the sea and breathes air","ex":"A blue whale’s heart is as big as a small car.","say":"WAYL","hook":"WH + ALE — magic e makes the a long."},{"w":"phone","def":"a device used to talk to people far away","ex":"The good news came by phone that evening.","say":"FOHN","hook":"PH is the Greek /f/ team — phone, photo, graph."},{"w":"dolphin","def":"a friendly sea animal that clicks and whistles","ex":"A dolphin leaped beside the boat.","say":"DOL-fin","hook":"The /f/ in the middle is PH — dol + PHin."},{"w":"kitchen","def":"the room where food is cooked","ex":"The kitchen smelled like warm cookies.","say":"KIH-chin","hook":"kit + CHen — TCH ch sound after a short vowel keeps the t."},{"w":"string","def":"a thin rope for tying things","ex":"Tie the balloons with a piece of string.","say":"STRING","hook":"STR blend up front, NG team at the end."},{"w":"clock","def":"a machine that shows the time","ex":"Her eyes kept jumping to the clock during the test.","say":"KLOK","hook":"Short o, so the /k/ ending is the CK team — never just k."}]},{"title":"Vowel Teams — ai, ay, ee, oa","category":"Spelling Bee Basics","difficulty":"easy","concept":"Long vowel sounds are usually spelled by two vowels teaming up: ai/ay for long a, ee/ea for long e, oa/ow for long o, oi/oy and au/aw for the twisty sounds. Position picks the team: ay, oy, ow like the END of words; ai, oi, oa work INSIDE.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>RAINBOW</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> RAYN-boh\n<b>Spell it.</b> R · A · I · N · B · O · W\n<b>Say it again.</b> RAYN-boh\n<b>Syllables.</b> rain · bow\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [RAYN=RAIN] [boh=BOW]\n<b>Exception.</b> two vowel teams in one word — AI works inside its syllable, OW takes the end position\n<b>Origin.</b> Old English\n<b>Root.</b> regn = rain + boga = bow, arch","cards":[{"title":"The Core","body":"Hear the long a in 'paint'? No magic e in sight — instead two vowels team up: AI. Vowel teams are the second great way English spells long vowels, and each team has a favorite seat in the word."},{"title":"The position rule","body":"Teams ending in Y or W love the END of a word: play, stay, boy, enjoy, snow, grow. Their twins work INSIDE: paint, rain, coin, point, coat, road. Same sound, different seat — pl-AY but p-AI-nt."},{"title":"Long e twins","body":"EE and EA both say long e: sweet, green — and eat, reason, team. There is no perfect rule for choosing, so meet each word once and let the hook stick: you EAT a pEAch; you SEE a bEE. (EA sometimes goes short: bread, head.)"},{"title":"The whiny sounds","body":"OI/OY is the 'annoyed' sound: coin, voice — boy, royal. OU/OW is the 'ouch' sound: loud, house — cow, tower. AU/AW is the 'awe' sound: author, because — saw, awesome. End of word? Pick the Y or W twin."},{"title":"Spell the team, not letters","body":"When you stretch a word and hit a long vowel, do not write one letter — ask WHICH TEAM spells it here. r-ai-n. b-oa-t. pl-ay. The team is a single spelling piece, exactly like sh or ch."}],"words":[{"w":"rainbow","def":"an arch of colors in the sky after rain","ex":"A double rainbow stretched over the valley.","say":"RAYN-boh","hook":"AI inside, OW at the end — two teams, both in position."},{"w":"crayon","def":"a stick of colored wax for drawing","ex":"She drew the bee with a yellow crayon.","say":"KRAY-on","hook":"AY ends its syllable: cray + on."},{"w":"paint","def":"colored liquid you brush onto things","ex":"They used blue paint for the ocean poster.","say":"PAYNT","hook":"Long a inside the word = AI: p-ai-nt."},{"w":"sweet","def":"tasting like sugar; very pleasant","ex":"Victory tasted sweet after all that practice.","say":"SWEET","hook":"EE in the middle — you SEE two e’s in sweet."},{"w":"reason","def":"why something happens; a cause","ex":"There is a reason for every strange spelling.","say":"REE-zun","hook":"EA says long e: r-ea-son."},{"w":"coast","def":"the land along the edge of the sea","ex":"They drove down the coast to the finals.","say":"KOHST","hook":"OA works inside: c-oa-st."},{"w":"window","def":"an opening in a wall filled with glass","ex":"Morning light came through the classroom window.","say":"WIN-doh","hook":"OW takes the end seat: wind + ow."},{"w":"voyage","def":"a long journey by sea or through space","ex":"The explorers began their voyage at dawn.","say":"VOY-ij","hook":"OY ends its syllable: voy + age."},{"w":"poison","def":"something that can make you sick if swallowed","ex":"Some bright frogs carry poison on their skin.","say":"POY-zun","hook":"OI inside the word: p-oi-son."},{"w":"author","def":"a person who writes books or stories","ex":"The author signed her book for every kid in line.","say":"AW-thur","hook":"AU inside: au + thor. (AW would end a word, like saw.)"}]},{"title":"Blends & Silent Letters — kn, wr, mb","category":"Spelling Bee Basics","difficulty":"easy","concept":"In a blend, every letter still speaks — st, str, spl: just spell what you hear, in order. Silent letters are the opposite: leftover letters from old English that went quiet — the k in knee, w in write, b in climb. Blends you hear; silents you remember.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>KNIGHT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> NYT\n<b>Spell it.</b> K · N · I · G · H · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> NYT\n<b>Syllables.</b> knight (one beat)\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [n=KN] [y=IGH] [t=T]\n<b>Exception.</b> a ghost word — silent k (people once said k-nicht!) and silent gh; only three sounds in six letters\n<b>Origin.</b> Old English\n<b>Root.</b> Old English cniht = boy, servant, warrior","cards":[{"title":"The Core","body":"Two kinds of letter clusters, opposite rules. BLENDS: every letter sounds — /s//t/ in stop, /s//t//r/ in strong. Stretch and spell. SILENT LETTERS: a letter sits in the word saying nothing — knee starts with /n/ but writes KN."},{"title":"Blends: trust your ears","body":"st, sp, sk, bl, cl, fr, gr, str, spl, scr — in all of these, each letter earns its sound. Stretch 'splash': /s/ /p/ /l/… every sound is there. Blends never need memorizing; they need careful ears."},{"title":"Silents: little ghosts","body":"Hundreds of years ago, people really said the k in knee and the w in write. Speech moved on; spelling stayed. So the silent letters are ghosts of old pronunciations — invisible to your ears, required by your pencil."},{"title":"The ghost families","body":"KN- says /n/: knee, knight, knock, know. WR- says /r/: write, wrist, wrong. -MB says /m/: climb, thumb, lamb, comb. Learn them as families and one memory covers a dozen words."},{"title":"Which is it?","body":"Hear /n/ at the start? It might be N or KN. Hear /r/? Maybe WR. The meaning helps: writing words take WR (write, wrote); knowing-and-body words often take KN (know, knee, knuckle). At the bee, the definition question is your friend."}],"words":[{"w":"knight","def":"a warrior in armor who served a king","ex":"The knight bowed before the queen.","say":"NYT","hook":"Silent k, silent gh — six letters, three sounds."},{"w":"knee","def":"the joint in the middle of your leg","ex":"She scraped her knee on the playground.","say":"NEE","hook":"KN family — the k is a ghost from old English."},{"w":"knock","def":"to hit a door to be let in","ex":"Knock twice before you come in.","say":"NOK","hook":"Ghost k up front, CK team at the back."},{"w":"write","def":"to make letters and words on paper","ex":"Write each word three times to lock it in.","say":"RYT","hook":"WR family — writing words keep the silent w."},{"w":"wrist","def":"the joint between your hand and arm","ex":"He wore his lucky band around his wrist.","say":"RIST","hook":"WR + ist — silent w, then a clean blend."},{"w":"climb","def":"to go up using your hands and feet","ex":"They climb the hill behind school every spring.","say":"KLYM","hook":"-MB family — the b is silent: clim(b)."},{"w":"lamb","def":"a young sheep","ex":"The lamb followed the farmer everywhere.","say":"LAM","hook":"Silent b: lam(b), like thumb and comb."},{"w":"ghost","def":"the spirit of a dead person in stories","ex":"The old house creaked like it had a ghost.","say":"GOHST","hook":"GH up front is not silent here — /g/ + host."},{"w":"strong","def":"having great power; not weak","ex":"Strong spellers stretch every blend.","say":"STRONG","hook":"STR blend — all three letters speak, then the NG team."},{"w":"island","def":"land with water all around it","ex":"The lighthouse stood on a tiny island.","say":"EYE-lund","hook":"Silent s — is + land, but say EYE-land."}]},{"title":"Stress — find the loud beat","category":"Spelling Bee Basics","difficulty":"easy","concept":"Every word with two or more beats has one beat that shouts: ba-NA-na, to-MOR-row, va-CA-tion. Stressed syllables are spelled the way they sound; the quiet ones are where letters hide. Find the loud beat first — then guard the quiet ones.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>DELICIOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> dih-LIH-shus\n<b>Spell it.</b> D · E · L · I · C · I · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> dih-LIH-shus\n<b>Syllables.</b> de · li · cious\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [dih=DE] [LIH=LI] [shus=CIOUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> the loud beat LI is easy; the quiet tail -cious hides c-i-o-u-s behind one small /shus/\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin deliciae = delight","cards":[{"title":"The Core","body":"Say 'banana' three ways: BA-na-na, ba-NA-na, ba-na-NA. Only one sounds right — the middle one. That loud beat is the STRESS, and every long word has exactly one main stress. Your ears already know where it is."},{"title":"Find it fast","body":"Call the word like you’re shouting it across a playground — the syllable you naturally lean on is the stress. Or hum the word: the loudest hum is the stressed beat. va-CA-tion. to-MA-to. mu-SE-um."},{"title":"Loud beats are honest","body":"Stressed syllables say their vowels clearly: the CA in vacation is a clean long a; the MOR in tomorrow is a clear or. Whatever you hear in the loud beat, you can trust — spell it exactly as it sounds."},{"title":"Quiet beats tell lies","body":"Unstressed syllables get mumbled — the first a in 'banana' and the last two sound like lazy 'uh'. That mumble is where spellers slip. Rule: trust the loud beat, double-check every quiet one. (The mumble has a name — meet the schwa, next concept.)"},{"title":"Stress can move","body":"In word families the stress hops around: PHO-to, pho-TOG-ra-phy. When it hops, hidden vowels come out to speak. Can’t hear a vowel in one word? Say its relative — the same letters get loud somewhere else."}],"words":[{"w":"delicious","def":"tasting extremely good","ex":"The victory pancakes were delicious.","say":"dih-LIH-shus","hook":"Stress on LI — the quiet -cious tail hides five letters."},{"w":"banana","def":"a long curved yellow fruit","ex":"A banana is good brain food before a bee.","say":"buh-NAN-uh","hook":"Only the middle NA is loud — the other two a’s mumble."},{"w":"tomato","def":"a round red fruit eaten as a vegetable","ex":"She sliced a tomato for the salad.","say":"tuh-MAY-toh","hook":"Stress on MA — to-MA-to, all spelled with plain o’s and a’s."},{"w":"potato","def":"a starchy vegetable that grows underground","ex":"Baked potato night is Friday night.","say":"puh-TAY-toh","hook":"po-TA-to — same tune as tomato, stress on the middle."},{"w":"vacation","def":"time away from school or work to rest or travel","ex":"They visited three national parks on vacation.","say":"vay-KAY-shun","hook":"The loud CA says long a clearly — va-CA-tion."},{"w":"tomorrow","def":"the day after today","ex":"Tomorrow is the last practice before the finals.","say":"tuh-MOR-oh","hook":"Stress on MOR — one m in the quiet start, two r’s at the loud middle."},{"w":"museum","def":"a building where interesting objects are shown","ex":"The science museum has a giant bee model.","say":"myoo-ZEE-um","hook":"mu-SE-um — the loud ZEE is a plain SE."},{"w":"eleven","def":"the number after ten","ex":"Eleven spellers made it to the final round.","say":"ih-LEV-un","hook":"e-LEV-en — trust the loud LEV; the ends mumble."},{"w":"gorilla","def":"the largest kind of ape","ex":"The gorilla watched the visitors calmly.","say":"guh-RIL-uh","hook":"go-RIL-la — loud RIL keeps the twin l’s."},{"w":"important","def":"mattering a lot","ex":"The stress test: im-POR-tant, loud in the middle.","say":"im-POR-tunt","hook":"POR is loud and honest; the quiet -tant needs an a."}]},{"title":"The Sneaky Schwa — the mumbled uh","category":"Spelling Bee Basics","difficulty":"easy","concept":"In quiet syllables, English mumbles every vowel into the same lazy 'uh': the a in about, the o in lemon, the i in pencil. That mumble is the schwa — the #1 spelling trap in the language, because ANY vowel letter can hide behind it.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>CHOCOLATE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> CHOK-lut\n<b>Spell it.</b> C · H · O · C · O · L · A · T · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> CHOK-lut\n<b>Syllables.</b> choc · o · late\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [CHOK=CHOC] [uh=O] [lut=LATE]\n<b>Exception.</b> two vowels vanish into mumbles — say choc-O-LATE like a robot to hear the hidden o and a\n<b>Origin.</b> Spanish, from Nahuatl\n<b>Root.</b> Nahuatl xocolatl = bitter water","cards":[{"title":"The Core","body":"Say 'about'. That first sound is not a clean /a/ — it’s a lazy 'uh'. Say 'lemon' — the o mumbles to 'uh' too. Same mumble, different letters! This shy little sound is the SCHWA, and it lives in almost every long English word."},{"title":"Why it is dangerous","body":"The schwa erases the clue. If you hear 'uh', the letter could be A (about), E (taken), I (pencil), O (lemon), or U (circus). Your ears alone cannot pick — which is exactly why quiet syllables cause most misspellings."},{"title":"Trick 1: robot voice","body":"Say the word the way it is SPELLED, like a robot: choc-O-late. sep-A-rate. def-I-nite. Champions call this spelling pronunciation. Store the robot voice in your head, and the hidden letter is never hidden again."},{"title":"Trick 2: call a relative","body":"Can’t hear the vowel in defin_tion? Call its relative: deFINE — there’s the i, loud and clear. Family words share letters, and the stress moves around the family, so some relative usually shouts the vowel you need."},{"title":"Schwa radar","body":"Before spelling a long word, mark the quiet beats — that’s where schwas hide. Loud beats: trust your ears. Quiet beats: use robot voice, call a relative, or ask for the word’s origin. Radar on, trap disarmed."}],"words":[{"w":"chocolate","def":"a sweet food made from cacao beans","ex":"Hot chocolate is her reward after practice.","say":"CHOK-lut","hook":"Robot voice: choc-O-LATE — the middle o and the a-e are mumbled."},{"w":"about","def":"concerning; on the subject of","ex":"This chapter is about the sneakiest sound in English.","say":"uh-BOWT","hook":"The opening ‘uh’ is the letter A — a-bout."},{"w":"lemon","def":"a sour yellow fruit","ex":"She squeezed a lemon into her water.","say":"LEM-un","hook":"The mumbled ending is O — lem-ON, robot voice: lem-ON."},{"w":"pencil","def":"a writing tool with a graphite center","ex":"Spell it in the air with your pencil first.","say":"PEN-sul","hook":"The mumble hides an I — pen-CIL."},{"w":"wagon","def":"a four-wheeled cart pulled by hand or horses","ex":"The kids pulled their books in a red wagon.","say":"WAG-un","hook":"wag-ON — the quiet o mumbles to uh."},{"w":"camera","def":"a device for taking photographs","ex":"The camera flashed when she spelled the winning word.","say":"KAM-ruh","hook":"Robot voice: cam-E-ra — a hidden e lives in the middle."},{"w":"animal","def":"a living creature that can move on its own","ex":"Every animal in the zoo has a name tag.","say":"AN-ih-mul","hook":"an-i-MAL — the last a mumbles; robot voice saves it."},{"w":"purpose","def":"the reason something is done","ex":"Every step of the routine has a purpose.","say":"PUR-pus","hook":"pur-POSE — the quiet o hides in -pose."},{"w":"magazine","def":"a thin book with articles and pictures, published regularly","ex":"Her photo was in the school magazine.","say":"mag-uh-ZEEN","hook":"mag-A-zine — the mumbled middle is an a."},{"w":"definition","def":"the meaning of a word","ex":"Ask for the definition when you need a clue.","say":"def-uh-NIH-shun","hook":"Can’t hear the i? Call the relative: deFINE."}]},{"title":"Ask the Right Questions — be a word detective","category":"Spelling Bee Basics","difficulty":"easy","concept":"At the bee you may ask: the definition, the language of origin, the part of speech, the sentence, and other pronunciations. Each answer is a clue — French origin hints at -eau and ch=/sh/; the sentence separates flour from flower. Champions never spell blind.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>BOUQUET</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> boo-KAY\n<b>Spell it.</b> B · O · U · Q · U · E · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> boo-KAY\n<b>Syllables.</b> bou · quet\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [boo=BOU] [KAY=QUET]\n<b>Exception.</b> ask the origin! French — so /k/ is QU and the final /ay/ is a silent-t -ET, like ballet\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> French bosquet = little wood, bunch","cards":[{"title":"The Core","body":"On stage you are a detective, and questions are free. 'May I have the definition? The language of origin? The part of speech? Could you use it in a sentence? Are there alternate pronunciations?' Every answer narrows down the spelling."},{"title":"Origin is the master clue","body":"French words love silent endings and soft sounds: ballet, bouquet, machine. Greek words use ph, y, and ch=/k/: photo, gym, chorus. Spanish brings canyon and tornado; Japanese brings karate. Hear the origin, predict the letters."},{"title":"The sentence saves you","body":"Hear /FLOW-er/ — is it flour or flower? You cannot know until the sentence: 'The baker sifted the ___.' Homophones sound identical, so the sentence question is not politeness — it is the only way to pick the right word."},{"title":"Definition & part of speech","body":"The definition connects the word to relatives you can already spell ('it means to see ahead' → fore-, like forecast). The part of speech picks endings: the noun is 'practice', and in many spellings the verb is 'practise' — small grammar, real letters."},{"title":"Alternate pronunciations","body":"Some words are said two ways — and the second way often reveals a hidden vowel or letter the first way mumbles. It costs nothing to ask. Detectives collect every clue before they write a single letter."}],"words":[{"w":"bouquet","def":"a bunch of flowers arranged nicely","ex":"The winner received a bouquet of roses.","say":"boo-KAY","hook":"French: silent-t ending -QUET says /kay/."},{"w":"ballet","def":"a graceful kind of dance that tells a story","ex":"Her sister takes ballet on Saturdays.","say":"ba-LAY","hook":"French: the final /ay/ is -ET with a silent t."},{"w":"chorus","def":"a group of singers; the repeated part of a song","ex":"The whole chorus sang the school song.","say":"KOR-us","hook":"Greek: ch says /k/ — chorus, echo, school."},{"w":"echo","def":"a sound that bounces back so you hear it again","ex":"Her voice made an echo in the empty gym.","say":"EK-oh","hook":"Greek: the /k/ is spelled CH — e-CHo."},{"w":"flour","def":"the powder made from grain, used for baking","ex":"The baker sifted the flour twice.","say":"FLOW-er","hook":"Sounds exactly like flower — the sentence tells you which."},{"w":"plain","def":"simple, with nothing added; flat open land","ex":"She wore a plain blue shirt.","say":"PLAYN","hook":"Homophone of plane — ask for a sentence!"},{"w":"canyon","def":"a deep valley with steep rocky sides","ex":"The river carved this canyon over millions of years.","say":"KAN-yun","hook":"Spanish: the /ny/ sound is spelled NY — can-yon."},{"w":"karate","def":"a Japanese way of fighting using hands and feet","ex":"He earned a new belt in karate class.","say":"kuh-RAH-tee","hook":"Japanese: every vowel is said — ka-ra-te ends in a clean e."},{"w":"waffle","def":"a crisp breakfast cake with a grid of squares","ex":"Saturday means a waffle with syrup.","say":"WAH-ful","hook":"Dutch: double f + -LE ending holds the final beat."},{"w":"suite","def":"a set of connected rooms; a matching set","ex":"The hotel suite had a view of the stadium.","say":"SWEET","hook":"French: sounds like sweet but spelled S-U-I-T-E — origin is everything."}]},{"title":"Ego & Self — ego / auto / alter","category":"Personality Themes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Words built on Latin ego = I and Greek autos = self describe how people relate to themselves. Master this cluster and you unlock personality vocabulary from egotist to autodidact.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>EGOTISTICAL</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ee-guh-TIH-stih-kuhl\n<b>Spell it.</b> E · G · O · T · I · S · T · I · C · A · L\n<b>Say it again.</b> ee-guh-TIH-stih-kuhl\n<b>Syllables.</b> iy · gah · tih · stih · kah · l\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [EE=E] [goh=GO] [TIS=TIS] [tih=TI] [kul=CAL]\n<b>Exception.</b> double-T: egotist TALKS about himself — the extra T stands for Talking; -al is the adjective suffix\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin ego = I + -t- + -istical = characterized by","cards":[{"title":"The Core","body":"Ego = Latin \"I.\" An egoist cares only about themselves. An egotist constantly talks about themselves — the extra t stands for talking. Both from ego; only the suffix differs."},{"title":"Scaling Up","body":"An egocentric (ego + centrum = center) believes the universe revolves around them. An egomaniac (ego + Greek mania = madness) takes self-obsession to a pathological extreme."},{"title":"The Opposite — alter","body":"Latin alter = other. Altruistic = puts others first. Magnanimous (magna = great + animus = soul) = great-souled generosity. Philanthropist (philos = love + anthropos = human) = lover of humanity."},{"title":"auto- (Greek self)","body":"Autobiography = writes own life. Autodidact (auto- + didaskein = teach) = self-taught. Autonomous = self-governing. Autocracy = rule by one alone. When you see auto-, think \"by itself/by oneself.\""},{"title":"Bee Traps","body":"Egoism (philosophy of self-interest) ≠ egotism (excessive self-talk). Narcissism has double-s from Greek name Narcissus. Solipsism (solus = alone + ipse = self) = only the self exists — rare root, common bee word."}],"words":[{"w":"egoist","def":"a conceited and self-centered person","ex":"The notorious egoist never once asked how his teammates were feeling after the loss.","say":"EE-goh-ist","hook":"An EGO+IST is one who practices putting the EGO first — the artist of self-interest."},{"w":"egotist","def":"a conceited and self-centered person","ex":"The egotist spent the entire dinner talking about himself without asking a single question.","say":"EE-guh-tihst","hook":"An EGO+T+IST talks about themselves constantly — the T stands for 'Talks about himself incessantly.'"},{"w":"egocentric","def":"a self-centered person with little regard for others","ex":"The egocentric team captain always took credit for victories but blamed teammates for every loss.","say":"ee-goh-SEH-ntrihk","hook":"An EGO-CENTRIC person puts their EGO at the CENTER of everything — ego+center+ic."},{"w":"egomaniac","def":"an abnormally egotistical person","ex":"The class president was such an egomaniac that he insisted every school project be named after him.","say":"ee-goh-MAY-nee-ak","hook":"An EGO+MANIA+C is a maniac whose obsession is their own ego — spot the MANIA in the middle."},{"w":"altruistic","def":"showing unselfish concern for the welfare of others","ex":"Her altruistic decision to donate her entire prize money to the shelter inspired everyone in town.","say":"aw-ltroo-IH-stihk","hook":"ALTRUISTIC people are TRUE to others — no sneaky extra 'i': A-L-T-R-U-I-S-T-I-C, ten clean letters."},{"w":"magnanimous","def":"is generous in forgiving insult or injury","ex":"a greathearted general","say":"m-a-g-n-A-n-uh-m-uh-s","hook":"A magnANIMous person has a GREAT ANIMAL spirit — big-souled and forgiving."},{"w":"philanthropist","def":"someone who makes charitable donations intended to increase human well-being","ex":"The philanthropist donated enough money to build a new library for every school in the district.","say":"fuh-LA-nthruh-puhst","hook":"A philanthropIST puts people on his LIST of those to help — no H after anthrop!"},{"w":"autodidact","def":"a person who has taught himself","ex":"The famous inventor was a proud autodidact who had never attended college yet revolutionized electrical engineering.","say":"aw-toh-DY-dakt","hook":"AUTO (self) + DIDACT (teach) = self-taught person."},{"w":"autonomous","def":"(of political bodies) not controlled by outside forces","ex":"an autonomous judiciary","say":"aw-TAH-nuh-muhs","hook":"An autoNOMous region makes its own NORMS — spell NOM then add -ous, not just -us."},{"w":"narcissism","def":"is excessive self-love vanity","ex":"self-love that shut out everyone else","say":"n-AH-r-s-ih-s-ih-z-uh-m","hook":"NARCISSISM has double-s twice — so self-obsessed it even doubles its letters twice."},{"w":"solipsism","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"egotism","def":"an exaggerated opinion of your own importance","ex":"His egotism was exhausting; every conversation somehow circled back to his own accomplishments.","say":"EE-guh-tih-zuhm","hook":"EGO+T+ISM — the extra T stands for 'Talking about myself' — egotism has a T that egoism lacks."},{"w":"egoism","def":"(ethics) the theory that the pursuit of your own welfare in the basis of morality","ex":"The philosophy teacher challenged her students to debate whether egoism could ever lead to a just society.","say":"EE-goh-ih-zuhm","hook":"EGOISM is the doctrine (ISM) that the great 'I' (EGO) comes first — ego+ism."},{"w":"autocracy","def":"a political system governed by a single individual","ex":"The citizens grew frustrated living under an autocracy where a single ruler made every decision without question.","say":"aw-TAH-kruh-see","hook":"AUTO-CRACY: one ruler rules by themselves — C-R-A-C-Y, like democracy but with AUTO in front."},{"w":"autobiography","def":"a biography of yourself","ex":"Maya Angelou's autobiography describes her childhood in the American South with vivid and moving detail.","say":"aw-tuh-beye-AH-gruh-fee","hook":"AUTO + BIO + GRAPHY: a self (auto) life (bio) writing (graphy) — PH makes the F sound, not plain F."}]},{"title":"Talking & Speaking — loqu / phon / verb","category":"Personality Themes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin loqui = to speak and Greek phonē = sound/voice are two of the most productive roots in English. Together they explain dozens of words about how, how much, and how well people communicate.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>LOQUACIOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> l-oh-k-w-AY-sh-uh-s\n<b>Spell it.</b> L · O · Q · U · A · C · I · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> l-oh-k-w-AY-sh-uh-s\n<b>Syllables.</b> l · o · q · u · a · c · i · o · u · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [loh=LO] [KWAY=QUA] [shus=CIOUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> qu always together; /sh/ = CIOUS (Latin adjective suffix); stress on second syllable lo-KWAY-shus\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin loqui = to speak","cards":[{"title":"The loqu- Root","body":"Latin loqui = to speak. Loquacious = talks too freely. Eloquent = speaks beautifully (e- = out, so speaking out well). Grandiloquent = pompously grand speech. Ventriloquist (ventri = belly) = speaks from the belly."},{"title":"Silence vs Talk Scale","body":"Taciturn (Latin tacere = silent) = habitually quiet. Reticent = reluctant to speak. Laconic (from Sparta) = brief and to-the-point. Verbose (verbum = word) = uses too many words. Garrulous = excessively chatty."},{"title":"loqu- Word Families","body":"Soliloquy (solo + loquy) = talking to yourself on stage. Colloquy (col- + loquy) = formal two-way conversation. Colloquial = everyday spoken language. Obloquy (ob- against) = harsh public criticism. Interlocutor = the person you are speaking with."},{"title":"The phon- Family (Greek)","body":"phonē = sound/voice. Always spelled ph not f — the Greek signal. Cacophony (kakos = bad) = harsh noise. Euphony (eu = good) = pleasant sound. Symphony (sym = together) = harmonious sounds. Polyphony (poly = many) = many simultaneous voices."},{"title":"High-Value Bee Words","body":"Magniloquent = inflated boastful speech. Pauciloquent (pauci = few) = using very few words. Somniloquy (somni = sleep) = talking in one's sleep. These long compounds decode instantly if you know -loqu-."}],"words":[{"w":"loquacious","def":"is talking or tending to talk too freely","ex":"kept from her housework by gabby neighbors","say":"l-oh-k-w-AY-sh-uh-s","hook":"A loquacious person SQUAWKS like a parrot — loquACIOUS"},{"w":"eloquent","def":"expressing yourself readily, clearly, effectively","ex":"able to dazzle with his facile tongue","say":"EH-luh-kwuhnt","hook":"An ELOquent speaker lets words FLOW out beautifully."},{"w":"grandiloquent","def":"lofty in style","ex":"he engages in so much tall talk, one never really realizes what he is saying","say":"gra-NDIH-luh-kwuhnt","hook":"GRANDI-LO-QUENT rhymes with eloquent — a grandiloquent speaker is an eloquent speaker gone grand and pompous."},{"w":"ventriloquist","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"soliloquy","def":"is a discourse by a person who is talking to himself","ex":"The actor delivered Hamlet's famous soliloquy so powerfully that the entire audience held their breath.","say":"s-uh-l-IH-l-uh-k-w-ee","hook":"A soliloquy is a SOLO speech — SOL-I-LOQU-Y: alone + speak, with a Q-U-Y ending like obloquy."},{"w":"colloquy","def":"a conversation especially a formal one","ex":"The two diplomats held a private colloquy before the official summit began.","say":"KAH-luh-kwee","hook":"A COLLOQUY is a TALK — col-LOQUY has LOQUACIOUS buried inside it."},{"w":"colloquial","def":"characteristic of informal spoken language or conversation","ex":"wrote her letters in a colloquial style","say":"kuh-LOH-kwee-uhl","hook":"COLLOQUIAL speech is how people TALK together — double L, double the chatter."},{"w":"obloquy","def":"is abusive language aimed at a person","ex":"After betraying his teammates, the captain faced obloquy from fans throughout the entire city.","say":"AW-bluh-kwee","hook":"OBLOQUy — people LOQUACIOUSLY speak AGAINST (ob) you."},{"w":"interlocutor","def":"the performer in the middle of a minstrel line who engages the others in talk","ex":"During the roundtable debate, the teacher acted as interlocutor, drawing out each student's argument in turn.","say":"ih-nter-LAH-kyuh-ter","hook":"An interlocutor LOCUTES (speaks) BETWEEN people."},{"w":"taciturn","def":"means inclined to silence","ex":"The taciturn new student rarely spoke in class, but her written essays were bold and full of ideas.","say":"t-A-s-ih-t-ur-n","hook":"TACITURN: someone TACIT and STERN who never speaks turns away in silence"},{"w":"reticent","def":"is someone disposed to be silent or not to speak freely","ex":"Although she knew the answer, the reticent girl sat quietly and let the others debate for several minutes.","say":"r-EH-t-ih-s-uh-n-t","hook":"A RETICENT person is not reTICkEt — spell it with -ENT like SILENT, because silence is their talent."},{"w":"verbose","def":"using or containing too many words","ex":"long-winded (or windy) speakers","say":"ver-BOHS","hook":"VERBOSE ends in '-ose' like 'grandiose' — a verbose person is grandiose with words."},{"w":"garrulous","def":"full of trivial conversation","ex":"The garrulous tour guide talked nonstop for two hours, sharing every detail about each painting until the visitors were exhausted.","say":"GEH-ruh-luhs","hook":"GARRULous people GARGLE with words"},{"w":"cacophony","def":"is a harsh discordance of sound","ex":"The construction site next to the library created such a cacophony that students could barely concentrate on their reading.","say":"k-a-k-AH-f-uh-n-ee","hook":"CACO-PHONY: bad (caco) PHONE (phon) call — all noise and no sense, spelled with phony at the end."},{"w":"euphony","def":"any agreeable (pleasing and harmonious) sounds","ex":"he fell asleep to the music of the wind chimes","say":"YOO-fuh-nee","hook":"Euphony = EU + PHONY — but unlike a phony friend, euphony is genuinely pleasant to the ear!"},{"w":"symphony","def":"a long and complex sonata for symphony orchestra","ex":"we heard the Vienna symphony","say":"SIH-mfuh-nee","hook":"A symPHONy is sounds (PHON) together — not symphAny, the O holds the note!"},{"w":"polyphony","def":"music arranged in parts for several voices or instruments","ex":"The cathedral filled with rich polyphony as four separate vocal parts wove together in perfect harmony.","say":"puh-LIH-fuh-nee","hook":"POLYphony = POLY voices; remember the 'y' ending like harmony and symphony, its musical cousins."},{"w":"magniloquent","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"pauciloquent","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"somniloquy","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""}]},{"title":"Honesty & Deception — ver / mendax / cred / pseudo","category":"Personality Themes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin veritas = truth and mendax = lying create perfectly opposite word families. Greek pseudos = false adds a third. These cover the full honesty spectrum and appear frequently in spelling bees.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>MENDACIOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> m-eh-n-d-AY-sh-uh-s\n<b>Spell it.</b> M · E · N · D · A · C · I · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> m-eh-n-d-AY-sh-uh-s\n<b>Syllables.</b> m · e · n · d · a · c · i · o · u · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [men=MEN] [DAY=DA] [shus=CIOUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> /sh/ sound = CIOUS not SHUS — the Latin adjective suffix; stress on second syllable men-DAY-shus\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> Latin mendax = lying, from mendum = fault, defect","cards":[{"title":"The Truth Root — ver-","body":"Latin veritas = truth. Veracious = truthful (≠ voracious = greedy!). Veracity = habitual truthfulness. Verify = prove true. Verdict (ver + dict = say) = what is truly stated. Aver = firmly declare as true. Verisimilitude = the appearance of truth."},{"title":"The Lying Root — mendax","body":"Mendacious = habitually untruthful. Mendacity = the habit of lying. Memory trick: a mendacious person mends (bends) the truth. This root is rare in English — which is exactly why it keeps appearing in bees."},{"title":"Deception Words","body":"Duplicitous (duplex = double) = two-faced. Dissemble = conceal true feelings. Prevaricate = speak evasively. Equivocate (equi = equal + voc = voice) = use deliberately ambiguous language. Disingenuous = not candid, pretending to be naïve."},{"title":"The cred- Family — Believing","body":"Latin credere = to believe. Credulous = too easily believing. Incredulous = refusing to believe. Credibility = worthiness of belief. Miscreant (mis- + credere = believe wrongly) = a villain. Discredit = remove credibility."},{"title":"pseudo- (Greek false)","body":"Greek pseudos = false. Pseudonym (pseudo- + onoma = name) = false name. Pseudoscience = fake science. ⚠️ Pseudo- begins with a SILENT p — P-S-E-U-D-O. The ps- cluster is a Greek signal; say /SOO-doh/ but spell P-S."}],"words":[{"w":"veracious","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"veracity","def":"unwillingness to tell lies","ex":"The judge praised the witness for her veracity, noting that every detail she provided matched the evidence exactly.","say":"ver-A-sih-tee","hook":"VERACity: VERy ACcurate = truth"},{"w":"verify","def":"confirm the truth of","ex":"Please verify that the doors are closed","say":"VEH-ruh-feye","hook":"VERIFY starts with VERI — VERy Important to spell it with an E, not an A!"},{"w":"verdict","def":"(law) the findings of a jury on issues of fact submitted to it for decision; can be used in formulating a judgment","ex":"The courtroom fell completely silent as the jury foreman rose to announce the long-awaited verdict.","say":"VUR-dihkt","hook":"A VERDICT is what is truly DICT-ated (said) by the jury — VERily DiCTated!"},{"w":"verisimilitude","def":"the appearance of truth; the quality of seeming to be true","ex":"The novelist researched Medieval armor for months to give her fantasy story enough verisimilitude that readers would forget they were reading fiction.","say":"v-eh-r-uh-s-uh-m-IH-l-uh-t-oo-d","hook":"VERI (very true) + SIMILAR: something so similar to truth it seems real"},{"w":"mendacious","def":"is telling lies especially habitually","ex":"The mendacious salesman promised that the ancient car had never broken down, but the thick stack of repair receipts stuffed under the seat told a completely different and far more honest story.","say":"m-eh-n-d-AY-sh-uh-s","hook":"MENDACious — you can't MEND a liar's ways; -acious not -atious"},{"w":"mendacity","def":"the tendency to be untruthful","ex":"The journalist's report exposed the politician's long history of mendacity, revealing dozens of misleading statements.","say":"meh-NDA-sih-tee","hook":"MENDACITY: a MENDed story is a LIE — liars MEND the truth with DACity of deceit."},{"w":"duplicitous","def":"marked by deliberate deceptiveness especially by pretending one set of feelings and acting under the influence of another; - Israel Zangwill; ; - W.M.Thackeray","ex":"she was a deceitful scheming little thing","say":"doo-PLIH-sih-tuhs","hook":"A DUPLICITOUS person has a double face — no extra I after DUPLIC, just -ITOUS."},{"w":"dissemble","def":"make believe with the intent to deceive","ex":"The spy had to dissemble perfectly, pretending to be a simple baker while gathering crucial information for her country.","say":"dih-SEH-mbuhl","hook":"diSSEMble — to diSSEMble is to disSEMinate a false SEMBLANCE of yourself."},{"w":"prevaricate","def":"be deliberately ambiguous or unclear in order to mislead or withhold information","ex":"The detective warned the suspect not to prevaricate, because every evasive answer only made him look more guilty.","say":"pruh-VEH-ruh-kayt","hook":"preVARIcate — a liar VARIes the truth; to preVARIcate is to VARY your story to mislead."},{"w":"equivocate","def":"be deliberately ambiguous or unclear in order to mislead or withhold information","ex":"The politician continued to equivocate when reporters pressed him for a direct answer about the new tax plan.","say":"ih-KWIH-vuh-kayt","hook":"To EQUIVOCATE is to speak with TWO EQUAL VOICES—VOC in the middle gives it away."},{"w":"disingenuous","def":"not straightforward or candid; giving a false appearance of frankness; - David Cannadine","ex":"an ambitious, disingenuous, philistine, and hypocritical operator, who...exemplified...the most disagreeable traits of his time","say":"dih-sih-NJEH-nyoo-uhs","hook":"DIS-IN-GENU-OUS hides the Latin for 'genuine' — someone disingenuous is NOT genuine."},{"w":"credulous","def":"disposed to believe on little evidence","ex":"the gimmick would convince none but the most credulous","say":"KREH-juh-luhs","hook":"A CREDULOUS person believes too EASILY — the '-ulous' suffix stuffs them full of misplaced trust."},{"w":"incredulous","def":"not disposed or willing to believe; unbelieving","ex":"Mia was incredulous when her brother claimed he had finished a week's worth of homework in just twenty minutes.","say":"ih-NKREH-juh-luhs","hook":"An INCREDULOUS person is so full of doubt they raise their brow — remember the -ous ending."},{"w":"miscreant","def":"a person without moral scruples","ex":"The sheriff finally tracked down the miscreant who had been stealing from local farmers for months.","say":"MIH-skree-uhnt","hook":"A MISCREANT mis-CREATES chaos — spot CREATE in the middle; the villain CREATES misery."},{"w":"pseudonym","def":"a fictitious name used when the person performs a particular social role","ex":"The famous author used a pseudonym so readers wouldn't know her real identity.","say":"SOO-duh-nihm","hook":"A PSEUDONYM is a FALSE NAME — PSEUDO+NYM; think 'Sue Doh Nim' uses a fake name to hide from Sue."},{"w":"pseudoscience","def":"an activity resembling science but based on fallacious assumptions","ex":"The school board voted to remove the textbook chapter that taught astrology as if it were science rather than pseudoscience.","say":"soo-doh-SEYE-uhns","hook":"PSEUDOSCIENCE = PSEUDO + SCIENCE — fake science wearing a lab coat; the silent P is as bogus as the field."}]},{"title":"Feelings & Emotions — the Four Humors","category":"Personality Themes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Medieval medicine believed four bodily fluids controlled personality. This gave English four core emotion words still used today — each with an unusual spelling pattern that spelling bees love.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>MELANCHOLY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> m-EH-l-uh-n-k-ah-l-ee\n<b>Spell it.</b> M · E · L · A · N · C · H · O · L · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> m-EH-l-uh-n-k-ah-l-ee\n<b>Syllables.</b> m · e · l · a · n · c · h · o · l · y\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [MEL=MEL] [an=AN] [kol=CHOL] [ee=Y]\n<b>Exception.</b> ch = /k/ (Greek origin signal!); final -y = /ee/; do NOT spell it melancholy with double-l: mel-AN-chol-y\n<b>Origin.</b> Greek\n<b>Root.</b> Greek melas = black + khole = bile","cards":[{"title":"The Four Humors","body":"Blood → sanguine (optimistic). Yellow bile → choleric (quick-tempered). Phlegm → phlegmatic (calm, unemotional). Black bile → melancholy (deeply sad). From a 2,000-year-old medical theory — still the best set of personality adjectives in English."},{"title":"Sanguine & Choleric","body":"Sanguine (SANG-gwin) from Latin sanguis = blood; the silent e at end. Choleric (KOL-er-ik) from Greek khole = bile; ch = /k/ (Greek signal). Blood brought joy; bile brought anger. Opposite types, opposite spelling origins."},{"title":"Phlegmatic — the Hardest Spelling","body":"From Greek phlegma = mucus. Phlegm alone = P-H-L-E-G-M (silent g). Phlegmatic = P-H-L-E-G-M-A-T-I-C (silent g again). Both the ph AND the silent g are Greek signals in one word."},{"title":"Positive Emotion Words","body":"Ebullient (ebullire = boil up) = bubbling with enthusiasm. Effervescent = lively like fizzy bubbles. Exuberant = overflowing with energy. Vivacious (vivax = lively) = attractively animated. Sanguine = optimistically cheerful."},{"title":"Calm & Neutral Emotions","body":"Apathetic (a- + pathos) = without feeling. Stoic (from the Stoa porch in Athens) = endures hardship without complaint. Imperturbable = impossible to upset. Equanimous = steadily even-tempered. Phlegmatic = so calm as to seem indifferent."}],"words":[{"w":"sanguine","def":"a blood-red color","ex":"Despite the team's difficult loss in the semifinals, the coach remained sanguine about their chances next season, telling reporters with a calm smile that every setback contains a valuable lesson.","say":"SA-nggwihn","hook":"SANGUINE is blood-red — the U-I-N-E at the end spells the color into your veins."},{"w":"choleric","def":"easily moved to anger; - H.G.Wells","ex":"men of the choleric type take to kicking and smashing","say":"KAH-ler-ihk","hook":"A CHOLERIC person is full of bile — ch + ol + eric, imagine an angry guy named Eric."},{"w":"phlegmatic","def":"is not easily excited to action","ex":"a phlegmatic...and certainly undemonstrative man","say":"f-l-eh-g-m-A-t-ih-k","hook":"PHLEGMATIC: the silent PH mirrors how phlegmatic people are — quiet and still, just like the silent letters"},{"w":"melancholy","def":"is a gloomy state of mind","ex":"growing more melancholy every hour","say":"m-EH-l-uh-n-k-ah-l-ee","hook":"MELANCHOLY: MELANcholy is not about a MELON — remember black (melan) + bile (choly), not fruit."},{"w":"ebullient","def":"joyously unrestrained","ex":"The ebullient crowd cheered and danced when their team scored the winning goal in overtime.","say":"ih-BUH-lyuhnt","hook":"An eBULLient person BULLS their way through a room bubbling with joy — double the 'l' like a boiling bubble."},{"w":"effervescent","def":"used of wines and waters; charged naturally or artificially with carbon dioxide","ex":"The effervescent new student bubbled with energy from the very first day, cracking jokes, complimenting everyone's artwork, and making the entire classroom feel lighter and more fun simply by walking through the door each morning.","say":"eh-f-ur-v-EH-s-uh-n-t","hook":"EFFERVescent = bubbles FERVOR-ing out — think of a soda bottle fizzing over."},{"w":"exuberant","def":"joyously unrestrained","ex":"The exuberant puppy bounded across the yard, leaping into the pile of autumn leaves and scattering them in every colorful direction with joyful abandon.","say":"ih-GZOO-ber-uhnt","hook":"EXUBERANT ends in -ANT: the exuberant ANT throws the most enthusiastic picnic."},{"w":"vivacious","def":"vigorous and animated","ex":"The vivacious host bounded onto the stage with a huge smile, instantly energizing the audience with her contagious enthusiasm.","say":"vuh-VAY-shuhs","hook":"VIVACious — full of VIVA (life)!"},{"w":"apathetic","def":"showing little or no emotion or animation","ex":"a woman who became active rather than apathetic as she grew older","say":"a-puh-THEH-tihk","hook":"Someone apathetic has NO PATHOS — the 'path' of feeling is blocked by the 'a' at the front."},{"w":"stoic","def":"a member of the ancient Greek school of philosophy founded by Zeno","ex":"a Stoic achieves happiness by submission to destiny","say":"STOH-ihk","hook":"A STOIC feels no pain — spelled simply s-t-o-i-c, as calmly as a stoic faces hardship."},{"w":"imperturbable","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"equanimous","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"vehement","def":"marked by extreme intensity of emotions or convictions; inclined to react violently; fervid","ex":"The defense attorney delivered a vehement argument, passionately insisting that the evidence was flawed and that her client deserved to walk free from the courtroom that very day.","say":"VEE-uh-muhnt","hook":"A VEHEMENT speaker shouts — remember the hidden HE: 'HE is VEHEMENT!'"},{"w":"ardent","def":"characterized by intense emotion","ex":"Maria was such an ardent fan of the local soccer team that she painted her face in team colors, arrived two hours early to every match, and memorized every player's statistics.","say":"AH-rduhnt","hook":"An ARDENT fan burns with passion — the fire is in the E: ardENt, not ardAnt."},{"w":"fervent","def":"characterized by intense emotion","ex":"Maya delivered a fervent speech about protecting the local river, her passionate voice rising and falling as she urged every community member to take immediate action.","say":"FUR-vuhnt","hook":"FervENT not fervANT — think of the INTENSE ENERGY boiling inside, E for Energy in the ending."},{"w":"fervid","def":"characterized by intense emotion","ex":"The young activist delivered a fervid speech about climate change that left the entire audience breathless, moved by the intensity of her passion and the urgency of her message.","say":"FUR-vuhd","hook":"FERVid feelings BURN VIDly — think 'vivid' heat inside you."},{"w":"impassioned","def":"characterized by intense emotion","ex":"The young activist delivered an impassioned speech at the town hall meeting, her voice trembling with emotion as she pleaded with city officials to protect the local wetlands from industrial development.","say":"ih-MPA-shuhnd","hook":"An imPASSIONed speech is full of PASSION — you can see passion right inside it."}]},{"title":"Wisdom & Foolishness — sap / sophos / stult","category":"Personality Themes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin sapientia = wisdom and Greek sophos = wise generate the intelligence vocabulary. The -acious/-acity cluster gives you character adjectives and their noun twins in one pattern.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PERSPICACIOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> per-spuh-KAY-shuhs\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · E · R · S · P · I · C · A · C · I · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> per-spuh-KAY-shuhs\n<b>Syllables.</b> per · spi · ca · cious\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [per=PER] [spih=SPI] [KAY=CA] [shus=CIOUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> -cac- not -cak-; noun twin is perspicACITY (same spelling, different stress); stress: per-spih-KAY-shus\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin perspicere = to see clearly, from per = through + specere = to l","cards":[{"title":"The Wisdom Scale","body":"Omniscient (knows everything) → sagacious (wise from experience) → perspicacious (sharply insightful) → sapient (genuinely wise) → prudent (wisely careful) → obtuse (slow to understand) → fatuous (smugly foolish) → vacuous (empty-headed). One scale, eight vocabulary words."},{"title":"The -acious → -acity Pattern","body":"Perspicacious/perspicacity, sagacious/sagacity, tenacious/tenacity, voracious/voracity, audacious/audacity, loquacious/loquacity. The rule is locked: drop -ious, add -ity. One spelling family unlocks twelve words."},{"title":"Foolishness Words","body":"Fatuous (fatuus = foolish) = smugly foolish. Vacuous (vacuus = empty) = empty-headed. Obtuse (obtusus = blunt) = slow to understand. Asinine (asinus = donkey) = extremely stupid. Inane = pointlessly silly. Puerile (puer = boy) = childishly silly."},{"title":"sophos- (Greek wisdom)","body":"Sophisticated = worldly wise. Sophomore (sophos + moros = fool) = a wise fool — a second-year student who thinks they know everything! Philosophy (philos = love + sophia) = love of wisdom. Sophistry = clever but misleading argument."},{"title":"The Knowing Roots","body":"Latin scire = to know: science, omniscient, conscience, prescient (knowing before). Greek gnosis = knowledge: agnostic (without certainty), prognosis (pro- + gnosis = knowing before = forecast), diagnosis (dia- = apart = identifying by analysis)."}],"words":[{"w":"perspicacious","def":"acutely insightful and wise","ex":"The perspicacious young detective noticed a tiny mud stain on the suspect's shoe that everyone else had overlooked.","say":"per-spuh-KAY-shuhs","hook":"PER-SPIC-acious: someone who sees (SPIC) through everything"},{"w":"sagacious","def":"showing acute mental discernment or being shrewd","ex":"much too perspicacious to be taken in by such a spurious argument","say":"suh-GAY-shus","hook":"A SAGE is wise; sagaCIOUS has SAGE inside it"},{"w":"sapient","def":"acutely insightful and wise","ex":"much too perspicacious to be taken in by such a spurious argument","say":"SAY-pee-int","hook":"SAPIENT — Homo sapiens means 'wise human,' so sapient means wise, just like our species name."},{"w":"omniscient","def":"infinitely wise","ex":"In many fantasy novels, the narrator is omniscient, able to reveal the secret thoughts of every character in the story.","say":"ah-MNIH-shuhnt","hook":"OMNI + SCIENT: SCIENT relates to SCIENCE (knowing) — omniscient knows ALL sciences"},{"w":"prudent","def":"careful and sensible; marked by sound judgment","ex":"It was prudent of the hikers to pack extra water and a detailed map before setting out on the long mountain trail, even though the weather forecast had promised a clear and sunny day.","say":"PROO-duhnt","hook":"A PRUDENT person is wise—end it with -ENT, not -ANT, just as wisdom is never aNTsy."},{"w":"obtuse","def":"of an angle; between 90 and 180 degrees","ex":"too obtuse to grasp the implications of his behavior","say":"ah-BTOOS","hook":"An obtuse angle is MORE than 90° and a dull person is MORE than slow — both are blunt, spell it ob-TUSE like a blunt fuse!"},{"w":"fatuous","def":"devoid of intelligence","ex":"His fatuous comment about the moon being made of cheese made everyone in the science class groan.","say":"FA-chuh-wuhs","hook":"A FATUOUS remark is FAT with foolishness — no extra E, just pure empty fat."},{"w":"vacuous","def":"Completely empty of meaning, substance, or intelligence; lacking serious thought or depth.","ex":"The vacuous reality show offered nothing educational or meaningful, featuring contestants who spent thirty minutes debating which shade of pink best represented their personal brand without ever saying anything remotely interesting or thoughtful.","say":"v-A-k-y-oo-uh-s","hook":"VACUOUS means full of emptiness—no double-C, just one C: a truly hollow word for hollow minds."},{"w":"asinine","def":"devoid of intelligence","ex":"Everyone in the meeting thought it was asinine to cancel the field trip over such a minor issue.","say":"A-suh-neyen","hook":"ASININE has nine letters and refers to acting like a donkey — 'an ASS IN INE stupidity'."},{"w":"sophisticated","def":"make less natural or innocent","ex":"After spending a summer in Paris, she returned with a sophisticated taste for art that impressed even her teachers.","say":"suh-FIH-stuh-kay-tihd","hook":"SOPHI-stic-ated: a SOPHIST (wise one) is sophisticated"},{"w":"sophomore","def":"a second-year undergraduate","ex":"As a sophomore, Delia finally felt comfortable navigating the large high school campus, knowing where every classroom was and understanding the unspoken social rules that had confused her during her first year.","say":"SAH-fmawr","hook":"A SOPHOMORE is a 'wise fool'—sopho+MORE: you know MORE but still act foolish, so keep that silent 'o' in sophoMORE."},{"w":"sophistry","def":"a deliberately invalid argument displaying ingenuity in reasoning in the hope of deceiving someone","ex":"The debate judge warned that clever sophistry would not substitute for real evidence and honest reasoning.","say":"SAW-fih-stree","hook":"A SOPHIST tries to TRY to trick you with clever-sounding lies—sophisTRY ends in -TRY, not -TERY."},{"w":"perspicacity","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"sagacity","def":"the mental ability to understand and discriminate between relations","ex":"The elder's sagacity helped the community solve problems that had stumped even the youngest scholars.","say":"suh-GAS-ih-tee","hook":"SAGA + city — a wise person's saga fills a whole city of knowledge: s-a-g-a-c-i-t-y."},{"w":"tenacious","def":"means holding fast","ex":"Despite failing her driving test twice, Leila remained tenacious in her determination to pass, practicing parallel parking every single evening until she could execute it smoothly, confidently, and without a single cone knocked over.","say":"t-uh-n-AY-sh-uh-s","hook":"Tenacious holds fast to every letter — especially that sneaky I before OUS: ten-A-CI-OUS."},{"w":"voracious","def":"excessively eager avid insatiable","ex":"a rapacious divorcee on the prowl","say":"v-aw-r-AY-sh-uh-s","hook":"VORACIOUS: a VORACious eater devours — remember V-O-R-A-C-I-O-U-S, no T, just a ravenous C gobbling the word up."},{"w":"audacious","def":"invulnerable to fear or intimidation","ex":"The audacious climber scaled the sheer cliff face without ropes, impressing everyone who watched from below.","say":"ah-DAY-shuhs","hook":"AUDacious people DARE to be heard — like a loud AUDIO blast"},{"w":"agnostic","def":"someone who is doubtful or noncommittal about something","ex":"My uncle describes himself as an agnostic because he believes it is impossible to know for certain whether any god exists.","say":"a-GNAH-stihk","hook":"An AGNOSTIC is 'a' person who does 'NOT' claim to KNOW — silent 'g' like in 'gnosis.'"},{"w":"prognosis","def":"a prediction about how something (as the weather) will develop","ex":"The doctor gave an encouraging prognosis, saying the patient should fully recover within six weeks.","say":"prah-GNOH-suhs","hook":"A proGNOSis is what the doctor KNOWS before the outcome — one 's' in the middle, end in '-sis'."},{"w":"diagnosis","def":"identifying the nature or cause of some phenomenon","ex":"After weeks of confusing symptoms, the doctor finally delivered a diagnosis that allowed the patient to begin the right treatment.","say":"deye-uh-GNOH-suhs","hook":"A diagnosis is KNOWLEDGE (gnosis) gained THROUGH (dia) examination — one S, not two!"}]},{"title":"Courage & Fear — aud / fort / tim / phob","category":"Personality Themes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin audere = to dare, fortis = strong, and timor = fear create an elegant bravery vocabulary. Greek phobos = fear adds the medical compound fear words — all long, all appearing in bees.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>AUDACIOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ah-DAY-shuhs\n<b>Spell it.</b> A · U · D · A · C · I · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> ah-DAY-shuhs\n<b>Syllables.</b> aa · dey · shah · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [aw=AU] [DAY=DA] [shus=CIOUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> from Latin audax = bold/daring NOT from audire = hear — same aud- prefix, two different Latin roots\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin 'audax' = bold, daring, from 'audere' = to dare","cards":[{"title":"Courage Root — aud-","body":"Latin audere = to dare. Audacious = daringly bold. Audacity = boldness, sometimes shocking nerve. ⚠️ BEE TRAP: audacious (daring) shares aud- with audible (hearing, from audire) — two different Latin roots with identical prefix. The definition tells you which is which."},{"title":"fort- = Strong","body":"Latin fortis = strong. Fortitude = inner strength. Fortify = make strong. Comfortable (com- + fort) = made strong and at ease together. Effort (ex- + fort) = force pushed outward. Fortissimo (Italian music) = very loud/strong. One root explains a fort, comfort, effort, and a musical term."},{"title":"Fearfulness — tim-","body":"Latin timor = fear. Timid = easily frightened. Timorous = full of trembling fear. Intimidate (in- + timid + -ate) = put fear into someone. ⚠️ Temerity (temere = recklessly) = reckless boldness — confusingly the OPPOSITE of timidity. A classic bee trap."},{"title":"phob- Family (Greek)","body":"Greek phobos = fear. Agoraphobia (agora = marketplace) = fear of open/crowded spaces. Claustrophobia (claustrum = enclosed) = fear of enclosed spaces. Xenophobia (xenos = stranger) = fear of foreigners. Triskaidekaphobia = fear of the number 13 — the longest common fear word."},{"title":"Brave vs Reckless","body":"Valiant = showing genuine courage. Intrepid (in- + trepidus = trembling) = fearless. Dauntless = not daunted. Temerity = reckless boldness (lacks wisdom). Audacity = daring boldness (can be admirable). Knowing the distinction wins vocabulary rounds."}],"words":[{"w":"audacious","def":"invulnerable to fear or intimidation","ex":"The audacious climber scaled the sheer cliff face without ropes, impressing everyone who watched from below.","say":"ah-DAY-shuhs","hook":"AUDacious people DARE to be heard — like a loud AUDIO blast"},{"w":"audacity","def":"fearless daring","ex":"he had the audacity to question my decision","say":"ah-DA-suh-tee","hook":"AUDACITy: it takes AUDACI-TY — bold enough to drop an 's' that doesn't belong."},{"w":"fortitude","def":"strength of mind that enables one to endure adversity with courage","ex":"It took tremendous fortitude for the young climber to push through the blizzard and reach the summit.","say":"FAW-rtih-tood","hook":"A person with fortITUDE has the ATTITUDE to endure — both end in TUDE."},{"w":"fortify","def":"make strong or stronger","ex":"This exercise will strengthen your upper body","say":"FAW-rtih-feye","hook":"FORTIFY = FORTI + FY — think FORT + I + FY: a fort I will fortiFY with an I not an E."},{"w":"comfortable","def":"providing or experiencing physical well-being or relief (`comfy' is informal)","ex":"After hiking through the muddy trail for six exhausting hours, the campers were finally comfortable sitting beside the warm fire, wrapped in dry blankets and sipping hot cocoa.","say":"KUH-mfer-tuh-buhl","hook":"COMFORTABLE has COMFORT right inside it — if you can spell comfort, just add ABLE."},{"w":"effort","def":"earnest and conscientious activity intended to do or accomplish something","ex":"made an effort to cover all the reading material","say":"EH-fert","hook":"EFFORT takes FORT-itude — you must be FORT-strong (ef-FORT) to push through the task."},{"w":"timid","def":"people who are fearful and cautious","ex":"whitewater rafting is not for the timid","say":"TIH-mihd","hook":"A TIMID mouse hides with just one 'm' — too scared to double up."},{"w":"timorous","def":"timid by nature or revealing timidity","ex":"timorous little mouse","say":"TIH-mer-uhs","hook":"A TIMOROUS person is full of TIMOR (fear) — spot the Latin root hiding inside."},{"w":"intimidate","def":"to make fearful.","ex":"Her boss intimidates her","say":"ih-n-t-IH-m-ih-d-ay-t","hook":"To INTIMIDATE someone, you put TIMID in them — you make them timid!"},{"w":"temerity","def":"excessive confidence or boldness; audacious daring, often in the face of danger or opposition","ex":"Priya had the temerity to challenge the reigning chess champion despite having played for only six months.","say":"tuh-MEH-ruh-tee","hook":"teMERity — MERE boldness pushed too far"},{"w":"agoraphobia","def":"a morbid fear of open spaces or of being alone in a public place where escape might be difficult","ex":"Because of her agoraphobia, the woman rarely left her apartment and felt her heart race at the thought of walking through a crowded mall.","say":"uh-gaw-ruh-FOH-bee-uh","hook":"AGORA (marketplace) + PHOBIA — fear of the open marketplace"},{"w":"claustrophobia","def":"a morbid fear of being closed in a confined space","ex":"Zara's claustrophobia made riding the crowded elevator feel like a terrifying adventure every single morning.","say":"klaw-struh-FOH-bee-uh","hook":"CLAUS(TRO) = locked door + PHOBIA = fear: fear of locked spaces"},{"w":"xenophobia","def":"a fear of foreigners or strangers","ex":"The community worked hard to overcome xenophobia by hosting cultural festivals that celebrated their diverse neighbors.","say":"zeh-nuh-FOH-bee-uh","hook":"XENO means stranger, PHOBIA means fear — xenophobia is fear of strangers, spelled just as it sounds: x-e-n-o-p-h-o-b-i-a."},{"w":"triskaidekaphobia","def":"is a fear of the number 13","ex":"Because of his triskaidekaphobia, he refused to stay in room 13 at any hotel he ever visited.","say":"tris-ky-dek-uh-FOH-bee-uh","hook":"TRISKAIDEKA spells out 3+and+10=13—fear the KAI in the middle!"},{"w":"valiant","def":"having or showing valor","ex":"The valiant soldier crawled through enemy fire to rescue his wounded comrade.","say":"VA-lyuhnt","hook":"VALIANT — VALOR and VALIANT share the same root: strength."},{"w":"intrepid","def":"invulnerable to fear or intimidation","ex":"The intrepid young journalist traveled alone through four war zones to document the stories of civilians whose lives had been upended by a conflict the rest of the world had largely ignored.","say":"ih-NTREH-puhd","hook":"An intrepid hero doesn't TREMBLE — trepid means trembling, and in- means NOT, so no shaking!"},{"w":"dauntless","def":"invulnerable to fear or intimidation","ex":"The dauntless young climber pressed on through howling wind and driving sleet, refusing to turn back even as the mountain's summit disappeared behind a wall of dark, churning storm clouds.","say":"DAWNT-les","hook":"Dauntless heroes have LESS fear — the '-less' at the end means without daunting!"}]},{"title":"Kindness & Cruelty — ben / mal / clem","category":"Personality Themes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin bene = well/good and malus = bad/evil are the fundamental moral roots in English. Swapping the prefix flips the meaning — know one side of every pair and you know both.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>MALEVOLENT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> muh-LEH-vuh-luhnt\n<b>Spell it.</b> M · A · L · E · V · O · L · E · N · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> muh-LEH-vuh-luhnt\n<b>Syllables.</b> ma · lev · o · lent\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [muh=MA] [LEV=LEV] [uh=O] [lent=LENT]\n<b>Exception.</b> mal- = bad (Latin); -vol- = wish (from velle); -ent not -ant; full etymology: wishing evil on others\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin male = badly + volens = wishing (from velle = to wish)","cards":[{"title":"The ben-/bene- Root (good)","body":"Latin bene = well. Benevolent (bene + velle = wish well) = wishing good for others. Benefactor (bene + facere) = one who does good. Benign (bene + genus = kind) = gentle and harmless. Benediction (bene + dicere) = a spoken blessing."},{"title":"The mal- Root (bad)","body":"Latin malus = bad. Malevolent = wishing harm. Malfeasance (mal- + facere = do wrong) = official wrongdoing. Malicious = intending harm. Malignant = growing harmfully. Maladroit (mal- + French adroit = skillful) = clumsy. The prefix paints everything it touches as bad."},{"title":"The Perfect Pairs","body":"Benevolent ↔ malevolent. Beneficent ↔ maleficent. Benign ↔ malignant. Benediction ↔ malediction. These are structural opposites — swap ben- for mal- and the meaning reverses. In a bee, knowing one word of each pair gives you the other for free."},{"title":"clem- = Merciful","body":"Latin clemens = mild, merciful. Clemency = merciful treatment. Clement = mild (weather or character). Inclement (in- + clement) = harsh, stormy. Clemency appears in legal vocabulary: appeal for clemency = asking for a lighter sentence."},{"title":"Malaise & Malaria — Etymology Reveals History","body":"Malaise (mal- + French aise = ease) = general feeling of being unwell. Malaria (mal- + Italian aria = air) = bad air — Italians believed this disease came from bad swamp air before mosquitoes were discovered. Etymology IS history."}],"words":[{"w":"benevolent","def":"intending or showing kindness","ex":"a benevolent society","say":"buh-NEH-vuh-luhnt","hook":"A BENEvolent person wishes you WELL — bene means 'well' in Latin, spelled B-E-N-E."},{"w":"benefactor","def":"a person who helps people or institutions (especially with financial help)","ex":"An anonymous benefactor donated enough money to rebuild the school library after it was destroyed in the flood.","say":"BEH-nuh-fa-kter","hook":"A benefACTOR is an ACTOR who does good deeds — remember the -OR ending like 'actor.'"},{"w":"benign","def":"is having a kindly disposition","ex":"The doctor reassured the worried family that the small growth was completely benign, explaining that it posed no threat to the patient's health and required no further treatment whatsoever.","say":"b-ih-n-AY-n","hook":"beNIGN ends in -IGN like 'sign' — a benign tumor is a good SIGN, spelled G-N."},{"w":"benediction","def":"the act of praying for divine protection","ex":"The priest offered a warm benediction at the end of the ceremony, sending the congregation home with words of peace and hope.","say":"beh-nuh-DIH-kshuhn","hook":"A BENEficial DICTION: a benediction is literally 'well-spoken' words of blessing."},{"w":"beneficent","def":"doing or producing good","ex":"The beneficent billionaire donated millions of dollars to build new schools and hospitals in impoverished communities around the world.","say":"beh-nuh-FIH-shuhnt","hook":"BENE (good) + FICENT — bene-FICENT does good things, like magnificent but good"},{"w":"malevolent","def":"wishing or appearing to wish evil to others; arising from intense ill will or hatred","ex":"The malevolent sorcerer cast a spell that turned the entire village's crops to ash overnight.","say":"muh-LEH-vuh-luhnt","hook":"MALEvolent = MALE (bad) + VOLENT (wishing) — wishing badly; ends in -lent not -lant"},{"w":"malfeasance","def":"is wrongdoing by a public official","ex":"The city treasurer was removed from office after investigators uncovered evidence of blatant malfeasance.","say":"m-a-l-f-EE-z-uh-n-s","hook":"MALFEASance — a bad official does bad FEATS; end it with -ance, not -ence."},{"w":"malicious","def":"marked by evil intention","ex":"The malicious rumor spread through the school within hours, and the damage it caused to the student's reputation took weeks of honest conversations to undo and repair completely.","say":"m-uh-l-IH-sh-uh-s","hook":"One L of malice is enough to be MALICIOUS — only one L: M-A-L-I-C-I-O-U-S."},{"w":"malignant","def":"tending to produce death or deterioration used in medicine","ex":"The doctor delivered the frightening news that the tumor was malignant and would require immediate treatment.","say":"m-uh-l-IH-g-n-uh-n-t","hook":"A MALIGNANT tumor is not gentle — remember the ANT at the end marching through: M-A-L-I-G-N-A-N-T."},{"w":"maladroit","def":"Lacking skill, dexterity, or cleverness; clumsy or awkward in movement, thought, or social situations, often causing embarrassing or unfortunate results due to poor judgment or coordination.","ex":"a maladroit movement of his hand caused the car to swerve","say":"ma-luh-DROYT","hook":"MAL-adroit: someone who does it all WRONG has no DROIT (right/skill)."},{"w":"clemency","def":"mercy and lenience shown toward someone it is within one's power to punish; also mildness of weather","ex":"The defendant's lawyer pleaded for clemency, arguing that her client had already suffered enough and deserved a second chance.","say":"KLEH-muh-nsee","hook":"CLEMENCY: think of a CLEMENT (mild) judge — CLEMENt+CY = mercy."},{"w":"clement","def":"(of weather or climate) physically mild","ex":"The farmers were grateful for the clement weather during harvest season, as the mild temperatures and gentle breezes made it easy to work long hours in the fields.","say":"KLEH-muhnt","hook":"CLEMENT weather is mild — think of a KIND person named Clem who is gentle and MILD-mannered."},{"w":"inclement","def":"(of weather or climate) severe","ex":"the harsh sentence of an inclement judge","say":"ih-NKLEH-muhnt","hook":"Inclement weather is not CLEMENT (mild) — the opposite of clemency from the sky."},{"w":"malaise","def":"a general feeling of physical discomfort, illness, or mental unease","ex":"After staying up until 2 a.m. studying, Elena dragged herself to school feeling a heavy malaise that lasted all day.","say":"ma-LAYZ","hook":"MALAISE — MAL means BAD and you feel bad when you have malaise"},{"w":"malaria","def":"is a disease characterized by chills or fever caused by the bite of a mosquito","ex":"Aid workers distributed mosquito nets to the villages to help prevent the spread of malaria.","say":"m-uh-l-EH-r-ee-uh","hook":"MALARIA = MALA (bad) ARIA — bad air once thought to cause this fever; sing the 'a' in aria!"},{"w":"maleficent","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"malediction","def":"the act of calling down a curse that invokes evil (and usually serves as an insult)","ex":"he suffered the imprecations of the mob","say":"mal-eh-DIK-shun","hook":"MALE (bad) + DICTION (words): bad words spoken as a curse — opposite of benediction."}]},{"title":"Social & Solitary — greg / anthrop / soci / mis","category":"Personality Themes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin grex = flock and Greek anthropos = human being create vocabulary about how people relate to society. These are some of the richest theme words in English.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>GREGARIOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> gruh-GEH-ree-uhs\n<b>Spell it.</b> G · R · E · G · A · R · I · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> gruh-GEH-ree-uhs\n<b>Syllables.</b> grah · geh · riy · ah · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [gruh=GRE] [GAIR=GAR] [ee=I] [us=OUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> -gar- not -gare-; from Latin grex/gregis = flock; -ious suffix; stress on second syllable gruh-GAIR-ee-us\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin grex/gregis = flock + -arious = tending to","cards":[{"title":"The greg- Root (flock)","body":"Latin grex = flock. Gregarious = loves being in groups like sheep. Congregate (con- + greg-) = flock together. Segregate (se- = apart) = separate from the flock. Aggregate (ad- + greg-) = gathered into a total. ⚠️ Egregious (e- = out of + greg-) = standing out from the flock — outstandingly BAD."},{"title":"mis- = Hatred (Greek misos)","body":"Greek misos = hatred. Misanthrope (misos + anthropos) = hates humanity. Misogynist (misos + gyne = woman) = hates women. Misogamist (misos + gamos = marriage) = hates marriage. ⚠️ This mis- is GREEK (hatred) — completely different from LATIN mis- (wrongly). Same spelling, entirely different origin."},{"title":"anthrop- = Human Being","body":"Greek anthropos = human. Anthropology = study of humans. Philanthropist (philos = love + anthropos) = lover of humanity. Misanthrope = hater of humanity. Anthropomorphic = giving human form to non-humans. Anthropocentric = placing humans at the center of everything."},{"title":"soci- = Companion","body":"Latin socius = companion. Sociable = friendly and sociable. Associate = join as a companion. Dissociate = separate from. Convivial (con- + vivere = live together) = friendly and lively at a gathering. Affable (af- + fari = speak to) = easy and pleasant to talk with."},{"title":"The Loner Words","body":"Misanthrope = hates people. Solitary (solus = alone) = prefers being alone. Recluse = withdraws from society. Hermit (Greek eremos = desert) = lives alone. Anchorite = withdraws for religious seclusion. Note: a loner avoids people; a misanthrope hates them — critically different."}],"words":[{"w":"gregarious","def":"(of animals) tending to form a group with others of the same species","ex":"gregarious bird species","say":"gruh-GEH-ree-uhs","hook":"A GREGARIOUS person flocks with others — greg = flock in Latin, so spell it g-r-e-g, then -arious like 'various.'"},{"w":"egregious","def":"is extraordinary in some bad way","ex":"The referee made such an egregious error during the championship game that even fans from the winning team shook their heads in disbelief and demanded an instant replay review.","say":"ih-g-r-EE-j-uh-s","hook":"EGREGIOUS has GREG in the middle — imagine Greg the bad sheep who stood so far OUT from the flock his error was egregious."},{"w":"congregate","def":"come together, usually for a purpose","ex":"The crowds congregated in front of the Vatican on Christmas Eve","say":"KAH-nggruh-gayt","hook":"People conGREGate in a GREAT group — GREG leads the flock!"},{"w":"segregate","def":"someone who is or has been segregated","ex":"This neighborhood is segregated","say":"SEH-gruh-gayt","hook":"To SEGREGATE is to separate the flock — SE+GREGATE, think 'Greg ATE alone, apart from the group.'"},{"w":"aggregate","def":"the whole amount","ex":"In the aggregate, the students raised over two thousand dollars for the school's new science lab.","say":"A-gruh-guht","hook":"AGGREGATE gathers a flock — DOUBLE G + GREG (like congregate) — the whole herd AGGREGATES."},{"w":"misanthrope","def":"someone who dislikes people in general","ex":"The grumpy misanthrope refused all party invitations and preferred to stay home alone.","say":"MIH-suh-nthrohp","hook":"A MISerable ANTHRO-PE-rson hates all people — 'anthro' sounds like 'and throw,' as if they'd throw everyone away."},{"w":"misogynist","def":"a misanthrope who dislikes women in particular","ex":"The reformer challenged the misogynist who believed women should have no voice in government or education.","say":"MIH-zuh-jih-nihst","hook":"A misoGYNIST hates women — end with -IST like a specialist in hatred, not -yst."},{"w":"misogamist","def":"a person who hates marriage","ex":"The grumpy misogamist refused to wed.","say":"mih-SOG-uh-mist","hook":"from Greek misos 'hatred' + gamos 'marriage'"},{"w":"anthropology","def":"the social science that studies the origins and social relationships of human beings","ex":"Her fascination with ancient cultures led her to major in anthropology at the university.","say":"a-nthruh-PAH-luh-jee","hook":"ANTHRO-PO-LOGY: 'a POLO player studying humans' — remember the hidden POLO in anthroPoLOgy."},{"w":"philanthropist","def":"someone who makes charitable donations intended to increase human well-being","ex":"The philanthropist donated enough money to build a new library for every school in the district.","say":"fuh-LA-nthruh-puhst","hook":"A philanthropIST puts people on his LIST of those to help — no H after anthrop!"},{"w":"anthropomorphic","def":"suggesting human characteristics for animals or inanimate things","ex":"The animated film featured anthropomorphic animals who spoke, wore clothes, and faced very human problems.","say":"a-nthruh-puh-MAW-rfihk","hook":"MORPHIC means shaped — anthropoMORPHIC means shaped like a human; think of a MORPHing robot taking human form."},{"w":"anthropocentric","def":"human-centered","ex":"our anthropocentric view of the world","say":"a-nthruh-puh-SEH-ntrihk","hook":"ANTHROPO-CENTRIC: humans (anthropo) at the CENTER (centri) — spell it like you're centering yourself: no K at the end!"},{"w":"sociable","def":"a party of people assembled to promote sociability and communal activity","ex":"Because she was naturally sociable and genuinely curious about people, Maya made friends easily at her new school, striking up conversations with classmates during lunch on her very first day.","say":"SOH-shuh-buhl","hook":"A SOCIABLE person is SOCI-ABLE to make friends—drop the E from society before adding ABLE."},{"w":"associate","def":"a person who joins with others in some activity or endeavor","ex":"he had to consult his associate before continuing","say":"uh-SOH-see-uht","hook":"An ASSOCIATE is a SOCIAL companion — find SOC-I inside, then add -ATE at the end."},{"w":"convivial","def":"means friendly or agreeable","ex":"a convivial atmosphere at the reunion","say":"k-uh-n-v-IH-v-ee-uh-l","hook":"conVIVIal people are VIVID and ALIVE together — spot VIV meaning life"},{"w":"affable","def":"friendly, easy to talk to, and pleasant in manner","ex":"Our new neighbor was so affable that within minutes of meeting her, we felt as if we had known her for years.","say":"A-fuh-buhl","hook":"AFfable people are FABulous to talk to — 'FAB' is right in the middle"},{"w":"recluse","def":"one who lives in solitude","ex":"After years of fame, the retired actress became a recluse who rarely left her mountain cabin.","say":"rih-KLOOS","hook":"A recluse is CLOSED off (re-CLUSE) from the world."},{"w":"hermit","def":"one retired from society for religious reasons","ex":"The old hermit lived alone in a cave on the mountainside, spending his days in prayer and quiet contemplation.","say":"HUR-muht","hook":"A HERMIT lives alone with only one T for company."}]},{"title":"in- / im- / il- / ir- (not / without)","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin in- = not. It assimilates — changes shape — to match whatever consonant follows. This doubling is both a spelling signal and a meaning signal: the doubled letter reveals the hidden prefix.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>IRREFUTABLE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ih-ruh-FYOO-tuh-buhl\n<b>Spell it.</b> I · R · R · E · F · U · T · A · B · L · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> ih-ruh-FYOO-tuh-buhl\n<b>Syllables.</b> ih · rah · fyuw · tah · bah · l\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [ih=IR] [REF=REF] [yuh=U] [tuh=TA] [bul=BLE]\n<b>Exception.</b> double-R from in+r assimilation; -able not -ible; stress on second syllable ih-REF-yuh-tuh-bul\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin in+refutare = not able to be refuted, from re+futare = to beat b","cards":[{"title":"The Assimilation Rule","body":"in- = not. Before l → il-: illegal, illegible, illicit. Before m/b/p → im-: impossible, immoral, impeccable. Before r → ir-: irregular, irrefutable, irrevocable. Before everything else → in-: insane, inimical, inexorable. The doubled first letter of the root IS the spelling signal."},{"title":"High-Value im- Words","body":"Impeccable (im- + pecca = sin) = without flaw. Imperturbable = cannot be disturbed. Impecunious (im- + pecunia = money) = penniless. Impetuous = without restraint, rash. Implacable (im- + placare = appease) = cannot be calmed or satisfied. Each carries \"not/without\" into rich vocabulary."},{"title":"High-Value in- Words","body":"Inexorable (in- + exorare = beg out of) = cannot be moved by pleading = relentless. Inimical (in- + amicus = friend) = not friendly = hostile. Inscrutable = cannot be understood. Innuendo (in- + nuendo = nodding toward) = an indirect suggestion. Ineffable = too great to express in words."},{"title":"il- and ir- Words","body":"Illicit (il- + licitus = allowed) = not permitted. ⚠️ Confusable with elicit (to draw out) — completely different word! Illusory = not real. Irascible = quickly angered. Irreverent = not respectful. Irremediable = cannot be fixed. Irrevocable = cannot be called back."},{"title":"The Dangerous Exception","body":"in- can ALSO mean \"into/toward\" (not just \"not\"): inflammable = catches fire easily — NOT fireproof! Invaluable = so valuable it cannot be measured = priceless, NOT worthless. Context and origin tell you which. When uncertain: get the definition before spelling."}],"words":[{"w":"impeccable","def":"is faultless or flawless","ex":"The young chef presented a dish with impeccable attention to detail, each garnish placed so precisely and every flavor so perfectly balanced that the judges sat in stunned, appreciative silence.","say":"ih-m-p-EH-k-uh-b-uh-l","hook":"ImPECCAble has no PECCADILLO — peccABLE means 'can sin,' so imPECCAble means flawless."},{"w":"imperturbable","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"impecunious","def":"not having enough money to pay for necessities","ex":"The impecunious student survived on peanut butter sandwiches because he could barely afford groceries after paying rent.","say":"im-puh-KYOO-nee-us","hook":"IMPECUNious means no PECUNIA (money) — a PECULIAR person with no PECUN-iary funds spells it with -IOUS, not -EOUS."},{"w":"impetuous","def":"is characterized by sudden or rash action","ex":"a hotheaded decision","say":"ih-m-p-EH-ch-w-uh-s","hook":"Impetuous behavior is full of force — end with the full '-uous,' not just '-os.'"},{"w":"implacable","def":"incapable of being placated","ex":"The implacable storm battered the coast for three days, ignoring every weather forecaster's hope that it would weaken.","say":"ih-MPLA-kuh-buhl","hook":"IM(not)+PLAC(placate)+ABLE: impossible to PLACATE"},{"w":"inexorable","def":"is unyielding or unalterable","ex":"No matter how many times the students begged for more time, the inexorable approach of the test deadline continued, and their teacher reminded them calmly that no extension would be granted.","say":"ih-n-EH-k-s-ur-uh-b-uh-l","hook":"INEXORABLE ends in -ABLE — you'll NEVER be ABLE to beg your way to changing that ending."},{"w":"inimical","def":"not friendly","ex":"The freezing temperatures were inimical to the survival of the tropical plants left outside overnight.","say":"ih-NIH-mih-kuhl","hook":"INIMICal sounds like 'enemy'—because it means exactly that."},{"w":"inscrutable","def":"is incapable of being investigated or analyzed","ex":"the new insurance policy is written without cryptic or mysterious terms","say":"ih-n-s-k-r-OO-t-uh-b-uh-l","hook":"INSCRUTable cannot be SCRUtinized — find SCRU in both words and remember just one T."},{"w":"innuendo","def":"is an indirect intimation about a person usually of a derogatory nature","ex":"The rival candidate's speech was full of innuendo, hinting at wrongdoing without ever making a direct accusation.","say":"ih-n-y-oo-EH-n-d-oh","hook":"An INNUENDO sneaks IN with a nudge — double-N nudges you twice before you notice the hint."},{"w":"ineffable","def":"defying expression or description","ex":"Standing at the edge of the Grand Canyon, Maya was struck by an ineffable sense of wonder she could not put into words.","say":"ih-NEH-fuh-buhl","hook":"INEFFable feelings are too big to FABricate into words."},{"w":"illicit","def":"is not legally permitted","ex":"an illicit association with his secretary","say":"ih-l-IH-s-uh-t","hook":"ILLICIT has two L's — doubly forbidden; find LICIT (permitted) inside and slap IL- in front."},{"w":"irascible","def":"is easily provoked to anger","ex":"a hotheaded commander","say":"ih-r-A-s-ih-b-uh-l","hook":"IRASCible people ERASE their calm in an instant of anger."},{"w":"irrevocable","def":"incapable of being retracted or revoked","ex":"Once the treaty was signed, the agreement was irrevocable, and neither country could back out without consequences.","say":"ih-REH-vuh-kuh-buhl","hook":"Irrevocable: you cannot RE-VOKE (call back) the decision — it's gone forever."},{"w":"immutable","def":"not subject or susceptible to change or variation in form or quality or nature","ex":"the view of that time was that all species were immutable, created by God","say":"ih-MYOO-tuh-buhl","hook":"imMUTable has no E before -able because it CANNOT CHANGE its spelling — MUTe things don't speak up to add extra letters."},{"w":"incomprehensible","def":"incapable of being explained or accounted for","ex":"The ancient manuscript was so damaged that its symbols were completely incomprehensible to even the most experienced historians.","say":"ih-ngkah-mpruh-HEH-nsih-buhl","hook":"Can you HENS-ibly explain it? If not, it's incompreHENSible!"},{"w":"indelible","def":"cannot be removed or erased","ex":"The vivid memories of that extraordinary summer trip to the mountains left an indelible impression on the young girl's mind, one so deeply engraved that she could still recall every color and smell decades later as an adult.","say":"ih-NDEH-lih-buhl","hook":"An inDELible mark won't let you DELETE it — keep 'del' from 'delete' in the middle."},{"w":"irrefutable","def":"impossible to deny or disprove","ex":"incontrovertible proof of the defendant's innocence","say":"ih-ruh-FYOO-tuh-buhl","hook":"IRREFUTable: no E before -able. The argument is so strong you cannot REFUTE it — ir+REFUT+able."},{"w":"illusory","def":"based on or having the nature of an illusion","ex":"illusive hopes of finding a better job","say":"ih-LOO-ser-ee","hook":"ILLUSORY ends in -ory not -ary — the 'o' is the ghost letter that seems to disappear."}]},{"title":"un- (not / reverse action)","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"easy","concept":"Old English/Latin un- = not (before adjectives) or reverse the action of (before verbs). The same two letters, two completely different jobs — word class determines meaning.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>UNCONSCIONABLE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> uh-n-k-AH-n-sh-uh-n-uh-b-uh-l\n<b>Spell it.</b> U · N · C · O · N · S · C · I · O · N · A · B · L · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> uh-n-k-AH-n-sh-uh-n-uh-b-uh-l\n<b>Syllables.</b> u · n · c · o · n · s · c · i · o · n · a · b · l · e\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [un=UN] [KON=CON] [shuh=SCION] [uh=A] [bul=BLE]\n<b>Exception.</b> -scion- = /shun/ from Latin conscientia; -able not -ible; stress on second syllable un-KON-shuh-nuh-bul\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin conscientia = moral sense (con=with + scire=know)","cards":[{"title":"Two Jobs","body":"un- before an adjective = \"not\": unkempt (not combed), unrequited (not returned), unprecedented (not before done). un- before a verb = \"reverse\": undo, unwrap, unravel. The same two letters — word class determines which meaning applies."},{"title":"High-Value un- Adjectives","body":"Unkempt (un- + kempt = combed). Unfettered (un- + fetter = chain) = not restrained. Unimpeachable = beyond reproach. Unscrupulous = without moral principles. Unwieldy = hard to handle. Unconscionable = shockingly unethical."},{"title":"Spelling Signal — Double-N","body":"When un- precedes a root starting with n, you get double-n: unnecessary = U-N-N-E-C-E-S-S-A-R-Y. Unnatural = U-N-N-A-T-U-R-A-L. Unnerve = U-N-N-E-R-V-E. The first n is the prefix; the second is the root. Not a doubling rule — just prefix meeting root."},{"title":"un- vs in-","body":"Both mean \"not\" but: un- is Old English/Germanic; in- is Latin. Unhappy (un- + Germanic). Infelicitous (in- + Latin felix = happy). The question \"What language does this word come from?\" at the microphone helps — Latin-origin words more often use in- negation, Germanic-origin words use un-."},{"title":"Classic Bee un- Words","body":"Unequivocal = not ambiguous. Unfathomable = cannot be fathomed/understood. Unprecedented = not before existing. Unrequited = love not returned. Unimpeachable = beyond any challenge. All negations of strong adjectives — and all with the simple, reliable U-N prefix."}],"words":[{"w":"unkempt","def":"is disheveled or messy","ex":"After hiking for three days through the muddy forest trail without a mirror or comb, the explorer arrived at camp looking completely unkempt, with tangled hair and dirt-streaked clothes.","say":"uh-n-k-EH-m-p-t","hook":"KEMPT means combed — UN-kempt is the opposite of neat."},{"w":"unconscionable","def":"means unscrupulous or not guided by conscience","ex":"a conscienceless villain","say":"uh-n-k-AH-n-sh-uh-n-uh-b-uh-l","hook":"UN + CONSCIENCE + ABLE: not able to be guided by conscience"},{"w":"unrequited","def":"is not returned or reciprocated","ex":"unrequited (unanswered) love","say":"uh-n-r-ee-k-w-AY-t-ih-d","hook":"QUIT has only one T — unreQUITed love means the other person QUIT on you without doubling their effort."},{"w":"unprecedented","def":"having no precedent; novel","ex":"an unprecedented expansion in population and industry","say":"uh-NPREH-sih-deh-ntihd","hook":"unPRECEDented: no PRECEDE came before it — keep PRECE-D-E-N-T inside."},{"w":"unfettered","def":"not bound by shackles and chains","ex":"With summer stretching ahead of her, Priya felt unfettered and free to pursue every creative project she had been dreaming about.","say":"uh-NFEH-terd","hook":"UNFETTEREd — FETTERs are chains; double the T like tightening a shackle, then set it free with un-."},{"w":"unimpeachable","def":"beyond doubt or reproach","ex":"an unimpeachable source","say":"uh-nih-MPEE-chuh-buhl","hook":"UNIMPEACHABLE ends in -ABLE not -IBLE — you ABLE-solutely cannot impeach a PEACH of a person."},{"w":"unscrupulous","def":"without scruples or principles","ex":"unscrupulous politicos who would be happy to sell...their country in order to gain power","say":"uh-NSKROO-pyuh-luhs","hook":"UNSCRUPULOUS ends in -ULOUS—remember: a scrupULOUS person has scruples, an unscrupULOUS one does not."},{"w":"unwieldy","def":"difficult to use or handle or manage because of size or weight or shape","ex":"we set about towing the unwieldy structure into the shelter","say":"uh-NWEE-ldee","hook":"UNWIELDY: I before E — WIELD follows 'I before E' and that heavy thing is hard to carry."},{"w":"unnecessary","def":"not necessary","ex":"The teacher reminded students to avoid unnecessary details and stick to the main point.","say":"uh-NNEH-suh-seh-ree","hook":"Unnecessary has one C and double S — 'Not necessary: one C, two S's, please.'"},{"w":"unnatural","def":"not in accordance with or determined by nature; contrary to nature","ex":"The eerie silence in the forest felt completely unnatural, as if every bird and creature had suddenly vanished, warning the hikers that something unusual and unsettling was lurking nearby.","say":"uh-NNA-cher-uhl","hook":"UN-natural has UN doubled up, just like something unnatural doubles up the oddness."},{"w":"unnerve","def":"disturb the composure of","ex":"The sudden crack of thunder was enough to unnerve even the bravest campers in the tent.","say":"uh-NURV","hook":"UNNerve has double N — it takes NERVE to spell it with two N's without getting unnerved."},{"w":"unequivocal","def":"admitting of no doubt or misunderstanding; having only one meaning or interpretation and leading to only one conclusion","ex":"unequivocal evidence","say":"uh-nih-KWIH-vuh-kuhl","hook":"UN-EQUI-VOC-AL: no equal VOICE (vox) — only one clear meaning; remember 'voc' like vocal."},{"w":"unfathomable","def":"of depth; not capable of being sounded or measured","ex":"the abyssal depths of the ocean","say":"uh-NFA-thuh-muh-buhl","hook":"UNFATHOMable depths — you can't FATHOM it; keep FATHOM and add -able, not -ible."},{"w":"unmistakable","def":"clearly evident to the mind","ex":"his opposition to slavery was unmistakable","say":"uh-nmih-STAY-kuh-buhl","hook":"UNMISTAKABLE drops the E in MISTAKE before -ABLE — no E needed when it's that obvious."}]},{"title":"dis- (apart / not / opposite)","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin dis- = apart, not, or deprived of. When it meets a root beginning with s, the result is double-s. Recognizing this doubling is the key to spelling dissipate, dissolve, and dissemble correctly.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>DISINGENUOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> dih-sih-NJEH-nyoo-uhs\n<b>Spell it.</b> D · I · S · I · N · G · E · N · U · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> dih-sih-NJEH-nyoo-uhs\n<b>Syllables.</b> dih · sih · njheh · nyuw · ah · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [dis=DIS] [in=IN] [JEN=GEN] [yoo=U] [us=OUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> BOTH dis- AND in- are prefixes here; -gen- = birth/kind; -uous not -eous; stress: dis-in-JEN-yoo-us\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin dis- = not + ingenuus = freeborn, frank, candid","cards":[{"title":"What dis- Does","body":"dis- = apart, not, or deprive of. Dissonance (dis- + sonus = sound apart) = harsh discord. Discern (dis- + cernere = separate) = separate truth from error. Disdain (dis- + dignare = deem worthy) = think something not worthy. Disparity = lack of equality. Dissemble = disguise one's true appearance."},{"title":"dis- + s-root = double-s","body":"When the root begins with s, you get dis- + s- = diss-: dissipate (scatter apart), dissolve, dissent, dissertation, dissemble, disseminate (dis- + semen = seed = scatter seeds of ideas). The double-s is the dis- prefix meeting a root that starts with s."},{"title":"Spellings That Trap","body":"Discernible = discern + -ible (use -ible because discern is from Latin — the stem cannot stand alone). Distraught = dis- + trahere = pulled apart = extremely upset — note the -aught from Old English. Disingenuous = dis- + in- + gen — two negating prefixes stacked."},{"title":"dis- vs de-","body":"Both weaken or remove things. dis- = separation or absence. de- = removal or reversal. Disarm = remove the ability to use arms. Dearm = not a word. Disintegrate = fall apart. Decompose = break down chemically. Disagree = the opposite of agree."},{"title":"High-Value dis- Words","body":"Disparage = speak with disdain. Dissonance = lack of harmony. Discrepancy = a gap between things. Disconcert = unsettle. Discomfit = defeat or thwart. ⚠️ Discomfit ≠ discomfort — discomfit means to defeat, not merely to make uncomfortable. A classic vocabulary-round distinction."}],"words":[{"w":"disingenuous","def":"not straightforward or candid; giving a false appearance of frankness; - David Cannadine","ex":"an ambitious, disingenuous, philistine, and hypocritical operator, who...exemplified...the most disagreeable traits of his time","say":"dih-sih-NJEH-nyoo-uhs","hook":"DIS-IN-GENU-OUS hides the Latin for 'genuine' — someone disingenuous is NOT genuine."},{"w":"discernible","def":"means capable of being distinguished","ex":"things happen in the earth and sky with no discernible cause","say":"d-ih-s-UR-n-uh-b-uh-l","hook":"DisCERNible ends in -IBLE not -ABLE — if it's discernible, you're ABLE to see it, but spell it with an 'i' because you use your EYE."},{"w":"distraught","def":"means deeply agitated","ex":"distraught with grief","say":"d-ih-s-t-r-AW-t","hook":"DISTRAUGHT — the GH is silent but the emotion is not; the AU combination sounds like AW in 'awful.'"},{"w":"dissipate","def":"to cause to separate and go in different directions","ex":"By noon, the morning fog had begun to dissipate, revealing a brilliant blue sky over the harbor.","say":"DIH-suh-payt","hook":"diSSIPate — watch it SLIP away like water you SIP that dribbles away."},{"w":"disseminate","def":"cause to become widely known","ex":"Health officials worked urgently to disseminate accurate information about the new vaccine to every community center, school, and local clinic across the entire region within one week.","say":"dih-SEH-muh-nayt","hook":"To disSEMinate is to scatter SEEDS widely — double S scatters the information like seeds in the wind."},{"w":"dissonance","def":"a conflict of people's opinions or actions or characters","ex":"modern music is just noise to me","say":"DIH-suh-nuhns","hook":"DisSonance: two SONic clashes — the double 's' sounds like two notes scraping against each other."},{"w":"disparage","def":"express a negative opinion of","ex":"She disparaged her student's efforts","say":"dih-SPEH-rihj","hook":"To DISPARAGE is to put someone below your PAR — think of a golfer who trashes par, spelled -age at the end."},{"w":"discrepancy","def":"a difference between conflicting facts or claims or opinions","ex":"a growing divergence of opinion","say":"dih-SKREH-puh-nsee","hook":"Hear the CREP-A-NCY: the A in discrepANcy marks the gap between the facts."},{"w":"disconcert","def":"cause to feel embarrassment","ex":"The constant attention of the young man confused her","say":"dih-skuh-NSURT","hook":"DisCONCERT ruins a CONCERT — when musicians dis-agree, the concert falls apart!"},{"w":"discomfit","def":"cause to lose one's composure","ex":"The unexpected question seemed to discomfit the speaker, who fumbled nervously with his notes.","say":"dis-KUM-fit","hook":"DisCOMFIT ends in -FIT not -FORT — you are so un-FIT with discomfort that you discomFIT!"},{"w":"dissemble","def":"make believe with the intent to deceive","ex":"The spy had to dissemble perfectly, pretending to be a simple baker while gathering crucial information for her country.","say":"dih-SEH-mbuhl","hook":"diSSEMble — to diSSEMble is to disSEMinate a false SEMBLANCE of yourself."},{"w":"disparate","def":"fundamentally different or distinct in quality or kind","ex":"The science fair attracted disparate projects ranging from solar-powered cars to studies on the psychology of color.","say":"DIH-sper-iht","hook":"disPARate — remember PAR means equal, so disparate means NOT equal or alike."},{"w":"disparity","def":"inequality or difference in some respect","ex":"The report highlighted a troubling disparity in test scores between students from wealthy and low-income schools.","say":"dih-SPEH-ruh-tee","hook":"DISPARITY hides PAR — when there's no PAR (equality), you have a DISPARITY; mind the A."},{"w":"dissolute","def":"unrestrained by convention or morality","ex":"The dissolute nobleman squandered his entire fortune on reckless gambling and extravagant midnight parties.","say":"DIS-uh-loot","hook":"A disSolute person is so loose they LOOSEn all rules — the double 's' is as unrestrained as they are."},{"w":"disquisition","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""}]},{"title":"de- (down / away / reverse)","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin de- removes, reverses, takes down, or completely intensifies. It is one of the most stable Latin prefixes — it never assimilates. The challenge is always what comes after de-.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>DESICCATE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> d-EH-s-uh-k-ay-t\n<b>Spell it.</b> D · E · S · I · C · C · A · T · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> d-EH-s-uh-k-ay-t\n<b>Syllables.</b> d · e · s · i · c · c · a · t · e\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [DES=DES] [ik=IC] [kayt=CATE]\n<b>Exception.</b> double-C from Latin desiccare (inherited, not from prefix meeting root); silent final -e; DES-ih-kayt\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin desiccare = to dry up, from de-(completely)+siccare(to dry)+sicc","cards":[{"title":"What de- Does","body":"de- removes (decaffeinate, defrost), reverses (decode, decompose), goes down (descend, decline), or means thoroughly (devout, demolish). Desiccate = de- + siccus (dry) = remove all moisture. Denouement (de- + French nouer = untie) = the final unraveling of a story's plot."},{"title":"de- Removing Words","body":"Decimate = de- + decimus (tenth) = originally kill one in ten (Roman military punishment); now: destroy a large portion. Denigrate = de- + niger (black) = blacken someone's reputation. Deracinate = de- + radix (root) = uproot entirely. Denude = strip completely bare."},{"title":"French de- Words","body":"Many French loanwords begin de-: Demesne (an estate's private land), Demitasse (demi = half + tasse = cup = small coffee cup), Débâcle (sudden collapse), Débonnaire/Debonair (from de bon aire = of good air = charming). The accent often disappears in English but the spelling stays."},{"title":"de- vs dis-","body":"de- = reversal or removal; dis- = separation or absence. Decode = reverse the coding. Disagree = the opposite of agree. Defrost = remove frost. Disintegrate = fall apart. Both prefixes weaken or oppose — the nuance is direction vs absence."},{"title":"Spelling Details","body":"Desiccate = D-E-S-I-C-C-A-T-E — the double-c is from the Latin siccare, not from prefix meeting root. Denouement = D-E-N-O-U-E-M-E-N-T (French -ou- vowel pair). Deign = D-E-I-G-N (silent g from Old French). Deft — de- here is part of an Old English root, not the Latin prefix."}],"words":[{"w":"desiccate","def":"To desiccate something means to preserve it by removing all of its water and moisture content.","ex":"carry dehydrated food on your camping trip","say":"d-EH-s-uh-k-ay-t","hook":"DESICCATE has a double C—think of two C's squeezing all the moisture out"},{"w":"decaffeinate","def":"To decaffeinate a beverage means to extract the caffeine from it so that it has little or no stimulating effect.","ex":"The company uses a special water process to decaffeinate its coffee beans without altering the rich flavor.","say":"d-ee-k-A-f-uh-n-ay-t","hook":"DECAFFEINATE has a DOUBLE F — think of two coffee beans being pulled out: de-CAFFEINE-ate!"},{"w":"denouement","def":"the final outcome or resolution of a complex sequence of events, especially in a story","ex":"In the thrilling denouement of the mystery novel, the detective revealed that the butler had hidden the stolen jewels in the clock.","say":"d-ay-n-oo-m-AH-n","hook":"The dénouement UNKNOTs the story — dé(undo)+noue(knot)"},{"w":"decimate","def":"kill one in every ten, as of mutineers in Roman armies","ex":"the plague wiped out an entire population","say":"DEH-suh-mayt","hook":"Roman soldiers were DECIMATEd — one in ten chosen by FATE, spelled with just one 'm' and '-ate'."},{"w":"denigrate","def":"cause to seem less serious; play down","ex":"Don't belittle his influence","say":"DEH-nuh-grayt","hook":"To DENIGRATE is to blacken someone's name — spot 'nigr' (black, like Nigeria's name root) in the middle."},{"w":"deracinate","def":"move (people) forcibly from their homeland into a new and foreign environment","ex":"The war uprooted many people","say":"dih-RAS-ih-nayt","hook":"De-RACIN-ate: picture pulling a RACE of people out by the roots like a plant."},{"w":"demesne","def":"is possession of land as one's own","ex":"the family owned a large estate on Long Island","say":"duh-MAYN","hook":"A demesSNE is a lord's estate — the tricky SNE at the end is SILENT, like a secret domain."},{"w":"demitasse","def":"is a small cup for serving strong black coffee","ex":"After dinner, the host offered each guest a demitasse of thick, fragrant espresso.","say":"DEM-ee-tas","hook":"A DEMITASSE is a DEMI (half) cup with a TASSE (cup) — double S in tasse, like the strong espresso gives you a double kick."},{"w":"debacle","def":"a sudden and violent collapse","ex":"The school play turned into a complete debacle when the backdrop fell, the microphones cut out, and the lead forgot every line.","say":"duh-BAH-kuhl","hook":"A DEBACLE has no K — think of ice suddenly cracking: dé-BA-CLE, smooth and French, no clunky K."},{"w":"debonair","def":"having a sophisticated charm","ex":"a debonair gentleman","say":"deh-buh-NEHR","hook":"A debonair gentleman has good AIR about him — the word ends in 'air' because his charm is breezy."},{"w":"deprecate","def":"express strong disapproval of; deplore","ex":"The teacher should not deprecate his student's efforts","say":"DEH-pruh-kayt","hook":"To DEPREcate is to PRAY something away — de+PREC(prayer)+ate, like a priest praying against evil."},{"w":"depreciate","def":"To reduce or lessen the value, worth, or importance of something; to belittle something or cause it to decrease in monetary or perceived value over time.","ex":"The teacher should not deprecate his student's efforts","say":"dih-PREE-shee-ayt","hook":"To depreciate is to lower the PRICE — keep 'preci' in the middle to remember the price root."},{"w":"deference","def":"a courteous expression (by word or deed) of esteem or regard","ex":"his deference to her wishes was very flattering","say":"DEH-fer-uhns","hook":"Show DEFERENCe by letting others go FIRST — spot DEFER inside deFERENCE and add -ENCE."},{"w":"deign","def":"to think fit or to condescend","ex":"The famous chef did not deign to answer questions from food bloggers he considered beneath his level of expertise.","say":"d-AY-n","hook":"The queen would not DEIGN to explain — she has DIGNITY and DEIGN share the same root; both have the silent GN."},{"w":"detriment","def":"a damage or loss","ex":"Staying up until midnight every night was a clear detriment to his ability to focus in class.","say":"DEH-truh-muhnt","hook":"DETRIMENT ends in -MENT likeMENT-al damage — remember DE-TRI-MENT: rubbing away leaves a MENT-al scar."},{"w":"derogate","def":"cause to seem less serious; play down","ex":"She tried to derogate his achievements, but everyone in the room knew how hard he had worked.","say":"DER-uh-gate","hook":"DEROGATE: to take away (de) from someone's ROGUE-ness — ask (rogare) less of them, spelled de+ROG+ATE."}]},{"title":"ex- / e- / ef- (out / former / thoroughly)","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin ex- = out of. It appears as ex-, e-, or ef- depending on what follows. Before f it assimilates to ef-; before many consonants the x drops to just e-. Same prefix, three shapes.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>EFFERVESCENT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> eh-f-ur-v-EH-s-uh-n-t\n<b>Spell it.</b> E · F · F · E · R · V · E · S · C · E · N · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> eh-f-ur-v-EH-s-uh-n-t\n<b>Syllables.</b> e · f · f · e · r · v · e · s · c · e · n · t\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [ef=EF] [fer=FER] [VES=VES] [ent=CENT]\n<b>Exception.</b> ef- = ex- before f (assimilation gives double-f); -escent = becoming; stress on third syllable ef-fer-VES-ent\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin effervescere = to boil up, from ex-(out)+fervere = to boil","cards":[{"title":"Three Forms","body":"ex- before vowels and most consonants: exquisite, extraneous. Before f → ef-: effervescent (ef- + fervere = boil = bubbling over), efface (ef- + facies = face = rub out). Before many consonants the x drops to e-: eloquent, elaborate, elicit, emit."},{"title":"Out-Of Words","body":"Excoriate (ex- + corium = skin) = strip the skin = criticize savagely. Exculpate (ex- + culpa = fault) = free from blame. Exigent (ex- + agere = drive out) = pressing, urgent. Exiguous = extremely scanty. Expatiate = speak at great length. Expunge (ex- + pungere = prick) = erase entirely."},{"title":"Former / From Words","body":"Ex- before a title = former: ex-president. Expatriate = one who has left their homeland. Extirpate = pull out by the roots. Exhume (ex- + humus = earth) = dig out of the ground."},{"title":"Thorough / Intensive ex-","body":"ex- intensifies the root: exacerbate = make thoroughly more bitter/worse. Exasperate = thoroughly roughen = irritate deeply. Excruciating (ex- + crux = cross) = thoroughly cross-like = intensely painful. Exhilarating = thoroughly lift the spirits."},{"title":"Spelling Traps","body":"Exquisite = E-X-Q-U-I-S-I-T-E (not exquissite). Extemporaneous = E-X-T-E-M-P-O-R-A-N-E-O-U-S — from ex tempore = out of the moment. Extraordinary = E-X-T-R-A-O-R-D-I-N-A-R-Y — note: extra- here not ex-! Different prefix entirely."}],"words":[{"w":"exquisite","def":"is of special beauty or charm","ex":"suffered exquisite pain","say":"EH-k-s-k-w-uh-z-uh-t","hook":"EXQUISITE things are EXceptionallyQUISITELY crafted"},{"w":"extemporaneous","def":"is done without special preparation","ex":"his ad-lib comments showed poor judgment","say":"ek-stem-puh-RAY-nee-us","hook":"EX TEMPORE means 'out of the moment'—no prep time!"},{"w":"effervescent","def":"used of wines and waters; charged naturally or artificially with carbon dioxide","ex":"The effervescent new student bubbled with energy from the very first day, cracking jokes, complimenting everyone's artwork, and making the entire classroom feel lighter and more fun simply by walking through the door each morning.","say":"eh-f-ur-v-EH-s-uh-n-t","hook":"EFFERVescent = bubbles FERVOR-ing out — think of a soda bottle fizzing over."},{"w":"exacerbate","def":"is to make something worse","ex":"This drug aggravates the pain","say":"ih-g-z-A-s-ur-b-ay-t","hook":"To exACERBate is to make things ACERBic — bitterly worse."},{"w":"exasperate","def":"to irritate intensely; to make someone very annoyed or frustrated","ex":"It began to exasperate her teammates when she changed the project plan for the fifth time the night before it was due.","say":"ih-GZA-sper-ayt","hook":"exASPERate — it makes things ASPERously rough and irritating"},{"w":"excruciating","def":"torment emotionally or mentally","ex":"The sinners will be tormented in Hell, according to the Bible","say":"ih-KSKROO-shee-ay-tihng","hook":"exCRUCIating pain — see the CRUCI as in crucifix — nailed to the cross level of pain!"},{"w":"exhilarate","def":"fill with sublime emotion","ex":"The children were thrilled at the prospect of going to the movies","say":"ih-GZIH-ler-ayt","hook":"EXHILARATE has a hidden 'h' and only one 'l' — feel the HILARIOUS joy in 'hilar'!"},{"w":"excoriate","def":"express strong disapproval of","ex":"We condemn the racism in South Africa","say":"eh-KSKAW-ree-ayt","hook":"exCORIATE — the CORE of your skin is stripped away, leaving an I and ATE ending!"},{"w":"exculpate","def":"pronounce not guilty of criminal charges","ex":"The suspect was cleared of the murder charges","say":"eh-KSKUH-lpayt","hook":"EX means OUT — exculpate pulls the CULPRIT out of blame."},{"w":"exigent","def":"demanding attention; ; ; - H.L.Mencken","ex":"The emergency room doctor faced an exigent situation when three critically injured patients arrived at exactly the same moment, requiring her to make rapid decisions that could mean the difference between life and death.","say":"EH-ksih-juhnt","hook":"An EXIgent situation is URGENT — both end in -ent, demanding your immediate attention."},{"w":"expatiate","def":"to speak or write at length; to add details and elaborate on a subject freely","ex":"The professor asked the students not to expatiate on every minor point but to focus on the main argument.","say":"ik-SPAY-shee-ayt","hook":"To expatiate is to spread your ideas across SPACIOUS territory"},{"w":"expunge","def":"remove by erasing or crossing out or as if by drawing a line","ex":"Please strike this remark from the record","say":"ih-KSPUHNJ","hook":"Expunge has a PLUNGE-like ending — plunge your eraser in and wipe it out, keeping the E at the end."},{"w":"extirpate","def":"destroy completely, as if down to the roots","ex":"the vestiges of political democracy were soon uprooted","say":"EH-kster-payt","hook":"EX-STIR-PATE: to extirpate is to stir up and pull out by the root — stir is hidden right inside."},{"w":"eloquent","def":"expressing yourself readily, clearly, effectively","ex":"able to dazzle with his facile tongue","say":"EH-luh-kwuhnt","hook":"An ELOquent speaker lets words FLOW out beautifully."},{"w":"elaborate","def":"add details, as to an account or idea; clarify the meaning of and discourse in a learned way, usually in writing","ex":"She elaborated on the main ideas in her dissertation","say":"ih-LA-bruht","hook":"ELABORATE means to work OUT the details — e+LABOR+ate; there's real LABOR in the middle of this word."},{"w":"elicit","def":"call forth (emotions, feelings, and responses)","ex":"The teacher asked a surprising, thought-provoking question designed to elicit a genuine, emotional response from every student sitting quietly in the classroom.","say":"ih-LIH-siht","hook":"To ELICIT a response, you lure it out — don't confuse it with ILLICIT (illegal), which starts with two L's like 'law'."}]},{"title":"re- (again / back)","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin re- = again or back. One of the most common prefixes in English. But beware: not every word starting with re- uses it as a prefix — sometimes it is part of the root itself.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>RECALCITRANT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> r-ih-k-A-l-s-ih-t-r-uh-n-t\n<b>Spell it.</b> R · E · C · A · L · C · I · T · R · A · N · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> r-ih-k-A-l-s-ih-t-r-uh-n-t\n<b>Syllables.</b> r · e · c · a · l · c · i · t · r · a · n · t\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [reh=RE] [KAL=CAL] [sih=CI] [trant=TRANT]\n<b>Exception.</b> re- + calcitrare (kick) = kicking back; -ant not -ent; stress on second syllable reh-KAL-sih-trant\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin recalcitrare = to kick back (calx = heel)","cards":[{"title":"What re- Does","body":"re- = again (redo, restart) or back (return, retract). Recalcitrant (re- + calcitrare = kick) = kicking back = stubbornly resistant. Redoubtable (re- + douter = fear) = worth fearing again and again. Repartee = a quick, ready reply. Recidivism (re- + cadere = fall) = falling back into crime."},{"title":"Again Words","body":"Renaissance (re- + naissance = birth) = rebirth. Rendezvous = meet again at a set place. Reconnoiter (re- + connoître = know) = look over again to gather information. Rescind (re- + scindere = cut) = cut back = cancel. Remonstrate (re- + monstrare = show) = show opposition again = protest."},{"title":"Back Words","body":"Repudiate (re- + pudere = shame) = push back with rejection. Recriminate = re- + criminare = counter-accuse. Retract (re- + trahere = drag) = drag back = withdraw a statement. Recant = withdraw a previously stated belief. Renounce = formally give up a claim."},{"title":"When re- is NOT a Prefix","body":"Reticent = reticere (be silent) — the re- is part of the Latin root. Relevant — re- is part of relevare. Test: remove re- — if the remainder is not a meaningful English word, re- is part of the root. Reticent minus re- = ticent (not a word) → part of root."},{"title":"French re- Spelling Traps","body":"Rendezvous = R-E-N-D-E-Z-V-O-U-S (French; final -s silent). Renaissance = R-E-N-A-I-S-S-A-N-C-E (double-s). Reconnaissance = R-E-C-O-N-N-A-I-S-S-A-N-C-E (double-n AND double-s). These French re- words carry French spelling patterns inside them."}],"words":[{"w":"recalcitrant","def":"means resisting authority","ex":"a fractious animal that would not submit to the harness","say":"r-ih-k-A-l-s-ih-t-r-uh-n-t","hook":"A rECALCITRANT student kicks back like a mule — remember the ANT who refuses to march."},{"w":"redoubtable","def":"is that that is to be feared formidable","ex":"the formidable prospect of major surgery","say":"r-uh-d-OW-t-uh-b-uh-l","hook":"A redouBTable foe makes you doubt — the B hides silently in the middle like a lurking enemy."},{"w":"repartee","def":"is a quick witty reply","ex":"The debate champion's sharp repartee left her opponent speechless and the audience laughing.","say":"r-eh-p-ur-t-EE","hook":"Good repartee ends with a TEE shot — it always lands perfectly"},{"w":"renaissance","def":"the period of European history at the close of the Middle Ages and the rise of the modern world; a cultural rebirth from the 14th through the middle of the 17th centuries","ex":"Artists from across Europe were inspired by the renaissance, filling cathedrals and palaces with breathtaking paintings and sculptures.","say":"reh-nuh-SAHNS","hook":"RENAISSANCE = RE + NAIS + SANCE — one 'n,' one 's': a rebirth needs only one of each to spring anew."},{"w":"rendezvous","def":"a meeting planned at a certain time and place","ex":"he was waiting for them at the rendezvous","say":"RAH-ndih-voo","hook":"RENDEZVOUS ends in -vous — you (vous) must show up at the meeting!"},{"w":"reconnoiter","def":"explore, often with the goal of finding something or somebody","ex":"The scouts were sent ahead to reconnoiter the forest trail before the rest of the troop attempted the hike.","say":"ree-kuh-NOY-ter","hook":"RE + CONnoiter — go out again to CONfirm what's out there"},{"w":"recidivism","def":"habitual relapse into crime","ex":"The new rehabilitation program was designed specifically to reduce recidivism among young offenders.","say":"ruh-SIH-dih-vih-zuhm","hook":"ReCIDivism: criminals who keep falling back — the CID (like 'slide') takes them down again and again."},{"w":"repudiate","def":"To firmly reject, deny, or refuse to accept something such as a claim, belief, or person, often publicly cutting all ties with it.","ex":"The scientist was quick to repudiate the false data that had been attributed to her research lab.","say":"ree-PYOO-dee-ayt","hook":"To REPUDIATE is to say PUT it away — I want nothing to do with it"},{"w":"rescind","def":"is to annul or repeal","ex":"He revoked the ban on smoking","say":"r-ih-s-IH-n-d","hook":"ResCIND has a hidden SC — to reSCind is to CUT back a law, and SC cuts right through the middle."},{"w":"remonstrate","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"recriminate","def":"return an accusation against someone or engage in mutual accusations; charge in return","ex":"Instead of working together to solve the problem, the two teammates began to recriminate each other publicly.","say":"rih-krih-mih-NAYT","hook":"To RECRIMINATE is to CRIME-back — you throw the CRIMIN-ation right back."},{"w":"retract","def":"formally reject or disavow a formerly held belief, usually under pressure","ex":"He retracted his earlier statements about his religion","say":"ree-TRAKT","hook":"RETRACT pulls back — like a TRACTor in reverse: re-TRACT."},{"w":"recant","def":"formally reject or disavow a formerly held belief, usually under pressure","ex":"He retracted his earlier statements about his religion","say":"ree-KANT","hook":"rECANT: to take back what you CHANTED before — unsing your song of belief."},{"w":"renounce","def":"give up, such as power, as of monarchs and emperors, or duties and obligations","ex":"The King abdicated when he married a divorcee","say":"rih-NOWNS","hook":"To reNOUNCE is to take back your NOUN — your name or claim — so find NOUNCE inside."},{"w":"recondite","def":"difficult to penetrate; incomprehensible to one of ordinary understanding or knowledge","ex":"the professor's lectures were so abstruse that students tended to avoid them","say":"REH-kuh-ndeyet","hook":"RECONDite knowledge is hidden — it's conDITed (stored) away where few can DITE it out."},{"w":"refulgent","def":"radiating or as if radiating light","ex":"The refulgent glow of the full moon was so brilliantly bright on the snowy mountaintop that the hikers could clearly read their trail map without needing a flashlight at all.","say":"rih-FUL-jent","hook":"reFULGent — FULG sounds like FULL of light; it ends in -ENT not -ANT."}]},{"title":"pre- / pro- (before / forward)","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin pre- = before in time or position. Latin pro- = forward, in favor of, on behalf of. Two prefixes, closely related in meaning, producing very different vocabularies.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PROPITIOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> p-r-uh-p-IH-sh-uh-s\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · R · O · P · I · T · I · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> p-r-uh-p-IH-sh-uh-s\n<b>Syllables.</b> p · r · o · p · i · t · i · o · u · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [pruh=PRO] [PISH=PI] [us=TIOUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> -tious = /shus/ (Latin -tiosus); -pit- from pietas = favor; stress on second syllable pruh-PISH-us\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> Latin propitius = favorable, gracious","cards":[{"title":"pre- = Before","body":"Precocious (pre- + coquere = cook) = cooked before its time = unusually mature early. Precursor = one who runs before. Prescient (pre- + scire = know) = knowing before it happens. Preponderant (pre- + ponderare = weigh) = weighing more = dominant. Prevaricate = straddle before = dodge the truth."},{"title":"pro- = Forward / For","body":"Propitious (pro- + pietas = favor) = presenting favorable signs ahead. Prodigious = extraordinarily great. Provenance (pro- + venire = come) = where something came from. Protagonist (pro- + Greek agonist = actor) = the forward-acting main character. Profligate = wildly extravagant."},{"title":"The Key pre- Spelling Detail","body":"Precocious = P-R-E-C-O-C-I-O-U-S (two c's; the first comes from prefix + root). Prescience = P-R-E-S-C-I-E-N-C-E (the sc- cluster from scire). Predilection = P-R-E-D-I-L-E-C-T-I-O-N — note -lection not -lekshun."},{"title":"Prescribe vs Proscribe","body":"Prescribe (pre- + scribere = write before) = a doctor writes a prescription in advance. Proscribe (pro- = put forward publicly) = ban or forbid. A doctor prescribes; a government proscribes. Precede (come before) vs proceed (move forward). Same-sounding prefixes, opposite directions."},{"title":"Prodigal & Prodigious","body":"Prodigal (prodigere = drive forward wastefully) = wastefully extravagant. Prodigious (prodire = go forward beyond normal) = extraordinarily great in size or degree. Both from pro- but from different Latin roots — the definitions distinguish them clearly at the bee."}],"words":[{"w":"precocious","def":"is prematurely developed","ex":"The precocious six-year-old stunned her kindergarten teacher by reading an entire chapter book aloud during free time, then politely asked whether the school library carried any books on ancient Roman architecture.","say":"p-r-ih-k-OH-sh-uh-s","hook":"A precocious child is PRECIOUS but EARLY — precocIOUS, that -ious ending means full of early ripeness."},{"w":"precursor","def":"a substance from which another substance is formed (especially by a metabolic reaction)","ex":"Scientists discovered that a simple amino acid was the precursor to the complex protein found in muscle tissue.","say":"p-r-ee-k-UR-s-ur","hook":"A precursor RUNS before — like a CURSOR racing ahead on screen"},{"w":"prescient","def":"perceiving the significance of events before they occur","ex":"Her prescient warning about the bridge's weak supports was ignored for years before the structure finally collapsed.","say":"PREH-see-uhnt","hook":"PRESCIENT people have pre-SCIENCE — they know things before they happen"},{"w":"preponderant","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"prevaricate","def":"be deliberately ambiguous or unclear in order to mislead or withhold information","ex":"The detective warned the suspect not to prevaricate, because every evasive answer only made him look more guilty.","say":"pruh-VEH-ruh-kayt","hook":"preVARIcate — a liar VARIes the truth; to preVARIcate is to VARY your story to mislead."},{"w":"propitious","def":"encouraging : favorable.","ex":"With clear skies, gentle winds, and a high tide perfectly timed for their departure, the sailing team agreed that the morning conditions could not have been more propitious for setting off on their race.","say":"p-r-uh-p-IH-sh-uh-s","hook":"Propitious has ITI in the middle — a favorable sign has I-T-I, like 'It Is Indeed' good."},{"w":"prodigious","def":"so great in size or force or extent as to elicit awe","ex":"The young pianist displayed a prodigious talent, performing a full concerto from memory at age nine.","say":"pruh-DIH-juhs","hook":"A PRODIGY has PRODIGIOUS talent — both share the root!"},{"w":"provenance","def":"where something originated or was nurtured in its early existence","ex":"the birthplace of civilization","say":"PRAH-vuh-nuhns","hook":"PROVE where it came from — provENANCE tracks its ancestral DANCE back to its origin."},{"w":"protagonist","def":"a person who backs a politician or a team etc.","ex":"all their supporters came out for the game","say":"proh-TA-guh-nuhst","hook":"The proTAGonist wears the first name TAG in the story — proTAGonist, the star who's TAGGED as number one."},{"w":"profligate","def":"a dissolute man in fashionable society","ex":"prodigal in their expenditures","say":"PRAW-flih-gayt","hook":"A profliGATE person flung open the GATE to ruin — remember the hidden 'gate' at the end."},{"w":"prescribe","def":"issue commands or orders for","ex":"The doctor decided to prescribe a mild antibiotic to treat the stubborn infection.","say":"pruh-SKREYEB","hook":"A doctor PRESCRIBES by writing — PRE+SCRIBE — the SCRIBE writes the order before you take the pill."},{"w":"proscribe","def":"command against","ex":"I forbid you to call me late at night","say":"proh-SKREYEB","hook":"PROscribe PROHIBITS — both start with PRO; a doctor PREscribes (pre = before), but a ruler PROscribes (bans publicly)."},{"w":"precede","def":"is to go before","ex":"Stone tools precede bronze tools","say":"p-r-ih-s-EE-d","hook":"To preCEDE is to go before — remember: cede ends in E not EE."},{"w":"proceed","def":"continue talking;  he continued,","ex":"After the principal finished her morning announcements and the hallways had quieted down, she gave the signal for the science fair participants to proceed with setting up their colorful display boards.","say":"pruh-SEED","hook":"PROCEED has two E's charging forward together — think 'pro' + 'ceed' (like 'speed' without the sp)."},{"w":"preempt","def":"a high bid that is intended to prevent the opposing players from bidding","ex":"live broadcast of the presidential debate preempts the regular news hour","say":"PREE-ehmpt","hook":"To preEMPT is to take something EMPTY before someone else fills it — grab it first!"},{"w":"predilection","def":"a predisposition in favor of something","ex":"Zoe had a predilection for mystery novels, always choosing them over any other genre at the school book fair.","say":"preh-duh-LEH-kshuhn","hook":"Before you SELECT, your predilECTION already chose for you"}]},{"title":"sub- / sur- / super- / supra- (under / above)","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin sub- = under. It assimilates just like ad- and in-. Its opposite super- = above/beyond. Recognizing the doubled letter in sur-/suf-/sug-/sup- forms reveals the hidden sub- prefix.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>SURREPTITIOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> sur-uh-PTIH-shuhs\n<b>Spell it.</b> S · U · R · R · E · P · T · I · T · I · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> sur-uh-PTIH-shuhs\n<b>Syllables.</b> sur · rep · ti · tious\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [sur=SUR] [rep=REP] [TI=TI] [shus=TIOUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> sur- = sub- before r (assimilation gives double-r); -reptus = seized; -tious suffix; stress: sur-rep-TI-shus\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin surrepticius, from surripere = to snatch secretly","cards":[{"title":"sub- Assimilation","body":"sub- = under. Before r → sur-: surreptitious (sub- + reptus = seized) = seized from under = done secretly. Surfeit = sub- + French fait = overdone = excess. Before f → suf-: suffice, suffuse. Before g → sug-: suggest. Before p → sup-: supplant, suppress."},{"title":"Under-Words","body":"Subcutaneous (sub- + cutis = skin) = under the skin. Subpoena (sub- + Latin poena = penalty) = under penalty = legal demand to appear. Subterfuge (sub- + fuga = flight) = flight under cover = deceptive trick. Subliminal (sub- + limen = threshold) = below the threshold of awareness."},{"title":"super- = Above/Beyond","body":"Supersede (super- + sedere = sit) = sit above and replace. ⚠️ Spelled -sede NOT -cede! It is the only common word ending in -sede. All others (precede, recede, concede) end in -cede. Supercilious (super- + cilium = eyebrow) = raising the eyebrow above others = contemptuous."},{"title":"supra- = Above (Technical)","body":"Supranational = above the national level. Suprarenal = above the kidney (= adrenal). Supra- tends toward scientific/formal usage; super- is more common in everyday vocabulary. Both mean \"above\" but occupy different registers."},{"title":"Spelling Traps","body":"Surreptitious = double-r from sur- + r-root. Supersede = -sede not -cede — unique in English. Surfeit = S-U-R-F-E-I-T (-ei- from French). Supplant = sup- + planta (sole of foot) = trip up = replace — not sub-plant!"}],"words":[{"w":"surreptitious","def":"marked by quiet and caution and secrecy; taking pains to avoid being observed","ex":"The spy cast a surreptitious glance over his shoulder before slipping the coded note under the door.","say":"sur-uh-PTIH-shuhs","hook":"SURprise + REPTile + IOUS: a reptile sneaking up is surreptitious"},{"w":"surfeit","def":"means excess an excessive amount","ex":"After Thanksgiving dinner, there was such a surfeit of food that the family was still eating leftovers on Sunday.","say":"s-UR-f-uh-t","hook":"A SURFEIT is when you SURF through an OVERFLOW of something"},{"w":"subcutaneous","def":"means lying under the skin as tissue","ex":"The veterinarian explained that the small lump was simply a harmless subcutaneous cyst located just beneath the dog's skin, posing no danger and requiring no treatment unless it grew significantly larger over time.","say":"suh-bkyoo-TAY-nee-uhs","hook":"SUBCUTANEOUS means SUB (under) the CUTIS (skin) — like a submarine under water!"},{"w":"subpoena","def":"is the usual writ for the summoning of witnesses","ex":"The witness and her records were subpoenaed","say":"s-uh-p-EE-n-uh","hook":"subPOENA has POEtic justice — the OE together means penalty is hiding in plain sight."},{"w":"subterfuge","def":"something intended to misrepresent the true nature of an activity","ex":"he wasn't sick--it was just a subterfuge","say":"SUH-bter-fyooj","hook":"SubterFUGE — fugitives use SUBTERFUGE to FLEE secretly underground."},{"w":"subliminal","def":"below the threshold of conscious perception","ex":"Researchers debated whether subliminal advertising — flashing images too fast to consciously see — could really change what people buy.","say":"suh-BLIH-mih-nuhl","hook":"SUBLIMINAL is SUB (below) the LIMEN (threshold) — below your mental radar!"},{"w":"supersede","def":"is to replace in power or acceptance","ex":"Smith replaced Miller as CEO after Miller left","say":"s-oo-p-ur-s-EE-d","hook":"To supersEDE is to sit above — remember the SEDE comes from 'sedere' (to sit), not 'cede.'"},{"w":"supercilious","def":"having or showing arrogant superiority and disdain toward those one views as unworthy","ex":"The supercilious student rolled her eyes every time a classmate asked the teacher to slow down, as if the question were beneath her.","say":"soo-per-SIH-lee-uhs","hook":"SUPERCILIOUS people raise their SUPERCILIA (eyebrows) at others — one L, not two!"},{"w":"superintendent","def":"is a person who oversees or directs some work","ex":"The school superintendent visited every classroom to check on the new reading program.","say":"s-oo-p-ur-uh-n-t-EH-n-d-uh-n-t","hook":"The SUPERINTENDENT intends to oversee — spell 'intend' inside: super-INTEND-ent, ending in '-ent' not '-ant'."},{"w":"superfluous","def":"serving no useful purpose; having no excuse for being","ex":"otiose lines in a play","say":"SOO-per-flwuhs","hook":"SUPERFLUOUS things overflow uselessly — spot 'flu' flowing in the middle: super-FLU-ous."},{"w":"supplant","def":"take the place or move into the position of","ex":"Smith replaced Miller as CEO after Miller left","say":"suh-PLANT","hook":"To SUPPLANT is to trip someone under their PLANT-ed foot and take their place — sub + PLANT."},{"w":"subvert","def":"cause the downfall of; of rulers","ex":"The Czar was overthrown","say":"suh-BVURT","hook":"To subVERT is to turn something UNDER — VERT means turn, remember to spell it with E."},{"w":"suppress","def":"to put down by force or authority","ex":"suppress a nascent uprising","say":"suh-PREHS","hook":"SUPPRESs it — double P pushes DOWN and double S squeezes it shut: SUP + PRESS + S."},{"w":"surreptitiously","def":"in a surreptitious manner","ex":"he was watching her surreptitiously as she waited in the hotel lobby","say":"sur-uh-PTIH-shuh-slee","hook":"Surreptitiously hides a REPTILE inside — sneaking quietly through the grass."},{"w":"supranational","def":"transcending established national boundaries or spheres of interest","ex":"a supranational economy","say":"soo-pruh-NA-shuh-nuhl","hook":"SUPRA not SUPER — a supranational body rises ABOVE nations, spelled with the Latin A."}]},{"title":"com- / con- / col- / cor- / co- (together / with)","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin com- = with, together. Like ad- and in-, it assimilates to match the root. The doubled letter in the resulting word IS the prefix meeting the root — the spelling tells you the origin.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>CONNOISSEUR</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> k-ah-n-uh-s-UR\n<b>Spell it.</b> C · O · N · N · O · I · S · S · E · U · R\n<b>Say it again.</b> k-ah-n-uh-s-UR\n<b>Syllables.</b> c · o · n · n · o · i · s · s · e · u · r\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [kon=CON] [uh=NOIS] [SUR=SEUR]\n<b>Exception.</b> double-N (con- + n-root) AND double-S from French origin; -eur = French agent ending; stress: kon-uh-SUR\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> French connaître = to know","cards":[{"title":"The Assimilation Rule","body":"com- = with. Before l → col-: collaborate, collateral, colloquy. Before r → cor-: correlate, corroborate, corrupt. Before b/m/p stays com-: combine, commiserate, compel. Before vowels/most others → con-: contrite, conciliate. The doubled letter signals the assimilation."},{"title":"com- Words","body":"Compunction (com- + punct = prick) = pricking of conscience = guilt. Complacent (com- + placere = please) = pleased with oneself. Complaisant = eager to please others. ⚠️ Complacent ≠ complaisant: one is smugly satisfied; the other is obligingly pleasant. A classic vocabulary-round trap."},{"title":"con- Words","body":"Contrite (con- + terere = grind) = ground down with guilt = deeply sorry. Consternation (con- + sternere = overthrow) = complete dismay. Conciliatory (con- + ciliare = win over) = trying to make peace. Concatenate (con- + catena = chain) = link together in a series."},{"title":"col- and cor- Words","body":"Collaborate = work together. Colloquy = speak together formally. Corroborate (cor- + robur = strength) = strengthen together = confirm evidence. Corrugated (cor- + ruga = wrinkle) = wrinkled together = ridged. Double-ll or double-rr IS the assimilation."},{"title":"Hardest Words","body":"Connoisseur = C-O-N-N-O-I-S-S-E-U-R (double-n AND double-s AND French -eur). Commemorate = C-O-M-M-E-M-O-R-A-T-E (double-m). Continuum = C-O-N-T-I-N-U-U-M (double-u from Latin). These compound difficulty by combining assimilation doublings with additional Latin or French patterns."}],"words":[{"w":"connoisseur","def":"is a person competent to pass critical judgment","ex":"The art museum hired a connoisseur of Renaissance paintings to authenticate the newly discovered canvas.","say":"k-ah-n-uh-s-UR","hook":"A connoisseur KNOWS their stuff — double n, double s"},{"w":"compunction","def":"a feeling of deep regret (usually for some misdeed)","ex":"She felt absolutely no compunction after cheating on the test until she saw how disappointed her teacher was.","say":"kuh-MPUH-ngkshuhn","hook":"COM + PUNCTION — like a puncture that pricks your conscience"},{"w":"complacent","def":"contented to a fault with oneself or one's actions","ex":"he had become complacent after years of success","say":"kuh-MPLAY-suhnt","hook":"A COMPLACENT person is pleased with their place — they're too comfortable in their PLACE-nt."},{"w":"complaisant","def":"showing a cheerful willingness to do favors for others","ex":"to close one's eyes like a complaisant husband whose wife has taken a lover","say":"kuh-MPLAY-suhnt","hook":"A COMPLAISANT person is always pleased to say oui — note the French '-ais-' spelling tucked inside."},{"w":"contrite","def":"feeling or expressing pain or sorrow for sins or offenses","ex":"After snapping at his little sister, Owen looked genuinely contrite and spent the afternoon teaching her his favorite card game to make up for it.","say":"kuh-NTREYET","hook":"conTRITE — being contrite means feeling TRITEly sorry, ground down by guilt"},{"w":"consternation","def":"fear resulting from the awareness of danger","ex":"The students stared in consternation when their teacher announced a surprise ten-page essay due the very next morning.","say":"kah-nster-NAY-shuhn","hook":"CONSTERNation — you CONCERN + STERN face when alarmed"},{"w":"conciliatory","def":"tending to win over from a state of hostility or distrust","ex":"loneliness tore through him...whenever he thought of...even the compromising Louis du Tillet","say":"k-uh-n-s-IH-l-ee-uh-t-aw-r-ee","hook":"A conciliatory person is like a CONCIL-ium (council) — they bring people together, and the word keeps the full 'concili' before '-atory'."},{"w":"concatenate","def":"combine two strings to form a single one","ex":"In computer class, we learned how to concatenate two lists of names into one long alphabetical list.","say":"kuh-NKA-tuh-nayt","hook":"CON + CATENA (chain) — to chain things together one after another"},{"w":"collaborate","def":"work together on a common enterprise of project","ex":"The soprano and the pianist did not get together very well","say":"kuh-LA-ber-ayt","hook":"To colLABorate you share the LABor — hide LAB in the middle."},{"w":"colloquy","def":"a conversation especially a formal one","ex":"The two diplomats held a private colloquy before the official summit began.","say":"KAH-luh-kwee","hook":"A COLLOQUY is a TALK — col-LOQUY has LOQUACIOUS buried inside it."},{"w":"corroborate","def":"establish or strengthen as with new evidence or facts","ex":"his story confirmed my doubts","say":"ker-AH-ber-ayt","hook":"To CORROBORATE is to strengthen a story — picture a ROBUST oak tree with double R and double O holding up your evidence."},{"w":"corrugated","def":"fold into ridges","ex":"The corrugated metal roof rattled loudly during the rainstorm, its wavy ridges channeling streams of water down into the gutters on both sides of the old farmhouse.","say":"KAW-ruh-gay-tihd","hook":"CORRUGATED cardboard has rippling ridges — spot the RUG hiding in cor-RUG-ated, wrinkled like a bunched-up rug."},{"w":"commemorate","def":"is to serve as a reminder of","ex":"The citizens mark the anniversary of the revolution with a march and a parade","say":"k-uh-m-EH-m-ur-ay-t","hook":"To COMMEMORATE you need a good MEMORY — spot MEM in the middle: com-MEM-orate."},{"w":"continuum","def":"a continuous nonspatial whole or extent or succession in which no part or portion is distinct or distinguishable from adjacent parts","ex":"The science teacher explained that visible light is actually part of a continuum of electromagnetic radiation stretching from radio waves to gamma rays.","say":"k-uh-n-t-IH-n-y-oo-uh-m","hook":"a continUUM has a double U — the sequence just keeps going, UU and on"},{"w":"convivial","def":"means friendly or agreeable","ex":"a convivial atmosphere at the reunion","say":"k-uh-n-v-IH-v-ee-uh-l","hook":"conVIVIal people are VIVID and ALIVE together — spot VIV meaning life"},{"w":"concupiscence","def":"a desire for sexual intimacy","ex":"Many medieval writers warned against concupiscence, urging people to focus on spiritual matters instead.","say":"kon-KYOO-pih-sens","hook":"CONCUPIScence — 'CUPId' hides inside, and Cupid sparks desire; remember CUPId = desire."}]},{"title":"mal- (bad / evil / ill)","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin malus = bad, evil. mal- is a reliable negative signal — every word it touches is associated with badness, illness, or wrongdoing. And it never assimilates: always spelled M-A-L.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>MALFEASANCE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> m-a-l-f-EE-z-uh-n-s\n<b>Spell it.</b> M · A · L · F · E · A · S · A · N · C · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> m-a-l-f-EE-z-uh-n-s\n<b>Syllables.</b> m · a · l · f · e · a · s · a · n · c · e\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [mal=MAL] [FEE=FEA] [zants=SANCE]\n<b>Exception.</b> -feasance from French faire = to do; -ance not -ence; /z/ sound in -eas-; stress: mal-FEE-zants\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> Latin malus = bad + French faisance = doing","cards":[{"title":"The mal- Signal","body":"Latin malus = bad, evil. Malfeasance = doing bad things in an official capacity. Malevolent (mal- + velle = wish) = wishing evil. Malicious = harboring ill intent. Malignant = growing in a harmful way. Maladroit (mal- + French adroit = skillful) = clumsy. Every mal- word carries its Latin warning."},{"title":"Perfect Opposites","body":"Every mal- word has a ben- counterpart: malevolent ↔ benevolent. Maleficent ↔ beneficent. Malignant ↔ benign. Malediction ↔ benediction. Knowing one side of each pair = knowing both. In a bee, if you know the ben- word, swap the prefix."},{"title":"Malaise & Malaria — Etymology is History","body":"Malaise (mal- + French aise = ease) = general feeling of being unwell. Malaria (mal- + Italian aria = air) = bad air — Italians blamed swamp air before mosquitoes were discovered. Word etymology literally records how humans once understood the world."},{"title":"Maladroit & Malapropism","body":"Maladroit (mal- + French adroit = skillful) = clumsy, lacking skill. Malapropism (mal- + French à propos = to the purpose) = a word wrongly used in place of a similar-sounding one. Example: \"for all intensive purposes\" instead of \"for all intents and purposes.\""},{"title":"Medical mal- Words","body":"Malignant = growing harmfully (opposite of benign). Malnutrition = insufficient or wrong nutrition. Malpractice = wrong professional practice. Malformation = wrong or abnormal formation. Malabsorption = poor absorption of nutrients. In medicine, mal- always signals something going wrong with the body's normal function."}],"words":[{"w":"malfeasance","def":"is wrongdoing by a public official","ex":"The city treasurer was removed from office after investigators uncovered evidence of blatant malfeasance.","say":"m-a-l-f-EE-z-uh-n-s","hook":"MALFEASance — a bad official does bad FEATS; end it with -ance, not -ence."},{"w":"malevolent","def":"wishing or appearing to wish evil to others; arising from intense ill will or hatred","ex":"The malevolent sorcerer cast a spell that turned the entire village's crops to ash overnight.","say":"muh-LEH-vuh-luhnt","hook":"MALEvolent = MALE (bad) + VOLENT (wishing) — wishing badly; ends in -lent not -lant"},{"w":"malicious","def":"marked by evil intention","ex":"The malicious rumor spread through the school within hours, and the damage it caused to the student's reputation took weeks of honest conversations to undo and repair completely.","say":"m-uh-l-IH-sh-uh-s","hook":"One L of malice is enough to be MALICIOUS — only one L: M-A-L-I-C-I-O-U-S."},{"w":"malignant","def":"tending to produce death or deterioration used in medicine","ex":"The doctor delivered the frightening news that the tumor was malignant and would require immediate treatment.","say":"m-uh-l-IH-g-n-uh-n-t","hook":"A MALIGNANT tumor is not gentle — remember the ANT at the end marching through: M-A-L-I-G-N-A-N-T."},{"w":"malodorous","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"malcontent","def":"a person who is discontented or disgusted","ex":"One malcontent in the group kept complaining that the camping trip was badly organized, ruining the mood for everyone.","say":"ma-lkuh-NTEHNT","hook":"A MALcontent is never content — mal means bad, and they feel bad about everything."},{"w":"malefactor","def":"someone who has committed a crime or has been legally convicted of a crime","ex":"The detective promised the town she would track down the malefactor responsible for the string of break-ins.","say":"MA-luh-fa-kter","hook":"A maleFACTOR is one who does (FACTOR) bad (MALE-) things — remember -or, not -er."},{"w":"malediction","def":"the act of calling down a curse that invokes evil (and usually serves as an insult)","ex":"he suffered the imprecations of the mob","say":"mal-eh-DIK-shun","hook":"MALE (bad) + DICTION (words): bad words spoken as a curse — opposite of benediction."},{"w":"malaise","def":"a general feeling of physical discomfort, illness, or mental unease","ex":"After staying up until 2 a.m. studying, Elena dragged herself to school feeling a heavy malaise that lasted all day.","say":"ma-LAYZ","hook":"MALAISE — MAL means BAD and you feel bad when you have malaise"},{"w":"malaria","def":"is a disease characterized by chills or fever caused by the bite of a mosquito","ex":"Aid workers distributed mosquito nets to the villages to help prevent the spread of malaria.","say":"m-uh-l-EH-r-ee-uh","hook":"MALARIA = MALA (bad) ARIA — bad air once thought to cause this fever; sing the 'a' in aria!"},{"w":"maladroit","def":"Lacking skill, dexterity, or cleverness; clumsy or awkward in movement, thought, or social situations, often causing embarrassing or unfortunate results due to poor judgment or coordination.","ex":"a maladroit movement of his hand caused the car to swerve","say":"ma-luh-DROYT","hook":"MAL-adroit: someone who does it all WRONG has no DROIT (right/skill)."},{"w":"malapropism","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"maleficent","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"malpractice","def":"professional wrongdoing that results in injury or damage","ex":"the widow sued his surgeon for malpractice","say":"ma-LPRA-ktuhs","hook":"Malpractice ends in '-tice' not '-tise' — bad practice with a C for Court case."},{"w":"malnutrition","def":"faulty nourishment due to a lack of or imbalance in substances that promote growth","ex":"The charity worked hard to provide food to children suffering from malnutrition in the drought-stricken region.","say":"m-a-l-n-oo-t-r-IH-sh-uh-n","hook":"MAL nutrition = BAD NUTRITION — spell it straight through: M-A-L-N-U-T-R-I-T-I-O-N."}]},{"title":"mis- (wrongly / badly)","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin/Old English mis- = wrongly, badly, or astray. When it meets a root beginning with s, the result is double-s. ⚠️ This is NOT the same as Greek misos (hatred) — same spelling, completely different origin.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>MISCHIEVOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> m-IH-s-ch-uh-v-uh-s\n<b>Spell it.</b> M · I · S · C · H · I · E · V · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> m-IH-s-ch-uh-v-uh-s\n<b>Syllables.</b> m · i · s · c · h · i · e · v · o · u · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [MIS=MIS] [chiv=CHIE] [us=VOUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> only 3 syllables: MIS-chiv-us — NOT mis-CHIEV-i-ous which is the most common mispronunciation error\n<b>Origin.</b> Anglo-Norman\n<b>Root.</b> Old French meschever = to meet with misfortune","cards":[{"title":"What mis- Signals","body":"mis- = done wrongly or badly. Miscellaneous (mis- + cella = room) = mixed into wrong rooms = varied kinds. Mischievous = mis- + chevir = achieving wrongly. ⚠️ MIS-chiev-ous = 3 syllables, NOT mis-CHIEV-i-ous = 4. The 4-syllable pronunciation is wrong and wrong spelling often follows it."},{"title":"High-Value mis- Words","body":"Miscreant (mis- + credere = believe wrongly) = villain. Misnomer (mis- + nomen = name) = a wrongly applied name. Misprision = wrongful concealment of knowledge of a crime. Misconstrue = interpret wrongly. Misanthrope starts with mis- but is Greek misos (hatred) — a different root entirely."},{"title":"mis- + s-root = double-s","body":"Misspell = M-I-S-S-P-E-L-L (one s from prefix, one from spell). Misstep = M-I-S-S-T-E-P. Misstate = M-I-S-S-T-A-T-E. The double-s is simply prefix mis- meeting a root that starts with s — not a doubling rule."},{"title":"When mis- is NOT a Prefix","body":"Miserable (miser = wretched in Latin) — the mis- is part of the root, not a prefix. Mistletoe = from Old English misteltan — the mis- is part of the ancient word. Test: remove mis- — if the remainder is not a standard English word, mis- is probably part of the root."},{"title":"mis- vs dis-","body":"Both can mean \"badly/not\" but: mis- = done in a wrong way; dis- = apart or the opposite of. Misguide = guide wrongly. Disuse = no longer in use. Misuse = use wrongly. Displace = move to a wrong place. Both prefixes describe something going wrong — the nuance is method (mis-) vs absence (dis-)."}],"words":[{"w":"mischievous","def":"is maliciously or playfully annoying","ex":"teasing and worrying with impish laughter","say":"m-IH-s-ch-uh-v-uh-s","hook":"Mischievous has no extra 'i' after the 'v' — a mischievous kid hides the extra letter just to trick you!"},{"w":"miscreant","def":"a person without moral scruples","ex":"The sheriff finally tracked down the miscreant who had been stealing from local farmers for months.","say":"MIH-skree-uhnt","hook":"A MISCREANT mis-CREATES chaos — spot CREATE in the middle; the villain CREATES misery."},{"w":"misnomer","def":"an incorrect or unsuitable name","ex":"Calling a starfish a fish is actually a misnomer, since starfish are not fish at all.","say":"mih-SNOH-mer","hook":"A MIS-NO-MER is a MISsed NAME — one R, no double letters, just a wrong label."},{"w":"misprision","def":"In law, the deliberate concealment of one's knowledge of a crime or treasonous act without actively participating in it; more broadly, a mistake, oversight, or neglect of duty.","ex":"The lawyer explained that misprision of a crime means knowing about it but failing to report it.","say":"mih-SPRIH-zhuh-n","hook":"MIS + PRISON — a mistake that could land you near a PRISON for staying silent."},{"w":"miscellaneous","def":"is of mixed character","ex":"an arrangement of assorted spring flowers","say":"m-ih-s-uh-l-AY-n-ee-uh-s","hook":"MISCELLANEOUS has CELL in it — a cell that holds ALL kinds of mixed things; no I before -ous."},{"w":"misanthrope","def":"someone who dislikes people in general","ex":"The grumpy misanthrope refused all party invitations and preferred to stay home alone.","say":"MIH-suh-nthrohp","hook":"A MISerable ANTHRO-PE-rson hates all people — 'anthro' sounds like 'and throw,' as if they'd throw everyone away."},{"w":"misconstrue","def":"interpret in the wrong way","ex":"Please don't misconstrue my silence as agreement — I was simply too shocked to respond right away.","say":"mih-skuh-NSTROO","hook":"misCONSTRUE — if you CONSTRUE something wrong you MISconstrue it; ends in -strue like construe"},{"w":"misspell","def":"spell incorrectly","ex":"It is surprisingly common to misspell the word 'necessary' by doubling the wrong consonant.","say":"mih-SSPEHL","hook":"Don't MISSPELL misspell—mis- plus spell gives you double s AND double l."},{"w":"misstep","def":"an unintentional but embarrassing blunder","ex":"he recited the whole poem without a single trip","say":"mih-SSTEHP","hook":"A misSSTEP has an extra S because you slipped on it — double S slows you down."},{"w":"misdemeanor","def":"a crime less serious than a felony","ex":"Jaywalking and minor vandalism are often classified as misdemeanors rather than serious felonies in most states.","say":"mih-sduh-MEE-ner","hook":"misDEMEANor — a bad DEMEANOR can be a misdemeanor; the -or spelling is American"},{"w":"misgiving","def":"uneasiness about the fitness of an action","ex":"Her heart misgave her that she had acted inexcusably","say":"mih-SGIH-vihng","hook":"A MISGIVING gives you a mis-gift: a knot of dread in your stomach."},{"w":"misapprehend","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"misanthropic","def":"Believing the worst of human nature and motives; having a sneering disbelief in, for example, the selflessness of others, and generally distrusting or disliking people.","ex":"The misanthropic hermit refused all visitors, convinced that people only caused trouble and heartbreak.","say":"mis-an-THROP-ik","hook":"MIS (hate) + ANTHRO (humans) + PIC — picture someone who hates the whole human photo album."},{"w":"misogyny","def":"hatred of women","ex":"The author's essay exposed the deep misogyny embedded in centuries of unfair laws targeting women.","say":"MIH-zuh-jih-nee","hook":"MISO-GYN-Y: the GYN is key — like GYNecology — hatred of women ends in -Y."}]},{"title":"inter- / intra- (between / within)","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin inter- = between two or more things. Latin intra- = inside or within one thing. One letter changes the entire meaning. Keeping them straight is one of the most useful vocabulary distinctions in English.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>INTRANSIGENT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ih-n-t-r-A-n-s-uh-j-uh-n-t\n<b>Spell it.</b> I · N · T · R · A · N · S · I · G · E · N · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> ih-n-t-r-A-n-s-uh-j-uh-n-t\n<b>Syllables.</b> i · n · t · r · a · n · s · i · g · e · n · t\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [in=IN] [TRAN=TRAN] [suh=SI] [jent=GENT]\n<b>Exception.</b> intra- + transigere = drive through; -ent not -ant; note: this uses intra- not inter-; stress: in-TRAN-suh-jent\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> Spanish intransigente = uncompromising","cards":[{"title":"The Essential Distinction","body":"inter- = between (separates two things). intra- = within (contains within one thing). International = between nations. Intramural = within the walls of one school. Intercollegiate = between colleges. Intravenous = within the vein. One letter. Entirely different meaning."},{"title":"Key inter- Words","body":"Intermezzo (inter- + Italian mezzo = middle) = piece played between acts. Intercede (inter- + cedere = go) = go between parties to help. Interpolate (inter- + polire = polish) = insert something between existing material. Internecine (inter- + nex = death) = destructive to both sides."},{"title":"Key intra- Words","body":"Intransigent (intra- + transigere = drive through) = not willing to move = stubbornly uncompromising. Intravenous = within the vein. Intracranial = within the skull. Intractable = not able to be handled. ⚠️ Intractable uses in- (negation) not intra- — always check before assuming!"},{"title":"Confusables","body":"Interpolate (insert between) vs extrapolate (extra- = outside = extend beyond known data — entirely different prefix and meaning). Interloper (inter- + Dutch lopen = run between) = one who intrudes. Interregnum (inter- + regnum = reign) = period between rulers — no doubling here."},{"title":"Spelling the inter-/intra- Words","body":"Intermezzo = I-N-T-E-R-M-E-Z-Z-O (Italian mezzo has double-z). Internecine = I-N-T-E-R-N-E-C-I-N-E (from nex = death, necis). Intravenous = I-N-T-R-A-V-E-N-O-U-S (four syllables). Intransigent = I-N-T-R-A-N-S-I-G-E-N-T (five syllables)."}],"words":[{"w":"intransigent","def":"is refusing to agree or compromise","ex":"he is adamant in his refusal to change his mind","say":"ih-n-t-r-A-n-s-uh-j-uh-n-t","hook":"An intransigENT person won't budge — like a stubborn GENT who ends in -ENT not -ANT."},{"w":"intermezzo","def":"is a short musical entertainment between the acts of a drama or opera","ex":"The audience murmured appreciatively as the orchestra performed a gentle intermezzo while the stagehands changed the scenery.","say":"in-tur-MET-soh","hook":"interMEZZO is played in the MIDDLE — MEZZanine, MEZZo — double Z like the buzz of an intermission."},{"w":"intercede","def":"is to act in behalf of someone in difficulty","ex":"He interceded in the family dispute","say":"ih-n-t-ur-s-EE-d","hook":"To interCEDE is to go between — it ends in CEDE like conCEDE; one E then D, not double E."},{"w":"interpolate","def":"estimate the value of","ex":"The scientist had to interpolate the missing data points on the graph to complete the temperature trend analysis.","say":"ih-TUR-puh-layt","hook":"To interPOLate is to POLish in a value between points — no extra O needed."},{"w":"internecine","def":"(of conflict) within a group or organization","ex":"The internecine rivalry between the two factions of the student council made it impossible to plan the school fair.","say":"ih-NTUR-nuh-seen","hook":"Internecine conflict KILLS (Latin nec) from within."},{"w":"intravenous","def":"means within a vein","ex":"an intravenous inflammation","say":"ih-n-t-r-uh-v-EE-n-uh-s","hook":"IntraVENous goes into the VEIN — VEN is the vein, and there's no I before -ous."},{"w":"intracranial","def":"within the skull","ex":"The doctor ordered a scan to check for any intracranial pressure that might explain the patient's severe headaches.","say":"ih-ntruh-KRAY-nee-uhl","hook":"INTRAcranial is inside the CRANIUM — the skull word cranium is hiding right there."},{"w":"intramural","def":"carried on within the bounds of an institution or community","ex":"most of the students participated actively in the college's intramural sports program","say":"ih-ntruh-MYUU-ruhl","hook":"Intramural sports stay within the MURAL walls of your own school — one R, like one wall."},{"w":"international","def":"any of several international socialist organizations","ex":"international affairs","say":"ih-nter-NA-shuh-nuhl","hook":"InterNATIONal puts NATION right in the center — nations between nations."},{"w":"intercollegiate","def":"used of competition between colleges or universities","ex":"intercollegiate basketball","say":"ih-nter-kuh-LEE-juht","hook":"IntercollegIATE sports happen between COLLEGEs — COLLEGE hides inside, ending in -IATE."},{"w":"interregnum","def":"is the time between the close of reign and the beginning of the next","ex":"During the interregnum, rival nobles fought bitterly for control of the kingdom before a new ruler was crowned.","say":"ih-n-t-ur-r-EH-g-n-uh-m","hook":"Between two REIGNS there is an inter-REGNUM — spot the REGN like 'reign' inside it."},{"w":"interloper","def":"someone who intrudes on the privacy or property of another without permission","ex":"The new student felt like an interloper when he accidentally walked into the wrong classroom during lunch.","say":"IH-nter-loh-per","hook":"An interloper LOPES (runs) in between where they don't belong."},{"w":"interstitial","def":"of or relating to interstices","ex":"The biology textbook explained how interstitial fluid fills the tiny spaces between cells throughout the body.","say":"ih-nter-STIH-shuhl","hook":"INTERSTITial: tiny spaces where things STAND BETWEEN — picture a small ad that STANDS IN THE MIDDLE of a webpage."},{"w":"intractable","def":"not tractable; difficult to manage or mold","ex":"an intractable disposition","say":"ih-NTRA-ktuh-buhl","hook":"An intractable problem can't be TRACT-ed, handled, or pulled — remember -able not -ible."}]},{"title":"trans- / per- (across / through)","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin trans- = across, beyond, or through complete change. Latin per- = through, thoroughly, completely. Both signal movement or penetration — but in different directions.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PERFIDIOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> —\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · E · R · F · I · D · I · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> —\n<b>Syllables.</b> p · e · r · f · i · d · i · o · u · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [per=PER] [FID=FID] [ee=I] [us=OUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> per- + fides = faith; -ious suffix; -fid- not -phid-; full meaning: thoroughly faithless; stress: per-FID-ee-us\n<b>Origin.</b> —\n<b>Root.</b> —","cards":[{"title":"trans- = Across","body":"Transcend (trans- + scandere = climb) = climb across and beyond limits. Transient = passing across quickly. Translucent (trans- + lucere = shine) = light shines across/through. Transmogrify = change entirely across forms. Transgress (trans- + gradi = step) = step across a boundary = violate."},{"title":"per- = Through/Thoroughly","body":"Perfidy (per- + fides = faith) = faith broken through = treachery. Pernicious (per- + nex = death) = thoroughly deadly. Perennial (per- + annus = year) = through all years = lasting. Perspicacious (per- + specere = look) = looking thoroughly = sharply perceptive. Perfunctory = done merely to get through it = superficial."},{"title":"Translucent vs Transparent","body":"Both involve light. Translucent (trans- + lucere = emit light) = light passes through but is scattered = you see glow, not clear shapes. Transparent (trans- + parere = appear) = light passes through clearly = you see through it. One lets you see a shape; the other only shows there is light."},{"title":"per- at the Microphone","body":"Per- is tricky because many per- words have it as part of the root: perceive (per- + capere = seize), permit (per- + mittere = send), perform (per- + French fournir). Asking for origin at the bee — if Latin and you hear \"per\" — probably a prefix."},{"title":"Spelling Traps","body":"Perennial = P-E-R-E-N-N-I-A-L (double-n from Latin annus). Persiflage (per- + French siffler = whistle) = P-E-R-S-I-F-L-A-G-E = light banter. Perspicuous (clearly expressed) vs perspicacious (sharply insightful) — both from per- + specere but different meanings."}],"words":[{"w":"perfidious","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"perfidy","def":"is a deliberate breach of trust treachery","ex":"The general's perfidy was revealed when he secretly passed battle plans to the enemy camp.","say":"p-UR-f-ih-d-ee","hook":"PERFIDY breaks FAITH — spot FID (from fides=faith) in the middle: per-FID-y, against faith."},{"w":"pernicious","def":"means ruinous injurious hurtful","ex":"glaucoma is an insidious disease","say":"p-ur-n-IH-sh-uh-s","hook":"PeRNICIOus is NASTY — spell out per-NI-CI-OUS: a perNICIOus villain is as NICkIng and devIOUS as they come."},{"w":"perennial","def":"is lasting for a long time enduring","ex":"the common buttercup is a popular perennial plant","say":"p-ur-EH-n-ee-uh-l","hook":"PERENNIAL has double N — two N's because it comes back Not once but Never-endingly, year after year."},{"w":"perspicacious","def":"acutely insightful and wise","ex":"The perspicacious young detective noticed a tiny mud stain on the suspect's shoe that everyone else had overlooked.","say":"per-spuh-KAY-shuhs","hook":"PER-SPIC-acious: someone who sees (SPIC) through everything"},{"w":"perspicuous","def":"is clearly expressed or presented","ex":"writes in a limpid style","say":"per-SPIK-yoo-us","hook":"PERSPICUOUS is clearly expressed — see SPIC (look) inside: clear enough to see straight through."},{"w":"perfunctory","def":"hasty and without attention to detail; not thorough","ex":"a casual (or cursory) inspection failed to reveal the house's structural flaws","say":"per-FUH-ngkter-ee","hook":"A perFUNCTory job is done without FUNCTION or care — spot FUNCT in the middle to spell it right."},{"w":"transcend","def":"to go beyond the limits of; to be greater in scope or significance than","ex":"Their loyalty exceeds their national bonds","say":"t-r-a-n-s-EH-n-d","hook":"TRANSCEND means to CLIMB BEYOND — TRANS(beyond)+SCEND(like ascend)."},{"w":"transient","def":"means not lasting or enduring","ex":"The joy of winning the spelling bee was intense but transient, quickly replaced by the nervous excitement of preparing for the next, far more difficult round of competition.","say":"t-r-A-n-zh-uh-n-t","hook":"TRANS-I-ENT: a transient is briefly going across — remember the I before ENT, like a tiny visitor passing through."},{"w":"translucent","def":"is letting pass through but not clearly","ex":"The translucent curtains let soft morning light filter gently into the room, casting pale golden shadows across the floor without revealing the private details of the space inside.","say":"t-r-a-n-s-l-OO-s-uh-n-t","hook":"transLUCent lets LUCY the light shine through — LUC holds the light, no extra S."},{"w":"transmogrify","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"transgress","def":"act in disregard of laws, rules, contracts, or promises","ex":"offend all laws of humanity","say":"tra-NZGREHS","hook":"TRANS-GRESS: to step across a line — GRESS has a double S because crossing rules makes a big MESS."},{"w":"transmute","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"persiflage","def":"light teasing","ex":"The two best friends engaged in cheerful persiflage all through lunch, poking fun at each other's fashion choices without any real malice.","say":"PUR-sih-flahzh","hook":"PERSIFLAGe — like blowing a WHISTLE at someone as a joke"},{"w":"perquisite","def":"is a gratuity or tip","ex":"a limousine is one of the fringe benefits of the job","say":"p-UR-k-w-uh-z-ih-t","hook":"A perquisite is a perk — PERQUISite hides QUIS (Latin for seek), and seekers earn their perks."},{"w":"pertinacious","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""}]},{"title":"ab- / abs- (away from / off)","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin ab- = away from, off, or down from. Before s and t it becomes abs-. Before v it shortens to a-. One of the cleanest-meaning prefixes in Latin: it always signals departure.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>ABSCOND</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> a-BSKAHND\n<b>Spell it.</b> A · B · S · C · O · N · D\n<b>Say it again.</b> a-BSKAHND\n<b>Syllables.</b> ae · bskaa · nd\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [ab=AB] [SKOND=SCOND]\n<b>Exception.</b> -scond- from Latin condere = to hide; abs- before sc cluster; stress: ab-SKOND; note ab+scond not abs+cond\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin abscondere = to hide away, from ab-(away)+condere(to hide/store)","cards":[{"title":"ab- = Away From","body":"Aberrant (ab- + errare = wander) = wandering away from the norm. Abjure (ab- + jurare = swear) = swear away from = formally renounce. Abrogate (ab- + rogare = ask) = repeal formally. Ablution (ab- + luere = wash) = washing away = ritual cleansing. Abnegate = deny oneself = renounce."},{"title":"abs- Before s/t","body":"Abscond = abs- + condere (hide) = hide oneself away and flee. Abstain = abs- + tenere (hold) = hold away from = voluntarily refrain. Abstinence = state of holding away. Abstruse = abs- + trudere (push) = pushed away = hard to understand. Abstract = abs- + trahere (draw) = drawn away from the concrete."},{"title":"a- Before v (shortened ab-)","body":"Avert (a- + vertere = turn) = turn away. Aversion = strong turning-away feeling = deep dislike. Aversive = causing avoidance. Avow = a- + Latin vocare = voice outward = declare openly. These are the same prefix as ab- — just shortened before v."},{"title":"Abstemious & Abstract","body":"Abstemious (abs- + temetum = strong drink) = holding away from excess = moderate in eating and drinking. The -stemi- is hard to spell: A-B-S-T-E-M-I-O-U-S. Abstract = abs- + trahere = drawn away from the concrete = existing in thought not in physical form."},{"title":"ab- vs de- vs ex-","body":"All three move away from something. ab- = departing from. de- = going down from or reversing. ex- = out of. Abhor = shrink away from with disgust. Detest = hate thoroughly. Exclude = shut out. The prefix marks direction and intensity of the movement away."}],"words":[{"w":"abscond","def":"run away; usually includes taking something or somebody along","ex":"The thief made off with our silver","say":"a-BSKAHND","hook":"To abSCOND is to SCOOT and hide CONDtemptibly — the thief abSCONDed with the cash."},{"w":"aberrant","def":"Departing from the normal or expected course; straying from the usual type or standard.","ex":"The biologist discovered an aberrant specimen with an unusual coloration that set it apart from every other member of the species.","say":"a-BEH-ruhnt","hook":"AB (away) + ERR (wander) + ANT: something that wanders away from the norm"},{"w":"abjure","def":"formally reject or disavow a formerly held belief, usually under pressure","ex":"Under intense questioning, the scientist refused to abjure his groundbreaking theory despite the committee's pressure.","say":"ab-JOOR","hook":"To ABJURE is to swear (JURE) something AWAY — like a juror who renounces the verdict; keep the U-R-E."},{"w":"abrogate","def":"revoke formally","ex":"The new government moved quickly to abrogate the outdated treaty that had been in place for over a century.","say":"A-bruh-gayt","hook":"ABROgate — AB-olish + ROGue laws; a rogue leader abrogates the rules"},{"w":"ablution","def":"the ritual washing of a priest's hands or of sacred vessels","ex":"Before the ceremony began, the priest performed an ablution, carefully washing his hands over a golden basin.","say":"uh-BLOO-shuhn","hook":"ABLUTion: think 'ab-LOOT' — washing away impurities, spelled with a U not OO: ab-LU-tion."},{"w":"abnegate","def":"deny oneself (something); restrain, especially from indulging in some pleasure","ex":"The monk chose to abnegate all worldly possessions before entering the monastery.","say":"AB-nih-gayt","hook":"ABNEGATe = ab + NEGATE — to abnegate is to negate yourself, to push yourself AWAY (ab-)."},{"w":"abstain","def":"refrain from voting","ex":"I abstain from alcohol","say":"uh-BSTAYN","hook":"AbsTAIN — hold yourself away, like a stain you refuse to make: ends in -a-i-n."},{"w":"abstemious","def":"sparing in consumption of especially food and drink; - John Galsworthy","ex":"the pleasures of the table, never of much consequence to one naturally abstemious","say":"ab-STEE-mee-uhs","hook":"An abstemious person stays away from temetum — remember the rare -emi- in the middle, not -emy-."},{"w":"abstinence","def":"the trait of abstaining (especially from alcohol)","ex":"The athlete's strict abstinence from sugary drinks helped her maintain peak performance throughout the entire season.","say":"A-bstuh-nuhns","hook":"Abstinence ends in -ence (not -ance) — remember: it takes diligENCE to practice abstinENCE."},{"w":"abstruse","def":"difficult to penetrate; incomprehensible to one of ordinary understanding or knowledge","ex":"The professor's abstruse explanation of quantum mechanics left even the advanced students scratching their heads in confusion.","say":"uh-BSTROOS","hook":"ABSTRUSe — ABSTRact and conFUSEd — if it's abstruse, you're confused"},{"w":"abstract","def":"a concept or idea not associated with any specific instance","ex":"he loved her only in the abstract--not in person","say":"a-BSTRAKT","hook":"Abstract ideas are DRAWN AWAY from reality — tractors DRAW, so abs-TRACT means drawn away."},{"w":"aversion","def":"a feeling of intense dislike","ex":"averting her gaze meant that she was angry","say":"uh-VUR-zhuhn","hook":"An aVERSION turns you AWAY — picture VERSing someone you hate and turning your back."},{"w":"avert","def":"prevent the occurrence of; prevent from happening","ex":"Let's avoid a confrontation","say":"uh-VURT","hook":"aVERT: turn away danger with VERT (turn) — like diVERT or reVERT, same turning root."},{"w":"aversive","def":"tending to repel or dissuade","ex":"aversive conditioning","say":"uh-VUR-suhv","hook":"aVERSIVE ends in -IVE because it's actIVE in pushing you away — remember the I before VE."},{"w":"abominate","def":"find repugnant","ex":"Many people abominate cruelty to animals and work hard to prevent it.","say":"uh-BOM-ih-nayt","hook":"You abominate bad OMENS — spot 'omin' hiding inside abomINate."},{"w":"abscissa","def":"the value of a coordinate on the horizontal axis","ex":"In math class, we plotted each point by finding its abscissa along the horizontal axis.","say":"ab-SIS-ah","hook":"abSCISSa has double-s like a pair of scissor blades — it cuts across the x-axis."}]},{"title":"ad- (toward / near) — the Great Assimilator","category":"Latin Prefixes","difficulty":"hard","concept":"Latin ad- = toward, near, in addition to. It is the most enthusiastic assimilator in Latin — it changes its final d to match whatever consonant follows, doubling it in the process. The doubled letter IS the prefix.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>ASSIDUOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> uh-SIH-dwuhs\n<b>Spell it.</b> A · S · S · I · D · U · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> uh-SIH-dwuhs\n<b>Syllables.</b> ah · sih · dwah · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [uh=AS] [SIJ=SID] [oo=U] [us=OUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> double-S from ad+s assimilation (ad+siduous → assiduous); -uous not -ious; stress: uh-SIJ-oo-us\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin 'assiduus' = constantly present, from 'assidere' = to sit beside","cards":[{"title":"The Full Assimilation Chart","body":"ad- + consonant → double that consonant. Before c/q → ac-: acquire, acquiesce. Before f → af-: affect, affirm. Before g → ag-: aggrandize, aggravate. Before l → al-: alleviate, allure. Before n → an-: annotate, annihilate. Before p → ap-: appease, append. Before r → ar-: arraign. Before s → as-: assiduous, assimilate. Before t → at-: attenuate, attrition."},{"title":"ac- Words","body":"Acquiesce (ac- + quiescere = rest) = agree without protest. Accolade (ac- + French col = neck) = embrace/award. Acquit (ac- + quietare = set at rest) = declare not guilty. Accrue (ac- + crescere = grow) = accumulate over time. Double-c is the ac- assimilation signal."},{"title":"al- Words","body":"Alleviate (al- + levis = light) = make lighter = ease pain. Allure (al- + lure) = draw toward with appeal. Allude (al- + ludere = play) = hint toward. Allocate (al- + locus = place) = assign toward a purpose. Double-l is the al- assimilation signal."},{"title":"ap- Words","body":"Appease (ap- + pacare = pacify) = satisfy a demand. Approbation (ap- + probare = prove) = formal approval. Append (ap- + pendere = hang) = add on. Appropriate = ap- + proprius = take for one's own use. Double-p is the ap- assimilation signal."},{"title":"as- and at- Words","body":"Assiduous (as- + sedere = sit) = diligently attending = persistently hardworking. Assimilate (as- + similis = like) = absorb and become like. Attenuate (at- + tenuis = thin) = reduce in force or density. Attrition (at- + terere = rub) = gradual wearing away. The doubled letter always reveals the ad- prefix."}],"words":[{"w":"assiduous","def":"marked by care and persistent effort","ex":"The assiduous student reviewed her notes every evening and never missed a homework assignment, which is why she earned the top grade.","say":"uh-SIH-dwuhs","hook":"assiDUous — an assiduous person is always DUE to be at their desk working"},{"w":"acquiesce","def":"to agree or express agreement","ex":"After hours of debate, Marcus finally decided to acquiesce to his teammates' plan even though he still had doubts about it.","say":"a-kwee-EHS","hook":"ACQUIesce — QUIET agreement; when you acquiesce, you quietly give in"},{"w":"accolade","def":"a tangible symbol signifying approval or distinction","ex":"an award for bravery","say":"A-kuh-layd","hook":"An acCOLade is a hug around the COLlar — reward spelled with double C and ends in -lade."},{"w":"acquit","def":"pronounce not guilty of criminal charges","ex":"The suspect was cleared of the murder charges","say":"uh-KWIHT","hook":"To acquit is to quietly free someone — keep the 'c' before 'quit' to set them free."},{"w":"accrue","def":"grow by addition","ex":"The interest accrues","say":"uh-KROO","hook":"Your savings accrue — the account gets a double 'c' bonus before '-rue'."},{"w":"alleviate","def":"provide physical relief, as from pain","ex":"This pill will relieve your headaches","say":"uh-LEE-vee-ayt","hook":"To allevIATE, think 'a LEVY lifted' — LEVI carries the light load, ending in -ATE."},{"w":"allure","def":"the power to entice or attract through personal charm","ex":"We were tempted by the delicious-looking food","say":"uh-LUUR","hook":"The allure of a fishing LURE draws fish in — all-LURE ends with the very bait it describes."},{"w":"allude","def":"make a more or less disguised reference to","ex":"He alluded to the problem but did not mention it","say":"uh-LOOD","hook":"To allude is to playfully hint — think of a court JESTER who PLAYS (ludere) at the truth with double l's."},{"w":"allocate","def":"distribute according to a plan or set apart for a special purpose","ex":"I am allocating a loaf of bread to everyone on a daily basis","say":"A-luh-kayt","hook":"ALLOCATE: to assign a LOCation — the LOC in the middle tells you it's about placing things."},{"w":"appease","def":"cause to be more favorably inclined; gain the good will of","ex":"She managed to mollify the angry customer","say":"uh-PEEZ","hook":"AppEASE — to appease someone is to bring them EASE and PEACE; double P then EASE."},{"w":"approbation","def":"official approval","ex":"The young playwright beamed with pride when she received the approbation of the theater's most respected critic.","say":"a-pruh-BAY-shuhn","hook":"Approbation has 'probe' in it — the committee must PROBE a plan before giving official approval."},{"w":"append","def":"add to the very end","ex":"He appended a glossary to his novel where he used an invented language","say":"uh-PEHND","hook":"APPEND has double P — picture hanging two P's at the end of a document."},{"w":"appropriate","def":"give or assign a resource to a particular person or cause","ex":"I will earmark this money for your research","say":"uh-PROH-pree-uht","hook":"Two P's are PROPER when you APPROPRIATE: ap-PROPRI-ate — the double-P is part of 'proper' ownership."},{"w":"attenuate","def":"weaken the consistency of (a chemical substance)","ex":"the faded tones of an old recording","say":"uh-TEH-nyoo-ayt","hook":"ATTENUATE makes something thin — picture a double-t tightrope getting thinner and thinner until it's a fine line."},{"w":"attrition","def":"erosion by friction","ex":"The marathon's brutal heat and steep hills caused significant attrition among the runners, and by mile twenty only half of the original field remained strong enough to finish.","say":"uh-TRIH-shuhn","hook":"atTRITion — the double-T army was ground down through attrition; keep both T's standing."},{"w":"aggrandize","def":"add details to","ex":"The politician tried to aggrandize his modest role in the project, claiming credit for ideas that weren't his.","say":"uh-GRA-ndeyez","hook":"To AGGRANDIZE your GRAND plans, you need DOUBLE G to make them truly GREAT — end in -IZE."},{"w":"annihilate","def":"kill in large numbers","ex":"The invading army threatened to annihilate every village in its path, leaving nothing but ash and silence.","say":"uh-NEYE-uh-layt","hook":"ANNIhilate contains ANNI — double N, double L in the middle"},{"w":"arraign","def":"call before a court to answer an indictment","ex":"The suspect was arraigned on Monday morning, and the judge read the charges aloud before setting a bail amount.","say":"er-AYN","hook":"arraIGN — contains REIGN; a king REIGNS in court where you are arraigned"},{"w":"affidavit","def":"written declaration made under oath; a written statement sworn to be true before someone legally authorized to administer an oath","ex":"The witness submitted an affidavit confirming she had seen the defendant at the park that afternoon.","say":"a-fuh-DAY-vuht","hook":"He has stated his FAITH — affidavit ends in 'davit,' like a sworn DAVid staTEment."}]},{"title":"anti- / hyper- / hypo- (against / over / under)","category":"Greek Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Greek anti- = against, hyper- = over/excessive, hypo- = under/insufficient. In medicine, knowing the prefix IS knowing the diagnosis. In literature, hyperbole and hypocrisy are built from this same trio.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>HYPERBOLE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> h-ay-p-UR-b-uh-l-ee\n<b>Spell it.</b> H · Y · P · E · R · B · O · L · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> h-ay-p-UR-b-uh-l-ee\n<b>Syllables.</b> h · y · p · e · r · b · o · l · e\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [hy=HY] [PER=PER] [buh=BO] [lee=LE]\n<b>Exception.</b> final -e is NOT silent — it is pronounced /ee/ (Greek!); -bole from ballein = throw; hy-PER-buh-lee\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Greek hyper=beyond + ballein=to throw","cards":[{"title":"anti- = Against","body":"Antipathy (anti- + pathos) = feeling against = deep dislike. Antithesis = placed against = direct opposite. Antidote (anti- + didonai = give) = given against a poison. Anticlimactic = against the expected climax = disappointingly flat after a buildup. Antipodal (anti- + pous = foot) = feet opposite = exactly opposite side of the earth."},{"title":"hyper- = Over/Excessive","body":"Hyperbole (hyper- + ballein = throw) = throwing over = deliberate exaggeration for effect. Hypertrophy (hyper- + trophe = nourishment) = excessive growth. Hyperopia (hyper- + ops = eye) = over-seeing = farsightedness. Hypercritical = excessively critical. Hyperventilate = breathe excessively fast."},{"title":"hypo- = Under/Insufficient","body":"Hypothesis (hypo- + thesis = placing) = placed under consideration. Hypocrisy (hypo- + krinein = judge) = judging from under a mask = pretending to have values you lack. Hypochondria (hypo- + khondros = cartilage) = below the ribs = once thought the seat of anxiety."},{"title":"Medical hyper-/hypo- Pairs","body":"Hypertension = blood pressure TOO HIGH. Hypotension = TOO LOW. Hyperthyroid = thyroid overactive. Hypothyroid = underactive. Hyperglycemia = too much blood sugar. Hypoglycemia = too little. Knowing prefix = knowing diagnosis. One pattern unlocks twelve medical terms."},{"title":"Spelling Traps","body":"Hyperbole ends in -le and the e is PRONOUNCED: hy-PER-buh-lee. Hypocrisy = H-Y-P-O-C-R-I-S-Y (not -acy). Hypothesis → plural hypotheses (Greek -es plural). Antipathy = A-N-T-I-P-A-T-H-Y (-thy not -thee). The -th- = /th/ from Greek theta."}],"words":[{"w":"antipathy","def":"a feeling of intense dislike","ex":"The two rival teams developed a deep antipathy toward each other after years of intense competition.","say":"a-NTIH-puh-thee","hook":"ANTI-PATHy — you are on the ANTI PATH to liking someone"},{"w":"antithesis","def":"exact opposite","ex":"Wearing pajamas to school would be the antithesis of the dress code the principal had just announced.","say":"a-NTIH-thuh-suhs","hook":"ANTI + THESIS — the opposite of your thesis"},{"w":"antidote","def":"a remedy that stops or controls the effects of a poison","ex":"The doctor administered the antidote quickly after the child accidentally swallowed a toxic substance.","say":"A-ntih-doht","hook":"ANTIDOTE: the DOT in the middle is your cure — find the DOT and you've found the remedy."},{"w":"anticlimactic","def":"of or relating to a sudden change from an impressive to a ludicrous style","ex":"everything after the discovery of the murderer was anticlimactic","say":"a-ntee-kleye-MA-ktihk","hook":"antiCLIMACtIC: spot CLIMAC in the middle — it climbs up then crashes down, just like the meaning."},{"w":"antipodal","def":"the relation of opposition along a diameter","ex":"antipodean latitudes","say":"a-NTIH-puh-duhl","hook":"ANTIPODal — their PODS (feet) point opposite to yours through the earth."},{"w":"hyperbole","def":"is obvious exaggeration","ex":"Saying you have a million hours of homework is a classic hyperbole that most students use every week.","say":"h-ay-p-UR-b-uh-l-ee","hook":"HyperbolE ends in a silent E — that silent E is itself an exaggeration, throwing sound beyond the word."},{"w":"hypertrophy","def":"abnormal enlargement of a body part or organ","ex":"The cardiologist warned that the patient's heart hypertrophy, caused by years of untreated high blood pressure, needed immediate treatment.","say":"HEYE-per-troh-fee","hook":"HYPER(too much)+TROPHY = a body part that 'wins' too much growth"},{"w":"hyperopia","def":"abnormal condition in which vision for distant objects is better than for near objects","ex":"Her optometrist diagnosed her with hyperopia, explaining why she could read the distant scoreboard but not her textbook.","say":"heye-per-OH-pee-ah","hook":"HyperOPIA — the OP in the middle are your OPtics seeing too far BEYOND; end simply with -IA."},{"w":"hypothesis","def":"is a proposition set forth to explain some occurrence","ex":"a scientific hypothesis that survives experimental testing becomes a scientific theory","say":"h-ay-p-AH-th-uh-s-uh-s","hook":"A hypoTHESIS is a THESIS placed UNDER scrutiny — it literally contains the word THESIS inside it."},{"w":"hypocrisy","def":"is pretending to something that one doesn't believe","ex":"The politician's hypocrisy was exposed when reporters discovered he had broken the very law he championed.","say":"h-ih-p-AH-k-r-uh-s-ee","hook":"HYPOcrites CRISP-ly say one thing and do another — spell the CRISIS of fakery: h-y-p-o-c-r-i-s-y."},{"w":"hypochondria","def":"chronic and abnormal anxiety about imaginary symptoms and ailments","ex":"Whenever Marcus read about a new disease online, his hypochondria convinced him he had every symptom listed on the page.","say":"heye-puh-KAH-ndree-uh","hook":"HYPO-CHONDRIA: always worried about what's UNDER your CHEST"},{"w":"hypocaust","def":"a central heating system of an ancient Roman building consisting of an underground furnace and a series of tile flues for distribution of the heat.","ex":"The Roman bathhouse was kept warm by a hypocaust, which circulated hot air beneath the tiled floors.","say":"HY-poh-kawst","hook":"A HYPOcaust burns HYPO (under) the floor — the Romans CAUSed heat below their feet."},{"w":"hypertension","def":"a common disorder in which blood pressure remains abnormally high (a reading of 140/90 mm Hg or greater)","ex":"The doctor advised the patient to reduce salt intake and exercise regularly to manage his hypertension.","say":"heye-per-TEH-nshuhn","hook":"HyperTENSION is spelled with -SION not -TION — the TENSION is already in the word, don't change it."},{"w":"hypotension","def":"abnormally low blood pressure","ex":"After standing up too quickly, Marcus experienced a brief spell of hypotension that made the room spin.","say":"heye-poh-TEH-nshuhn","hook":"HypoTENSION is LOW blood TENSION (pressure) — hypo pulls the number DOWN, hyper pushes it UP."},{"w":"hyperglycemia","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"hypoglycemia","def":"abnormally low blood sugar usually resulting from excessive insulin or a poor diet","ex":"The athlete felt dizzy and shaky during practice, and her doctor later diagnosed her with hypoglycemia.","say":"heye-poh-gleye-SEE-mee-uh","hook":"HypoGLYCEMIA: GLYCE sounds like GLYCERIN (sweet) — too LITTLE sugar in the blood, so you feel icky: -emia at the end."}]},{"title":"auto- / tele- / micro- / macro- / mega-","category":"Greek Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Five Greek prefixes of size and distance — from \"self\" to \"far,\" from \"tiny\" to \"enormous.\" These appear in science, technology, and everyday vocabulary. Learning them unlocks everything from microscope to megalomania.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>AUTOMATON</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> aw-t-AH-m-uh-t-ah-n\n<b>Spell it.</b> A · U · T · O · M · A · T · O · N\n<b>Say it again.</b> aw-t-AH-m-uh-t-ah-n\n<b>Syllables.</b> a · u · t · o · m · a · t · o · n\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [aw=AU] [TOM=TO] [uh=MA] [ton=TON]\n<b>Exception.</b> -maton from Greek matos = acting of itself; -on not -an; stress: aw-TOM-uh-ton; plural automatons or automata\n<b>Origin.</b> Greek\n<b>Root.</b> Greek automatos = acting of itself","cards":[{"title":"auto- = Self","body":"Automaton (auto- + matos = acting) = acts by itself. Autophagy (auto- + phagein = eat) = a cell digests itself. Autodidact (auto- + didaskein = teach) = self-taught person. Autocracy (auto- + kratos = rule) = rule by one person alone. Autonomy (auto- + nomos = law) = self-governance."},{"title":"tele- = Far","body":"Telepathy (tele- + pathos) = feeling from far away. Teleology (tele- + logos) = study of purposes/ends. Telekinesis (tele- + kinesis = movement) = moving things from a distance. Telegraph = write from far. Telescope = see far. Telemetry = measure from far (used in spacecraft)."},{"title":"micro- vs macro-","body":"Microcosm (mikros = small + kosmos) = small world. Macrocosm = the large or entire world. Microscope = looks at tiny things. Macroscopic = visible to the naked eye. Microphone = makes small voices large. Macroeconomics = large-scale economics. Small vs large — one prefix difference."},{"title":"mega- = Very Large","body":"Megalomania (mega- + mania) = delusions of great power. Megalopolis (mega- + polis = city) = a vast metropolitan area. Megalith (mega- + lithos = stone) = a very large stone (like Stonehenge). Megahertz = one million cycles per second. mega- became a general intensifier in everyday language."},{"title":"Spelling Traps","body":"Automaton = A-U-T-O-M-A-T-O-N (singular); Greek plural = automata. Telepathy ends in -thy not -tee. Megalomaniac = M-E-G-A-L-O-M-A-N-I-A-C. Autodidact = A-U-T-O-D-I-D-A-C-T. Each is built precisely from Greek parts — if you know the roots, you can spell the word."}],"words":[{"w":"automaton","def":"is another word for a robot","ex":"only an automaton wouldn't have noticed","say":"aw-t-AH-m-uh-t-ah-n","hook":"An autoMATon is ONE robot acting on its own — singular, one T, ends in -on."},{"w":"autophagy","def":"The biological process by which a cell breaks down and recycles its own damaged or unnecessary components.","ex":"Scientists discovered that autophagy helps cells survive periods of starvation by digesting their own proteins for energy.","say":"aw-TOF-uh-jee","hook":"AUTO (self) + PHAGY (eating) — the cell eats itself"},{"w":"autodidact","def":"a person who has taught himself","ex":"The famous inventor was a proud autodidact who had never attended college yet revolutionized electrical engineering.","say":"aw-toh-DY-dakt","hook":"AUTO (self) + DIDACT (teach) = self-taught person."},{"w":"autocracy","def":"a political system governed by a single individual","ex":"The citizens grew frustrated living under an autocracy where a single ruler made every decision without question.","say":"aw-TAH-kruh-see","hook":"AUTO-CRACY: one ruler rules by themselves — C-R-A-C-Y, like democracy but with AUTO in front."},{"w":"autonomy","def":"immunity from arbitrary exercise of authority: political independence","ex":"The teenagers appreciated the autonomy their teacher gave them to choose their own research topics.","say":"aw-TAH-nuh-mee","hook":"AutoNOMy = self-law — NOM not NAM, think of NORMS you set for yourself."},{"w":"telepathy","def":"is communication between minds","ex":"The twins seemed to communicate by telepathy, finishing each other's sentences without hesitation.","say":"t-uh-l-EH-p-uh-th-ee","hook":"TELEPATHY: feelings travel a long TELE-PATH-Y — the PATH is right there in the middle of the word!"},{"w":"teleology","def":"a philosophical doctrine that explains phenomena by the purposes or goals they serve rather than by prior causes","ex":"In philosophy class, we debated teleology — whether nature has built-in purposes, like how eyes seem perfectly designed for seeing.","say":"TEE-lee-aw-luh-jee","hook":"TELE-OLOGY — studying the TELOS (end goal) of everything"},{"w":"telekinesis","def":"the power to move something by thinking about it without the application of physical force","ex":"In the movie, the girl used telekinesis to slam the door without ever touching it.","say":"teh-leh-kih-NEE-sis","hook":"TELE (far) + KINESIS (movement) — moving things from far away; remember 'kinetic energy' for the 'kinesis' part."},{"w":"telegraph","def":"apparatus used to communicate at a distance over a wire (usually in Morse code)","ex":"The telegraph revolutionized long-distance communication in the nineteenth century, allowing news to travel in minutes rather than days.","say":"TEH-luh-graf","hook":"A TELEGRAPH GRAPHS writing from FAR away — ends in -GRAPH like photograph and autograph!"},{"w":"telescope","def":"a magnifier of images of distant objects","ex":"In the accident, the cars telescoped","say":"TEH-luh-skohp","hook":"A TELESCOPE lets you SCOPE (look) from TELE (far) — scope out distant stars!"},{"w":"microcosm","def":"is a world in miniature","ex":"The tiny tide pool was a microcosm of the ocean, filled with crabs, snails, and darting fish.","say":"m-AY-k-r-uh-k-ah-z-uh-m","hook":"A microCOSM is a small COSMos — spot COSM inside, like cosmonaut, and you'll never misspell it."},{"w":"macrocosm","def":"everything that exists anywhere; the whole universe","ex":"The philosopher argued that every human life is a microcosm that reflects the patterns of the larger macrocosm.","say":"MAK-roh-koz-um","hook":"MACROcosm = MACRO (big) + COSM (cosmos/universe)"},{"w":"microscope","def":"magnifier of the image of small objects","ex":"the invention of the microscope led to the discovery of the cell","say":"MEYE-kruh-skohp","hook":"A MICROSCOPE lets you SCOPE out (look at) MICRO (tiny) things—micro+scope."},{"w":"microphone","def":"device for converting sound waves into electrical energy","ex":"The nervous singer tapped the microphone to check if the audience could hear her.","say":"MEYE-kruh-fohn","hook":"A MICROPHONE amplifies small PHONE (sound)—micro+phone, just like telephone and saxophone."},{"w":"megalomania","def":"a psychological state characterized by delusions of grandeur","ex":"The dictator's megalomania was evident when he ordered statues of himself placed in every public square in the country.","say":"meh-guh-loh-MAY-nee-uh","hook":"A megalomaniac thinks they're MEGA great to the point of MANIA — one L in megalo, double the delusion."},{"w":"megalopolis","def":"a very large urban complex (usually involving several cities and towns)","ex":"The northeastern coast of the United States forms a megalopolis stretching from Boston all the way down to Washington, D.C.","say":"meh-guh-LAH-puh-luhs","hook":"A MEGALOPOLIS is a MEGA POLIS — a super-city; 'polis' means city in Greek, just like metropolis."},{"w":"megalith","def":"memorial consisting of a very large stone forming part of a prehistoric structure (especially in western Europe)","ex":"Each massive megalith at the ancient site weighed several tons and had been dragged miles across the plain.","say":"MEG-uh-lith","hook":"A MEGA LITH is a MEGA stone — think of Stonehenge; 'lith' always means stone, spelled L-I-T-H."},{"w":"telemetry","def":"automatic transmission and measurement of data from remote sources by wire or radio or other means","ex":"Mission controllers monitored the astronaut's heart rate through telemetry sent directly from sensors aboard the spacecraft.","say":"tuh-LEH-muh-tree","hook":"TELEMETRY MEASURES from afar — TELE+METRY, and METER is hiding right in the middle!"}]},{"title":"bio- / geo- / photo- / hydro- / thermo-","category":"Greek Prefixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Five Greek scientific prefixes — life, earth, light, water, heat — forming the backbone of natural science vocabulary. Every science class uses them; every spelling bee tests them. All require ph not f.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PHOTOSYNTHESIS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> f-oh-t-oh-s-IH-n-th-uh-s-ih-s\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · H · O · T · O · S · Y · N · T · H · E · S · I · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> f-oh-t-oh-s-IH-n-th-uh-s-ih-s\n<b>Syllables.</b> p · h · o · t · o · s · y · n · t · h · e · s · i · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [foh=PHO] [toh=TO] [SIN=SYN] [thuh=THE] [sis=SIS]\n<b>Exception.</b> photo- = light; -syn- = together; -thesis = placing; -th- = /th/ (Greek theta); ph not f = Greek signal\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Greek photos = light + synthesis = putting together","cards":[{"title":"bio- = Life","body":"Biology = study of life. Biome = a life community. Biopsy (bio- + opsis = seeing) = visual examination of living tissue. Symbiosis (sym- + bio-) = living together mutually. Antibiotic (anti- + bio-) = substance that kills living organisms (bacteria). All life is bio-."},{"title":"geo- = Earth","body":"Geography = writing about the earth. Geology = study of earth. Geothermal = earth-heat. Geodesic (geo- + daiein = divide) = shortest path on a sphere. Geocentric = earth-centered view. Apogee (apo- + geo-) = point in orbit farthest from earth."},{"title":"photo- = Light","body":"Photosynthesis = plants make food from light. Photogenic = looks good in light. Photon = a particle of light. Photograph = written by light. Photophobia = sensitivity to light. ⚠️ All photo- words use ph — never f — because this is Greek."},{"title":"hydro- = Water","body":"Hydrolysis (hydro- + lysis = breaking) = breaking by water. Hydroponics = growing in water. Hydraulic (hydro- + aulos = pipe) = water through pipes. Hydrophobia = fear of water. Dehydrate = de- + hydro- = remove water from."},{"title":"thermo- = Heat","body":"Thermometer = measures heat. Thermostat (thermo- + statos = standing) = keeps heat steady. Thermodynamics = study of heat and energy. Endothermic (endo- = within) = absorbs heat. Exothermic (exo- = out) = releases heat. Note: geothermal combines both geo- and thermo- in one word."}],"words":[{"w":"biology","def":"the science that studies living organisms","ex":"the biology of viruses","say":"beye-AH-luh-jee","hook":"BIO + LOGY — every -logy word studies something; this one studies life (bio). Don't skip the 'o' in logy."},{"w":"biome","def":"a major biotic community characterized by the dominant forms of plant life and the prevailing climate","ex":"The rainforest biome supports more species of plants and animals than any other on Earth.","say":"BEYE-ohm","hook":"A BIOMEis a living HOME — HOME and BIOME both end in '-ome,' and every biome is a home for life."},{"w":"biopsy","def":"examination of tissues or liquids from the living body to determine the existence or cause of a disease","ex":"The doctor ordered a biopsy of the unusual tissue to determine whether it was cancerous.","say":"BEYE-ah-psee","hook":"A bioPS-Y is a doctor's way of taking a SPY look at living tissue — bioPSY ends in -PSY like autoPSY."},{"w":"symbiosis","def":"the relation between two different species of organisms that are interdependent; each gains benefits from the other","ex":"The clownfish and the sea anemone demonstrate a classic example of symbiosis, each protecting and benefiting the other in the ocean.","say":"sih-mbeye-OH-suhs","hook":"SYMBIOsis — SYM + BIO: two species sharing one BIO(logy) class together, the perfect partnership."},{"w":"antibiotic","def":"a chemical substance derivable from a mold or bacterium that can kill microorganisms and cure bacterial infections","ex":"when antibiotics were first discovered they were called wonder drugs","say":"a-ntee-beye-AH-tihk","hook":"ANTI-BIO-TIC: BIO means life — an antibiotic is AGAINST the life of bacteria; think of a BIOlogist's worst enemy ending in -TIC."},{"w":"geography","def":"study of the earth's surface; includes people's responses to topography and climate and soil and vegetation","ex":"In geography class, students traced the path of the Amazon River across a giant wall map.","say":"jee-AH-gruh-fee","hook":"GEOGRAPHY = GEO+GRAPHY — writing (GRAPHY) about the earth (GEO); keep the PH, it's a GRAPH of the globe."},{"w":"geology","def":"a science that deals with the history of the earth as recorded in rocks","ex":"Her geology class took a field trip to study the layers of rock exposed along the canyon wall.","say":"jee-AH-luh-jee","hook":"GEO-logy: the earth (GEO) keeps a LOG of its own history in rocks."},{"w":"geothermal","def":"of or relating to the heat in the interior of the earth","ex":"Iceland generates most of its electricity from geothermal energy by harnessing the intense heat produced by the volcanic activity beneath the island.","say":"jee-oh-THUR-muhl","hook":"GEO-THERM-AL: the earth's THERMOSTAT turned way up — remember geo + therm + al."},{"w":"geodesic","def":"(mathematics) the shortest line between two points on a mathematically defined surface (as a straight line on a plane or an arc of a great circle on a sphere)","ex":"Buckminster Fuller's geodesic dome became an iconic architectural structure admired for its strength and efficiency.","say":"jee-uh-DEH-sihk","hook":"GEODESIC ends in -SIC not -SICK — the shortest path on earth never gets sick, it stays trim."},{"w":"photosynthesis","def":"the formation of carbohydrates from carbon dioxide and a source of hydrogen in chlorophyll-containing cells","ex":"During photosynthesis, the leaves of the sunflower convert sunlight into the energy it needs to grow.","say":"f-oh-t-oh-s-IH-n-th-uh-s-ih-s","hook":"PHOTO-SYN-THE-SIS: plants use PHOTO (light) to SYN-THE-SIZE food — end it with -SIS like 'crisis.'"},{"w":"photogenic","def":"looking attractive in photographs","ex":"The golden retriever was so photogenic that every snapshot of him looked like a professional portrait.","say":"foh-tuh-JEH-nihk","hook":"PHOTOGENic people are born (GENerated) to look great in the light — no extra E."},{"w":"photon","def":"a quantum of electromagnetic radiation; an elementary particle that is its own antiparticle","ex":"A single photon of light struck the sensor and triggered the alarm system.","say":"FOH-tahn","hook":"A PHOTon is a particle of light — PH not F, just like PHOTO, its parent word."},{"w":"hydrolysis","def":"is chemical decomposition by reacting with water","ex":"During hydrolysis, the complex starch molecule breaks apart when it reacts with water.","say":"h-ay-d-r-AH-l-uh-s-uh-s","hook":"HY-DROL-Y-SIS: water (hydro) causes a loosening (lysis) — remember SIS at the end like 'analysis.'"},{"w":"hydroponics","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"hydraulic","def":"is employing water or other liquids in motion","ex":"The engineering students marveled at how the hydraulic lift at the auto shop could raise an entire vehicle effortlessly using only the power of pressurized fluid flowing through a compact network of metal tubes.","say":"h-ay-d-r-AW-l-ih-k","hook":"HydrAULic pipes HAUL water with powerful force — remember the AU in HAUL."},{"w":"hydrophobia","def":"a symptom of rabies in humans consisting of an aversion to swallowing liquids","ex":"The doctor explained that hydrophobia in the patient was an alarming sign that the rabies infection had progressed severely.","say":"heye-druh-FOH-bee-uh","hook":"A HYDROphobic person FEARS water — hydro (water) + phobia (fear) — both Greek roots drip with meaning."},{"w":"thermometer","def":"measuring instrument for measuring temperature","ex":"The nurse placed a thermometer under the child's tongue to check whether his fever had gone down overnight.","say":"ther-MAH-muh-ter","hook":"THERMO-METER: a METER that measures THERMO (heat) — meter is always spelled M-E-T-E-R, never miter."},{"w":"thermostat","def":"a regulator for automatically regulating temperature by starting or stopping the supply of heat","ex":"She programmed the thermostat to lower the heat at night and warm the house again before her alarm went off each morning.","say":"THUR-muh-stat","hook":"THERMO-STAT: it makes heat STAY STATIC — a thermoSTAT keeps temperature STATionary, spelled S-T-A-T."}]},{"title":"neuro- / cardio- / osteo- / psycho- / derm- / hem-","category":"Greek Prefixes — Body & Mind","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Six Greek body-system prefixes that unlock all medical specialist names and condition vocabulary. Know these six and the science section of any spelling bee becomes a pattern-matching exercise.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>NEUROLOGY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> nuu-RAH-luh-jee\n<b>Spell it.</b> N · E · U · R · O · L · O · G · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> nuu-RAH-luh-jee\n<b>Syllables.</b> nuh · raa · lah · jhiy\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [nyoor=NEU] [OL=ROL] [uh=O] [jee=GY]\n<b>Exception.</b> -neuro- = nerve; -logy = study; -gy = /jee/ at end; eu = /yoor/ diphthong: nyoor-OL-uh-jee\n<b>Origin.</b> Greek\n<b>Root.</b> Greek neuron = nerve + logos = study","cards":[{"title":"neuro- = Nerve","body":"Neurology = study of the nervous system. Neuropathy = nerve disease. Neuroticism = anxiety-prone personality trait. Neurosis = a mild mental disorder. Neurotransmitter = chemical messenger between nerve cells. The eu = /yoor/ pronunciation catches many spellers off guard."},{"title":"cardio- = Heart","body":"Cardiology = study of the heart. Cardiovascular = heart and blood vessels. Electrocardiogram = E-L-E-C-T-R-O-C-A-R-D-I-O-G-R-A-M = record of heart electricity (EKG). Myocardium (myo- = muscle) = the heart muscle. Pericardium (peri- = around) = membrane surrounding the heart."},{"title":"osteo- = Bone / psycho- = Mind","body":"Osteoporosis (osteo- + poros = passage + -osis) = bones becoming porous and fragile. Osteopathy = treating disease through bone/tissue manipulation. Psychology = study of the mind. Psychosis = a serious mental disorder. Psychosomatic (psycho- + soma = body) = mind-body interaction. ⚠️ Psyche has a SILENT p: P-S-Y-C-H-E."},{"title":"derm- = Skin","body":"Dermatology = study of skin. Dermatitis = skin inflammation. Epidermis (epi- + derma) = outer skin layer. Hypodermic (hypo- + derm-) = under the skin = type of injection. Taxidermy (taxi- = arrange + derma) = arranging skin = mounting animals."},{"title":"hem- = Blood","body":"Hematology = study of blood. Hemoglobin = the oxygen-carrying protein in blood. Hemorrhage (hem- + rhegnynai = burst) = blood bursting out. ⚠️ British spelling: haemorrhage — both are correct. Hemophilia (hem- + philia = love) = condition where blood loves to flow (does not clot properly)."}],"words":[{"w":"neurology","def":"the branch of medical science that deals with the nervous system","ex":"She decided to specialize in neurology after becoming fascinated by how the brain controls every movement we make.","say":"nuu-RAH-luh-jee","hook":"NEURO-LOGY: nerves need LOGIC — study them with NEUROLOgy."},{"w":"neuropathy","def":"any pathology of the peripheral nerves","ex":"The diabetic patient developed neuropathy in her feet, causing a constant tingling and numbness.","say":"NUU-roh-pa-thee","hook":"NEUROPATHy: the nerve's PATH leads to suffering — feel the PATHos of damaged nerves."},{"w":"neuroticism","def":"a mental or personality disturbance not attributable to any known neurological or organic dysfunction","ex":"The psychology textbook described neuroticism as a core trait that makes some people more prone to worry and mood swings.","say":"noo-ROT-ih-siz-um","hook":"NEUROTIC + ISM — neurotICISM is the condition of being neurotic"},{"w":"cardiology","def":"the branch of medicine dealing with the heart and its diseases","ex":"She decided to specialize in cardiology after watching her professor perform a life-saving procedure.","say":"kah-rdee-AH-luh-jee","hook":"CARDIOLOGY ends in -LOGY like biology — it's the LOGIC of the heart, spelled heart-logically."},{"w":"cardiovascular","def":"of or pertaining to or involving the heart and blood vessels","ex":"cardiovascular conditioning","say":"kah-rdee-oh-VA-skyuh-ler","hook":"CARDIOVASCULAR — your heart pumps through VASCUlar tubes; no extra A sneaks into VASCUL."},{"w":"electrocardiogram","def":"a graphical recording of the cardiac cycle produced by an electrocardiograph","ex":"The doctor studied the electrocardiogram carefully to check whether the patient's heartbeat was regular.","say":"ih-leh-ktroh-KAH-rdee-uh-gram","hook":"An ELECTROCARDIOGRAM is an ELECTRO-CARDIO-GRAM: electricity + heart + graph — three Greek parts, one life-saving word."},{"w":"myocardium","def":"the middle muscular layer of the heart wall","ex":"A healthy myocardium pumps blood efficiently throughout the entire body with every heartbeat.","say":"meye-uh-KAH-rdee-uhm","hook":"The MYOCARDIUM is the heart's muscular medium — -IUM ends it like a stadium for muscle."},{"w":"pericardium","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"osteology","def":"the branch of anatomy that studies the bones of the vertebrate skeleton","ex":"Her passion for osteology led her to spend years studying the skeletal remains of ancient human civilizations.","say":"os-tee-OL-oh-jee","hook":"OSTEOLOGY: OSTEO (bone) + LOGY (study) — the study of your skeleton's STORY."},{"w":"osteoporosis","def":"abnormal loss of bony tissue resulting in fragile porous bones attributable to a lack of calcium; most common in postmenopausal women","ex":"The doctor advised the elderly patient to take calcium supplements to slow the progression of osteoporosis.","say":"aw-stee-ah-per-OH-sihs","hook":"OSTEOPOROSIS: POROUS bones get OSTEOPOROSIS — pore-OH-sis, the O-S-I-S ending like 'diagnosis.'"},{"w":"osteopathy","def":"therapy based on the assumption that restoring health is best accomplished by manipulating the skeleton and muscles","ex":"She visited an osteopathy clinic where the doctor used gentle manipulation to relieve her back pain.","say":"os-tee-OP-uh-thee","hook":"OSTEO-PATHY: 'osteo' (bone) + pathy (treatment/suffering) — treating the body through BONE and structure."},{"w":"psychology","def":"the science of mental life","ex":"Her fascination with why people behave the way they do led her to pursue a career in psychology.","say":"seye-KAH-luh-jee","hook":"PSYCHOlogy — the PSYCHO at the start is the mind gone wild; don't forget the silent P."},{"w":"psychosis","def":"any severe mental disorder in which contact with reality is lost or highly distorted","ex":"The doctor explained that untreated psychosis can make everyday life extremely difficult and frightening for the patient.","say":"seye-KOH-suhs","hook":"PSYCHOsis — the mind (-PSYCHO) has an abnormal condition (-OSIS); think neurOSIS for the ending."},{"w":"psychosomatic","def":"used of illness or symptoms resulting from neurosis","ex":"The doctor believed that many of the patient's headaches were psychosomatic, triggered by extreme workplace stress.","say":"seye-koh-suh-MA-tihk","hook":"PSYCHOSOmatic — the PSYCHO (mind) affects the SOMA (body); mind over matter, spelled out."},{"w":"dermatology","def":"the branch of medicine dealing with the skin and its diseases","ex":"Her doctor referred her to a specialist in dermatology to diagnose the unusual rash on her back.","say":"dur-muh-TAH-luh-jee","hook":"DERMATOLOGY = DERMA+TO+LOGY — the study OF (logy) the skin (derma), don't forget the O before LOGY."},{"w":"epidermis","def":"the outer layer of the skin covering the exterior body surface of vertebrates","ex":"A bad sunburn damages the epidermis and can leave the skin red, peeling, and painfully sensitive.","say":"eh-puh-DUR-muhs","hook":"Your EPIDERMis is the skin that sits UPON your DERMIS — the outer layer wears an 'epi-' hat."},{"w":"hypodermic","def":"a piston syringe that is fitted with a hypodermic needle for giving injections","ex":"The school nurse carefully explained how a hypodermic needle works, showing students that the hollow tip passes just beneath the skin to deliver medicine quickly and directly into the bloodstream.","say":"heye-puh-DUR-mihk","hook":"A hypoDERMic needle goes UNDER your DERM (skin) — think DERMatologist + hypo."},{"w":"hematology","def":"the branch of medicine that deals with diseases of the blood and blood-forming organs","ex":"The doctor specialized in hematology and spent her career finding new treatments for blood diseases.","say":"heh-muh-TAH-luh-jee","hook":"HEMAtology: doctors who study blood HEM in patients."},{"w":"hemorrhage","def":"is a profuse discharge of blood","ex":"The emergency room doctors worked quickly to stop the hemorrhage before the patient lost too much blood.","say":"h-EH-m-ur-ih-j","hook":"HEMOrrhage — think HEM(atology) = blood; double the R in the middle"}]},{"title":"meta- / para- / epi- / syn- / peri-","category":"Greek Prefixes — Position & Relationship","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Five Greek positional prefixes describing relationships between things — appearing in philosophy, science, grammar, medicine, and championship spelling bees. Each has a precise spatial or relational meaning.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>METAMORPHOSIS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> meh-tuh-MAW-rfuh-suhs\n<b>Spell it.</b> M · E · T · A · M · O · R · P · H · O · S · I · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> meh-tuh-MAW-rfuh-suhs\n<b>Syllables.</b> meh · tah · mao · rfah · sah · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [meh=ME] [tuh=TA] [MOR=MOR] [fuh=PHO] [sis=SIS]\n<b>Exception.</b> meta- = beyond/change; -morph- = form; -ph- = /f/ (Greek!); -osis = process; stress: meh-tuh-MOR-fuh-sis\n<b>Origin.</b> Greek\n<b>Root.</b> Greek meta = change + morphe = form + sis = process","cards":[{"title":"meta- = Beyond / Change","body":"Metamorphosis = change of form beyond what came before. Metaphor (meta- + pherein = carry) = carrying meaning beyond the literal. Metabolism (meta- + ballein = throw) = chemical throwing-around = bodily chemical processes. Metacognition = thinking about your own thinking = thinking beyond ordinary thought."},{"title":"para- = Beside / Beyond","body":"Parable (para- + ballein = throw beside) = a story placed alongside the point = allegory. Paralysis (para- + lysis = loosening beside function) = inability to move. Paraphernalia = things beside the main items. Paradox (para- + doxa = opinion) = opinion beside expectation = a self-contradicting statement."},{"title":"epi- = Upon / Over / At","body":"Epiphany (epi- + phainein = show) = a showing upon you = sudden realization. Epithet (epi- + tithenai = place) = placed upon = a descriptive label. Epilogue = words upon the end. Epidemic (epi- + demos = people) = upon the people = spreading disease. Epitaph = words upon a tomb."},{"title":"syn-/sym- = Together","body":"Synonym (syn- + onoma = name) = same-name word. Synchronize = put in time together. Synthesis = place together = combine. Symphony = sounds together. ⚠️ Sym- before b/m/p: symbol, symmetry, sympathy. Syn- everywhere else: synagogue, syntax, syndrome."},{"title":"peri- = Around","body":"Periphery (peri- + pherein = carry) = carried around the edge. Perimeter (peri- + metron = measure) = measurement around a shape. Pericardium = membrane around the heart. Perihelion (peri- + helios = sun) = nearest point to the sun in an orbit. Peripatetic (peri- + patein = walk) = traveling from place to place."}],"words":[{"w":"metamorphosis","def":"the marked and rapid transformation of a larva into an adult that occurs in some animals","ex":"the metamorphosis of the old house into something new and exciting","say":"meh-tuh-MAW-rfuh-suhs","hook":"metaMORPHosis: the caterpillar MORPHs through a process (-osis), not an 'a'."},{"w":"metaphor","def":"is a figure of speech in which a term is applied to something to which it isn't literally applicable","ex":"When the poet wrote that life is a rollercoaster, she was using a metaphor to describe its unpredictable ups and downs.","say":"m-EH-t-uh-f-aw-r","hook":"A metaPHOR carries meaning across — it PHORwarded an idea to a new place."},{"w":"metabolism","def":"the marked and rapid transformation of a larva into an adult that occurs in some animals","ex":"Regular exercise can speed up your metabolism and help you feel more energetic.","say":"muh-TA-buh-lih-zuhm","hook":"METABOLISM — META + BOL + ISM: beyond-throw-process, the body's engine always has an A after MET and a B in the middle."},{"w":"metacognition","def":"The awareness and understanding of one's own thought processes, including the ability to monitor, evaluate, and regulate how one learns and solves problems.","ex":"Using metacognition, she thought carefully about how she studies and decided to change her approach.","say":"meh-tuh-kog-NIH-shun","hook":"META-COGNITION: META = beyond, COGNITION = thinking — THINKING ABOUT YOUR OWN THINKING."},{"w":"parable","def":"a short moral story, often using everyday situations or characters to illustrate a lesson or principle","ex":"the parable of the prodigal son","say":"p-EH-r-uh-b-uh-l","hook":"A PARABLE throws (ballo) ideas BESIDE each other to teach a lesson"},{"w":"paralysis","def":"is a loss of movement in a body part caused by disease or injury","ex":"After the accident, the athlete suffered temporary paralysis in his left leg and had to undergo months of therapy.","say":"p-ur-A-l-uh-s-uh-s","hook":"PARALYSIS ends in LYSIS — the body's systems come LOOSE: P-A-R-A-L-Y-S-I-S."},{"w":"paraphernalia","def":"is apparatus necessary for a particular activity","ex":"The camping paraphernalia spread across the garage floor included tents, sleeping bags, lanterns, and cooking supplies.","say":"p-eh-r-uh-f-uh-n-AY-l-y-uh","hook":"PARAPHERNalia — remember PHERN sounds like FERN, a bride's fern-filled accessories beside her dowry."},{"w":"paradox","def":"(logic) a statement that contradicts itself","ex":"`I always lie' is a paradox because if it is true it must be false","say":"PEH-ruh-dahks","hook":"A PARADOX defies your DOXa (belief) — spell it para-DOX, with an X that crosses out your expectations."},{"w":"epiphany","def":"is a Christian festival","ex":"Beyond its religious meaning, Maya used the word epiphany to describe the sudden moment she realized the solution to the math problem.","say":"ih-p-IH-f-uh-n-ee","hook":"An EPIPHAny is when truth APPEARS (PHANy = phainein = show) — one 'n,' one shining moment of clarity."},{"w":"epithet","def":"a defamatory or abusive word or phrase","ex":"The bully hurled a cruel epithet at his classmate, earning himself a swift trip to the principal's office.","say":"EH-puh-theht","hook":"An EPIthet is a label placed UPON (EPI) someone — like a name tag that sticks."},{"w":"epilogue","def":"a short speech (often in verse) addressed directly to the audience by an actor at the end of a play","ex":"the epilogue told what eventually happened to the main characters","say":"EH-puh-lawg","hook":"An EPILOGue ends with a VOGUE bow — the actor's final fashionable words include that silent -ue."},{"w":"epidemic","def":"a widespread outbreak of an infectious disease; many people are infected at the same time","ex":"an epidemic outbreak of influenza","say":"eh-puh-DEH-mihk","hook":"An EPIDEMic falls UPON the DEMO(cracy) — it spreads across all the people."},{"w":"epitaph","def":"an inscription on a tombstone or monument in memory of the person buried there","ex":"The poet's epitaph read simply, 'He gave the world beauty in words,' and made every visitor pause in reflection.","say":"EH-puh-taf","hook":"An EPITAPH sits upon (EPI) a TOMB (TAPH) — the PH spells out the final breath."},{"w":"synonym","def":"is a word having nearly the same meaning as another","ex":"The teacher asked us to find a synonym for the word happy, and most students wrote joyful.","say":"s-IH-n-uh-n-ih-m","hook":"A SYNonym gives a word a NEW NAME (onym) that means the SAME thing."},{"w":"synchronize","def":"make synchronous and adjust in time or manner","ex":"Let's synchronize our efforts","say":"SIH-ngkruh-neyez","hook":"SYNCHRONize your watches — the CHRON inside reminds you of CHRONology, so don't drop the H."},{"w":"synthesis","def":"the process of producing a chemical compound (usually by the union of simpler chemical compounds)","ex":"The lab report explained the synthesis of aspirin by combining salicylic acid with acetic anhydride.","say":"SIH-nthuh-suhs","hook":"SynthESIS — think of placing pieces TOGETHER; remember the ending is -ESIS like 'thesis.'"},{"w":"symbol","def":"an arbitrary sign (written or printed) that has acquired a conventional significance","ex":"the eagle is a symbol of the United States","say":"SIH-mbuhl","hook":"SYMBol — SYM sounds like 'seem,' and a symbol SEEMS to mean more than it shows; end in -bol not -bel."},{"w":"symmetry","def":"(mathematics) an attribute of a shape or relation; exact reflection of form on opposite sides of a dividing line or plane","ex":"A butterfly's wings display remarkable symmetry, with each side being nearly a perfect mirror image of the other.","say":"SIH-muh-tree","hook":"Remember syMMetry needs two M's — one for each matching half!"},{"w":"periphery","def":"is the external boundary of any area","ex":"The shy new student stood at the periphery of the group, watching the others play.","say":"p-ur-IH-f-ur-ee","hook":"PERIPHERY: at the EDGE, things get FUZZY — peri (around) + PHER (carry) + Y, carried around the boundary."},{"w":"perimeter","def":"the boundary line or the area immediately inside the boundary","ex":"To find the perimeter of the rectangle, the student added up the lengths of all four sides.","say":"per-IH-muh-ter","hook":"A PERIMETER MEASURES AROUND a shape — PERI + METER, the measure goes all the way around."},{"w":"peripatetic","def":"a person who walks from place to place","ex":"The peripatetic journalist traveled from city to city interviewing ordinary people, never staying in one place longer than a week as she gathered stories for her upcoming book about everyday heroes.","say":"peh-ruh-puh-TEH-tihk","hook":"A PERIPATETIC person PATters their feet walking around — peri (around) + PAT (walk) + etic."}]},{"title":"Number Prefixes 1–10: Latin & Greek","category":"Number Prefixes","difficulty":"easy","concept":"English borrows number prefixes from both Latin and Greek. Knowing both sets doubles your ability to decode scientific, mathematical, and historical vocabulary at sight.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>QUINTET</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> kwih-NTEHT\n<b>Spell it.</b> Q · U · I · N · T · E · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> kwih-NTEHT\n<b>Syllables.</b> kwih · nteh · t\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [kwin=QUIN] [TET=TET]\n<b>Exception.</b> quin- = five (Latin); -tet from Italian quartetto; qu always together; stress on second syllable: kwin-TET\n<b>Origin.</b> Italian\n<b>Root.</b> Latin quintus = fifth","cards":[{"title":"One and Two","body":"Latin uni- / Greek mono-: unicorn, universe, uniform vs monologue, monopoly, monocle. Latin bi-/du- / Greek di-: bicycle, bilingual vs dialogue, dichotomy, dilemma. Learning both systems means you can decode words from either classical language."},{"title":"Three and Four","body":"Tri- is the same in both Latin and Greek! trilogy, triangle, trinity AND triptych (tri- + ptychē = fold = three-paneled artwork). Latin quad-/quart- / Greek tetra-: quadrant, quartet vs tetrahedron, tetralogy, tetrarch."},{"title":"Five through Seven","body":"Penta-/quint-: pentagon, pentathlon, quintessence, quintet. Hex-/sex-: hexagon, hexameter, sextuple, sextet. Hept-/sept-: heptagon, septuagenarian (70-year-old). September = originally the 7th month before Rome added January and February."},{"title":"Eight through Ten","body":"Oct-: octave, octopus, October (originally 8th month). Nov-/ennea-: November (9th), nonagenarian (90-year-old). Dec-/deca-: decade, December (10th), decathlon. The months from September to December are mislabeled by 2 because of the Roman calendar reform."},{"title":"Beyond Ten","body":"Cent- = 100: century, centimeter, percent. Milli- = 1,000: millennium, millimeter. Kilo- = 1,000 (Greek): kilometer, kilogram. Millennium = M-I-L-L-E-N-N-I-U-M — double-l AND double-n (from mille + annum). One of the most commonly misspelled words in English."}],"words":[{"w":"unicorn","def":"an imaginary creature represented as a white horse with a long horn growing from its forehead","ex":"The little girl drew a glittery unicorn with a silver horn on her birthday card.","say":"YOO-nih-kawrn","hook":"A UNICORNer has UNI (one) CORN-shaped horn — no 'k', it's Latin fancy."},{"w":"monologue","def":"speech you make to yourself","ex":"The actor delivered a powerful monologue that left the entire audience holding its breath.","say":"MAH-nuh-lawg","hook":"A MONOlogue is ONE person's LOGUE (speech) — one mouth, lots of words, add the UE."},{"w":"bicycle","def":"a wheeled vehicle that has two wheels and is moved by foot pedals","ex":"He rode his bicycle to school every morning, weaving through the quiet neighborhood streets.","say":"BEYE-sih-kuhl","hook":"A BICYCLE has TWO (bi-) CYCLES — two wheels going round and round, spelled with a Y not an I: bi-CY-cle."},{"w":"dialogue","def":"is conversation with two or more people","ex":"he has read Plato's Dialogues in the original Greek","say":"d-AY-uh-l-aw-g","hook":"A dialogUE always ends politely with a silent UE — the quiet goodbye at the end of a conversation."},{"w":"dichotomy","def":"is division into two parts","ex":"the dichotomy between eastern and western culture","say":"d-ay-k-AH-t-uh-m-ee","hook":"DICHOTOMY cuts things in two — spot the CH and remember 'cut in two halves.'"},{"w":"trilogy","def":"a set of three literary or dramatic works related in subject or theme","ex":"She stayed up all weekend to finish the final book of the fantasy trilogy she had been reading all month.","say":"TRIH-luh-jee","hook":"A TRILOGY tells THREE stories—tri+LOGY like biology and geology, ends in Y not IE."},{"w":"triptych","def":"art consisting of a painting or carving (especially an altarpiece) on three panels (usually hinged together)","ex":"The museum's most famous triptych showed three scenes from the life of a medieval saint side by side.","say":"TRIH-ptihk","hook":"A TRIPTYCH has a silent PtYCH—think 'three PSYCHIC panels' folded together."},{"w":"quadrant","def":"a quarter of the circumference of a circle","ex":"The math teacher asked students to plot the coordinates in the upper-right quadrant of the graph.","say":"KWAH-druhnt","hook":"QUADRANT ends in ANT — a tiny ant marking one of four equal sections."},{"w":"tetrahedron","def":"any polyhedron having four plane faces","ex":"The geometry student carefully folded the paper template into a perfect tetrahedron, marveling at its four triangular faces.","say":"teh-truh-HEE-druhn","hook":"TETRAHEDRON: TETRA(four) + HEDRON(face) — a four-faced solid; 'HE DRON' flew a four-sided drone."},{"w":"pentagon","def":"a government building with five sides that serves as the headquarters of the United States Department of Defense","ex":"Officials at the Pentagon held a press conference to address the nation's new defense strategy.","say":"PEH-ntih-gahn","hook":"A PENTAgon has FIVE angles — pen-ta sounds like 'penta' which always means five."},{"w":"quintessence","def":"is the pure and concentrated essence of a substance","ex":"With her calm wisdom and generous spirit, the village elder was the quintessence of good leadership.","say":"k-w-ih-n-t-EH-s-uh-n-s","hook":"QUINTESSENCE contains ESSENCE — the fifth and purest form hides ESSENCE right inside it."},{"w":"hexagon","def":"a six-sided polygon","ex":"Each cell in a honeycomb is shaped like a perfect hexagon, making the structure incredibly strong.","say":"HEH-ksuh-gahn","hook":"A HEXAGOn has six GO-corners — bees know this because their honeycombs are perfect hexagons."},{"w":"septuagenarian","def":"is between 70 and 80 years of age","ex":"The sprightly septuagenarian celebrated her 75th birthday by running her first 5K race.","say":"s-eh-p-ch-oo-uh-j-uh-n-EH-r-ee-uh-n","hook":"A SEPTUAGENARIAN is in their SEPTU(seventy)s — spot SEVEN hiding in SEPTU, and -ARIAN like a librarian who's been reading for 70 years."},{"w":"octave","def":"a feast day and the seven days following it","ex":"During the octave of the holiday, the monks observed special prayers and ceremonies each morning.","say":"AH-ktihv","hook":"An octave spans eight notes—'oct' for eight, '-ave' like 'wave'; ride the wave of eight notes."},{"w":"decathlon","def":"an athletic contest consisting of ten different events","ex":"The decathlon champion had to master ten different track and field events to claim the gold medal.","say":"dee-KA-thlawn","hook":"A DECAthlon has ten (DECA) ATHLetic events — no extra 'a' hiding after ATH!"},{"w":"millennium","def":"is a period of 1000 years","ex":"Scientists predicted it would take a millennium for the ancient forest to fully recover from the fire.","say":"m-uh-l-EH-n-ee-uh-m","hook":"MILLENNIUM: double L, double N, -ium at the end—two pairs for two thousand years of confusion."},{"w":"centimeter","def":"a metric unit of length equal to one hundredth of a meter","ex":"The surgeon made a precise incision just one centimeter long during the delicate procedure.","say":"SEH-ntuh-mee-ter","hook":"A centiMETER METERS out one hundredth — a ruler's tiny tick between big numbers."},{"w":"nonagenarian","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""}]},{"title":"poly- / multi- / omni- / pan- (many / all)","category":"Number Prefixes — Many & All","difficulty":"easy","concept":"Greek poly- = many, Latin multi- = many, Latin omni- = all, Greek pan- = all. Four ways to say \"many/all\" — each with its own vocabulary territory and spelling patterns.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>OMNISCIENT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ah-MNIH-shuhnt\n<b>Spell it.</b> O · M · N · I · S · C · I · E · N · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> ah-MNIH-shuhnt\n<b>Syllables.</b> om · ni · scient\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [om=OM] [NISH=NI] [ent=SCIENT]\n<b>Exception.</b> omni- = all; -scient from scire = know; -sc- cluster; -ent not -ant; stress: om-NISH-ent\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin omnis = all + sciens = knowing","cards":[{"title":"poly- = Many (Greek)","body":"Polygon (poly- + gon = angle) = many-angled figure. Polyglot (poly- + glotta = tongue) = speaks many languages. Polyphony = many voices. Polymath (poly- + manthanein = learn) = one who knows many things. The y in poly- is a Greek vowel signal — not the same as the English word \"poly.\""},{"title":"multi- = Many (Latin)","body":"Multilingual = many languages (Latin parallel of polyglot). Multifaceted = many faces/aspects. Multitudinous = very great in number. Multifarious (multi- + fari = speak) = of many different varied kinds. Multi- and poly- are largely interchangeable in everyday meaning."},{"title":"omni- = All (Latin)","body":"Omniscient = knows everything. Omnipotent (omni- + potens = powerful) = all-powerful. Omnivore (omni- + vorare = eat) = eats everything. Omnipresent = present everywhere. Omnibus (omni- + bus = for all) = for all = hence bus — the modern word \"bus\" is short for omnibus!"},{"title":"pan- = All (Greek)","body":"Pandemic (pan- + demos) = disease affecting all people. Panorama (pan- + horama = view) = all-encompassing view. Panacea (pan- + akos = remedy) = remedy for all ills. Pandemonium (pan- + daimon = spirit) = all the spirits together = utter chaos. Pantheon (pan- + theos = god) = all the gods."},{"title":"Spelling Details","body":"Omniscient = O-M-N-I-S-C-I-E-N-T (the sc cluster from scire). Omnipotent = O-M-N-I-P-O-T-E-N-T. Pandemic = P-A-N-D-E-M-I-C (not panedemic). Polyphony = P-O-L-Y-P-H-O-N-Y (ph not f — Greek signal!). Polymath = P-O-L-Y-M-A-T-H (-th from Greek mathein)."}],"words":[{"w":"omniscient","def":"infinitely wise","ex":"In many fantasy novels, the narrator is omniscient, able to reveal the secret thoughts of every character in the story.","say":"ah-MNIH-shuhnt","hook":"OMNI + SCIENT: SCIENT relates to SCIENCE (knowing) — omniscient knows ALL sciences"},{"w":"omnipotent","def":"having unlimited power","ex":"In the myth, the god was described as omnipotent, able to reshape the world with a single thought.","say":"ah-MNIH-puh-tuhnt","hook":"OMNIPOTENT ends in '-ent' — all-powerful beings are competENT, not competANT."},{"w":"omnivore","def":"a person who eats all kinds of foods","ex":"As a true omnivore, Marcus happily ate both the grilled vegetables and the roasted chicken at the feast.","say":"OM-nih-vor","hook":"An OMNIvore eats OMNI-thing — all kinds of food, from veggies to meat."},{"w":"omnipresent","def":"being present everywhere at once","ex":"During the holiday season, cheerful music seemed omnipresent in every store and hallway.","say":"ah-mnih-PREH-zuhnt","hook":"OMNIPRESENT has PRESENT inside — being everywhere includes being presENT, not presANT."},{"w":"omnibus","def":"an anthology of articles on a related subject or an anthology of the works of a single author","ex":"The library purchased an omnibus of Sherlock Holmes stories so students could read all of Arthur Conan Doyle's mysteries in one volume.","say":"AH-mnuh-buhs","hook":"OMNI means ALL — an omnibus has ALL the works in one bus-sized book"},{"w":"pandemic","def":"an epidemic that is geographically widespread; occurring throughout a region or even throughout the world","ex":"a pandemic outbreak of malaria","say":"pa-NDEH-mihk","hook":"A panDEMic affects ALL the DEMOS — all the people — remember the 'dem' like democracy."},{"w":"panorama","def":"an unobstructed and wide view of an extensive area in all directions","ex":"From the top of the mountain, the hikers gasped at the stunning panorama of valleys, rivers, and distant peaks stretching in every direction.","say":"pa-ner-A-muh","hook":"PAN + ORAMA: a PAN sweeps across everything, just like a panoramic view"},{"w":"panacea","def":"a remedy supposed to cure all diseases or solve all problems","ex":"The scientist warned that the new vitamin supplement was not a panacea and could not replace a balanced diet and exercise.","say":"p-a-n-uh-s-EE-uh","hook":"A PANacea cures everything—like a magic PAN that cooks away all illness"},{"w":"pandemonium","def":"a state of extreme confusion and disorder","ex":"When the fire alarm went off in the middle of the assembly, absolute pandemonium broke out in the hallway.","say":"pa-ndih-MOH-nee-uhm","hook":"PANDEMONium is where ALL the DEMONs live — pure chaos, just like the word sounds."},{"w":"pantheon","def":"all the gods of a religion collectively","ex":"Our mythology unit covered the Greek pantheon, from mighty Zeus to clever Hermes and wise Athena.","say":"PA-nthee-ahn","hook":"The PANTHEON holds PAN + THEO: ALL the GODS together"},{"w":"polygon","def":"a closed plane figure bounded by straight sides","ex":"A stop sign is a classic example of a polygon, specifically an octagon with eight equal sides and eight equal angles.","say":"PAH-lih-gahn","hook":"POLY-GON: MANY ANGLES — GON like in 'agonize over all these corners'; no final E, just gone when you reach the last side."},{"w":"polyglot","def":"a person who speaks more than one language","ex":"Being a polyglot, Maya could greet her classmates in Spanish, Mandarin, and French on the very first day of the international exchange program.","say":"pah-lee-glaht","hook":"POLY = many + GLOT = tongue: a polyglot has MANY TONGUES (languages)!"},{"w":"polyphony","def":"music arranged in parts for several voices or instruments","ex":"The cathedral filled with rich polyphony as four separate vocal parts wove together in perfect harmony.","say":"puh-LIH-fuh-nee","hook":"POLYphony = POLY voices; remember the 'y' ending like harmony and symphony, its musical cousins."},{"w":"polymath","def":"a person of great and varied learning","ex":"Leonardo da Vinci was a true polymath, excelling in art, science, engineering, and music.","say":"POL-ee-math","hook":"A POLYMATh knows MANY subjects — they aced MATH and everything else too!"},{"w":"multifaceted","def":"having many aspects","ex":"a many-sided subject","say":"muh-ltee-FA-suh-tihd","hook":"MULTIFACETED — a diamond has many FACETS, spell FACET not FACIT, because each face has an E for edge."},{"w":"multitudinous","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"multifarious","def":"having many aspects","ex":"The multifarious duties of a school principal include managing budgets, counseling students, and meeting with parents every single day.","say":"mul-tih-FAIR-ee-us","hook":"MULTI (many) + FARIOUS sounds like VARIOUS = multifarious means many and varied"}]},{"title":"-tion / -sion / -cion (action / state / result)","category":"Latin Suffixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"The most common suffix in English — from Latin -tionem. Three spellings, one /shun/ sound, thousands of words. The right spelling depends on the root that precedes it.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>EXACERBATION</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ih-gza-ser-BAY-shuhn\n<b>Spell it.</b> E · X · A · C · E · R · B · A · T · I · O · N\n<b>Say it again.</b> ih-gza-ser-BAY-shuhn\n<b>Syllables.</b> ih · gzae · ser · bey · shah · n\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [eg=EX] [ZAS=AC] [er=ER] [BAY=BA] [shun=TION]\n<b>Exception.</b> -tion = /shun/ always; from exacerbare = make harsh; ex- prefix; stress: eg-ZAS-er-BAY-shun\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin acerbus = harsh, bitter","cards":[{"title":"The Three Spellings","body":"-tion = after most roots: exacerbation, perdition, scintillation. -sion = after d, l, n, r + vowel: extension, mansion, revision. -ssion = after stressed vowel: mission, passion, session, permission. -cion = rare: coercion, suspicion."},{"title":"The Decision Rule","body":"Does the root end in d or se? Use -sion: extend → extension, revise → revision. Does it end in t or te? Use -tion: act → action, create → creation. Does it end in ess? Use -ssion: express → expression, suppress → suppression. The root ending is your guide."},{"title":"-tion Spelling Patterns","body":"Before -tion, a c sometimes appears: infect → infection, connect → connection. Before -tion, a p sometimes appears: prescribe → prescription (-ption). Assume → assumption (-ption). These consonant mutations come from how Latin combined roots with the suffix."},{"title":"High-Value Championship Words","body":"Propitiation = winning favor through a ritual act. Expiation = atoning for a wrong. Supplication = humble begging. Predilection (pre- + dilectus = chosen) = a strong preference. Juxtaposition (juxta = beside + posit) = placement side by side. All end in -tion."},{"title":"Counting Syllables in -tion Words","body":"-tion is always ONE syllable = /shun/. Count carefully for long words: exacerbation = 5 syllables (ex·ac·er·ba·tion). Predestination = 6. Transubstantiation = 7. The Spellbound Sound Trick (syllable by syllable) is essential for these long words."}],"words":[{"w":"exacerbation","def":"action that makes a problem or a disease (or its symptoms) worse","ex":"the aggravation of her condition resulted from lack of care","say":"ih-gza-ser-BAY-shuhn","hook":"An exACERBATION is the bitter process of making things worse."},{"w":"propitiation","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"supplication","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"predilection","def":"a predisposition in favor of something","ex":"Zoe had a predilection for mystery novels, always choosing them over any other genre at the school book fair.","say":"preh-duh-LEH-kshuhn","hook":"Before you SELECT, your predilECTION already chose for you"},{"w":"expiation","def":"compensation for a wrong","ex":"His tireless community service was seen as expiation for the harm he had caused.","say":"ek-spee-AY-shun","hook":"EXPIATION is the ACTION of making amends — hear -ATION at the end, the act of atoning."},{"w":"scintillation","def":"(physics) a flash of light that is produced in a phosphor when it absorbs a photon or ionizing particle","ex":"The scintillation detector in the lab lit up each time a gamma ray struck its crystal surface, recording every tiny flash of energy.","say":"sin-tih-LAY-shun","hook":"SCINTILLA (spark) + ATION: the process of SPARKLING or flashing"},{"w":"consternation","def":"fear resulting from the awareness of danger","ex":"The students stared in consternation when their teacher announced a surprise ten-page essay due the very next morning.","say":"kah-nster-NAY-shuhn","hook":"CONSTERNation — you CONCERN + STERN face when alarmed"},{"w":"predestination","def":"previous determination as if by destiny or fate","ex":"The preacher argued that predestination meant every soul's fate had been decided before birth.","say":"pree-deh-stuh-NAY-shuhn","hook":"PreDESTINation means your DESTINY is set before you arrive at your destiNATION — all three share DESTIN."},{"w":"transubstantiation","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"remonstration","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"perdition","def":"(Christianity) the abode of Satan and the forces of evil; where sinners suffer eternal punishment; - John Milton; ; -Dr. Johnson","ex":"Hurl'd headlong...To bottomless perdition, there to dwell","say":"per-DIH-shun","hook":"PERDItion is total PERDITION — you're DONE (perdi-DONE), lost forever with a T-I-O-N ending."},{"w":"enunciation","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"juxtaposition","def":"is the act of placing close together","ex":"it is the result of the juxtaposition of contrasting colors","say":"j-uh-k-s-t-uh-p-uh-z-IH-sh-uh-n","hook":"JUXTA+POSITION — two words placed side by side, just like their meaning!"},{"w":"obfuscation","def":"confusion resulting from failure to understand","ex":"The politician's obfuscation made it nearly impossible to understand his actual position on the issue.","say":"ah-bfuh-SKAY-shuhn","hook":"OBFUSCATION: the 'sc' in the middle is deliberately murky — the word itself obscures with a cloudy 'sc' combo."},{"w":"remuneration","def":"something that remunerates; payment or compensation for work or services","ex":"The artist accepted the commission only after negotiating fair remuneration for the weeks of work the mural would require.","say":"rih-myoo-nuh-RAY-shuhn","hook":"RE + MUNER + ATION — think of a MUNIFICENT reward returned"}]},{"title":"-ous / -ious / -eous / -uous (full of / having quality)","category":"Latin Suffixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"The -ous adjective family means \"full of\" or \"having the quality of.\" Choosing -ious, -eous, or -uous depends on the noun base. These endings produce some of the richest vocabulary in English.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PERSPICACIOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> per-spuh-KAY-shuhs\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · E · R · S · P · I · C · A · C · I · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> per-spuh-KAY-shuhs\n<b>Syllables.</b> per · spi · ca · cious\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [per=PER] [spih=SPI] [KAY=CA] [shus=CIOUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> -acious from Latin -ax stem; noun form = perspicACITY (same -cac- spelling, different stress)\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin perspicere = to see clearly, from per = through + specere = to l","cards":[{"title":"The Four Forms","body":"-ous: enormous, famous. -ious (abstract nouns in -y or -ce): audacious, facetious. -eous (inherent quality): simultaneous, extraneous, igneous. -uous (manner or habit): assiduous, ambiguous, sensuous. Each variant has a pattern."},{"title":"The -ious Treasure Words — the -acious Cluster","body":"From the Latin -ax stem: perspicacious (sharply insightful), sagacious (wise), tenacious (holding on), voracious (devouring), pugnacious (fighting), loquacious (talkative), audacious (bold), vivacious (lively). All turn into -acity nouns: perspicacity, sagacity, tenacity."},{"title":"-eous Words","body":"Miscellaneous = of mixed kinds. Extraneous = from outside. Simultaneous = at the same time. Spontaneous = arising on its own. Igneous (ignis = fire) = formed from volcanic fire. Erroneous = containing error. Nauseous = causing nausea. These use -eous because the root has an -an- or bare -e- base."},{"title":"-uous Words","body":"Describe habitual manner: Assiduous = habitually diligent. Ambiguous = two-way. Conspicuous = clearly visible. Tenuous = very thin/weak. Impetuous = acting without thinking. Perspicuous = clearly and plainly expressed. Promiscuous = indiscriminately mixed. The -u- is part of the Latin stem."},{"title":"Spelling Traps","body":"Facetious = F-A-C-E-T-I-O-U-S — contains all five vowels A-E-I-O-U in order! A fun mnemonic. Mischievous = MIS-CHIEV-OUS (3 syllables, NOT 4). Grievous = GRIEV-OUS (not griev-i-ous). Adding an extra -i- to these is the most common error with this suffix family."}],"words":[{"w":"perspicacious","def":"acutely insightful and wise","ex":"The perspicacious young detective noticed a tiny mud stain on the suspect's shoe that everyone else had overlooked.","say":"per-spuh-KAY-shuhs","hook":"PER-SPIC-acious: someone who sees (SPIC) through everything"},{"w":"sagacious","def":"showing acute mental discernment or being shrewd","ex":"much too perspicacious to be taken in by such a spurious argument","say":"suh-GAY-shus","hook":"A SAGE is wise; sagaCIOUS has SAGE inside it"},{"w":"tenacious","def":"means holding fast","ex":"Despite failing her driving test twice, Leila remained tenacious in her determination to pass, practicing parallel parking every single evening until she could execute it smoothly, confidently, and without a single cone knocked over.","say":"t-uh-n-AY-sh-uh-s","hook":"Tenacious holds fast to every letter — especially that sneaky I before OUS: ten-A-CI-OUS."},{"w":"voracious","def":"excessively eager avid insatiable","ex":"a rapacious divorcee on the prowl","say":"v-aw-r-AY-sh-uh-s","hook":"VORACIOUS: a VORACious eater devours — remember V-O-R-A-C-I-O-U-S, no T, just a ravenous C gobbling the word up."},{"w":"pugnacious","def":"tough and callous by virtue of experience","ex":"The pugnacious debater never backed down from a challenge, gleefully taking on opponents twice his age.","say":"puh-GNA-shihs","hook":"PUGnacious people fight like a PUG dog — always scrappy!"},{"w":"audacious","def":"invulnerable to fear or intimidation","ex":"The audacious climber scaled the sheer cliff face without ropes, impressing everyone who watched from below.","say":"ah-DAY-shuhs","hook":"AUDacious people DARE to be heard — like a loud AUDIO blast"},{"w":"vivacious","def":"vigorous and animated","ex":"The vivacious host bounded onto the stage with a huge smile, instantly energizing the audience with her contagious enthusiasm.","say":"vuh-VAY-shuhs","hook":"VIVACious — full of VIVA (life)!"},{"w":"facetious","def":"means not to be taken seriously","ex":"When Tyler suggested that the class should take a field trip to the moon for their science project, his teacher smiled and said he was being completely facetious and needed a more realistic idea.","say":"f-uh-s-EE-sh-uh-s","hook":"FACETIOUS contains all five vowels a-e-i-o-u in order — a facetious fact worth remembering!"},{"w":"mischievous","def":"is maliciously or playfully annoying","ex":"teasing and worrying with impish laughter","say":"m-IH-s-ch-uh-v-uh-s","hook":"Mischievous has no extra 'i' after the 'v' — a mischievous kid hides the extra letter just to trick you!"},{"w":"miscellaneous","def":"is of mixed character","ex":"an arrangement of assorted spring flowers","say":"m-ih-s-uh-l-AY-n-ee-uh-s","hook":"MISCELLANEOUS has CELL in it — a cell that holds ALL kinds of mixed things; no I before -ous."},{"w":"simultaneous","def":"is occurring or operating at the same time","ex":"a series of coincident events","say":"s-ay-m-uh-l-t-AY-n-ee-uh-s","hook":"SIMULTANEOUS events happen at the SAME time — remember 'simul' means same time, then add the long '-taneous' tail."},{"w":"extraneous","def":"not pertinent to the matter under consideration","ex":"an issue extraneous to the debate","say":"eh-KSTRAY-nee-uhs","hook":"EXTRANEOUS details are FOREIGN to the topic — spell it EXTRANE+OUS, not extrAN-I-ous."},{"w":"igneous","def":"produced under conditions involving intense heat","ex":"igneous rock is rock formed by solidification from a molten state; especially from molten magma","say":"IH-gnee-uhs","hook":"IGNEous rock is full of fire — IGNite and IGNEous both start with that fiery IGN."},{"w":"erroneous","def":"containing or characterized by error","ex":"erroneous conclusions","say":"eh-ROH-nee-uhs","hook":"An erRONEous answer has ONE too many errors in your thinking."},{"w":"assiduous","def":"marked by care and persistent effort","ex":"The assiduous student reviewed her notes every evening and never missed a homework assignment, which is why she earned the top grade.","say":"uh-SIH-dwuhs","hook":"assiDUous — an assiduous person is always DUE to be at their desk working"},{"w":"ambiguous","def":"open to two or more interpretations; or of uncertain nature or significance; or (often) intended to mislead","ex":"an equivocal statement","say":"a-MBIH-gyoo-uhs","hook":"Ambiguous meaning wanders — don't drop the 'u' before '-ous': ambi-GU-ous keeps the mystery in the middle."},{"w":"conspicuous","def":"obvious to the eye or mind","ex":"a tower conspicuous at a great distance","say":"kuh-NSPIH-kyoo-uhs","hook":"CONSpICUOUS has SPY in spirit — something so visible a spy could spot it instantly; don't forget the U before OUS."},{"w":"perspicuous","def":"is clearly expressed or presented","ex":"writes in a limpid style","say":"per-SPIK-yoo-us","hook":"PERSPICUOUS is clearly expressed — see SPIC (look) inside: clear enough to see straight through."}]},{"title":"-able / -ible (capable of being)","category":"Latin Suffixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Two spellings, one /uh-bul/ sound. The right choice depends on whether the root can stand alone as an English word. Championship spellers know both the rule and the exceptions.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>INDELIBLE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ih-NDEH-lih-buhl\n<b>Spell it.</b> I · N · D · E · L · I · B · L · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> ih-NDEH-lih-buhl\n<b>Syllables.</b> ih · ndeh · lih · bah · l\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [in=IN] [DEL=DEL] [uh=I] [bul=BLE]\n<b>Exception.</b> -ible not -able because root dele- cannot stand alone as an English word; in- = not; stress: in-DEL-uh-bul\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin indelebilis = indestructible, from in+delere = to destroy/erase","cards":[{"title":"The Main Rule","body":"Use -able when the root is a complete English word: comfort → comfortable, depend → dependable, break → breakable. Use -ible when the root is a Latin stem that cannot stand alone: aud- → audible, leg- → legible, vis- → visible, del- → indelible. Root completeness is the test."},{"title":"The -ible List (Memorize These 20)","body":"contemptible, digestible, discernible, divisible, eligible, fallible, feasible, flexible, gullible, indelible, intelligible, irresistible, legible, permissible, plausible, sensible, susceptible, tangible, terrible, visible. When you cannot identify the root as a standalone English word, try -ible."},{"title":"Negated -able/-ible","body":"in- + -able: incomprehensible, inscrutable, inexorable, inimitable, intractable. in- + -ible: indelible, infallible, ineligible, inflexible, irresistible. Knowing the negative prefix tells you the base suffix — and the base suffix tells you the spelling."},{"title":"-able After -ce and -ge","body":"Keep the e before -able to preserve the soft sound: notice → noticeable, change → changeable, manage → manageable, knowledge → knowledgeable. Without the e, the c or g would harden. The e is the softening guard."},{"title":"Championship -ible Traps","body":"Irresistible = I-R-R-E-S-I-S-T-I-B-L-E (double-r from ir- assimilation). Contemptible (capable of being contempted) vs contemptuous (showing contempt) — different suffix, different meaning. Indefatigable (in- + de- + fatigare = tire) = untiring — uses -able despite the complex root."}],"words":[{"w":"indelible","def":"cannot be removed or erased","ex":"The vivid memories of that extraordinary summer trip to the mountains left an indelible impression on the young girl's mind, one so deeply engraved that she could still recall every color and smell decades later as an adult.","say":"ih-NDEH-lih-buhl","hook":"An inDELible mark won't let you DELETE it — keep 'del' from 'delete' in the middle."},{"w":"irresistible","def":"impossible to resist; overpowering","ex":"irresistible (or resistless) impulses","say":"ih-rih-ZIH-stuh-buhl","hook":"Chocolate is irresistIBLE — the 'ible' is the tempting part you can't resist changing to -able."},{"w":"incomprehensible","def":"incapable of being explained or accounted for","ex":"The ancient manuscript was so damaged that its symbols were completely incomprehensible to even the most experienced historians.","say":"ih-ngkah-mpruh-HEH-nsih-buhl","hook":"Can you HENS-ibly explain it? If not, it's incompreHENSible!"},{"w":"inscrutable","def":"is incapable of being investigated or analyzed","ex":"the new insurance policy is written without cryptic or mysterious terms","say":"ih-n-s-k-r-OO-t-uh-b-uh-l","hook":"INSCRUTable cannot be SCRUtinized — find SCRU in both words and remember just one T."},{"w":"inimitable","def":"defying imitation; matchless","ex":"The jazz musician's inimitable style blended classical harmonies with street rhythms in a way that left audiences speechless, because no other performer in the world could replicate the effortless energy she brought to every single note.","say":"ih-NIH-muh-tuh-buhl","hook":"Spot IMITATE inside inIMITable — it cannot be imitated, even though imitate hides inside."},{"w":"contemptible","def":"meriting scorn and condemnation as paltry mean or vile","ex":"The bully's contemptible behavior toward the new student shocked everyone in the cafeteria.","say":"k-uh-n-t-EH-m-p-t-uh-b-uh-l","hook":"Contemptible ends in -IBLE not -ABLE — think: something contemptible is terrIBLE, and both share the -IBLE ending."},{"w":"discernible","def":"means capable of being distinguished","ex":"things happen in the earth and sky with no discernible cause","say":"d-ih-s-UR-n-uh-b-uh-l","hook":"DisCERNible ends in -IBLE not -ABLE — if it's discernible, you're ABLE to see it, but spell it with an 'i' because you use your EYE."},{"w":"eligible","def":"qualified for or allowed or worthy of being chosen","ex":"eligible to run for office","say":"EH-luh-juh-buhl","hook":"An ELIGIBLE candidate can be chosen — spell it with '-ible' like 'possible,' because it's possibly the best choice."},{"w":"fallible","def":"likely to fail or make errors","ex":"everyone is fallible to some degree","say":"FA-luh-buhl","hook":"FALLIBLE humans FALL and fail — double L, then IBLE, because we're capable of error."},{"w":"feasible","def":"is capable of being done","ex":"The engineers decided that building a bridge across the gorge was not feasible with the current budget.","say":"f-EE-z-uh-b-uh-l","hook":"If it's FEASIBLE, it's do-IBLE — remember the I: feasIBLE, not feasABLE."},{"w":"gullible","def":"naive and easily deceived or tricked","ex":"at that early age she had been gullible and in love","say":"GUH-luh-buhl","hook":"GULLIBLE ends in -IBLE not -ABLE — a gullible person is easily tricked, so they pick the WRONG ending too: remember -IBLE."},{"w":"permissible","def":"that may be permitted especially as according to rule","ex":"permissible behavior in school","say":"per-MIH-suh-buhl","hook":"Is it perMISSIble? Check the MISS — perMISSIble ends in '-ible' not '-able', and you'd MISS an 'a' if you used it."},{"w":"susceptible","def":"(often followed by `of' or `to') yielding readily to or capable of","ex":"susceptible to colds","say":"suh-SEH-ptuh-buhl","hook":"susceptIBLE — end in -ible not -able; think 'I'll Be LEt in easily' — I-B-L-E for things easily taken up."},{"w":"tangible","def":"perceptible by the senses especially the sense of touch; capable of being touched or felt","ex":"skin with a tangible roughness","say":"t-A-n-j-uh-b-uh-l","hook":"TANGIble — if you can TANG it (touch it), it's tangible"},{"w":"noticeable","def":"capable or worthy of being perceived","ex":"noticeable shadows under her eyes","say":"NOH-tuh-suh-buhl","hook":"Keep the E in noticEable — the E wants to be NOTICED and refuses to disappear."},{"w":"changeable","def":"is liable to change or to be changed","ex":"The weather along the coastline proved so changeable that morning sunshine gave way to afternoon thunderstorms and then back to clear skies again, forcing the campers to repack their bags three separate times before dinner.","say":"ch-AY-n-j-uh-b-uh-l","hook":"CHANGEABLE keeps the E before -able — unlike most words, it REFUSES to change its E!"},{"w":"indefatigable","def":"showing sustained enthusiastic action with unflagging vitality","ex":"The indefatigable athlete trained for six hours every day without ever complaining of exhaustion.","say":"ih-ndih-FA-tih-guh-buhl","hook":"In + de + FATIG(ue) + able: one who cannot be made FATIGUED"},{"w":"plausible","def":"apparently reasonable and valid, and truthful","ex":"The detective thought the suspect's alibi was plausible at first, but closer examination of the evidence revealed several inconsistencies that cast serious doubt on his story.","say":"PLAW-zuh-buhl","hook":"A PLAUSIBLE story gets APPLAUSE — end it with -IBLE not -ABLE."}]},{"title":"-ance / -ence / -ancy / -ency (state / quality)","category":"Latin Suffixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"These noun suffixes create abstract nouns from adjectives. The rule: adjectives in -ant become -ance; adjectives in -ent become -ence. But French-origin words may not follow — and those are the ones in bees.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>EFFERVESCENCE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ef-er-VES-ents\n<b>Spell it.</b> E · F · F · E · R · V · E · S · C · E · N · C · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> ef-er-VES-ents\n<b>Syllables.</b> ef · fer · ves · cence\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [ef=EF] [fer=FER] [VES=VES] [ents=CENCE]\n<b>Exception.</b> -escence = becoming (Latin -escere); -sc- cluster is the hard part; double-f from ef- assimilation\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> French: effervescence (French)","cards":[{"title":"The Core Rule","body":"Adjective ending -ant → noun ending -ance: relevant → relevance, important → importance, defiant → defiance. Adjective ending -ent → noun ending -ence: different → difference, evident → evidence, prominent → prominence. The adjective tells you the noun."},{"title":"High-Value -ence Words","body":"Effervescence = bubbly, sparkling quality. Eloquence = beautiful speaking. Benevolence = goodwill. Magniloquence = pompous speech. Renaissance (re- + naissance = birth) = R-E-N-A-I-S-S-A-N-C-E — double-s! Obeisance (-ance not -ence!) = respectful bow. Prescience = foreknowledge."},{"title":"-escent = Becoming","body":"-escent = in the process of becoming. Effervescent = becoming bubbly. Adolescent = becoming an adult. Luminescent = becoming light-emitting. Convalescent = becoming well again. Incandescent = becoming glowingly hot. Quiescent = becoming quiet/still. The -sc- cluster in all of these is the spelling challenge."},{"title":"French Exceptions","body":"French-origin words may not follow the -ant/-ent rule. Nuance = -ance (from French, no -ant adjective). Vengeance = -ance (not -ence). Conscience = -ence (from con- + scire). For words you cannot analyze, asking for the language of origin at the microphone helps — French words are more likely to break the rule."},{"title":"-ancy/-ency (Dynamic Forms)","body":"These match their base adjectives: buoyant → buoyancy, truant → truancy, vacant → vacancy (all -ancy). Decent → decency, efficient → efficiency, urgent → urgency (all -ency). The dynamic forms -ancy/-ency are simply the -ance/-ence forms with the suffix -y attached to a slightly shortened base."}],"words":[{"w":"effervescence","def":"the process of bubbling as gas escapes","ex":"The effervescence of the sparkling water tickled Maya's nose as she took her first sip.","say":"ef-er-VES-ents","hook":"Think 'ever fizzing': eff-EVER-ESCENCE — double 'e,' double 'f,' then bubbles rise to the end."},{"w":"eloquence","def":"is using language with fluency and aptness","ex":"his eloquence attracted a large congregation","say":"EH-l-uh-k-w-uh-n-s","hook":"ELOQUENCE ends in -ENCE not -ANCE — an eloquent speaker always ENds with an impactful sENtencE."},{"w":"benevolence","def":"disposition to do good","ex":"The community was moved by the benevolence of the woman who quietly paid off the school lunch debts of every struggling family in town.","say":"buh-NEH-vuh-luhns","hook":"BENEvolence ends in -ENCE, because a kind person gives e-n-c-e couragement to others."},{"w":"obeisance","def":"is a bow or a curtsy","ex":"The knight performed a deep obeisance before the queen before receiving his honored title.","say":"oh-BAY-suhns","hook":"OBEISANCE: bow and say 'oh-BAY' then add -SANCE — you obey with a bow of reverence."},{"w":"nuance","def":"is a subtle difference in meaning","ex":"without understanding the finer nuances you can't enjoy the humor","say":"n-OO-ah-n-s","hook":"NUANCE has no extra I — it's a subtle shade of meaning, so keep the spelling subtle and short."},{"w":"vigilance","def":"the process of paying close and continuous attention","ex":"wakefulness, watchfulness, and bellicosity make a good hunter","say":"VIH-juh-luhns","hook":"VIGILANCE ends in -ANCE like 'dance' — stay alert and keep dancing watch!"},{"w":"vengeance","def":"means violent revenge or getting back","ex":"Vengeance is mine; I will repay, saith the Lord","say":"v-EH-n-j-uh-n-s","hook":"VENGE-ANCE: avenge with ANCE — remember there's a hidden G before -EANCE, like a grudge hiding inside."},{"w":"conscience","def":"motivation deriving logically from ethical or moral principles that govern a person's thoughts and actions","ex":"a person of unflagging conscience","say":"KAH-nshuhns","hook":"Your conSCIENCE uses SCIENCE to know right from wrong."},{"w":"magniloquence","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"adolescent","def":"a juvenile between the onset of puberty and maturity","ex":"As an adolescent, Theo struggled to balance the pressures of middle school friendships, growing responsibilities at home, and his own rapidly changing feelings about who he wanted to become.","say":"a-duh-LEH-suhnt","hook":"An ADOLESCENT grows — spell the SCENT of growth: a-d-o-l-e-S-C-E-N-T."},{"w":"luminescent","def":"emitting light not caused by heat","ex":"The luminescent stickers on her ceiling glowed softly after the lights went out.","say":"loo-muh-NEH-suhnt","hook":"LUMINESCENT ends in '-ent' like a glowing agent — only an '-ent' student spells it right."},{"w":"incandescent","def":"strikingly bright radiant or clear","ex":"an incandescent bulb","say":"ih-n-k-uh-n-d-EH-s-uh-n-t","hook":"An incanDESCENT bulb glows as it DESCENDS into heat — spell the SCENT of hot wax: -s-c-e-n-t."},{"w":"quiescent","def":"is being at rest quiet inactive","ex":"the quiescent level of centimeter wave-length solar radiation","say":"k-w-ay-EH-s-uh-n-t","hook":"QUIESCENT ends in -SCENT: imagine a quiet, still room with a faint scent — perfectly at rest."},{"w":"convalescent","def":"a person who is recovering from illness","ex":"convalescent children are difficult to keep in bed","say":"kah-nvuh-LEH-suhnt","hook":"A convalESCENT patient is like an adolESCENT — both are slowly growing, and both end in -ESCENT."},{"w":"buoyancy","def":"cheerfulness that bubbles to the surface; also the tendency of an object to float in a fluid","ex":"Even after her team lost the championship match, Priya's natural buoyancy lifted everyone's spirits within minutes.","say":"BOY-uh-nsee","hook":"BUOYANCY—BUOY keeps things afloat; don't sink into 'bouyancy'—the U comes before O"},{"w":"decency","def":"the quality of conforming to standards of propriety and morality","ex":"She had the decency to apologize for her rude comment before the meeting ended.","say":"DEE-suh-nsee","hook":"DECency — decent people follow the rules, and so does this word: D-E-C-E-N-C-Y."},{"w":"urgency","def":"the state of being urgent; an earnest and insistent necessity","ex":"The urgency in the firefighter's voice made everyone evacuate the building without hesitation.","say":"UR-juh-nsee","hook":"URGENCY comes from URGE — a strong urge feels urgent."},{"w":"renaissance","def":"the period of European history at the close of the Middle Ages and the rise of the modern world; a cultural rebirth from the 14th through the middle of the 17th centuries","ex":"Artists from across Europe were inspired by the renaissance, filling cathedrals and palaces with breathtaking paintings and sculptures.","say":"reh-nuh-SAHNS","hook":"RENAISSANCE = RE + NAIS + SANCE — one 'n,' one 's': a rebirth needs only one of each to spring anew."}]},{"title":"-ity / -ness / -hood / -ship / -dom (abstract state)","category":"Latin & Old English Suffixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Five suffixes that convert other words into abstract nouns — from different linguistic origins, covering different territory. Together they create the vocabulary of qualities, conditions, and realms.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PERSPICACITY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> —\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · E · R · S · P · I · C · A · C · I · T · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> —\n<b>Syllables.</b> p · e · r · s · p · i · c · a · c · i · t · y\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [per=PER] [spuh=SPI] [KAS=CAC] [uh=I] [tee=TY]\n<b>Exception.</b> noun form of perspicacious; -acity from -acious adjectives; -cac- not -cak-; stress: per-spuh-KAS-uh-tee\n<b>Origin.</b> —\n<b>Root.</b> —","cards":[{"title":"-ity (Latin)","body":"The most formal abstract suffix from Latin -itas. Perspicacity, sagacity, audacity, mendacity, loquacity, voracity, tenacity, vivacity — all from -acious adjectives. Also: brevity (brevis = short), levity (levis = light), gravity (gravis = heavy), probity (probus = honest)."},{"title":"-ness (Old English)","body":"The most flexible abstract suffix — works with almost any adjective. Happiness, sadness, darkness (everyday). Also with complex Latinate adjectives: conscientiousness, fastidiousness, scrupulousness. When no -ity form exists, -ness is always available. That is why both weirdness and (no weirdity) work."},{"title":"-hood (Old English)","body":"Limited to specific life stages or communities: childhood, adulthood, knighthood, priesthood, neighborhood, falsehood (abstract!). Cannot be added freely — only to established words. The -hood suffix always implies membership in a state or condition."},{"title":"-ship (Old English)","body":"Scholarship, sportsmanship, workmanship, friendship, hardship, stewardship, ownership. Also: kinship, fellowship, penmanship. The suffix carries a sense of skill, relationship, or status. Seamanship = the skill of a seaman — both the role and the craft."},{"title":"-dom (Old English)","body":"Kingdom = realm of a king. Freedom = state of being free. Wisdom = state of being wise. Martyrdom = state of being a martyr. Used ironically for large groups: officialdom, boredom, stardom. Still actively used to coin new words in contemporary English — fandom is a modern -dom coinage."}],"words":[{"w":"perspicacity","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"sagacity","def":"the mental ability to understand and discriminate between relations","ex":"The elder's sagacity helped the community solve problems that had stumped even the youngest scholars.","say":"suh-GAS-ih-tee","hook":"SAGA + city — a wise person's saga fills a whole city of knowledge: s-a-g-a-c-i-t-y."},{"w":"audacity","def":"fearless daring","ex":"he had the audacity to question my decision","say":"ah-DA-suh-tee","hook":"AUDACITy: it takes AUDACI-TY — bold enough to drop an 's' that doesn't belong."},{"w":"mendacity","def":"the tendency to be untruthful","ex":"The journalist's report exposed the politician's long history of mendacity, revealing dozens of misleading statements.","say":"meh-NDA-sih-tee","hook":"MENDACITY: a MENDed story is a LIE — liars MEND the truth with DACity of deceit."},{"w":"alacrity","def":"brisk and cheerful readiness or willingness to do something","ex":"When the teacher announced a surprise pizza party, the students cleaned up the classroom with surprising alacrity.","say":"uh-LA-kruh-tee","hook":"alACRIty — think of ACRI (swift/sharp) — sharp eagerness"},{"w":"brevity","def":"the use of brief expressions","ex":"The teacher praised her essay for its brevity, noting how she expressed complex ideas in just three paragraphs.","say":"BREH-vuh-tee","hook":"BREVITY: 'i' before 'ty'—brief like Shakespeare said, 'Brevity is the soul of wit.'"},{"w":"levity","def":"feeling an inappropriate lack of seriousness","ex":"The comedian's levity helped ease the tension in the room after the long, serious debate.","say":"LEH-vih-tee","hook":"LEVITY is lightness — like LEVITATION, it 'LEV'-itates above seriousness; no extra vowels needed."},{"w":"gravity","def":"(physics) the force of attraction between all masses in the universe; especially the attraction of the earth's mass for bodies near its surface; ; ; --Albert Einstein","ex":"the more remote the body the less the gravity","say":"GRA-vuh-tee","hook":"GRAVity is so serious it could drag you to your GRAVE — GRAV starts both."},{"w":"probity","def":"complete and confirmed integrity; having strong moral principles","ex":"in a world where financial probity may not be widespread","say":"PROH-buh-tee","hook":"proBITY — a person of probity won't bite you dishonestly; -ITY signals a quality."},{"w":"conscientiousness","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"fastidiousness","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"childhood","def":"the time of person's life when they are a child","ex":"His childhood in the small mountain town shaped his love of hiking and the outdoors.","say":"CHEYE-ldhuud","hook":"CHILDHOOD wears a HOOD like Little Red Riding Hood — don't forget the double-O in -hood."},{"w":"knighthood","def":"aristocrats holding the rank of knight","ex":"The celebrated author was awarded a knighthood for his lifetime of contributions to literature.","say":"NEYE-thuud","hook":"KNIGHTHOOD is the HOOD of honor a KNIGHT wears — stack knight+hood and keep both the silent K and silent GH inside."},{"w":"falsehood","def":"a false statement","ex":"The journalist worked tirelessly to expose every falsehood in the politician's speech.","say":"FA-lshuud","hook":"A falsehood wears a HOOD to hide the truth—don't forget the 'e' before the hood."},{"w":"scholarship","def":"financial aid provided to a student on the basis of academic merit","ex":"After years of staying up late to study, Priya won a full scholarship to attend her dream university tuition-free.","say":"SKAH-ler-shihp","hook":"sCHOLARship — a SCHOLAR earns a scholarSHIP; don't forget the 'ch' that sounds like 'k.'"},{"w":"workmanship","def":"skill in an occupation or trade","ex":"The judge admired the fine workmanship of the hand-carved cabinet at the state fair competition.","say":"WUR-kmuh-nshihp","hook":"WORKMANSHIP: the SHIP carries the skill of the WORKMAN — one P in SHIP sails the quality home."},{"w":"stewardship","def":"the position of steward","ex":"Under her careful stewardship, the community garden grew from a small plot into a neighborhood treasure.","say":"STOO-er-dshihp","hook":"STEWARDSHIP is the office of a STEWARD — a SHIP needs a steward, and the word ends in SHIP."},{"w":"wisdom","def":"information gained over time","ex":"The old fisherman's wisdom about the sea came from decades of watching the tides and weathering fierce storms.","say":"w-IH-z-d-uh-m","hook":"WISDOM drops the E from WISE — the truly wise know when to leave things out."},{"w":"martyrdom","def":"death that is imposed because of the person's adherence of a religious faith or cause","ex":"The historian wrote a moving chapter about the martyrdom of those who refused to abandon their beliefs under persecution.","say":"MAH-rter-duhm","hook":"Martyrdom ends in -dom like kingdom — a martyr's kingdom is their suffering, spell it martyr+dom."}]},{"title":"-ism / -ist (doctrine / practitioner)","category":"Greek Suffixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Greek -ismos = doctrine or practice; -istes = practitioner. Every -ism is a belief system or practice; every -ist is the person who holds or practices it. The pair is always structurally parallel.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>NARCISSISM</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> n-AH-r-s-ih-s-ih-z-uh-m\n<b>Spell it.</b> N · A · R · C · I · S · S · I · S · M\n<b>Say it again.</b> n-AH-r-s-ih-s-ih-z-uh-m\n<b>Syllables.</b> n · a · r · c · i · s · s · i · s · m\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [nar=NAR] [SIS=CIS] [iz=SIS] [um=M]\n<b>Exception.</b> double-S from Greek name Narcissus; -ism not -izm; stress: NAR-sis-iz-um (4 syllables)\n<b>Origin.</b> English\n<b>Root.</b> Greek Narkissos = youth who fell in love with his own reflection","cards":[{"title":"The Pair","body":"-ism = the belief/practice itself. -ist = the person. Nihilism (nihil = nothing) = belief nothing has meaning; nihilist = one who holds this. Narcissism = excessive self-admiration; narcissist = one who is narcissistic. The pair is always perfectly parallel. Know the -ism, you know the -ist."},{"title":"-ism in Religion & Philosophy","body":"Monotheism (mono- + theos) = one god. Polytheism = many gods. Atheism (a- + theos) = no god. Agnosticism = uncertain about gods. Stoicism = philosophy of endurance. Sophism = clever but misleading argument. Solipsism (solus = alone + ipse = self) = only the self exists."},{"title":"-ism in Social/Political Terms","body":"Ostracism (ostrakon = clay tablet used for voting out) = exclusion. Schism (skhizein = split) = a major split in a group. ⚠️ Schism = SKIZ-um — the sch = /sk/, making it one of the trickiest spellings in English. Nepotism (nepos = nephew) = favoring relatives. Both are classic bee words."},{"title":"Literary -isms","body":"Euphemism (eu- + pheme = speech) = a gentler substitute word. Aphorism = a concise, wise saying. Malapropism = a word wrongly used for a similar-sounding one. Anachronism (ana- + chron-) = something out of its time. Pleonasm = using more words than necessary. Catachresis = deliberate misuse of a word for effect."},{"title":"Spelling Traps","body":"Schism = S-C-H-I-S-M (sch = /sk/; do not write shism or skism). Narcissism = N-A-R-C-I-S-S-I-S-M (double-s from Narcissus). Ostracism = O-S-T-R-A-C-I-S-M. Catechism (kata- + ekhein = sound down) = C-A-T-E-C-H-I-S-M (instruction by question and answer). All have the -ism ending but their roots vary dramatically."}],"words":[{"w":"nihilism","def":"a revolutionary doctrine that advocates destruction of the social system for its own sake; the belief that nothing has meaning or value","ex":"The villain's nihilism made him truly frightening — he believed nothing mattered and acted accordingly.","say":"n-AY-uh-l-ih-z-uh-m","hook":"NIHILism — NIHIL means NOTHING in Latin; nihilism = the belief in nothing"},{"w":"narcissism","def":"is excessive self-love vanity","ex":"self-love that shut out everyone else","say":"n-AH-r-s-ih-s-ih-z-uh-m","hook":"NARCISSISM has double-s twice — so self-obsessed it even doubles its letters twice."},{"w":"ostracism","def":"the state of being banished or ostracized (excluded from society by general consent)","ex":"the association should get rid of its elderly members--not by euthanasia, of course, but by Coventry","say":"AW-s-t-r-uh-s-ih-z-uh-m","hook":"OSTRACism — picture an OSTRICH who has been cast out of the flock"},{"w":"schism","def":"division of a group into opposing factions","ex":"A bitter schism over leadership split the student council into two rival camps.","say":"SKIH-zuhm","hook":"A schism SPLITS like scissors"},{"w":"monotheism","def":"belief in a single God","ex":"Christianity, Islam, and Judaism are all examples of monotheism, the belief in one God.","say":"MAH-nuh-thee-ih-zuhm","hook":"MONO=one, THEOS=god — monotheISM believes in one God; think 'mono' like one-channel audio."},{"w":"polytheism","def":"belief in multiple Gods","ex":"Ancient Greece was known for its polytheism, with gods governing everything from the sea to the harvest.","say":"PAH-lee-thee-ih-zuhm","hook":"POLYTHEism believes in MANY THEos (gods) — like a theology with a crowded pantheon."},{"w":"atheism","def":"the doctrine or belief that there is no God","ex":"The philosophy class debated atheism and religion for hours, with students sharing deeply personal perspectives.","say":"uh-THEYE-suhm","hook":"Atheism: a-(no) + the + ism — there is NO 'i' before 'e' here; remember 'the' is right in the middle, which is exactly what atheists reject."},{"w":"stoicism","def":"an indifference to pleasure or pain","ex":"With remarkable stoicism, the injured hiker kept moving forward without complaining once.","say":"STOH-uh-sih-zuhm","hook":"STOICISM is the philosophy of enduring pain — the 'o-i' pairing stays calm and steady in the middle: s-t-o-i-c-i-s-m."},{"w":"sophism","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"solipsism","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"euphemism","def":"an inoffensive or indirect expression that is substituted for one that is considered offensive or too harsh","ex":"Saying someone has 'passed away' instead of 'died' is a common euphemism used to soften the pain of loss.","say":"YOO-fuh-mih-zuhm","hook":"EUPHEMism: EU(good)+PHEME(speech) — saying something GOOD instead of harsh; the PH sounds like 'F' for 'Friendly speech.'"},{"w":"aphorism","def":"a short pithy instructive saying","ex":"Grandma always had a wise aphorism ready, like 'a stitch in time saves nine,' whenever we faced a problem.","say":"A-fer-ih-zuhm","hook":"An APHORISM draws the HORIzon of wisdom — APH+HOR(izon)+ISM, a saying that defines the boundary of truth."},{"w":"malapropism","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"anachronism","def":"something located at a time when it could not have existed or occurred","ex":"The knight carrying a smartphone in the historical film was an obvious anachronism that made viewers laugh.","say":"uh-NA-kruh-nih-zuhm","hook":"An ANACHRONISM fights against (ANA) CHRONOS (time) — keep 'chron' for time and end it with '-ism', not '-izm'."},{"w":"nepotism","def":"favoritism shown to relatives or close friends by those in power, as by giving them jobs","ex":"The students accused the club president of nepotism when she made her best friend treasurer without holding an election.","say":"NEH-puh-tih-zuhm","hook":"NEPOTism — the NEPOTs (nephews) always get the jobs"},{"w":"catechism","def":"a series of question put to an individual (such as a political candidate) to elicit their views","ex":"The students memorized the catechism so they could answer the priest's questions with confidence.","say":"KA-tuh-kih-zuhm","hook":"CATECHism sounds out the faith — CAT+ECHO+ISM: the echo of a cat teaching religion."},{"w":"solecism","def":"is a nonstandard or ungrammatical usage","ex":"Interrupting the guest speaker mid-sentence was considered a glaring solecism that made the entire audience cringe with embarrassment.","say":"SOL-ih-siz-um","hook":"A SOLECISM is a SOLE mistake in etiquette—you stand alone in your awkwardness."}]},{"title":"-ology / -ologist / -ographer (study of)","category":"Greek Suffixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Greek logos = word/reason/study. The -ology suffix = the study of. One of the most productive patterns in English — know the root, know the field, know the specialist name.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>OPHTHALMOLOGY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ah-p-th-uh-m-AH-l-uh-j-ee\n<b>Spell it.</b> O · P · H · T · H · A · L · M · O · L · O · G · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> ah-p-th-uh-m-AH-l-uh-j-ee\n<b>Syllables.</b> o · p · h · t · h · a · l · m · o · l · o · g · y\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [off=OPH] [thal=THAL] [MOL=MOL] [uh=O] [jee=GY]\n<b>Exception.</b> -ophthalm- from ophthalmos = eye; -ph- = /f/ AND -th- = /th/ both in same word; 5 syllables\n<b>Origin.</b> Greek\n<b>Root.</b> Greek ophthalmos = eye + logos = study","cards":[{"title":"The -ology Pattern","body":"Root + -ology = study of that root. Biology = study of life. Geology = earth. Vexillology (vexillum = flag) = flags. Campanology (campana = bell) = bells. Dendrochronology (dendro = tree + chron + -ology) = tree-ring dating. Know any root; add -ology; you have a field of study."},{"title":"The -ologist Specialist","body":"Add -ist after the -olog-: seismologist (seismos = earthquake). Graphologist = handwriting. Gerontologist (geron = old man) = aging. Ornithologist (ornis = bird) = birds. Entomologist (entomon = insect) = insects. ⚠️ Etymologist (word origins) ≠ entomologist (insects). A classic confusable pair."},{"title":"Long -ology Championship Words","body":"Dendrochronology = D-E-N-D-R-O-C-H-R-O-N-O-L-O-G-Y. Eschatology (eskhatos = last) = study of the end times. Epistemology (episteme = knowledge) = how we know things. Phenomenology = study of conscious experience. Paleontology = study of fossils. Break each into its roots and they spell themselves."},{"title":"-ographer = One Who Records","body":"-graphos = one who writes. Choreographer = designs dances. Stenographer = writes in shorthand. Biographer = writes a life story. Lexicographer = writes dictionaries. Oceanographer = records the oceans. Same -graph- root family as -ology — just focused on writing/recording rather than studying."},{"title":"Etymology vs Entomology","body":"Etymology = etymon (true form) + -logy = study of true word forms — E-T-Y-M-O-L-O-G-Y. Entomology = entomon (cut in pieces = insect's segmented body) + -logy — E-N-T-O-M-O-L-O-G-Y. The second letter is the tell: ety- vs ento-. These are the most confused -ology words in spelling bees."}],"words":[{"w":"ophthalmology","def":"is the branch of medicine dealing with anatomy functions and diseases of the eye","ex":"She chose to specialize in ophthalmology because she wanted to help patients who were losing their sight.","say":"ah-p-th-uh-m-AH-l-uh-j-ee","hook":"OPHTHALMOLOGY — the word itself needs an eye exam; spot the OPHTHALM hiding before -OLOGY."},{"w":"seismology","def":"the branch of geology that studies earthquakes","ex":"Students studying seismology learned how to read the wavy lines on a seismograph after an earthquake.","say":"seye-ZMAH-luh-jee","hook":"SEISmic waves MOVE the ground — seismOLOGY studies that movement scientifically."},{"w":"graphology","def":"the study of handwriting (especially as an indicator of the writer's character or disposition)","ex":"The detective used graphology to analyze the threatening letter and draw clues about its author.","say":"gruh-FAH-luh-jee","hook":"GraphOLOGY is the OLOGY (study) of GRAPH (handwriting) — study what you write!"},{"w":"gerontology","def":"the branch of medical science that deals with diseases and problems specific to old people","ex":"Advances in gerontology have helped many older adults live healthier, more active lives well into their eighties.","say":"jeh-ruh-NTAH-luh-jee","hook":"GERONTOLOGY is the study of the old — GERON sounds like 'groan,' what old bones do."},{"w":"ornithology","def":"the branch of zoology that studies birds","ex":"Her passion for ornithology began when she spotted a rare snowy owl perched outside her bedroom window on a winter morning.","say":"aw-rnih-THAH-luh-jee","hook":"ORNITHO + LOGY: ORNITHO = birds (like dinosaur Ornithomimus) + LOGY = study"},{"w":"entomology","def":"the branch of zoology that studies insects","ex":"Her passion for entomology started when she found a firefly colony in her backyard.","say":"eh-ntuh-MAH-luh-jee","hook":"ENTOMology — ENTOM sounds like 'into 'em,' diving INTO insects to study them."},{"w":"etymology","def":"a history of a word","ex":"By studying the etymology of the word 'volcano,' students discovered it traces back to Vulcan, the ancient Roman god of fire.","say":"eh-tuh-MAH-luh-jee","hook":"ETYMOLOGY studies true word origins — remember ETYMon + OLOGY, no A in the middle."},{"w":"dendrochronology","def":"the science of dating events and variations in environment in former periods by study of the rings of growth in trees and aged wood.","ex":"Through dendrochronology, researchers determined that the ancient timber beam had been cut from a tree felled in 1347.","say":"deh-ndroh-kruh-NAH-luh-jee","hook":"DENDRO (tree) + CHRONO (time) + LOGY (study): scientists study tree rings to time-travel through history."},{"w":"eschatology","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"epistemology","def":"the philosophical theory of knowledge","ex":"In philosophy class, students debated an epistemology question: how do we actually know that anything is real?","say":"eh-pih-stuh-MAH-luh-jee","hook":"EPISTEMOLOGY: the STUDY (-logy) of what SEEMS (-steme) to be KNOWN — don't drop the O before -logy."},{"w":"phenomenology","def":"a philosophical doctrine proposed by Edmund Husserl based on the study of human experience in which considerations of objective reality are not taken into account","ex":"Her philosophy paper explored phenomenology and how personal experience shapes the way we understand the world.","say":"fuh-NAH-muh-nah-lah-gee","hook":"PHENOMENOLOGY is the study (-LOGY) of phenomena — drop the A, it's PHENOMEN-O-LOGY."},{"w":"paleontology","def":"the earth science that studies fossil organisms and related remains","ex":"Her lifelong love of dinosaurs led her to pursue a career in paleontology at a natural history museum.","say":"pay-lee-uh-NTAH-luh-jee","hook":"PALEO + ONTO + LOGY: study (logy) of ancient (paleo) living things (onto) — think: 'Pale old dinosaur ONTO the study page.'"},{"w":"choreographer","def":"someone who creates new dances","ex":"The brilliant choreographer designed a routine that perfectly matched the music's shifting tempo, leaving the audience breathless.","say":"kaw-ree-AH-gruh-fer","hook":"A choreographer WRITES (graphs) the CHORUS of dance moves"},{"w":"stenographer","def":"someone skilled in the transcription of speech (especially dictation)","ex":"The court stenographer's fingers flew across the keys, capturing every word of the dramatic trial testimony.","say":"steh-NUH-gruh-fer","hook":"A STENOGRAPHER uses a STENO pad to GRAPH (write) speech."},{"w":"lexicographer","def":"a compiler or writer of a dictionary; a student of the lexical component of language","ex":"The dedicated lexicographer spent forty years tracking the origins and changing meanings of everyday English words.","say":"leh-ksih-KAH-gruh-fer","hook":"LEXicoGRAPHer: Someone who GRAPHs (writes) all the LEXico (words) — a dictionary WRITER: L-E-X-I-C-O-G-R-A-P-H-E-R."},{"w":"vexillology","def":"means the study of flags","ex":"His passion for vexillology led him to collect flags from every country he had ever visited on his travels.","say":"vek-sih-LAH-luh-jee","hook":"VEXILLology has double L — flags wave in the WIND with two poles, so double the L."},{"w":"campanology","def":"the art and study of bell ringing, including the design, casting, acoustics, and techniques involved in ringing church bells or carillons","ex":"The retired professor devoted her weekends to campanology, traveling to old churches to study and ring their ancient bells.","say":"kam-puh-NOL-uh-jee","hook":"Campanology is the study of bells — hear 'camp-a-nol-ogy' ring out, letter by letter."}]},{"title":"Medical Suffixes: -itis / -osis / -ectomy / -plasty / -scope / -meter","category":"Greek Medical Suffixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Six Greek medical suffixes that together explain the structure of nearly every medical and surgical term. Know these six patterns and you can decode medical vocabulary on sight — even words you have never seen before.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>APPENDECTOMY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> a-pih-NDEH-ktuh-mee\n<b>Spell it.</b> A · P · P · E · N · D · E · C · T · O · M · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> a-pih-NDEH-ktuh-mee\n<b>Syllables.</b> ae · pih · ndeh · ktah · miy\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [uh=AP] [pen=PEN] [DEK=DEC] [tuh=TO] [mee=MY]\n<b>Exception.</b> -ectomy = surgical removal; appendix + -ectomy; -ec- not -ik-; stress on third syllable uh-pen-DEK-tuh-mee\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin appendere = to hang + Greek ektome = excision, from ek- = out +","cards":[{"title":"-itis = Inflammation","body":"Any -itis word = inflammation of [root]. Laryngitis (larynx) = inflamed voice box. Gastritis (gaster) = inflamed stomach. Gingivitis (gingiva = gum) = inflamed gums. Appendicitis = inflamed appendix. The root tells you WHERE; -itis tells you WHAT is happening. Simple, reliable, powerful."},{"title":"-osis = Condition or Process","body":"Cirrhosis (kirrhos = yellow-orange) = liver scarring. Osmosis = passage through a membrane. Thrombosis = blood clot. Fibrosis = excess fibrous tissue. Diagnosis (dia- + gnosis) = knowing by analysis. Prognosis (pro- + gnosis) = knowing in advance. -osis = an ongoing condition or biological process."},{"title":"-ectomy and -otomy","body":"-ectomy (ek- = out + tome = cutting) = surgical REMOVAL: tonsillectomy, appendectomy, vasectomy, mastectomy. -otomy/-tomy = cutting INTO (but not necessarily removing): dichotomy (dikho- = in two), lobotomy, tracheotomy. Key: -ectomy = remove; -tomy = cut open."},{"title":"-scope and -meter","body":"-skopein = to look. Kaleidoscope (kalos = beautiful + eidos = form), periscope (peri- = around), stethoscope (stethos = chest), endoscope (endo- = within). -metron = measure. Altimeter (height), spectrometer (spectrum), odometer (distance), barometer (pressure)."},{"title":"-plasty = Surgical Repair","body":"-plastos = molded. Rhinoplasty (rhino- = nose) = nose surgery. Angioplasty (angio- = vessel) = vessel repair. Arthroplasty (arthro- = joint) = joint replacement. Otoplasty (oto- = ear) = ear surgery. The -plasty suffix always means molding or repairing tissue surgically."}],"words":[{"w":"laryngitis","def":"inflammation of the mucous membrane of the larynx; characterized by hoarseness or loss of voice and coughing","ex":"After cheering at every game all weekend, the team captain developed laryngitis and could barely whisper on Monday.","say":"l-eh-r-uh-n-j-AY-t-uh-s","hook":"LARYNGitis = inflammation of the LARYNX — the root is inside the word!"},{"w":"gastritis","def":"inflammation of the stomach especially of its mucous membrane","ex":"After eating too much spicy food, Marcus developed gastritis that made his stomach ache for days.","say":"g-a-s-t-r-AY-t-uh-s","hook":"Your GASter (stomach) is on FIRE with gastrITIS — the 'i' before 'tis' marks the inflammation."},{"w":"gingivitis","def":"inflammation of the gums","ex":"The dentist warned her young patient that skipping nightly flossing could lead to gingivitis, making the gums red and sore.","say":"jin-jih-VY-tis","hook":"GINGIVitis makes your GINGIVA (gums) inflamed — -itis means inflammation"},{"w":"appendicitis","def":"inflammation of the vermiform appendix","ex":"The sharp pain in her lower right side turned out to be appendicitis, requiring immediate surgery.","say":"uh-peh-ndih-SEYE-tihz","hook":"APPENDICITIS ends in -itis meaning inflammation — it IRRITATES you, just like spelling it wrong does."},{"w":"cirrhosis","def":"is a disease of the liver","ex":"The doctor warned his patient that continued alcohol abuse could eventually lead to cirrhosis of the liver.","say":"s-ur-OH-s-uh-s","hook":"CIRRH-OSIS: double-R like the scarring, then -OSIS for the disease condition."},{"w":"osmosis","def":"(biology, chemistry) diffusion of molecules through a semipermeable membrane from a place of higher concentration to a place of lower concentration until the concentration on both sides is equal","ex":"During the science experiment, we watched osmosis pull water through the membrane into the saltier solution, causing the bag to swell.","say":"aw-ZMOH-sihs","hook":"OSMOsis — molecules are PUSHED (osmo) through a membrane"},{"w":"thrombosis","def":"the formation or presence of a thrombus (a clot of coagulated blood attached at the site of its formation) in a blood vessel","ex":"Long flights with little movement can increase the risk of deep vein thrombosis, so doctors recommend walking the aisle regularly.","say":"thrah-MBOH-suhs","hook":"THROMBO + OSIS: a condition (-osis) where your blood turns into a THROMBO-clot disaster."},{"w":"appendectomy","def":"surgical removal of the vermiform appendix","ex":"After suffering severe abdominal pain, Marcus was rushed to the hospital for an emergency appendectomy.","say":"a-pih-NDEH-ktuh-mee","hook":"An APPENDECTOMY removes the appendix — spell it append+ectomy, stitching the two words together like a surgical suture."},{"w":"tonsillectomy","def":"is the operation removing one or both tonsils","ex":"After suffering from repeated infections, the doctor recommended that Marco have a tonsillectomy.","say":"t-ah-n-s-ih-l-EH-k-t-uh-m-ee","hook":"TONSILLECTOMY doubles the 'l' like two tonsils being removed at once — one 'l' per tonsil!"},{"w":"vasectomy","def":"surgical procedure that removes all or part of the vas deferens (usually as a means of sterilization); is sometimes reversible","ex":"The health teacher briefly explained that a vasectomy is a minor surgical procedure used as a permanent form of birth control.","say":"va-ZEH-ktuh-mee","hook":"VASECTOMY cuts the VAS deferens — VAS + ECTOMY, like an appendECTOMY but for the VAS."},{"w":"mastectomy","def":"surgical removal of a breast to remove a malignant tumor","ex":"The doctor explained every step of the mastectomy procedure to the patient.","say":"ma-STEH-ktuh-mee","hook":"MASTECTOMY has '-ectomy' like appendECTOMY — the surgeon cuts with an 'e', not an 'a'."},{"w":"dichotomy","def":"is division into two parts","ex":"the dichotomy between eastern and western culture","say":"d-ay-k-AH-t-uh-m-ee","hook":"DICHOTOMY cuts things in two — spot the CH and remember 'cut in two halves.'"},{"w":"lobotomy","def":"surgical interruption of nerve tracts to and from the frontal lobe of the brain; often results in marked cognitive and personality changes","ex":"After reading about the lobotomy procedure in her history of medicine textbook, Priya was grateful for modern psychiatric treatments.","say":"LOH-boh-toh-mee","hook":"A loBOTomy cuts the LOBE — loBO-TOMY, loBOtomy"},{"w":"kaleidoscope","def":"is a continually shifting pattern or scene","ex":"Looking through the kaleidoscope, she saw brilliant geometric patterns of red, blue, and gold spinning with every turn.","say":"k-uh-l-AY-d-uh-s-k-oh-p","hook":"KALeidoscope shows BEAUTIFUL (kalos) SHAPES (eidos) to SEE (scope)."},{"w":"periscope","def":"an optical instrument that provides a view of an otherwise obstructed field","ex":"The submarine crew used a periscope to scan the surface of the ocean without rising above the water.","say":"PEH-ruh-skohp","hook":"A PERISCOPE lets you SCOPE all AROUND — peri (around) + SCOPE (look), spelled just like it sounds."},{"w":"stethoscope","def":"a medical instrument for listening to the sounds generated inside the body","ex":"The doctor pressed the cold stethoscope against the boy's chest and listened carefully to his heartbeat.","say":"STEH-thuh-skohp","hook":"The STETHO-SCOPE lets doctors SCOPE out your CHEST — no 'e' sneaks in between."},{"w":"altimeter","def":"an instrument for measuring height as above sea level or ground level","ex":"The pilot checked the altimeter to confirm the plane was cruising at thirty thousand feet.","say":"a-l-t-IH-m-uh-t-ur","hook":"An ALTIMETER measures ALTItude — ALTIter sounds right but it's ALTIMETER, like a speedoMETER."},{"w":"spectrometer","def":"spectroscope for obtaining a mass spectrum by deflecting ions into a thin slit and measuring the ion current with an electrometer","ex":"Using the spectrometer, the chemistry students discovered that the mystery solution contained traces of copper.","say":"speh-KTRAH-muh-ter","hook":"A SPECTROMETER METERS (measures) the SPECTRUM of light."},{"w":"rhinoplasty","def":"cosmetic surgery to improve the appearance of your nose","ex":"The athlete considered rhinoplasty after his nose was badly broken during the championship game.","say":"reye-noh-PLA-stee","hook":"Rhinoplasty reshapes your rhino-nose — plastic surgery for the rh-ino snout."},{"w":"angioplasty","def":"an operation to repair a damaged blood vessel or unblock a coronary artery","ex":"After his heart attack, the cardiologist performed an angioplasty to restore blood flow through his blocked artery.","say":"a-njee-uh-PLA-stee","hook":"ANGIOPLASTY: think PLASTIC surgery for your ANGIO (vessels) — a plumber replasties your pipes."}]},{"title":"Agent Suffixes: -er / -or / -ist / -ian / -eur / -eer","category":"Agent Suffixes","difficulty":"medium","concept":"When English says \"a person who does something,\" it borrows from six different languages. Origin determines suffix. The French -eur and -eer words are the ones that trip spellers most.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>RESTAURATEUR</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> reh-ster-uh-TUR\n<b>Spell it.</b> R · E · S · T · A · U · R · A · T · E · U · R\n<b>Say it again.</b> reh-ster-uh-TUR\n<b>Syllables.</b> reh · ster · ah · ter\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [res=RES] [tor=TOR] [uh=A] [TUR=TEUR]\n<b>Exception.</b> French restaurer (restore) + -eur; NO -n- before -eur; restauranteur is WRONG; stress: res-tor-uh-TUR\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> French restaurer = to restore + -ateur = one who does","cards":[{"title":"-or (Latin) vs -er (Old English/Germanic)","body":"Latin roots take -or: actor, senator, elevator, narrator. Old English/Germanic roots take -er: builder, teacher, baker, singer. Works about 85% of the time. For a Latinate word you are unsure about: try -or first. Governor not governour."},{"title":"-ist (Greek) = Practitioner or Believer","body":"Added to nouns: pianist, violinist, cyclist. Added to ideologies: socialist, nihilist. Added to Greek roots: botanist, physicist. Lyricist = one who writes lyrics. Illusionist = one who creates illusions. The -ist ending always signals a person with a specific expertise or belief."},{"title":"-ian / -an (Latin) = One Who Practices","body":"Words ending in -ic drop the c before -ian: magic → magician, electric → electrician, music → musician, logic → logician. Words ending in -ist sometimes become -ian for specialist titles: pediatrician (not pediatrist). Mathematician = M-A-T-H-E-M-A-T-I-C-I-A-N."},{"title":"-eur (French) = One Who Does (Formal)","body":"Always -eur not -er for these French-origin agent words: connoisseur, chauffeur, raconteur, saboteur, voyageur, entrepreneur, provocateur. ⚠️ Restaurateur (one who restores/runs a restaurant) = NOT restauranteur. One of the most common misspellings in educated English."},{"title":"-eer (Mixed) = One Who Works With","body":"Old French origin, now naturalized: auctioneer, engineer (ingen- = clever device + -eer), pioneer, volunteer, puppeteer, profiteer. Also -ier (French variant): barrier, rapier, financier, cavalier. The -eer/-ier ending usually carries the stress: auction-EER, financ-IER."}],"words":[{"w":"restaurateur","def":"the proprietor of a restaurant","ex":"The celebrated restaurateur opened her fifth dining establishment downtown, promising a menu inspired by her grandmother's recipes.","say":"reh-ster-uh-TUR","hook":"A restauraTEUR has no N — unlike restaurant, the owner drops the N and gains -EUR elegantly."},{"w":"connoisseur","def":"is a person competent to pass critical judgment","ex":"The art museum hired a connoisseur of Renaissance paintings to authenticate the newly discovered canvas.","say":"k-ah-n-uh-s-UR","hook":"A connoisseur KNOWS their stuff — double n, double s"},{"w":"chauffeur","def":"is a person employed to drive an automobile","ex":"The chauffeur held the door open as the ambassador stepped out of the sleek black limousine.","say":"sh-oh-f-UR","hook":"A CHAUFFEUR has a silent H and ends in -EUR — think 'chauf' like 'show' plus fancy French -EUR."},{"w":"raconteur","def":"a person skilled in telling anecdotes","ex":"Uncle Bernard was such a gifted raconteur that his campfire stories kept everyone wide-eyed until midnight.","say":"ra-kah-NTOOR","hook":"A raconTEUR ends like connoissEUR — French -EUR crowns the master storyteller: r-a-c-o-n-t-e-u-r."},{"w":"saboteur","def":"someone who commits sabotage or deliberately causes wrecks","ex":"The saboteur slipped into the factory at midnight and disabled the machinery, halting production for days.","say":"sa-buh-TUR","hook":"A sabotEUR is a European wrecker — the French -EUR ending marks the doer of the deed."},{"w":"entrepreneur","def":"is a person who organizes or manages an enterprise","ex":"At just fourteen, the young entrepreneur launched her own custom jewelry business and sold her designs online.","say":"ah-n-t-r-uh-p-r-uh-n-UR","hook":"Remember the unusual 'eur' ending — the French entrepreneur ends like 'connoisseur'"},{"w":"provocateur","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"auctioneer","def":"an agent who conducts an auction","ex":"The auctioneer rattled off numbers so fast that Priya barely raised her hand before the painting was sold.","say":"ah-kshuh-NIHR","hook":"An auctionEER has an EER — he steers the bids; EER not EAR, because he speaks, not listens."},{"w":"engineer","def":"a person who uses scientific knowledge to solve practical problems","ex":"He engineered the water supply project","say":"eh-njuh-NIHR","hook":"An ENGINEER runs the ENGINE — spell ENGINE first, then add '-eer'."},{"w":"pioneer","def":"someone who helps to open up a new line of research or technology or art","ex":"they went west as pioneers with only the possessions they could carry with them","say":"peye-uh-NIHR","hook":"A pionEER blazes the trail — remember the double E at the end like two boots marching forward."},{"w":"volunteer","def":"(military) a person who freely enlists for service","ex":"He volunteered the information","say":"vah-luh-NTIHR","hook":"A VOLUNTEER freely offers their WILL — ends in TEER like a pioneer who chooses to go."},{"w":"puppeteer","def":"one who operates puppets or marionettes","ex":"The skilled puppeteer made the tiny wooden marionette dance so gracefully that the children forgot anyone was controlling it.","say":"puh-puh-TEER","hook":"A puppetEER steers the puppet — EER like 'steer', the puppeteer steers the strings."},{"w":"financier","def":"a person skilled in large scale financial transactions","ex":"The young financier closed a deal worth millions of dollars before lunch and was already planning his next investment.","say":"fih-nuh-NSIHR","hook":"FINANCIER — a FINANCIER handles FINANCE with a French FLAIR (-ier)"},{"w":"cavalier","def":"a gallant or courtly gentleman","ex":"The cavalier bowed deeply and offered his hand to escort the duchess across the ballroom floor.","say":"ka-vuh-LIHR","hook":"A CAVALIER rides a CAVA-LIER horse and doesn't care if he spells it wrong—but you do: I-E-R at the end."},{"w":"electrician","def":"a person who installs or repairs electrical or telephone lines","ex":"The electrician rewired the entire basement to bring the old house up to modern safety codes.","say":"ih-leh-KTRIH-shuhn","hook":"An ELECTRICIAN is like a MAGICIAN with wires — both end in '-ician' because they perform amazing feats."},{"w":"magician","def":"someone who performs magic tricks to amuse an audience","ex":"The magician made a whole flock of white doves appear from beneath his silky black cape, leaving the audience speechless.","say":"muh-JIH-shuhn","hook":"A magiCIAN is a magiC person — spell MAGIC first then add IAN"},{"w":"pediatrician","def":"a specialist in the care of babies","ex":"The pediatrician reassured the nervous parents that their baby's slight fever would pass within a day.","say":"pee-dee-uh-TRIH-shuhn","hook":"pediatrICIAN ends in -ICIAN like magICIAN — a pediatrician works magic healing children."},{"w":"mathematician","def":"a person skilled in mathematics","ex":"The brilliant mathematician solved a problem that had stumped scholars for over a hundred years.","say":"ma-thuh-muh-TIH-shuhn","hook":"A mathemaTICIAN has a TICIAN at the end — like a magICIAN, but with numbers instead of tricks."}]},{"title":"-eau ending (silent -x plural)","category":"French Loanword Patterns","difficulty":"medium","concept":"French words ending in -eau use the plural -eaux — the x is silent in both forms. The vowel combination e-a-u = /oh/ is a reliable French signal. Four letters make one sound.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>TABLEAU</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> t-uh-b-l-OH\n<b>Spell it.</b> T · A · B · L · E · A · U\n<b>Say it again.</b> t-uh-b-l-OH\n<b>Syllables.</b> t · a · b · l · e · a · u\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [TAB=TAB] [loh=LEAU]\n<b>Exception.</b> -eau = /oh/ sound — 4 letters make 1 sound; plural tableaux with silent X; stress: TAB-loh\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> French tableau = picture, board, diminutive of table(slab, board, from","cards":[{"title":"The -eau Pattern","body":"French -eau = /oh/. Four letters, one syllable, one sound. Tableau (picture/scene), plateau (flat highland), château (castle), bureau (desk/office), trousseau (bride's possessions), gateau (French cake), flambeau (torch). All pronounced with /oh/ at the end."},{"title":"The Silent Plural -eaux","body":"Singular -eau → plural -eaux — the x is completely silent. Both forms pronounced identically: tableau = tableaux = /TAB-loh/. This is a classic spelling bee trap: asked to spell the plural, many write -eaus. It is -eaux. Always. No exceptions."},{"title":"Portmanteau — a Special Word","body":"Portmanteau (porter = carry + manteau = cloak) = a large hinged suitcase. Lewis Carroll also coined portmanteau word for two words merged into one: smog = smoke + fog; brunch = breakfast + lunch; motel = motor + hotel. The suitcase that holds two things becomes the word that holds two words."},{"title":"More -eau Words","body":"Nouveau (new, as in nouveau riche = newly wealthy). Beau (admirer/boyfriend). Rondeau (a type of poem). Morceau (a short musical piece). Rideau (a curtain). Bordeau (Bordeaux wine region). Some words carry the circumflex accent (â) in French; this disappears in English but the spelling stays."},{"title":"The Confusables","body":"Plateau (flat high area) vs plaque vs plait (braid) — completely different words. Bureau (desk/government office) vs burrow (a hole) — wildly different origins. When you see -eau, it is always French, always /oh/, and always distinct from any similar-sounding English word."}],"words":[{"w":"tableau","def":"a group of people attractively arranged (as if in a painting)","ex":"The drama students created a stunning tableau representing the signing of the Declaration of Independence, holding perfectly still for thirty seconds.","say":"t-uh-b-l-OH","hook":"TABLEAU: a TABLE of living figures arranged like ART—the 'eau' is silent like a still painting"},{"w":"plateau","def":"is a land area having a relatively level surface considerably raised above adjoining land","ex":"The hikers rested on the wide plateau and gazed at the sweeping valley far below them.","say":"p-l-a-t-OH","hook":"A PLATEAU has a flat top spelled with -EAU at the end — think of the French word for water (eau) pooling on flat land."},{"w":"château","def":"an impressive country house (or castle) in France","ex":"The family spent their summer vacation touring a magnificent chateau surrounded by vineyards in the French countryside.","say":"sha-TOH","hook":"A French CHATEAU ends like a bow — E-A-U, the fancy French 'oh' sound."},{"w":"bureau","def":"an administrative unit of government","ex":"the Central Intelligence Agency","say":"BYUU-roh","hook":"BUREAU ends in -EAU, the French word for water — let that fancy French ending FLOW: bur-EAU."},{"w":"trousseau","def":"is clothing linen especially for a bride","ex":"Her grandmother spent months carefully embroidering linens for her trousseau before the wedding day arrived.","say":"TROO-soh","hook":"TROUSSEAU has double S like a bride's double joy — trouSSeau, and ends in the fancy French -EAU."},{"w":"gateau","def":"any of various rich and elaborate cakes","ex":"The bakery displayed a stunning chocolate gateau layered with cream and fresh raspberries in the window.","say":"gah-TOH","hook":"A gateau ends in -EAU like 'château'—rich cakes belong in fancy French châteaux."},{"w":"flambeau","def":"a flaming torch (such as are used in processions at night)","ex":"The masked marcher held a glowing flambeau high above his head as the Mardi Gras parade wound through the dark streets.","say":"FLAM-boh","hook":"A FLAMBEAU torch glows like a beautiful EAU — remember the French -EAU ending."},{"w":"nouveau","def":"French for 'new,' used in English especially in phrases such as 'nouveau riche' (newly wealthy) or 'art nouveau' (a late 19th-century decorative art style).","ex":"The nouveau restaurant served traditional dishes with unexpected modern twists that surprised every food critic in town.","say":"noo-VOH","hook":"NOUVeau — think NOVEL and NEW — same root!"},{"w":"beau","def":"a man who is the lover of a girl or young woman","ex":"if I'd known he was her boyfriend I wouldn't have asked","say":"BOH","hook":"Your BEAU is BEAUtiful — the first four letters of beautiful spell your beau: b-e-a-u."},{"w":"rondeau","def":"a musical form that is often the last movement of a sonata","ex":"The pianist finished the recital with a spirited rondeau that had the audience clapping along by the final bars.","say":"rah-NDOH","hook":"RONDEAU — ROND means ROUND, like music that circles back to the beginning"},{"w":"portmanteau","def":"a new word formed by joining two others and combining their meanings","ex":"Lewis Carroll was a master of the portmanteau, blending 'smoke' and 'fog' into the word 'smog.'","say":"PAW-rtmah-ntoh","hook":"A portmanteau CARRIES two words like a bag carries two halves"},{"w":"morceau","def":"a short literary or musical composition","ex":"The pianist performed a delicate morceau that moved the small audience to tears.","say":"mor-SOH","hook":"A MORCEAU is a musical morsel — think of it as a tiny BITE (MORS) of music ending in the fancy French -EAU."},{"w":"flambeau","def":"a flaming torch (such as are used in processions at night)","ex":"The masked marcher held a glowing flambeau high above his head as the Mardi Gras parade wound through the dark streets.","say":"FLAM-boh","hook":"A FLAMBEAU torch glows like a beautiful EAU — remember the French -EAU ending."},{"w":"gâteaux","def":"any of various rich and elaborate cakes","ex":"The bakery window displayed an assortment of stunning gateaux decorated with fresh berries and cream.","say":"ga-TOHZ","hook":"French plurals love an -X: gateaux, like châteaux—multiple fancy cakes deserve a fancy plural."},{"w":"châteaux","def":"an impressive country house (or castle) in France","ex":"The Loire Valley is famous for its stunning chateaux that once housed French royalty.","say":"shuh-TOH","hook":"French castles get the royal X treatment — CHATEAUX ends in the silent X of French nobility."},{"w":"tableaux","def":"a group of people attractively arranged (as if in a painting)","ex":"The drama students created stunning tableaux to represent key scenes from the history of ancient Rome.","say":"tuh-BLOH","hook":"TABLEAUX ends in -eaux like bordeaux wine — beautiful French paintings need a French plural."},{"w":"plateaux","def":"a relatively flat highland","ex":"The French geographers mapped the vast plateaux that stretched across the interior of the continent.","say":"pla-TOHZ","hook":"The French keep the X in plateaux, just as they keep the X in beaux — fancy flat endings for fancy flat lands."}]},{"title":"-oir / -oire (French vowel ending)","category":"French Loanword Patterns","difficulty":"medium","concept":"French words ending in -oir or -oire carry their French spelling into English intact. The -oir sounds like /wahr/ — a distinctively French pattern impossible to guess without knowing it.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>BOUDOIR</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> b-OO-d-oy-r\n<b>Spell it.</b> B · O · U · D · O · I · R\n<b>Say it again.</b> b-OO-d-oy-r\n<b>Syllables.</b> b · o · u · d · o · i · r\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [BOO=BOU] [dwahr=DOIR]\n<b>Exception.</b> -oir = /wahr/ sound; from French bouder = to sulk; stress on second syllable boo-DWAHR\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> French bouder = to sulk, pout","cards":[{"title":"The -oir Pattern","body":"French -oir = /wahr/ sound. Boudoir (bouder = to sulk) = a private sitting room. Abattoir (abattre = to strike down) = a slaughterhouse. Peignoir (peigner = to comb) = a lightweight dressing gown. Armoire (armarium = cupboard) = a tall wardrobe. The -oir ending is unmistakably French."},{"title":"More -oir/-oire Words","body":"Reservoir (réserver) = a lake storing water — R-E-S-E-R-V-O-I-R. Memoir (mémoire = memory) = a personal narrative. Repertoire (répertoire = inventory) = a known set of works — R-E-P-E-R-T-O-I-R-E (keeps the final e in American English). Conservatoire = a music school (British usage)."},{"title":"Memory Trick","body":"The -oir ending sounds like the English word \"war\" with a /w/ added: /wahr/. So boudoir = BOO + d + war = BOO-dwahr. Abattoir = uh-BAT + war = uh-BAT-wahr. Once you hear the /wahr/ ending, the -oir spelling becomes automatic."},{"title":"Reservoir Spelling Detail","body":"R-E-S-E-R-V-O-I-R — the -oir at the end, not -oire. Note the vowel sequence: E-R-V-O-I-R. Many misspell this as resevoir (dropping the r) or reservoire (adding an e). Say it syllable by syllable: res · er · voir — three clean syllables."},{"title":"-oire Variant","body":"Some French words keep -oire in American English: repertoire (R-E-P-E-R-T-O-I-R-E), conservatoire. Others drop the final e: reservoir, memoir. When in doubt, the question \"What language does this word come from?\" at the microphone = French → prepare for -oir or -oire."}],"words":[{"w":"boudoir","def":"is a woman's private sitting room","ex":"The duchess retreated to her boudoir each evening to write letters and read by candlelight.","say":"b-OO-d-oy-r","hook":"A BOUDOIR is where a lady goes to BROOD — bouder means to sulk, and the -oir is her private place."},{"w":"abattoir","def":"A slaughterhouse; a place where animals are killed for food on a large scale.","ex":"The journalist's expose revealed unsanitary conditions at the abattoir that were shocking to consumers who had never considered where their meat came from.","say":"a-buh-TWAHR","hook":"ABATTOIR has double-t—two t's like two blades in a slaughterhouse"},{"w":"peignoir","def":"is a woman's dressing gown","ex":"She slipped into her silk peignoir and settled into the armchair beside the window to read her novel.","say":"pen-WAHR","hook":"A PEIGNOIR is worn while combing your hair — the GN hides silently like a comb tucked in a robe pocket."},{"w":"armoire","def":"is a large wardrobe or movable cupboard","ex":"She discovered her grandmother's old love letters hidden at the back of the towering oak armoire.","say":"AH-m-w-ah-r","hook":"An armOIRE stores your wardrobe — think 'OIR' as in French 'voir' (to see) what you'll wear today."},{"w":"reservoir","def":"is a place where water is collected or stored","ex":"a reservoir of talent","say":"r-EH-z-uh-v-w-ah-r","hook":"A reserVOIR ends in -VOIR (French for 'see') — au reVOIR, see you at the water reservoir!"},{"w":"memoir","def":"is a record written by a person based on personal observation","ex":"The retired astronaut wrote a gripping memoir about her harrowing journey aboard the damaged space shuttle.","say":"m-EH-m-w-ah-r","hook":"A MEMOIR is a MEMory told with French flair — spell the French ending 'o-i-r', not 'i-o-r'."},{"w":"repertoire","def":"the entire range of skills or aptitudes or devices used in a particular field or occupation","ex":"the repertory of the supposed feats of mesmerism","say":"REH-per-twahr","hook":"rePERTOIRE ends in -OIRE like a French soirée — a collection you perform at every evening event."},{"w":"conservatoire","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""}]},{"title":"-ette (French diminutive)","category":"French Loanword Patterns","difficulty":"medium","concept":"French -ette = a small version of something (diminutive). Always double-t, always ends in silent -e. Once you see the pattern, every -ette word spells itself.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PIROUETTE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> p-ih-r-oo-EH\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · I · R · O · U · E · T · T · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> p-ih-r-oo-EH\n<b>Syllables.</b> p · i · r · o · u · e · t · t · e\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [pir=PIR] [oo=OU] [ET=ETTE]\n<b>Exception.</b> -ette = small/diminutive; from French pirer = to spin; final -ette not -et; stress on last syllable: pir-oo-ET\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> French pirouette = spinning top","cards":[{"title":"The -ette Diminutive","body":"French -ette makes things smaller or more delicate. Pirouette = a spinning turn. Marionette = a small puppet (originally \"little Mary\"). Palette (pale = shovel) = a small flat surface for colors. Layette = a set of small baby clothes. Coquette = a flirtatious woman. Silhouette = a dark outline."},{"title":"-ette for Compositions","body":"Vignette (vigne = vine) = a brief literary sketch. Roulette (rouler = roll) = little rolling wheel. Serviette = a small serving cloth = napkin. Brunette = having brown hair. Rosette = a rose-shaped decoration. Cassette = a small case. Etiquette = the small rules of polite behavior."},{"title":"Always Double-T","body":"The -ette ending always has double-t: P-I-R-O-U-E-T-T-E, never pirouete. The -tt- comes from the French diminutive form. ⚠️ Confetti (Italian, not French) = C-O-N-F-E-T-T-I — double-t here is Italian diminutive, not the French -ette pattern. Different language, same doubling instinct."},{"title":"-ette vs -et (Single-t)","body":"Some French words end in -et (single-t, silent final t): buffet, bouquet, ballet, ricochet, crochet. The -ette words have a pronounced vowel before the final t: pi-roo-ET (you hear the vowel). The -et words have a stressed vowel that ends the word: boo-KAY (the t is silent). Hearing the vowel before the t → -ette."},{"title":"Championship -ette Words","body":"Epaulette (épaule = shoulder) = a shoulder decoration on a uniform. Lorgnette (lorgner = to spy) = a pair of glasses on a handle. Marionette = M-A-R-I-O-N-E-T-T-E. Pirouette = P-I-R-O-U-E-T-T-E. Silhouette = S-I-L-H-O-U-E-T-T-E (silent h as well as double-t)."}],"words":[{"w":"pirouette","def":"is a whirling about on one foot as in ballet dancing","ex":"The ballerina completed a flawless pirouette at center stage, spinning so fast she seemed to blur.","say":"p-ih-r-oo-EH","hook":"PIROUETTE has FOUR vowels in a row (ouet) — the dancer spins four times before sticking the landing."},{"w":"marionette","def":"a small figure of a person operated from above with strings by a puppeteer","ex":"The marionette's wooden legs clattered on the tiny stage as the puppeteer made it dance a jig.","say":"mair-ee-uh-NET","hook":"Little MARION dances on a stage — mariONETTE"},{"w":"palette","def":"is a board with a thumb hole used by painters to mix colors","ex":"The artist squeezed bright colors onto her palette before painting the sunset.","say":"p-A-l-uh-t","hook":"A PALETTE has one 'l' and ends in -ette — remember: one layer of paint needs one 'l,' then -ette like 'kitchenette.'"},{"w":"layette","def":"is an outfit of clothing or bedding for a newborn baby","ex":"Grandma knitted several tiny sweaters to add to the layette she was preparing for the new arrival.","say":"lay-ET","hook":"A layETTE for a baby — think of a little French box (ETTE) where you LAY the newborn's clothes."},{"w":"coquette","def":"a seductive woman who uses her sex appeal to exploit men","ex":"The guys always try to chat up the new secretaries","say":"koh-KET","hook":"A coquETTE ends in ETTE like a fashionable French lady — double T, double charm."},{"w":"silhouette","def":"is a two-dimensional representation of the outline of an object","ex":"As the sun set behind the mountains, the silhouette of the ancient castle appeared dramatically against the glowing orange sky.","say":"s-ih-l-uh-w-EH-t","hook":"silHOUette — the HOUSE makes a silhouette against the sky; remember -ETTE at the end (double T, final E)."},{"w":"vignette","def":"a brief literary description","ex":"The author opened her novel with a vignette of a girl watching fireflies, instantly drawing readers into the story's dreamy mood.","say":"vih-NYEHT","hook":"viGNETTE has a silent 'g' — like a vine growing quietly."},{"w":"roulette","def":"is a game of chance","ex":"The players gathered around the spinning roulette wheel, each hoping the ball would land on their chosen number.","say":"r-oo-l-EH-t","hook":"ROULETTE is a little wheel — the -ETTE ending spins like the wheel, one T before the E, never two."},{"w":"serviette","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"brunette","def":"a person with dark (brown) hair","ex":"The lead actress in the school play was a tall brunette whose dark, glossy hair cascaded past her shoulders and caught the stage lights whenever she turned her head dramatically.","say":"broo-NEHT","hook":"BRUNETTE is feminine — she gets double T and an E, like a little extra flair."},{"w":"rosette","def":"an ornament or pattern resembling a rose that is worn as a badge of office or as recognition of having won an honor","ex":"The winning horse wore a bright blue rosette pinned proudly to its bridle.","say":"ruh-SEHT","hook":"A roSETTE is a little rose you SET on your lapel — one S, double T."},{"w":"cassette","def":"a container that holds a magnetic tape used for recording or playing sound or video","ex":"He found an old cassette of his favorite band tucked away in a dusty shoebox.","say":"kuh-SEHT","hook":"CASSETTE has double-S and double-T: two S's for the two spools of tape spinning inside."},{"w":"epaulette","def":"adornment consisting of an ornamental cloth pad worn on the shoulder","ex":"Each officer wore a silver epaulette on his right shoulder to show his rank.","say":"EP-uh-let","hook":"Epaulette has a double T at the end — two tassels dangling from that fancy shoulder pad."},{"w":"lorgnette","def":"eyeglasses that are held to the eyes with a long handle","ex":"The opera patron raised her lorgnette to study the performers on the distant stage.","say":"law-RNYEHT","hook":"A LORGNETTE lets you LORN-YET see who's across the room — keep the silent GN and double-T with -ETTE."},{"w":"etiquette","def":"is conventional requirements to social behavior","ex":"Before the formal dinner, the students attended a class on table etiquette so they would know which fork to use for each course.","say":"EH-t-uh-k-uh-t","hook":"ETIQUETTE has a DOUBLE T at the end — it takes TWO T's of effort to have good manners."},{"w":"statuette","def":"a small carved or molded figure","ex":"She won a tiny golden statuette at the regional drama competition and kept it on her desk.","say":"sta-choo-EHT","hook":"A statuETTE is a little statue — the '-ette' ending (double 't') means small, like a petite figurine."}]},{"title":"-esque / -ique / -que (French endings)","category":"French Loanword Patterns","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Three French/Italian-derived endings giving English some of its most distinctive-looking words. Silent -e at the end; qu sounds like /k/. These patterns are completely regular once learned.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PICTURESQUE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> p-IH-k-ch-ur-uh-s-k\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · I · C · T · U · R · E · S · Q · U · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> p-IH-k-ch-ur-uh-s-k\n<b>Syllables.</b> p · i · c · t · u · r · e · s · q · u · e\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [pik=PIC] [chur=TUR] [ESK=ESQUE]\n<b>Exception.</b> -esque = in the style of; silent final -e; stress on last syllable pik-chur-ESK\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> French pittoresque = like a picture","cards":[{"title":"-esque = In the Style Of","body":"Italian -esco → French -esque → English. Picturesque = like a picture = visually charming. Grotesque (grotta = cave/grotto) = bizarre and distorted. Arabesque = in the Arabic style. Burlesque = comic theatrical style. Statuesque = like a statue = impressively tall. Kafkaesque = surreally nightmarish (from the author Kafka)."},{"title":"-ique = French Origin Signal","body":"-ique words come from French. Boutique = a small specialty shop. Mystique = an air of mystery. Technique = a method. Physique = body structure. Antique = an old object. Unique = the only one of its kind. Oblique = slanting. All pronounced with /eek/ at the end — B-O-U-T-I-Q-U-E."},{"title":"-que at the End","body":"Rare but important: opaque (opacus = shaded) = does not allow light through. Plaque = a flat commemorative sign. Torque (torquere = to twist) = rotational force. Clique = a small exclusive group. The -que without a preceding -i- appears in only a few words."},{"title":"The qu Rule","body":"In all three endings, q is ALWAYS followed by u. English never has q without u — except in borrowed words like qi, qigong, qanat. For all -esque/-ique/-que words: always write qu, never just q. This is one of the most reliable spelling rules in English."},{"title":"High-Value Championship Words","body":"Arabesque = A-R-A-B-E-S-Q-U-E (often misspelled arbaesque). Grotesque = G-R-O-T-E-S-Q-U-E. Mystique = M-Y-S-T-I-Q-U-E (note the y = vowel). Technique = T-E-C-H-N-I-Q-U-E (-ch- = /k/ from Greek tekhnē through French). Unique = U-N-I-Q-U-E — only one u at the start."}],"words":[{"w":"picturesque","def":"is visually charming or quaint","ex":"a picturesque village","say":"p-IH-k-ch-ur-uh-s-k","hook":"A scene so pretty it belongs in a picture—add -ESQUE like a French flair at the end."},{"w":"grotesque","def":"is odd or unnatural in appearance or shape","ex":"tales of grotesque serpents eight fathoms long that churned the seas","say":"g-r-oh-t-EH-s-k","hook":"GROTESQUE art was found in GROTTO caves — grot+esque, ending in the fancy French -ESQUE."},{"w":"arabesque","def":"position in which the dancer has one leg raised behind and arms outstretched in a conventional pose","ex":"The ballerina held a flawless arabesque for several breathtaking seconds, her back leg perfectly parallel to the stage.","say":"ar-ah-BESK","hook":"Arabesque ends in -ESQUE like 'picturesque' — a beautifully posed, picture-like position."},{"w":"burlesque","def":"a theatrical entertainment of broad and earthy humor; consists of comic skits and short turns (and sometimes striptease)","ex":"The students spoofed the teachers","say":"ber-LEHSK","hook":"BURLESQUE ends in '-que' like a French joke — picture a clown asking 'What's the ESQUE of this?' with a wink."},{"w":"statuesque","def":"of size and dignity suggestive of a statue","ex":"The statuesque player towered over the other students at tryouts, moving with an effortless, graceful stride.","say":"sta-choo-EHSK","hook":"STATUESQUE ends in -ESQUE like grotESQUE — noble and grand!"},{"w":"boutique","def":"is a small shop within a larger store","ex":"She found the perfect dress at a tiny boutique tucked between a bakery and a bookstore on the cobblestone street.","say":"b-oo-t-EE-k","hook":"A BOUTIQUE has a UNIQUE quality — spot the word UNIQUE hiding inside boUTIQUE."},{"w":"mystique","def":"is an aura of mystery or mystical power","ex":"The reclusive artist's mystique grew stronger with every painting she refused to sell or explain.","say":"m-ih-s-t-EE-k","hook":"MYSTIQUE ends in QUE like a French boutique; she had the mystique of a chic French boutique."},{"w":"technique","def":"is the manner in which the technical skills of a particular art are used","ex":"practice greatly improves proficiency","say":"t-eh-k-n-EE-k","hook":"TECHNIQUE ends in -IQUE like UNIQUE — a unique technique needs that silent QUE: T-E-C-H-N-I-Q-U-E."},{"w":"physique","def":"constitution of the human body","ex":"Leonardo studied the human body","say":"fuh-ZEEK","hook":"Your physique is unique — both end in '-que', a classy French flourish."},{"w":"antique","def":"an elderly man","ex":"We went antiquing on Saturday","say":"a-NTEEK","hook":"An ANTIQUE always ends in -QUE — it's a uniquely old piece, and UNIQUE ends in -QUE too!"},{"w":"unique","def":"radically distinctive and without equal","ex":"he is alone in the field of microbiology","say":"yoo-NEEK","hook":"UNIQUE ends with QUE — it's the one word that uses Q without a U after it... wait, it does! That's unique."},{"w":"oblique","def":"any grammatical case other than the nominative","ex":"the oblique rays of the winter sun","say":"uh-b-l-EE-k","hook":"OBLIQUe — think of a slanted line that is not quite EQUAL to straight."},{"w":"opaque","def":"is not allowing light to pass through","ex":"opaque windows of the jail","say":"oh-p-AY-k","hook":"OPAQUE ends in '-que' like unique — both words end in a quirky silent 'ue' that blocks easy reading."},{"w":"plaque","def":"is a tablet or plate of metal intended for use as an ornament","ex":"A bronze plaque on the library wall honored the generous donor who funded its construction.","say":"p-l-A-k","hook":"A plAQUE hangs on the wall—it has a QUEUE of letters: Q-U-E at the end."},{"w":"torque","def":"is something that produces rotation","ex":"The mechanic used a special wrench to apply the correct torque when tightening the engine bolts.","say":"t-AW-r-k","hook":"TORQUE has a silent QUE — think: it QUEERLY twists, so keep the QUE."},{"w":"kafkaesque","def":"relating to or in the manner of Franz Kafka or his writings","ex":"the kafkaesque terror of the endless interrogations","say":"kah-fkuh-EHSK","hook":"Kafkaesque ends like grotesque — both describe something disturbingly strange: K-A-F-K-A-E-S-Q-U-E."},{"w":"romanesque","def":"a style of architecture developed in Italy and western Europe between the Roman and the Gothic styles after 1000 AD; characterized by round arches and vaults and by the substitution of piers for columns and profuse ornament and arcades","ex":"The old cathedral featured Romanesque arches and thick stone walls that had stood for nearly a thousand years.","say":"roh-muh-NEHSK","hook":"Romanesque arches look like a ROMAN's UNIQUE curved brow — end with -ESQUE like a grotesque gargoyle."}]},{"title":"French Silent Letters","category":"French Loanword Patterns","difficulty":"hard","concept":"French words in English frequently carry silent final consonants — -t, -s, -x, -p, -d. These were once pronounced in Old French but fell silent while spelling was preserved. The result: some of English's trickiest words.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>RENDEZVOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> RAH-ndih-voo\n<b>Spell it.</b> R · E · N · D · E · Z · V · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> RAH-ndih-voo\n<b>Syllables.</b> raa · ndih · vuw\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [RON=REN] [day=DEZ] [voo=VOUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> -ez = /ay/; -vous = /voo/; final -s completely silent; from rendez-vous = present yourselves\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> French rendez-vous = present yourselves","cards":[{"title":"Silent Final -t","body":"Ballet (ba-LAY), bouquet (boo-KAY), crochet (kroh-SHAY), ricochet (RIK-uh-shay), parquet (par-KAY), valet (VAL-ay), buffet (buh-FAY), debut (day-BYOO). The -t is spelled, never pronounced. \"Spell what you don't hear\" is the French rule."},{"title":"Silent Final -s","body":"Rendezvous (RON-day-voo), corps (kor — BOTH p AND s silent!), chassis (SHAS-ee), faux pas (FOH-PAH — two final consonants silent), debris (duh-BREE), fracas (FRAY-kus). These are borrowed exactly as written in French, where final -s was already silent."},{"title":"The Double Silent — corps","body":"Corps = C-O-R-P-S — the p is silent AND the s is silent. Pronounced simply /KOR/. Plural corps is /KORZ/ — the s becomes voiced in the plural. Hors d'oeuvre = /or-DURV/ — the h, the s, and the final e are all silent. French truly is a language where silence rules the ends of words."},{"title":"Silent -x","body":"In the -eau/-eaux pattern, the plural -x is always silent. Also: faux (FOH = false, as in faux fur). Beaux (BOH = plural of beau). In Old French, x was a shorthand abbreviation for s in plurals — the abbreviation became permanent in spelling but the s sound later fell silent."},{"title":"Microphone Strategy at the Bee","body":"When you identify a word as French: (1) final consonants are probably silent, (2) stress falls on the LAST syllable (opposite of English), (3) vowels have French sounds. Ask \"What language does this word come from?\" If French, apply these three rules automatically before spelling."}],"words":[{"w":"ballet","def":"a theatrical representation of a story that is performed to music by trained dancers","ex":"She had practiced ballet for ten years before landing the role of the Swan Queen.","say":"ba-LAY","hook":"BALLET ends in -ET (silent T) like a French baguETte — the T is there but never heard."},{"w":"bouquet","def":"an arrangement of flowers that is usually given as a present","ex":"The groom's hands trembled as he presented the bride with a bouquet of red roses and white lilies tied with a silk ribbon.","say":"b-oo-k-AY","hook":"BOUQUET ends in -QUET but sounds like -KAY—picture a bouquet at a boutiQUE"},{"w":"crochet","def":"is needlework with a needle having a hook at one end","ex":"Every evening, the grandmother would settle into her favorite armchair and crochet colorful blankets for the grandchildren, her hook moving so quickly that the yarn seemed to form patterns by magic.","say":"k-r-oh-sh-AY","hook":"CROCHET ends silently in -ET like a French beret — hook a loop and say 'shay'!"},{"w":"ricochet","def":"is the motion of an object after deflecting from another object","ex":"The rubber ball bounced","say":"r-IH-k-uh-sh-ay","hook":"RICOCHET ends in -CHET like a bouncing CATCH — it always comes back"},{"w":"parquet","def":"is a floor composed of strips or blocks of wood forming a pattern","ex":"The ballroom in the historic mansion featured a gleaming parquet floor of alternating oak and cherry wood laid in a herringbone design.","say":"p-ah-r-k-AY","hook":"PARQUET ends in -ET like a French word—it IS French, with a silent T"},{"w":"valet","def":"a manservant who acts as a personal attendant to his employer","ex":"Jeeves was Bertie Wooster's man","say":"va-LAY","hook":"A valet parks your car with élan — the silent T at the end is très French, like ballet."},{"w":"buffet","def":"a piece of furniture that stands at the side of a dining room; has shelves and drawers","ex":"Winds buffeted the tent","say":"BUH-fuht","hook":"A BUFFET has double F but only one T — you stuff yourself with food (FF) but stop at one T."},{"w":"debut","def":"the act of beginning something new","ex":"they looked forward to the debut of their new product line","say":"day-BYOO","hook":"DEBUT is French — say 'day-BYOO' but spell it like the French, with no E at the end!"},{"w":"rendezvous","def":"a meeting planned at a certain time and place","ex":"he was waiting for them at the rendezvous","say":"RAH-ndih-voo","hook":"RENDEZVOUS ends in -vous — you (vous) must show up at the meeting!"},{"w":"corps","def":"an army unit usually consisting of two or more divisions and their support","ex":"The Marine Corps trained intensively for months in the desert, preparing every soldier in the unit to work together as a disciplined team capable of handling the most challenging and dangerous missions.","say":"KAWR","hook":"CORPS is spelled like corpse but you drop the E — the corps is alive, so it keeps its silent P-S but sheds the final E."},{"w":"chassis","def":"alternative names for the body of a human being","ex":"Leonardo studied the human body","say":"CHA-see","hook":"The CHASSIS is the frame—it ends in '-is' like the skeleton it IS beneath the car."},{"w":"faux","def":"not genuine or real; being an imitation of the genuine article","ex":"it isn't fake anything; it's real synthetic fur","say":"FAWKS","hook":"FAUX is French for fake — it looks genuine with four letters but sounds like just one syllable, FOE — faux is itself a little fake!"},{"w":"faux pas","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"debris","def":"is the remains of things broken down or destroyed","ex":"After the storm passed, volunteers spent the morning clearing debris from the streets and helping neighbors repair their fences.","say":"d-uh-b-r-EE","hook":"DEBRIS ends silently in S — the French left the S lying around like scattered rubble you can't hear."},{"w":"silhouette","def":"is a two-dimensional representation of the outline of an object","ex":"As the sun set behind the mountains, the silhouette of the ancient castle appeared dramatically against the glowing orange sky.","say":"s-ih-l-uh-w-EH-t","hook":"silHOUette — the HOUSE makes a silhouette against the sky; remember -ETTE at the end (double T, final E)."},{"w":"esprit","def":"liveliness of mind or spirit","ex":"The drama club's performance was full of esprit, each actor delivering lines with sparkling energy and wit.","say":"eh-SPREE","hook":"ESPRIT is the SPIRIT that leaps out of a lively mind — e-SPRIT."},{"w":"nonchalant","def":"is coolly unconcerned unexcited","ex":"an ability to interest casual students","say":"n-ah-n-sh-uh-l-AH-n-t","hook":"A NON-CHALant person feels NO CHILL — they're too cool to care about anything."},{"w":"coiffure","def":"the arrangement of the hair (especially a woman's hair)","ex":"Before the graduation ceremony, Isabella spent an hour perfecting her coiffure, weaving tiny flowers through her elegantly pinned-up curls.","say":"kwah-FYOOR","hook":"A COIFFURE is when you COIFf your hair into a fancy 'do—double the F, double the flair."}]},{"title":"French Agent Words: -eur / -eur","category":"French Loanword Patterns","difficulty":"medium","concept":"French -eur = one who does (the French masculine agent suffix). These words never use -er — always -eur. And restaurateur never uses -n- before the -eur, despite what many people write.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>ENTREPRENEUR</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ah-n-t-r-uh-p-r-uh-n-UR\n<b>Spell it.</b> E · N · T · R · E · P · R · E · N · E · U · R\n<b>Say it again.</b> ah-n-t-r-uh-p-r-uh-n-UR\n<b>Syllables.</b> e · n · t · r · e · p · r · e · n · e · u · r\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [on=EN] [truh=TRE] [pruh=PRE] [NUR=NEUR]\n<b>Exception.</b> French -eur not -er; no N before -eur (restauranteur = WRONG); three silent e vowels; stress: on-truh-pruh-NUR\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> French entreprendre = to undertake, from entre- = between + prendre =","cards":[{"title":"The -eur Agent","body":"In French, -eur = one who does (masculine form). Chauffeur = one who drives (chauffe = heat — early cars needed coal-heating!). Raconteur = one who tells stories. Connoisseur = one who knows. Saboteur = one who sabotages. Provocateur = one who provokes. Never -er for these words."},{"title":"The Restaurateur Trap","body":"Restaurateur (one who runs a restaurant) comes from restaurer (to restore). There is NO n before the -eur. Restauranteur is wrong — it inserts the n from the word \"restaurant\" which does not belong in the agent form. R-E-S-T-A-U-R-A-T-E-U-R. One of the most common misspellings in educated English."},{"title":"Entrepreneur Breakdown","body":"entre (between/undertake) + prendre (to take) + -eur = one who undertakes between supplier and customer. The word has several low-stress vowels: E-N-T-R-E-P-R-E-N-E-U-R. Spell by syllables: en · tre · pre · neur. Four syllables, twelve letters. No double letters anywhere."},{"title":"Grandeur — the Abstract -eur","body":"Grandeur = greatness, magnificence. Unlike the agent -eur words, grandeur comes from grand (great) + -eur (abstract quality suffix). Pronounced GRAN-jur. Note: -eur in this word = abstract quality, not a person. The same suffix serves two functions in French."},{"title":"More -eur Words","body":"Voyageur (voyager = to travel) = one who voyages/travels. Coiffeur (coiffer = to style hair) = one who styles hair. Masseur = one who gives massages (feminine: masseuse). Amateur (amat- = love) = one who does something for love rather than money — A-M-A-T-E-U-R, not amatuer. The eu comes before the r."}],"words":[{"w":"entrepreneur","def":"is a person who organizes or manages an enterprise","ex":"At just fourteen, the young entrepreneur launched her own custom jewelry business and sold her designs online.","say":"ah-n-t-r-uh-p-r-uh-n-UR","hook":"Remember the unusual 'eur' ending — the French entrepreneur ends like 'connoisseur'"},{"w":"restaurateur","def":"the proprietor of a restaurant","ex":"The celebrated restaurateur opened her fifth dining establishment downtown, promising a menu inspired by her grandmother's recipes.","say":"reh-ster-uh-TUR","hook":"A restauraTEUR has no N — unlike restaurant, the owner drops the N and gains -EUR elegantly."},{"w":"chauffeur","def":"is a person employed to drive an automobile","ex":"The chauffeur held the door open as the ambassador stepped out of the sleek black limousine.","say":"sh-oh-f-UR","hook":"A CHAUFFEUR has a silent H and ends in -EUR — think 'chauf' like 'show' plus fancy French -EUR."},{"w":"raconteur","def":"a person skilled in telling anecdotes","ex":"Uncle Bernard was such a gifted raconteur that his campfire stories kept everyone wide-eyed until midnight.","say":"ra-kah-NTOOR","hook":"A raconTEUR ends like connoissEUR — French -EUR crowns the master storyteller: r-a-c-o-n-t-e-u-r."},{"w":"connoisseur","def":"is a person competent to pass critical judgment","ex":"The art museum hired a connoisseur of Renaissance paintings to authenticate the newly discovered canvas.","say":"k-ah-n-uh-s-UR","hook":"A connoisseur KNOWS their stuff — double n, double s"},{"w":"saboteur","def":"someone who commits sabotage or deliberately causes wrecks","ex":"The saboteur slipped into the factory at midnight and disabled the machinery, halting production for days.","say":"sa-buh-TUR","hook":"A sabotEUR is a European wrecker — the French -EUR ending marks the doer of the deed."},{"w":"voyageur","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"coiffeur","def":"a man hairdresser","ex":"The celebrated Parisian coiffeur trimmed the actress's hair before her appearance on the red carpet.","say":"kwah-FUR","hook":"A COIFFEUR has double 'f' and '-eur' — remember the French agent ending '-eur' like amateur or connoisseur."},{"w":"masseur","def":"a male massager","ex":"The masseur at the spa worked out the knots in my shoulders after the long hike.","say":"ma-SUR","hook":"A massEUR ends in EUR like EURope — the French suffix reveals his continental training."},{"w":"masseuse","def":"a woman who gives massages professionally","ex":"After the marathon, the exhausted runner visited the masseuse, who expertly worked out the painful knots in her legs.","say":"mah-SUHZ","hook":"massEUSE — the EUSE ending marks a French feminine profession"},{"w":"grandeur","def":"the quality of being magnificent or splendid or grand","ex":"Standing at the rim of the Grand Canyon, the students fell silent, overwhelmed by the sheer grandeur of the mile-deep chasm before them.","say":"gra-NDOOR","hook":"Grand + eur = the quality of being grand"},{"w":"provocateur","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"amateur","def":"someone who pursues a study or sport as a pastime","ex":"Although he was just an amateur photographer who had only owned his camera for a year, his stunning nature shots won first place at the regional art competition.","say":"A-muh-tur","hook":"An amateur does it for LOVE — the word ends in -EUR (French for 'one who'), not -URE; think 'amat-EUR' loves it."},{"w":"auteur","def":"a filmmaker who has a personal style and keeps creative control over his or her works","ex":"Fans of the celebrated auteur lined up around the block hoping to catch a glimpse of the director whose unique style they could recognize in any frame.","say":"oh-TUR","hook":"AUTEUR sounds like AUTHOR: the filmmaker is the author of the film"}]},{"title":"Italian Double Consonants: -zz / -cc / -ll / -pp","category":"Italian Loanword Patterns","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Italian loves doubled consonants — they mark a short preceding vowel and are always preserved in English borrowings. Recognizing the double consonant = recognizing the Italian origin.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>MOZZARELLA</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> mah-tsuh-REH-luh\n<b>Spell it.</b> M · O · Z · Z · A · R · E · L · L · A\n<b>Say it again.</b> mah-tsuh-REH-luh\n<b>Syllables.</b> m · o · z · z · a · r · e · l · l · a\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [mot=MOZ] [suh=ZA] [REL=REL] [uh=LA]\n<b>Exception.</b> double-Z from Italian; -ell- before -a; stress on penultimate (second-to-last) syllable: mot-suh-REL-uh\n<b>Origin.</b> English\n<b>Root.</b> Italian mozzare = to cut off, referring to how the cheese is formed","cards":[{"title":"The Double Consonant Rule","body":"Italian uses doubled consonants to signal a short vowel before them — and English keeps these doublings intact. Mozzarella = M-O-Z-Z-A-R-E-L-L-A (double-z AND double-l). Intermezzo = I-N-T-E-R-M-E-Z-Z-O (double-z). Palazzo (palace) = P-A-L-A-Z-Z-O (double-z)."},{"title":"-zz Words","body":"Mozzarella, intermezzo, palazzo, pizzicato (pizzicare = pinch), piazza (a square), paparazzi (paparazzo = a buzzing insect = a freelance photographer), mezzo (half). These zz words are among Italian's most recognizable exports to English."},{"title":"-cc Words","body":"Cappuccino = C-A-P-P-U-C-C-I-N-O (double-p AND double-c). Broccoli = B-R-O-C-C-O-L-I (double-c). Bocce (lawn bowling) = B-O-C-C-E. Staccato (staccare = detach) = S-T-A-C-C-A-T-O (double-c). A cappella (a cappella = in the chapel style) = unaccompanied singing."},{"title":"-ll/-pp Words","body":"Ballerina = B-A-L-L-E-R-I-N-A (double-l). Mozzarella has double-l too. Cappuccino has double-p. Soprano (NOT doubled — from sopra = above). Tempo (NOT doubled). The doubling signals a short stressed vowel — not all Italian words double."},{"title":"Paparazzi — One Word, Two Doublings","body":"Paparazzi = P-A-P-A-R-A-Z-Z-I (double-z). The singular is paparazzo (P-A-P-A-R-A-Z-Z-O). This is a plural form in Italian — like alumni in Latin. Using \"paparazzi\" as a singular is technically wrong, though common in English. Bees may ask for the singular!"}],"words":[{"w":"mozzarella","def":"is a mild white semi-soft Italian cheese","ex":"She stretched the warm mozzarella over the pizza dough before sliding it into the stone oven.","say":"mah-tsuh-REH-luh","hook":"MOZZARELLAhas a DOUBLE Z like pizza has double cheese — mozZZarella!"},{"w":"intermezzo","def":"is a short musical entertainment between the acts of a drama or opera","ex":"The audience murmured appreciatively as the orchestra performed a gentle intermezzo while the stagehands changed the scenery.","say":"in-tur-MET-soh","hook":"interMEZZO is played in the MIDDLE — MEZZanine, MEZZo — double Z like the buzz of an intermission."},{"w":"palazzo","def":"A large, impressive Italian palace or mansion, especially one from the Renaissance period; also refers to wide-legged trousers resembling the flowing lines of such architecture.","ex":"The class visited a 15th-century palazzo in Florence whose marble corridors were lined with priceless Renaissance paintings.","say":"puh-LAH-zoh","hook":"PALAZZO — a PALACE with a fancy Italian -zzo ending."},{"w":"pizzicato","def":"a note or passage that is played pizzicato","ex":"The violinists switched to pizzicato, plucking their strings to create a light, bouncy effect.","say":"pit-sih-KAH-toh","hook":"PIZZIcato has two Z's — pluck the strings TWICE, just like the double Z."},{"w":"piazza","def":"a public square with room for pedestrians","ex":"they met at Elm Plaza","say":"pee-A-zuh","hook":"Two z's keep the PIZZA of open Italian squares buzzing with life."},{"w":"paparazzi","def":"a freelance photographer who pursues celebrities trying to take candid photographs of them to sell to newspapers or magazines","ex":"A swarm of paparazzi crowded outside the theater, cameras flashing as the movie star stepped out.","say":"pah-pah-RAW-zee","hook":"PAPARAZZI has a double Z — like two camera shutters clicking at once to catch celebrities."},{"w":"cappuccino","def":"equal parts of espresso and hot milk topped with cinnamon and nutmeg and usually whipped cream","ex":"She wrapped her hands around the warm mug and savored every sip of her morning cappuccino before heading to school.","say":"ka-poo-CHEE-noh","hook":"cappUCCIno—double P, double C, like the two circular cups of espresso and milk a barista pours."},{"w":"broccoli","def":"plant with dense clusters of tight green flower buds","ex":"The chef steamed fresh broccoli and tossed it with garlic butter to make a simple but delicious side dish.","say":"BRAH-kuh-lee","hook":"BROCCOLI has two C's like two little green CROWNS clustered together."},{"w":"staccato","def":"(music) marked by or composed of disconnected parts or sounds; cut short crisply","ex":"The young pianist's fingers danced across the keys in a rapid staccato style, producing short, crisp, detached notes that filled the concert hall with an exciting, percussive energy.","say":"stuh-KAH-toh","hook":"Staccato has double-c like two short detached notes — stac-CA-to, crisp and clipped."},{"w":"ballerina","def":"a female ballet dancer","ex":"The young ballerina practiced her pirouettes every day until she could spin without wobbling even once.","say":"ba-ler-EE-nuh","hook":"A ballERINA has double L then -erina: think 'a ball-ER I kNow As' a dancer."},{"w":"mezzo","def":"a soprano with a voice between soprano and contralto","ex":"The mezzo captivated the audience with her rich, warm voice that filled every corner of the concert hall.","say":"MEH-zoh","hook":"MEZZO has a double Z — her voice is right in the middle, strong as two Z's."},{"w":"bocce","def":"Italian bowling played on a long narrow dirt court","ex":"Every Sunday afternoon, the neighbors gathered in the backyard to play a lively game of bocce.","say":"BOH-chee","hook":"BOCCE ends in -CE like 'ace' — roll the ball like an ace in this Italian game."},{"w":"capuccino","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"prosciutto","def":"Italian salt-cured ham usually sliced paper thin","ex":"The chef draped thin slices of prosciutto over the ripe melon for a classic Italian appetizer.","say":"pruh-SHOO-toh","hook":"Say it like 'pruh-SHOO-toh' — this Italian ham makes you shout SHOO as you chase people away from your plate; spell the silent C: proSCIutto."},{"w":"bruschetta","def":"toasted bread rubbed with garlic and topped with olive oil, tomatoes, and herbs","ex":"At the Italian restaurant, we started with crispy bruschetta topped with fresh tomatoes and basil.","say":"broo-SKEH-tah","hook":"BRUSCHETTA has no SH — it's broo-SKET-ta; the SC makes a K sound, like a knife scraping toast."},{"w":"risotto","def":"rice cooked with broth and sprinkled with grated cheese","ex":"The chef stirred the creamy mushroom risotto slowly for twenty minutes until every grain of rice was perfectly tender.","say":"ree-SAW-toh","hook":"RISOTTO has a double T — Two stirs to cook the rice just right."}]},{"title":"Italian Music & Art Vocabulary","category":"Italian Loanword Patterns","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Italian is the language of classical music. Every dynamic marking, tempo marking, and musical technique has an Italian name. Spelling bees love these words for their unusual consonant patterns.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>SFORZANDO</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> sfort-SAHN-doh\n<b>Spell it.</b> S · F · O · R · Z · A · N · D · O\n<b>Say it again.</b> sfort-SAHN-doh\n<b>Syllables.</b> sfor · zan · do\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [sfor=SFOR] [TSAN=ZAN] [doh=DO]\n<b>Exception.</b> sf- cluster (unusual in English); -z- = /ts/ sound in Italian; no double letters; stress: sfor-TSAN-doh\n<b>Origin.</b> Italian\n<b>Root.</b> Italian sforzare = to force, from Latin ex- + fortis = strong","cards":[{"title":"Volume Dynamics — Softest to Loudest","body":"Pianissimo (pp) → piano (p, soft) → mezzo-piano (mp) → mezzo-forte (mf) → forte (f, loud) → fortissimo (ff). Piano = soft (NOT the instrument in this context!); forte = loud/strong; mezzo = half. Sforzando = suddenly very loud. Crescendo = gradually getting louder."},{"title":"Tempo Markings — Slowest to Fastest","body":"Grave (very slow, solemn) → largo (broad, slow) → adagio (slowly) → andante (walking pace) → moderato (moderate) → allegretto (fairly quick) → allegro (fast) → vivace (lively) → presto (very fast) → prestissimo (as fast as possible)."},{"title":"Technique Words","body":"Staccato (staccare = detach) = short, clipped notes. Legato (legare = tie/bind) = smoothly connected notes. Pizzicato (pizzicare = pinch) = plucking strings. Tremolo (tremare = tremble) = rapid repetition. Vibrato (vibrare = vibrate) = slight pitch variation. All end in -o (Italian masculine endings)."},{"title":"The -issimo Superlative","body":"Italian -issimo = most/very: pianissimo (very soft), fortissimo (very loud), prestissimo (very fast), bellissimo (very beautiful). This is a living Italian superlative still fully functional in music vocabulary. Note the double-s: P-I-A-N-I-S-S-I-M-O."},{"title":"Art Terms","body":"Chiaroscuro (chiaro = clear + oscuro = dark) = use of light and shadow in painting. Sfumato (sfumare = to evaporate) = Leonardo's technique of blurred outlines. Fresco (fresco = fresh) = painting on wet plaster. Impasto (impastare = to knead) = thick paint texture. Trompe-l'oeil (French! = trick the eye) = hyper-realistic painting."}],"words":[{"w":"sforzando","def":"an accented chord","ex":"The pianist struck a sforzando on the final beat that made the audience jump in their seats.","say":"sfort-SAHN-doh","hook":"SFORZANDO: FORCE it—sforZANDO contains FORCE, which means play it HARD"},{"w":"pianissimo","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"fortissimo","def":"(music) very loud","ex":"The orchestra reached the fortissimo climax of the symphony, and the thunderous sound filled every corner of the concert hall.","say":"for-TIS-ih-moh","hook":"FORTissimo — FORT-like STRENGTH of sound, double the 's' like double the volume"},{"w":"allegretto","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"vivace","def":"(of tempo) very fast and lively","ex":"play this section vivace!","say":"vih-VAH-chay","hook":"Vivace ends in 'ace' — play it fast and lively to ace your performance!"},{"w":"prestissimo","def":"(of tempo) as fast as possible","ex":"this passage should be played prestissimo","say":"preh-STIS-see-moh","hook":"PRESTO (fast) + ISSIMO (most) = PRESTISSIMO — the most-est presto you can possibly play."},{"w":"staccato","def":"(music) marked by or composed of disconnected parts or sounds; cut short crisply","ex":"The young pianist's fingers danced across the keys in a rapid staccato style, producing short, crisp, detached notes that filled the concert hall with an exciting, percussive energy.","say":"stuh-KAH-toh","hook":"Staccato has double-c like two short detached notes — stac-CA-to, crisp and clipped."},{"w":"legato","def":"(music) without breaks between notes; smooth and connected","ex":"The cellist played the slow movement legato, drawing her bow smoothly across the strings so that each note flowed seamlessly into the next without the slightest interruption or gap.","say":"luh-GAH-toh","hook":"LEGATO means notes bound together smoothly — one G ties them gently, not two: l-e-G-a-t-o."},{"w":"pizzicato","def":"a note or passage that is played pizzicato","ex":"The violinists switched to pizzicato, plucking their strings to create a light, bouncy effect.","say":"pit-sih-KAH-toh","hook":"PIZZIcato has two Z's — pluck the strings TWICE, just like the double Z."},{"w":"tremolo","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"vibrato","def":"(music) a pulsating effect in an instrumental or vocal tone produced by slight and rapid variations in pitch","ex":"The cellist added a rich vibrato to the long notes, making the melody sound warm and deeply emotional.","say":"vee-BRAH-toh","hook":"VIBRATO ends in -ATO like a musical tomato—Italian music makes your voice shake and shimmer."},{"w":"adagio","def":"(music) a composition played in adagio tempo (slowly and gracefully)","ex":"they played the adagio too quickly","say":"uh-DAH-zhee-oh","hook":"Play it SLOWLY and at EASE — adagio has one G, as leisurely as the tempo itself."},{"w":"moderato","def":"(of tempo) moderate","ex":"The conductor instructed the orchestra to play the second movement moderato, keeping a steady and relaxed pace.","say":"mod-er-AH-toh","hook":"MODERATO is an Italian musical tempo—like a moderate TOMATO-red pace."},{"w":"intermezzo","def":"is a short musical entertainment between the acts of a drama or opera","ex":"The audience murmured appreciatively as the orchestra performed a gentle intermezzo while the stagehands changed the scenery.","say":"in-tur-MET-soh","hook":"interMEZZO is played in the MIDDLE — MEZZanine, MEZZo — double Z like the buzz of an intermission."},{"w":"crescendo","def":"(music) a gradual increase in loudness","ex":"The music crescendoes here","say":"krih-SHEH-ndoh","hook":"A cresCENDO builds to CENTER stage — find the SCENE growing louder inside it."},{"w":"diminuendo","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"chiaroscuro","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"sfumato","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"fresco","def":"a mural done with watercolors on wet plaster","ex":"The art class studied the famous fresco painted on the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel by Michelangelo.","say":"FREH-skoh","hook":"FRESCO is painted FRESH on wet plaster — FRES-CO starts with FRES like fresh."}]},{"title":"graph / gram (write / record)","category":"Greek Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Greek graphein = to write. One root unlocks three suffix families: -graph (the instrument/method), -gram (the written thing), and -graphy (the art or study of writing something).","method":"<div class='trick'><b>CHOREOGRAPHY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> kaw-ree-AH-gruh-fee\n<b>Spell it.</b> C · H · O · R · E · O · G · R · A · P · H · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> kaw-ree-AH-gruh-fee\n<b>Syllables.</b> kao · riy · aa · grah · fiy\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [kor=CHO] [ee=RE] [OG=OG] [ruh=RA] [fee=PHY]\n<b>Exception.</b> -ph- = /f/ (Greek!); -y = /ee/ at end; -chore- from choreia = dance; 5 syllables: kor-ee-OG-ruh-fee\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> Greek choros = dance + graphein = to write","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Greek graphein = to write. When you see -graph or -gram, ask: what is being written or recorded? Telegraph = write from far. Monograph = written about one thing. Autograph = written by oneself. One root family, unlimited words."},{"title":"-graph = The Instrument/Method","body":"Seismograph = records earthquakes. Cardiograph = records heart. Photograph = photo (light) + graph = written by light. Lithograph = lithos (stone) = printed from stone. Stenograph = stenos (narrow) = narrow fast writing."},{"title":"-gram = The Thing Written","body":"Telegram = the distant message. Anagram = ana (again) = letters rearranged. Epigram = epi (upon) = a witty inscription. Monogram = mono (one) = initials written. Cryptogram = crypto (hidden) = a coded message."},{"title":"-graphy = The Art/Study","body":"Calligraphy = kalli (beautiful) = beautiful writing. Choreography = choreia (dance) = the art of composing dances. Topography = topos (place) = describing physical features. Stenography = shorthand writing."},{"title":"-grapher = The Person","body":"Stenographer = shorthand typist. Choreographer = designs dances. Photographer = takes photographs. Biographer = writes a life story. Lexicographer = writes dictionaries (a word that describes itself!). The -er agent suffix pairs with the Greek -graph- root."}],"words":[{"w":"seismograph","def":"a measuring instrument for detecting and measuring the intensity and direction and duration of movements of the ground (as an earthquake)","ex":"Scientists studied the seismograph readings to determine the earthquake's magnitude and origin.","say":"SYZ-muh-graf","hook":"A seismoGRAPH GRAPHS the ground's shaking — remember 'graph' means to write or draw."},{"w":"cardiograph","def":"medical instrument that records electric currents associated with contractions of the heart","ex":"The technician attached electrodes to the patient's chest before turning on the cardiograph.","say":"KAR-dee-oh-graf","hook":"CARDIO (heart) + GRAPH (write/record) = the machine that writes the heart's story."},{"w":"lithograph","def":"a print produced by lithography","ex":"The museum displayed an original lithograph by the famous artist, showing incredible detail despite being over a century old.","say":"LIH-thuh-graf","hook":"A lithograph is writing on stone — 'litho' (stone) + 'graph' (write), like ancient graffiti on rock."},{"w":"stenograph","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"anagram","def":"a word or phrase spelled by rearranging the letters of another word or phrase","ex":"The puzzle book challenged readers to find that \"listen\" is a perfect anagram of the word \"silent.\"","say":"A-nuh-gram","hook":"An ANAGRAM writes (GRAM) letters AGAIN (ANA) in a new order — only ONE 'n'!"},{"w":"epigram","def":"a witty saying","ex":"The teacher had written an Oscar Wilde epigram on the board: 'I can resist everything except temptation,' which made the whole class laugh.","say":"EH-puh-gram","hook":"An EPIgram is a short bit of writing — like a telegram for the mind"},{"w":"monogram","def":"a graphic symbol consisting of 2 or more letters combined (usually your initials); printed on stationery or embroidered on clothing","ex":"The bride's initials were sewn as a golden monogram on each of the linen napkins.","say":"MAH-nuh-gram","hook":"A MONOgram is ONE set of letters — one GRAM of alphabet ink on your shirt."},{"w":"cryptogram","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"calligraphy","def":"beautiful handwriting","ex":"She spent the summer learning calligraphy so she could address all the graduation party envelopes by hand.","say":"kuh-LIH-gruh-fee","hook":"CALLIgraphy: CALLI sounds like 'calling' beauty onto the page — double L for double beauty."},{"w":"choreography","def":"a show involving artistic dancing","ex":"The choreography for the school musical was so impressive that the audience leapt to their feet in applause.","say":"kaw-ree-AH-gruh-fee","hook":"CHOREOGRAPHY = choreo + GRAPHY — like photography, it's always spelled with PH."},{"w":"topography","def":"the configuration of a surface and the relations among its man-made and natural features","ex":"The hikers studied the topography of the mountain range before choosing the safest trail.","say":"tuh-PAH-gruh-fee","hook":"TOP-O-GRAPHY: describe (GRAPH) a place (TOPO) from the TOP down."},{"w":"stenographer","def":"someone skilled in the transcription of speech (especially dictation)","ex":"The court stenographer's fingers flew across the keys, capturing every word of the dramatic trial testimony.","say":"steh-NUH-gruh-fer","hook":"A STENOGRAPHER uses a STENO pad to GRAPH (write) speech."},{"w":"choreographer","def":"someone who creates new dances","ex":"The brilliant choreographer designed a routine that perfectly matched the music's shifting tempo, leaving the audience breathless.","say":"kaw-ree-AH-gruh-fer","hook":"A choreographer WRITES (graphs) the CHORUS of dance moves"},{"w":"lexicographer","def":"a compiler or writer of a dictionary; a student of the lexical component of language","ex":"The dedicated lexicographer spent forty years tracking the origins and changing meanings of everyday English words.","say":"leh-ksih-KAH-gruh-fer","hook":"LEXicoGRAPHer: Someone who GRAPHs (writes) all the LEXico (words) — a dictionary WRITER: L-E-X-I-C-O-G-R-A-P-H-E-R."},{"w":"telegraph","def":"apparatus used to communicate at a distance over a wire (usually in Morse code)","ex":"The telegraph revolutionized long-distance communication in the nineteenth century, allowing news to travel in minutes rather than days.","say":"TEH-luh-graf","hook":"A TELEGRAPH GRAPHS writing from FAR away — ends in -GRAPH like photograph and autograph!"},{"w":"monograph","def":"a detailed and documented treatise on a particular subject","ex":"The scientist spent three years writing a monograph on the behavior of deep-sea bioluminescent creatures.","say":"MAH-nuh-graf","hook":"A MONOgraph is ONE topic written up thoroughly — one GRAPH of knowledge."},{"w":"autobiography","def":"a biography of yourself","ex":"Maya Angelou's autobiography describes her childhood in the American South with vivid and moving detail.","say":"aw-tuh-beye-AH-gruh-fee","hook":"AUTO + BIO + GRAPHY: a self (auto) life (bio) writing (graphy) — PH makes the F sound, not plain F."}]},{"title":"phon / phone (sound / voice)","category":"Greek Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Greek phonē = sound, voice. The ph spelling is an absolute Greek signal — never f in learned sound words. This root appears in music, linguistics, and technology.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>CACOPHONY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> k-a-k-AH-f-uh-n-ee\n<b>Spell it.</b> C · A · C · O · P · H · O · N · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> k-a-k-AH-f-uh-n-ee\n<b>Syllables.</b> c · a · c · o · p · h · o · n · y\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [kuh=CA] [KOF=COPH] [uh=O] [nee=NY]\n<b>Exception.</b> -ph- = /f/ not /p/ (Greek signal!); -cac- from kakos = bad; -y = /ee/; stress: kuh-KOF-uh-nee\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> Greek kakos = bad + phone = sound/voice","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Greek phonē = sound, voice. The ph = /f/ spelling is the Greek identity card. Never write f for sound words that come from Greek. Phonics = the study of sound-letter relationships. Phonetics = science of speech sounds. Phoneme = the smallest unit of sound."},{"title":"Good vs Bad Sound","body":"Greek eu = good; kako = bad. Euphony = pleasant harmonious sound. Cacophony = harsh, unpleasant noise. Symphony = syn (together) + phony = sounds in harmony. Polyphony = poly (many) = many simultaneous voices. Homophone = homo (same) = same sound, different spelling."},{"title":"Sound Instruments","body":"Microphone = mikros (small) + phone = makes small voices big. Saxophone = invented by Adolphe Sax + phone = his instrument's sound. Megaphone = megas (large) = makes voice large. Xylophone = xylo (wood) + phone = wooden sound. All these instruments work with sound — all spell the sound with ph."},{"title":"Language of Sound","body":"Phonics = sound-letter study. Phonetics = speech sound science. Homophone = same sound. Dysphonia (dys- = bad + phonia) = difficulty with voice production. Aphasia (a- = without + phasis = speech) = loss of ability to speak or understand language."},{"title":"Musical ph Words","body":"Philharmonic = phil (love) + harmonikos = loving harmony. The ph in the phil- component is also a Greek spelling signal. Saxophone keeps phone despite being named after a person. The Greek root outlasts any individual's name in English spelling."}],"words":[{"w":"cacophony","def":"is a harsh discordance of sound","ex":"The construction site next to the library created such a cacophony that students could barely concentrate on their reading.","say":"k-a-k-AH-f-uh-n-ee","hook":"CACO-PHONY: bad (caco) PHONE (phon) call — all noise and no sense, spelled with phony at the end."},{"w":"euphony","def":"any agreeable (pleasing and harmonious) sounds","ex":"he fell asleep to the music of the wind chimes","say":"YOO-fuh-nee","hook":"Euphony = EU + PHONY — but unlike a phony friend, euphony is genuinely pleasant to the ear!"},{"w":"symphony","def":"a long and complex sonata for symphony orchestra","ex":"we heard the Vienna symphony","say":"SIH-mfuh-nee","hook":"A symPHONy is sounds (PHON) together — not symphAny, the O holds the note!"},{"w":"polyphony","def":"music arranged in parts for several voices or instruments","ex":"The cathedral filled with rich polyphony as four separate vocal parts wove together in perfect harmony.","say":"puh-LIH-fuh-nee","hook":"POLYphony = POLY voices; remember the 'y' ending like harmony and symphony, its musical cousins."},{"w":"microphone","def":"device for converting sound waves into electrical energy","ex":"The nervous singer tapped the microphone to check if the audience could hear her.","say":"MEYE-kruh-fohn","hook":"A MICROPHONE amplifies small PHONE (sound)—micro+phone, just like telephone and saxophone."},{"w":"saxophone","def":"a single-reed woodwind with a conical bore","ex":"The jazz musician played a mellow saxophone solo that filled the entire club with warm, golden sound.","say":"SA-ksuh-fohn","hook":"SAX-O-PHONE: the Sax makes a PHONE call — no 'a' in the middle, just an o."},{"w":"megaphone","def":"a cone-shaped acoustic device held to the mouth to intensify and direct the human voice","ex":"The coach grabbed a megaphone to shout instructions to his players on the far end of the field.","say":"MEH-guh-fohn","hook":"A MEGAPHONE makes your PHONE (voice) MEGA loud — 'phone' always ends in P-H-O-N-E, never 'fone.'"},{"w":"xylophone","def":"a percussion instrument with wooden bars tuned to produce a chromatic scale and with resonators; played with small mallets","ex":"The kindergartner proudly played a simple tune on the colorful xylophone during the school recital.","say":"ZEYE-luh-fohn","hook":"A XYLOPHONE makes PHONe sounds from XYLO (wooden) bars — always start with X, not Z!"},{"w":"phonics","def":"teaching reading by training beginners to associate letters with their sound values","ex":"By using phonics in first grade, the students quickly learned to decode new words by sounding them out letter by letter.","say":"FAH-nihks","hook":"PHONICS is about PHONE-sounds — PHONe starts with the same sound-root."},{"w":"phonetics","def":"the branch of acoustics concerned with speech processes including its production and perception and acoustic analysis","ex":"Studying phonetics helped the language student understand exactly how to position her tongue and lips to produce new sounds.","say":"fuh-NEH-tihks","hook":"PHONETICS studies speech sounds — PHONETIC+S: add S for the whole science of sounds."},{"w":"homophone","def":"two words are homophones if they are pronounced the same way but differ in meaning or spelling or both (e.g. bare and bear)","ex":"The words 'knight' and 'night' are homophones because they sound identical but are spelled differently.","say":"HOH-moh-fohn","hook":"A homoPHONE sounds the same (PHONE = sound) — 'knight' and 'night' ring identically in your ear even though spelled differently."},{"w":"phoneme","def":"(linguistics) one of a small set of speech sounds that are distinguished by the speakers of a particular language","ex":"Changing a single phoneme can completely alter the meaning of a word, as when 'bat' becomes 'bad.'","say":"FOH-neem","hook":"A PHONEME is the smallest sound unit — PHON+EME: think of it as an EXTREME tiny sound."},{"w":"philharmonic","def":"a large orchestra; can perform symphonies","ex":"The seventh-grade music class attended a concert performed by the city's philharmonic and were stunned by the power of one hundred instruments playing together.","say":"fih-lhah-RMAH-nihk","hook":"PHILharmonic: a PHIL-anthropist LOVES people; philharmonic LOVES harmony"},{"w":"dysphonia","def":"speech disorder attributable to a disorder of phonation","ex":"The singer's dysphonia left her unable to perform for months as she rested her strained vocal cords.","say":"dis-FOH-nee-uh","hook":"DYSphonia means your PHONE (voice) has a DYSfunctional signal — speech is broken."},{"w":"aphasia","def":"inability to use or understand language (spoken or written) because of a brain lesion","ex":"After suffering a stroke, the journalist developed aphasia and had to relearn how to speak and read.","say":"uh-FAY-zhuh","hook":"A-PHASIA = A person who can't PHASE out words properly"}]},{"title":"path / pathy (suffering / feeling / disease)","category":"Greek Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Greek pathos = feeling, suffering. In medicine it means disease; in literature and rhetoric it means emotion. Two meanings, one root — context tells you which applies.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>ANTIPATHY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> a-NTIH-puh-thee\n<b>Spell it.</b> A · N · T · I · P · A · T · H · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> a-NTIH-puh-thee\n<b>Syllables.</b> ae · ntih · pah · thiy\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [an=AN] [TIP=TI] [uh=PA] [thee=THY]\n<b>Exception.</b> -th- = /th/ from Greek theta; -y at end = /ee/; -pathy not -pathee; stress: an-TIP-uh-thee\n<b>Origin.</b> Greek\n<b>Root.</b> Greek 'antipatheia' = opposite feeling, from 'anti-' = against + 'path","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Pathos = feeling, suffering. Sympathy = sym (with) = feeling with someone. Empathy = em (in) = feeling as if inside someone's experience. Antipathy = anti (against) = feeling against = deep dislike. Apathy = a- (without) = feeling nothing at all."},{"title":"The pathos Scale","body":"Apathy (no feeling) → sympathy (feeling alongside) → empathy (feeling as if it's yours). These three form a scale of emotional connection. In a bee: apathy = A-P-A-T-H-Y; sympathy = S-Y-M-P-A-T-H-Y; empathy = E-M-P-A-T-H-Y. Same ending, different prefix each time."},{"title":"Medical -pathy Words","body":"Neuropathy = neuro + pathy = nerve disease. Osteopathy = bone/tissue manipulation treatment. Psychopathy = psycho + pathy = mental disorder. Homeopathy = homeo (same) + pathy = treating with similar substances. Cardiopathy = heart disease. The root tells you what disease; -pathy tells you it IS a disease."},{"title":"Pathology Branch","body":"Pathology = path + logy = the study of disease. Pathogen = path + gen = a disease-causing organism. Pathological = relating to disease; also means compulsive (a pathological liar). Pathologist = a doctor who analyzes disease causes. The pathos root shifts from emotion to diagnosis in medical contexts."},{"title":"Pathos in Rhetoric","body":"Pathos = the quality in a work that evokes pity or sadness — one of Aristotle's three rhetorical appeals (alongside logos = reason and ethos = character). Bathos = an abrupt drop from the elevated to the trivial — the anti-pathos. Both Greek words, both kept their Greek spelling in English."}],"words":[{"w":"sympathy","def":"an inclination to support or be loyal to or to agree with an opinion","ex":"When Jordan broke her leg before the championship, her teammates sent a card full of sympathy and encouragement.","say":"SIH-mpuh-thee","hook":"SYMPATHY: feel the SAME (sym) PATHos—you walk the same feeling path"},{"w":"empathy","def":"understanding and entering into another's feelings","ex":"Her empathy for the injured stray cat led her to spend hours nursing it back to health.","say":"EH-mpuh-thee","hook":"EMPATHY: Enter My Pal's Agony To Help You — no extra 'h' after 'em'."},{"w":"antipathy","def":"a feeling of intense dislike","ex":"The two rival teams developed a deep antipathy toward each other after years of intense competition.","say":"a-NTIH-puh-thee","hook":"ANTI-PATHy — you are on the ANTI PATH to liking someone"},{"w":"apathy","def":"an absence of emotion or enthusiasm","ex":"The coach worried that the team's apathy after three straight losses would make it impossible to prepare them for the championship game.","say":"A-puh-thee","hook":"A-PATH-Y: apathy is being on a path with no destination — no feeling, no direction, just 'a' + 'path' + 'y'."},{"w":"neuropathy","def":"any pathology of the peripheral nerves","ex":"The diabetic patient developed neuropathy in her feet, causing a constant tingling and numbness.","say":"NUU-roh-pa-thee","hook":"NEUROPATHy: the nerve's PATH leads to suffering — feel the PATHos of damaged nerves."},{"w":"osteopathy","def":"therapy based on the assumption that restoring health is best accomplished by manipulating the skeleton and muscles","ex":"She visited an osteopathy clinic where the doctor used gentle manipulation to relieve her back pain.","say":"os-tee-OP-uh-thee","hook":"OSTEO-PATHY: 'osteo' (bone) + pathy (treatment/suffering) — treating the body through BONE and structure."},{"w":"psychopathy","def":"any disease of the mind; the psychological state of someone who has emotional or behavioral problems serious enough to require psychiatric intervention","ex":"Researchers studying psychopathy have found that certain brain differences may explain why some individuals feel no guilt or compassion.","say":"seye-KAH-puh-thee","hook":"PSYCHOpaTHY — the mind's disease ends in -PATHY, like empathy but darker."},{"w":"homeopathy","def":"a method of treating disease with small amounts of remedies that, in large amounts in healthy people, produce symptoms similar to those being treated","ex":"Some people turn to homeopathy as an alternative treatment, believing that highly diluted natural substances can trigger the body's healing response.","say":"hoh-mee-oh-PA-thee","hook":"HOMEOPATHY: treat disease with a SIMILAR remedy — spot the E-O in the middle."},{"w":"cardiopathy","def":"a disease of the heart","ex":"The cardiologist explained that the elderly man's cardiopathy had weakened his heart muscle over many years of high blood pressure.","say":"kar-dee-OP-uh-thee","hook":"CARDIO (heart) + PATHY (disease) = heart disease."},{"w":"pathology","def":"the branch of medical science that studies the causes and nature and effects of diseases","ex":"The forensic pathology report revealed that the ancient mummy had suffered from a bone disease.","say":"puh-THAH-luh-jee","hook":"PATHology is the LOGY (study) of the PATH disease takes — one G, not two."},{"w":"pathogen","def":"any disease-producing agent (especially a virus or bacterium or other microorganism)","ex":"Scientists worked around the clock to identify the pathogen responsible for the mysterious outbreak.","say":"PA-thuh-juhn","hook":"A PATHogen GENErates disease — remember PATH + O + GEN like a disease-generating gene."},{"w":"pathological","def":"of or relating to the practice of pathology","ex":"pathological laboratory","say":"pa-thuh-LAH-jih-kuhl","hook":"A PATHOLOGICAl liar follows a sick path — end with ‑ICAL not ‑ICLE."},{"w":"telepathy","def":"is communication between minds","ex":"The twins seemed to communicate by telepathy, finishing each other's sentences without hesitation.","say":"t-uh-l-EH-p-uh-th-ee","hook":"TELEPATHY: feelings travel a long TELE-PATH-Y — the PATH is right there in the middle of the word!"},{"w":"sociopathy","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"bathos","def":"triteness or triviality of style","ex":"The heroic poem collapsed into bathos when the knight's climactic battle cry was interrupted by a sneeze.","say":"BAY-thohs","hook":"BATHOS: the writing takes a bath and comes out flat and trivial"},{"w":"pathos","def":"a quality that arouses emotions (especially pity or sorrow)","ex":"the film captured all the pathos of their situation","say":"PAY-thahs","hook":"PATHOS stirs PATH of emotion in your heart — PATH + OS: P-A-T-H-O-S."}]},{"title":"chron (time)","category":"Greek Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Greek khronos = time. All chron- words relate to time. The ch = /k/ sound is a Greek signal. The god Kronos (Time) gave his name to this root — and to the planet Saturn in Roman mythology.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>ANACHRONISM</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> uh-NA-kruh-nih-zuhm\n<b>Spell it.</b> A · N · A · C · H · R · O · N · I · S · M\n<b>Say it again.</b> uh-NA-kruh-nih-zuhm\n<b>Syllables.</b> ah · nae · krah · nih · zah · m\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [uh=A] [NAK=NACH] [ruh=RO] [niz=NIS] [um=M]\n<b>Exception.</b> -ch- = /k/ in Greek words (signal!); -ism not -izm; stress: uh-NAK-ruh-niz-um\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Greek ana = against + chronos = time","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Greek Khronos = time (and the god of time). Chron- always appears with the ch = /k/ Greek spelling. Chronological = in time order. Anachronism = ana (against) + chron = something out of its proper time (a smartphone in a medieval movie). Synchronize = syn (together) + chron = make happen at the same time."},{"title":"Time Order Words","body":"Chronological = arranged by time. Diachronic (dia = through) = studied across time (how language changes). Synchronic (syn = together) = studied at one moment in time. Isochronal (iso = equal) = happening at equal time intervals. Greek prefixes combine with chron- to create precise temporal vocabulary."},{"title":"Measuring Time","body":"Chronometer = chron + meter = instrument that measures time precisely. Used by sailors for navigation — required the most accurate timekeeping available. Chronograph = chron + graph = records/writes time (a stopwatch-type instrument). Chronoscope = chron + scope = looks at and measures time."},{"title":"Time Stories","body":"Chronicle = a time-ordered record of events. Chronic = chron + -ic = lasting over a long time (chronic illness = ongoing). Anachronistic = out of its proper time period. Synchronicity = meaningful coincidence of events happening at the same time (Carl Jung's concept). The root remains stable in all compounds."},{"title":"The ch=/k/ Greek Signal in chron","body":"In Greek-origin words, ch = /k/: choreography, chemistry, chronology, chaos, character, choir, chorus. This is one of the most reliable Greek spelling signals. Hearing /k/ in a learned word = look for ch, not k or c, as the spelling."}],"words":[{"w":"anachronism","def":"something located at a time when it could not have existed or occurred","ex":"The knight carrying a smartphone in the historical film was an obvious anachronism that made viewers laugh.","say":"uh-NA-kruh-nih-zuhm","hook":"An ANACHRONISM fights against (ANA) CHRONOS (time) — keep 'chron' for time and end it with '-ism', not '-izm'."},{"w":"synchronize","def":"make synchronous and adjust in time or manner","ex":"Let's synchronize our efforts","say":"SIH-ngkruh-neyez","hook":"SYNCHRONize your watches — the CHRON inside reminds you of CHRONology, so don't drop the H."},{"w":"chronometer","def":"an accurate clock (especially used in navigation)","ex":"The ship's navigator relied on the chronometer to calculate their exact position in the middle of the Pacific Ocean.","say":"kruh-NOM-ih-ter","hook":"CHRONO (time) + METER (measure) = time measurer."},{"w":"chronograph","def":"an accurate timer for recording time","ex":"The Olympic coach used a chronograph to record each swimmer's exact finishing time down to the hundredth of a second.","say":"KROH-noh-graf","hook":"A chronograph GRAPHS time — CHRONOgraph writes (graphs) time for you."},{"w":"chronicle","def":"a record or narrative description of past events","ex":"The elderly historian decided to write a detailed chronicle of the town's founding, recording every important event from the first settlers' arrival to the present day.","say":"KRAH-nih-kuhl","hook":"A CHRONICLE tracks time in little bites — 'chron' for time, '-icle' like a tiny article."},{"w":"chronic","def":"being long-lasting and recurrent or characterized by long suffering","ex":"After years of playing competitive soccer without proper rest, the athlete developed chronic knee pain that forced her to visit a physical therapist every week just to stay comfortable enough to practice.","say":"KRAH-nihk","hook":"CHRONIC pain lasts through time — 'chron' = time, just like in chronology."},{"w":"diachronic","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"isochronal","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"chronological","def":"relating to or arranged according to temporal order","ex":"The teacher asked the class to arrange the historical events in chronological order, starting with the earliest date and working forward through the decades to the present day.","say":"krah-nuh-LAH-jih-kuhl","hook":"CHRONOLOGICAL order follows time's logic — 'chron' + 'logical' = time makes logical sense."},{"w":"synchronicity","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"chronoscope","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"anachronistic","def":"chronologically misplaced","ex":"English public schools are anachronistic","say":"uh-na-kruh-NIH-stihk","hook":"A knight with aCHRONOMETER is ANAchronistic — against the flow of time."}]},{"title":"morph (form / shape)","category":"Greek Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Greek morphē = form, shape. Morph- appears in biology, linguistics, mythology, and technology. The shape-shifting nature of the root makes it appear in transformation vocabulary across every field.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>METAMORPHOSIS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> meh-tuh-MAW-rfuh-suhs\n<b>Spell it.</b> M · E · T · A · M · O · R · P · H · O · S · I · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> meh-tuh-MAW-rfuh-suhs\n<b>Syllables.</b> meh · tah · mao · rfah · sah · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [meh=ME] [tuh=TA] [MOR=MOR] [fuh=PHO] [sis=SIS]\n<b>Exception.</b> meta- = beyond/change; -morph- = form; -ph- = /f/; -osis = process; 5 syllables\n<b>Origin.</b> Greek\n<b>Root.</b> Greek meta = change + morphe = form + sis = process","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Greek morphē = form, shape. Metamorphosis = meta (change) + morph (form) + -osis (process) = a complete change of form. Amorphous (a- + morph) = without shape = shapeless. Polymorphous (poly- + morph) = having many forms. Morphology = the study of form."},{"title":"Biological Morph Words","body":"Metamorphosis = caterpillar → butterfly = complete form change. Dimorphic (di- = two) = existing in two distinct forms. Anthropomorphic = anthropo + morphic = having human form. Geomorphic = geo + morphic = having earth-shaped features. Isomorphic = iso (equal) = having the same form."},{"title":"Linguistic Morph Words","body":"Morpheme = the smallest meaningful unit in language (-tion, un-, run). Morphology = the study of word forms and structure. Allomorph (allo- = different) = a different form of the same morpheme (the plural -s in cats vs -es in boxes). These are the building blocks of every word in this book."},{"title":"Technology & Culture","body":"Morph (verb) = to transform (as in computer graphics). Anamorphic = ana (back) + morph = distorted image that becomes clear from a specific angle. Anthropomorphism = attributing human characteristics to non-humans (giving animals human emotions in stories)."},{"title":"Spelling the ph","body":"The -ph- in morph = /f/. This is Greek phi (φ). Morphine (Morpheus = god of dreams = shapes of dreams) = the drug named after the dream god. Morpheus himself = the god of dreams who could take any human form. The drug, the god, and the root all share the /morf/ sound — always spelled with ph."}],"words":[{"w":"metamorphosis","def":"the marked and rapid transformation of a larva into an adult that occurs in some animals","ex":"the metamorphosis of the old house into something new and exciting","say":"meh-tuh-MAW-rfuh-suhs","hook":"metaMORPHosis: the caterpillar MORPHs through a process (-osis), not an 'a'."},{"w":"amorphous","def":"having no definite form or distinct shape","ex":"amorphous clouds of insects","say":"uh-MAW-rfuhs","hook":"Amorphous has 'morph' inside — morph means shape, and amorphous has NO shape."},{"w":"polymorphous","def":"relating to the crystallization of a compound in two or more different forms","ex":"polymorphous crystallization","say":"pol-ee-MOR-fus","hook":"POLY + MORPH + OUS: many morphs (shapes) — think of a shapeshifter with many forms."},{"w":"morphology","def":"the branch of biology that deals with the structure of animals and plants","ex":"In science class, we studied the morphology of insects, comparing the body structures of beetles and butterflies.","say":"maw-RFAH-luh-jee","hook":"MORPHOLOGY: the study of form — keep the PH because Greek PHilosophers loved studying PHorms."},{"w":"dimorphic","def":"occurring or existing in two different forms","ex":"The biology textbook explained that many bird species are dimorphic, with males displaying vivid, colorful feathers while females appear in dull, muted browns for camouflage.","say":"deye-MAW-rfihk","hook":"DiMORPHic means two (DI) shapes (MORPH) — like a Transformer with two forms."},{"w":"anthropomorphic","def":"suggesting human characteristics for animals or inanimate things","ex":"The animated film featured anthropomorphic animals who spoke, wore clothes, and faced very human problems.","say":"a-nthruh-puh-MAW-rfihk","hook":"MORPHIC means shaped — anthropoMORPHIC means shaped like a human; think of a MORPHing robot taking human form."},{"w":"geomorphic","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"isomorphic","def":"having similar appearance but genetically different","ex":"Two graphs are isomorphic if one can be rearranged to look exactly like the other.","say":"eye-soh-MOR-fik","hook":"ISO + MORPHIC — 'equal shape,' add -IC to isomorph: i-s-o-m-o-r-p-h-i-c."},{"w":"morpheme","def":"minimal meaningful language unit; it cannot be divided into smaller meaningful units","ex":"The teacher explained that the word 'unhappy' contains two morphemes: 'un' and 'happy.'","say":"MOR-feem","hook":"A MORPHEME ends in -EME like phoneme or grapheme — it's a team of linguistic units."},{"w":"allomorph","def":"any of several different crystalline forms of the same chemical compound","ex":"calcium carbonate occurs in the allomorphs calcite and aragonite","say":"A-luh-mawrf","hook":"An allomorph is ANOTHER FORM (morph) — like a shapeshifter with a double-L disguise at the start."},{"w":"anthropomorphism","def":"the representation of objects (especially a god) as having human form or traits","ex":"The author used anthropomorphism to give the forest animals human emotions and the ability to speak.","say":"a-nthruh-puh-MAW-rfih-zuhm","hook":"AnthropoMORPHISM: when you see a dog SMILing, that's anthropomorphISM — giving it human form, ending in -ISM."},{"w":"anamorphic","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"morphine","def":"is a narcotic used as a pain-killer or sedative","ex":"After the surgery, the patient was given morphine to manage the intense pain during recovery.","say":"m-AW-r-f-ee-n","hook":"MORPHINE: named for Morpheus the dream god — keep the PH or the spelling won't sleep well."}]},{"title":"scop / scope (see / examine)","category":"Greek Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Greek skopein = to look at. Every -scope word is an instrument for examining something. The root tells you what is being examined; -scope tells you it is a viewing/examining device.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>KALEIDOSCOPE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> k-uh-l-AY-d-uh-s-k-oh-p\n<b>Spell it.</b> K · A · L · E · I · D · O · S · C · O · P · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> k-uh-l-AY-d-uh-s-k-oh-p\n<b>Syllables.</b> k · a · l · e · i · d · o · s · c · o · p · e\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [kuh=KA] [LY=LEI] [duh=DO] [skohp=SCOPE]\n<b>Exception.</b> -kali- = kalos (beautiful) + eidos (form) + -scope; -ei- = /eye/; stress: kuh-LY-duh-skohp\n<b>Origin.</b> Greek\n<b>Root.</b> Greek kalos(beautiful)+eidos(shape)+skopein(to look at)","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Greek skopein = to look at. Kaleidoscope = kalos (beautiful) + eidos (form) + -scope = looks at beautiful forms. Microscope = mikros (small) = looks at tiny things. Telescope = tele (far) = looks at distant things. Periscope = peri (around) = looks around corners or over surfaces."},{"title":"Medical Scopes","body":"Stethoscope (stethos = chest) = listens to the chest. Endoscope (endo- = within) = looks inside the body. Laparoscope (laparo- = abdomen) = looks inside the abdomen. Ophthalmoscope (ophthalmos = eye) = examines the interior of the eye. Bronchoscope = examines the bronchial tubes."},{"title":"Science Scopes","body":"Oscilloscope (oscillare = to swing) = displays wave patterns. Spectroscope (spectrum = image) = analyzes light spectra. Cystoscope (kystis = bladder) = examines the bladder. Colonoscope = examines the colon. Each scope is named for exactly what it looks at — the root tells you everything."},{"title":"Horoscope — The Exception","body":"Horoscope (hora = hour/season + -scope) = looking at the hour of birth to tell the future. The hora here is not a body part or scientific field — it is time. Horoscope is the only common -scope word where the root is not something being physically examined."},{"title":"Kaleidoscope Spelling","body":"K-A-L-E-I-D-O-S-C-O-P-E — three combined Greek roots, fourteen letters. Break it: kali- (beautiful) + -eido- (form, from eidos) + -scope (look). The -ei- in kaleid- = /eye/ sound. The sc- in -scope = /sk/. Knowing the three parts makes the spelling manageable."}],"words":[{"w":"kaleidoscope","def":"is a continually shifting pattern or scene","ex":"Looking through the kaleidoscope, she saw brilliant geometric patterns of red, blue, and gold spinning with every turn.","say":"k-uh-l-AY-d-uh-s-k-oh-p","hook":"KALeidoscope shows BEAUTIFUL (kalos) SHAPES (eidos) to SEE (scope)."},{"w":"microscope","def":"magnifier of the image of small objects","ex":"the invention of the microscope led to the discovery of the cell","say":"MEYE-kruh-skohp","hook":"A MICROSCOPE lets you SCOPE out (look at) MICRO (tiny) things—micro+scope."},{"w":"telescope","def":"a magnifier of images of distant objects","ex":"In the accident, the cars telescoped","say":"TEH-luh-skohp","hook":"A TELESCOPE lets you SCOPE (look) from TELE (far) — scope out distant stars!"},{"w":"periscope","def":"an optical instrument that provides a view of an otherwise obstructed field","ex":"The submarine crew used a periscope to scan the surface of the ocean without rising above the water.","say":"PEH-ruh-skohp","hook":"A PERISCOPE lets you SCOPE all AROUND — peri (around) + SCOPE (look), spelled just like it sounds."},{"w":"stethoscope","def":"a medical instrument for listening to the sounds generated inside the body","ex":"The doctor pressed the cold stethoscope against the boy's chest and listened carefully to his heartbeat.","say":"STEH-thuh-skohp","hook":"The STETHO-SCOPE lets doctors SCOPE out your CHEST — no 'e' sneaks in between."},{"w":"endoscope","def":"a long slender medical instrument for examining the interior of a bodily organ or performing minor surgery","ex":"The doctor used an endoscope to examine the patient's stomach without requiring major surgery.","say":"EH-ndoh-skohp","hook":"An ENDOscope lets doctors look INSIDE — ENDO=within, SCOPE=look, just like a telescope looks far."},{"w":"laparoscope","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"ophthalmoscope","def":"medical instrument for examining the retina of the eye","ex":"The doctor shone light through the ophthalmoscope to carefully examine the blood vessels at the back of the patient's eye.","say":"ah-FTHA-lmuh-skohp","hook":"An OPHTHALMOSCOPE looks INTO the eye — OPHTHALM (eye) + SCOPE (look), a tool that sees inside."},{"w":"oscilloscope","def":"electronic equipment that provides visual images of varying electrical quantities","ex":"The physics class used an oscilloscope to see the wave pattern produced by a vibrating guitar string.","say":"aw-SIH-luh-skohp","hook":"An OSCILLOSCOPE lets you SEE oscillations — double-L plus SCOPE: you look (scope) at the swings (LL)."},{"w":"spectroscope","def":"an optical instrument for spectrographic analysis","ex":"Using a spectroscope, the student split white light into a rainbow of individual colors.","say":"SPEK-troh-skohp","hook":"SPECTRO + SCOPE: you SCOPE out the SPECTRUM — spectro-scope, two familiar pieces."},{"w":"cystoscope","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"colonoscope","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"horoscope","def":"a prediction of someone's future based on the relative positions of the planets","ex":"She read her horoscope every morning, though she never really believed the stars could predict her day.","say":"HAW-ruh-skohp","hook":"A horoSCOPE SCOPES out your future — spell it horo+scope, the O in horo is the full moon."},{"w":"bronchoscope","def":"a slender tubular instrument used to examine the bronchial tubes","ex":"The doctor used a bronchoscope to look inside the patient's airways and find the cause of his persistent cough.","say":"brah-nkuh-SKOHP","hook":"A bronchOSCOPE lets doctors SCOPE out your windpipe — the SCOPE part sees all."}]},{"title":"log / logy (word / reason / study)","category":"Greek Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Greek logos = word, reason, study. One of the most productive roots in all of English — it appears as the -logy study suffix, the -log/-logue conversation words, and even in theological vocabulary.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>MONOLOGUE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> MAH-nuh-lawg\n<b>Spell it.</b> M · O · N · O · L · O · G · U · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> MAH-nuh-lawg\n<b>Syllables.</b> maa · nah · lao · g\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [MON=MON] [uh=O] [log=LOGUE]\n<b>Exception.</b> -logue = /log/ sound; French form of Greek -logos; -ogue not -og at end; stress: MON-uh-log\n<b>Origin.</b> Greek\n<b>Root.</b> Greek monos=single + logos=word/speech","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Greek logos = word, reason, study. Dialogue (dia = between) = words between two people. Monologue (mono = one) = one person's long speech. Prologue (pro = before) = words before the main work. Epilogue (epi = upon/after) = words after the main work. Analogy (ana = up + logos) = reasoning up from comparison."},{"title":"-logy = Study Of","body":"This suffix is explored fully in C37 (-ology/-ologist). Key connections here: tautology (tauto = same) = saying the same thing twice. Eulogy (eu = good) = good words spoken of someone (usually at a funeral). Neologism (neo = new + logos) = a newly coined word. Syllogism = a logical argument in formal form."},{"title":"Demagogue & Pedagogue","body":"Demagogue (demos = people + ago = lead) = one who leads the people through manipulation. Pedagogue (pais = child + ago) = one who leads children = a teacher. Note: these end in -agogue = one who leads, not -logue = speech. Related by the -og- but different suffix."},{"title":"Theology & Related Words","body":"Theos = god + logos = theology = the study of God. Theocracy = theos + kratos = rule by God/religious law. Monotheism, polytheism, atheism all use theos. The logos root independently means \"the Word\" in biblical contexts — the opening of the Gospel of John: \"In the beginning was the logos.\""},{"title":"Spelling -logue vs -log","body":"American English prefers -log: catalog, dialog, prolog (though prologue is also accepted). British English uses -logue: catalogue, dialogue, prologue. In a competition: both spellings may be accepted — but know which dictionary the bee uses (Merriam-Webster for Scripps = American spellings)."}],"words":[{"w":"monologue","def":"speech you make to yourself","ex":"The actor delivered a powerful monologue that left the entire audience holding its breath.","say":"MAH-nuh-lawg","hook":"A MONOlogue is ONE person's LOGUE (speech) — one mouth, lots of words, add the UE."},{"w":"dialogue","def":"is conversation with two or more people","ex":"he has read Plato's Dialogues in the original Greek","say":"d-AY-uh-l-aw-g","hook":"A dialogUE always ends politely with a silent UE — the quiet goodbye at the end of a conversation."},{"w":"prologue","def":"an introduction to a play","ex":"The prologue hinted at the dark events that would unfold later in the play.","say":"PROH-lahg","hook":"A prOLOGUE opens the show — remember the 'ue' like the curtain cue before the play begins."},{"w":"epilogue","def":"a short speech (often in verse) addressed directly to the audience by an actor at the end of a play","ex":"the epilogue told what eventually happened to the main characters","say":"EH-puh-lawg","hook":"An EPILOGue ends with a VOGUE bow — the actor's final fashionable words include that silent -ue."},{"w":"analogy","def":"an inference that if things agree in some respects they probably agree in others","ex":"the operation of a computer presents and interesting analogy to the working of the brain","say":"uh-NA-luh-jee","hook":"An ANALOGY uses LOGIC (log) to draw a comparison — find the LOG in anaLOGy."},{"w":"tautology","def":"(logic) a statement that is necessarily true","ex":"The phrase 'a bachelor who has never been married' is a tautology, since the definition of bachelor already includes that meaning.","say":"taw-TOL-uh-jee","hook":"TAUTO means SAME so a TAUTOlogy says the same thing twice"},{"w":"eulogy","def":"is a speech in praise of a dead person","ex":"The grieving daughter delivered a heartfelt eulogy that made everyone in the church weep.","say":"y-OO-l-uh-j-ee","hook":"EUlogy = EU(good)+LOGY(words) — Good Words for the gone; keep EU at the front like 'YOU' speak first."},{"w":"neologism","def":"a newly invented word or phrase","ex":"The word 'selfie' began as a neologism but quickly entered dictionaries worldwide.","say":"nee-AH-luh-jih-zum","hook":"NEOLOGISM ends in ISM—it's the practice of making new words, so end it like 'journalism.'"},{"w":"syllogism","def":"deductive reasoning in which a conclusion is derived from two premises","ex":"The philosopher used a syllogism to prove that all humans are mortal.","say":"SIL-uh-jiz-um","hook":"SylLOGIsm — there's LOGIC inside sylLOGIsm, because it's all about logical reasoning."},{"w":"demagogue","def":"a political leader who seeks support by appealing to popular passions and prejudices","ex":"The historian warned that the fiery speaker was a demagogue who stirred up fear rather than offering real solutions.","say":"DEH-muh-gahg","hook":"A DEMAGOGUE has a silent OGUE at the end — like a rogue leader hiding behind the crowd: dem-a-GOGUE."},{"w":"pedagogue","def":"someone who educates young people","ex":"The old pedagogue paced the classroom, quizzing students on Latin grammar.","say":"PED-uh-gog","hook":"A PEDAGOGUE has a silent OGUE at the end — like catalogue and synagogue, Greek words love that -OGUE finale."},{"w":"theology","def":"the rational and systematic study of religion and its influences and of the nature of religious truth","ex":"During her theology course at university, Priya studied how different world religions understand the nature of creation, the divine, and humanity's place in the cosmos.","say":"thee-AH-luh-jee","hook":"THEOLOGY = THEO (God) + LOGY (study) — just like biology studies life, theology studies God."},{"w":"catalog","def":"a book or pamphlet containing an enumeration of things","ex":"he found it in the Sears catalog","say":"KA-tuh-lawg","hook":"A CATALOG LOGS items down the page — CATA+LOG, the American spelling drops the UE."},{"w":"travelogue","def":"a film or illustrated lecture on traveling","ex":"The geography teacher showed a captivating travelogue about life along the Amazon River.","say":"TRA-vuh-lawg","hook":"A traveLOGue is a LOG of your travels — the -OGUE wraps it up like a catalogue."},{"w":"apology","def":"an expression of regret at having caused trouble for someone","ex":"Marcus offered a sincere apology to his teammate after accidentally knocking him down during practice.","say":"uh-PAH-luh-jee","hook":"aPOLogy — say SORRY, it's POLite"},{"w":"trilogy","def":"a set of three literary or dramatic works related in subject or theme","ex":"She stayed up all weekend to finish the final book of the fantasy trilogy she had been reading all month.","say":"TRIH-luh-jee","hook":"A TRILOGY tells THREE stories—tri+LOGY like biology and geology, ends in Y not IE."}]},{"title":"phil / phile (love)","category":"Greek Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Greek philein = to love. Phil- appears at the start of words; -phile appears at the end. Together they create the vocabulary of love and affinity — for ideas, books, countries, and knowledge itself.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PHILANTHROPY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> fih-LA-nthruh-pee\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · H · I · L · A · N · T · H · R · O · P · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> fih-LA-nthruh-pee\n<b>Syllables.</b> fih · lae · nthrah · piy\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [fih=PHI] [LAN=LAN] [thruh=THRO] [pee=PY]\n<b>Exception.</b> -phil- = love; -anthrop- = human; -ph- = /f/ (Greek!); -y = /ee/ at end; stress: fih-LAN-thruh-pee\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Greek philanthropia = love of mankind (philos=loving + anthropos=human","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Greek philein = to love → phil- (at start) or -phile (at end). Philanthropy (phil + anthropos = human) = love of humanity. Philosophy (phil + sophia = wisdom) = love of wisdom. Philharmonic (phil + harmonikos) = loving harmony. Bibliophile (biblio = book + -phile) = one who loves books."},{"title":"-phile = One Who Loves","body":"Bibliophile = loves books. Anglophile = loves England/British culture. Francophile = loves French culture. Francophobe = fears/dislikes French culture (-phobe = opposite of -phile). Oenophile (oinos = wine) = loves wine. Cinephile = loves films. Xenophile (xenos = strange) = loves foreign things."},{"title":"-philia = Love of (as condition)","body":"Hemophilia (hemo- = blood + -philia) = love of blood = condition where blood does not clot. Bibliophilia = passionate love of books. Anglophilia = love of things English. The -philia form denotes the condition or tendency rather than the person."},{"title":"Philadelphia — the City of Brotherly Love","body":"Philadelphia (philos = loving + adelphos = brother) = city of brotherly love. The name is pure Greek etymology alive in American geography. Similarly: Philip (philippos) = philos + hippos = lover of horses. Philosophy = philos + sophia = lover of wisdom."},{"title":"Spelling the phil- Words","body":"Always ph not f — this is Greek and the ph is non-negotiable. Philanthropy = P-H-I-L-A-N-T-H-R-O-P-Y (two ph units — the -ph- in phil and the -p-h- from anthropos). Philosophy = P-H-I-L-O-S-O-P-H-Y (again two ph units). Count the Greek ph's carefully."}],"words":[{"w":"philanthropy","def":"voluntary promotion of human welfare","ex":"The billionaire devoted her retirement to philanthropy, donating millions to build schools in underserved communities around the world.","say":"fih-LA-nthruh-pee","hook":"PHIL loves ANTHROP-ology, so he gives generously — PHILanthropY = love of humanity."},{"w":"philosophy","def":"a belief (or system of beliefs) accepted as authoritative by some group or school","ex":"self-indulgence was his only philosophy","say":"fuh-LAH-suh-fee","hook":"PHIL-O-SOPH-Y: Phil loves Sophie — no letters skipped between them."},{"w":"philharmonic","def":"a large orchestra; can perform symphonies","ex":"The seventh-grade music class attended a concert performed by the city's philharmonic and were stunned by the power of one hundred instruments playing together.","say":"fih-lhah-RMAH-nihk","hook":"PHILharmonic: a PHIL-anthropist LOVES people; philharmonic LOVES harmony"},{"w":"bibliophile","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"anglophile","def":"an admirer of England and things English","ex":"As an anglophile, she decorated her room with images of Big Ben, drank tea every afternoon, and spoke with a slight British accent.","say":"A-ngluh-feyel","hook":"ANGLO + PHILE — a phile (lover) of all things ANGLO (English)"},{"w":"francophile","def":"an admirer of France and everything French","ex":"A true francophile, Mr. Dupont decorated his classroom with Eiffel Tower posters and played French jazz every morning.","say":"FRA-ngkuh-feyel","hook":"A FRANCOPHILE loves FRANCE — FRANCO + PHILE (lover), no K anywhere: F-R-A-N-C-O-P-H-I-L-E."},{"w":"oenophile","def":"someone who appreciates wine","ex":"The oenophile spent hours studying the vineyard's soil before selecting the perfect bottle.","say":"EE-nuh-feyel","hook":"An OENOphile loves OENology — both start with OENO; a wine lover has an OE-nose for fine vintages."},{"w":"cinephile","def":"A person who is extremely enthusiastic about and knowledgeable in the art of cinema and film history.","ex":"As a true cinephile, Marcus had watched over five hundred films before finishing middle school.","say":"SIN-uh-fyl","hook":"CINE + PHILE — a phile loves things, and a cinephile loves cinema."},{"w":"xenophile","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"hemophilia","def":"congenital tendency to uncontrolled bleeding; usually affects males and is transmitted from mother to son","ex":"Because he had hemophilia, even a minor cut required immediate medical attention to stop the bleeding.","say":"hee-muh-FEE-lee-uh","hook":"Hemophilia: blood has a 'philia' (love) for flowing — it just won't stop."},{"w":"philadelphia","def":"the largest city in Pennsylvania; located in the southeastern part of the state on the Delaware river; site of Independence Hall where the Declaration of Independence and the Constitution were signed; site of the University of Pennsylvania","ex":"Philadelphia is famous for its cheesesteaks, the Liberty Bell, and its rich Revolutionary War history.","say":"fih-luh-DEH-lfee-uh","hook":"PHILADELPHIA means brotherly love — PHIL(love)+ADELPH(brother)+IA — no I after PHIL, it's ADEL."},{"w":"bibliophilia","def":"A deep love of books and reading; the passionate enthusiasm for collecting, appreciating, and studying books as objects of beauty and knowledge.","ex":"Her bibliophilia was evident from the towering stacks of books that covered every surface of her bedroom.","say":"bib-lee-oh-FIL-ee-uh","hook":"BIBLIO (book) + PHILIA (love) — book LOVE, like Philadelphia means 'brotherly love' but for BOOKS."},{"w":"philology","def":"the humanistic study of language and literature","ex":"Her passion for philology led her to trace the surprising origins of dozens of everyday English words.","say":"fih-LOL-oh-jee","hook":"PhiloLOGY loves LOGOS — words and language; one L, like a single well-chosen word."},{"w":"philosophic","def":"of or relating to philosophy or philosophers","ex":"philosophical writing","say":"fih-luh-SAH-fihk","hook":"Phil loves Sophie's wisdom — PHILo+SOPHic."},{"w":"philanthropist","def":"someone who makes charitable donations intended to increase human well-being","ex":"The philanthropist donated enough money to build a new library for every school in the district.","say":"fuh-LA-nthruh-puhst","hook":"A philanthropIST puts people on his LIST of those to help — no H after anthrop!"}]},{"title":"gen / genesis (birth / origin / produce)","category":"Greek Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Greek genos = birth, race, kind → Latin borrowed it as genus. This root appears in biology, chemistry, medicine, and genealogy — any time words discuss origins, kinds, or creation.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>GENEALOGY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> jee-nee-AH-luh-jee\n<b>Spell it.</b> G · E · N · E · A · L · O · G · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> jee-nee-AH-luh-jee\n<b>Syllables.</b> jhiy · niy · aa · lah · jhiy\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [jee=GE] [nee=NEA] [AL=LO] [uh=GY]\n<b>Exception.</b> -gen- = birth/origin; -logy = study; initial ge- = /jee/ not /ghee/; stress: jee-nee-AL-uh-jee\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> Greek genea = generation + logos = study","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Greek genos = birth, race, kind. Genesis = the beginning = origin. Genealogy = study of family origins. Generate = to bring into being. Genetics = the science of inherited characteristics. Genre (genos through French) = a kind or category. One root, from family trees to gene science."},{"title":"-gen = Producing","body":"In chemistry, -gen = something that produces. Hydrogen (hydro + gen) = produces water (H₂O). Oxygen (oxys = sharp/acid + gen) = produces acid (original belief). Nitrogen (nitron = saltpeter + gen) = produces saltpeter. Pathogen = produces disease. Carcinogen = produces cancer."},{"title":"-genic = Producing / Born","body":"Photogenic = born/suited for photographs. Pathogenic = disease-producing. Carcinogenic = cancer-producing. Telegenic = suited for television. Psychogenic = originating in the mind. Neurogenic = originating in nerve tissue. The suffix -genic = \"producing\" or \"of that origin.\""},{"title":"Homogeneous vs Heterogeneous","body":"Homogeneous (homo = same + genos = kind) = of the same kind throughout. Heterogeneous (hetero = different + genos) = of different kinds. Both appear in chemistry, biology, and everyday language. The contrast pair uses the same root with opposite prefixes."},{"title":"Genus & Genre","body":"Latin genus = kind/class (from Greek genos). Genus in biology = a classification level above species. Genre = a type/category (music genre, literary genre). Congenital (con- + genitus = born with) = existing from birth. Indigenous (indu- = within + gen- = born) = born within the land = native."}],"words":[{"w":"genealogy","def":"successive generations of kin","ex":"After months of research into her genealogy, Mira discovered she was distantly related to a famous explorer.","say":"jee-nee-AH-luh-jee","hook":"GENEaLOGY: your GENE family LOG — remember the 'a' sits between gene and logy like an ancestor link."},{"w":"genesis","def":"a coming into being","ex":"Scientists still debate the genesis of the universe and what existed before the Big Bang.","say":"JEH-nuh-suhs","hook":"Genesis is the origin — the 'e' in the middle echoes 'begin': the beginning of all things."},{"w":"genetics","def":"the branch of biology that studies heredity and variation in organisms","ex":"Her fascination with genetics led her to study how inherited traits are passed from parents to children.","say":"juh-NEH-tihks","hook":"GENETICS begins with GENE — because genes are what this science is all about."},{"w":"generate","def":"bring into existence","ex":"The new manager generated a lot of problems","say":"JEH-ner-ayt","hook":"Generate keeps 'gene' at the start — genes generate life, so remember the spelling that way."},{"w":"hydrogen","def":"a nonmetallic univalent element that is normally a colorless and odorless highly flammable diatomic gas; the simplest and lightest and most abundant element in the universe","ex":"Hydrogen is the lightest element on the periodic table and makes up most of the universe's visible matter.","say":"HEYE-druh-juhn","hook":"HydroGEN GENerates water when burned — it's the water-making GENius of the periodic table."},{"w":"oxygen","def":"a nonmetallic bivalent element that is normally a colorless odorless tasteless nonflammable diatomic gas; constitutes 21 percent of the atmosphere by volume; the most abundant element in the earth's crust","ex":"The deep-sea diver carefully checked her oxygen tank before descending into the dark ocean waters.","say":"AH-ksuh-juhn","hook":"OXYGEN was named 'acid producer' — OXY-GEN, where GEN means to generate; it generates life."},{"w":"nitrogen","def":"a common nonmetallic element that constitutes 78 percent of the atmosphere","ex":"Plants need nitrogen to grow, which is why farmers often add special fertilizers to their soil.","say":"n-AY-t-r-uh-j-uh-n","hook":"NITROgen GENErates the air — remember the 'e' in gen, like 'generate.'"},{"w":"pathogen","def":"any disease-producing agent (especially a virus or bacterium or other microorganism)","ex":"Scientists worked around the clock to identify the pathogen responsible for the mysterious outbreak.","say":"PA-thuh-juhn","hook":"A PATHogen GENErates disease — remember PATH + O + GEN like a disease-generating gene."},{"w":"carcinogen","def":"any substance that produces cancer","ex":"Scientists confirmed that the chemical released by the factory was a carcinogen linked to higher cancer rates in the area.","say":"kah-RSIH-nuh-juhn","hook":"A carCINogen CINches cancer — remember the 'c' not 's' because Cancer starts with C."},{"w":"photogenic","def":"looking attractive in photographs","ex":"The golden retriever was so photogenic that every snapshot of him looked like a professional portrait.","say":"foh-tuh-JEH-nihk","hook":"PHOTOGENic people are born (GENerated) to look great in the light — no extra E."},{"w":"pathogenic","def":"able to cause disease","ex":"Scientists studying the pathogenic bacteria discovered that it spread rapidly in warm, humid environments, making proper handwashing and sanitation the most effective ways to prevent infection.","say":"pa-thuh-JEH-nihk","hook":"PATHogenic things GENerate Illness — PATH + O + GEN + IC, four clean blocks."},{"w":"carcinogenic","def":"causing or tending to cause cancer","ex":"Scientists confirmed that the factory had been releasing carcinogenic chemicals into the river for years, putting the health of nearby residents at serious risk.","say":"kah-rsuh-noh-JEH-nihk","hook":"CARCINO (cancer) + GENIC (producing) — carcinogenic produces cancer"},{"w":"homogeneous","def":"all of the same or similar kind or nature","ex":"a close-knit homogeneous group","say":"hoh-muh-JEE-nee-uhs","hook":"HomoGENEous — if everything shares the same GENE, the mixture is perfectly uniform and homogeneous."},{"w":"heterogeneous","def":"is different in kind unlike","ex":"the population of the United States is vast and heterogeneous","say":"h-eh-t-ur-uh-j-EE-n-y-uh-s","hook":"HETEROgenEOUS: remember EOUS not IOUS — DIFFERENT GENES make a mix that'sEOUS-ly diverse."},{"w":"genus","def":"a general kind of something","ex":"ignore the genus communism","say":"JEE-nuhs","hook":"GENUS and GENIUS are cousins — both start GEN, but genus is shorter, simpler: G-E-N-U-S."},{"w":"genre","def":"is a class of artistic endeavor having a particular form","ex":"Her favorite genre of music is jazz, but she also loves reading mysteries and watching science fiction films.","say":"zh-AH-n-r-uh","hook":"GENRE sounds fancy and French — keep the silent 'e' at the end like a French café."},{"w":"congenital","def":"present at birth but not necessarily hereditary; acquired during fetal development","ex":"The doctor explained that the infant's heart condition was congenital and had been present since before birth.","say":"kuh-NJEH-nuh-tuhl","hook":"CONGENITAL conditions are born with you — GENIT-al roots say 'at birth.'"},{"w":"indigenous","def":"originating where it is found","ex":"the autochthonal fauna of Australia includes the kangaroo","say":"ih-NDIH-juh-nuhs","hook":"INDIGENOUS has GEN in the middle — indigenous people GENerated the original culture of a place."}]},{"title":"dem / demo (people)","category":"Greek Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Greek demos = people. This root creates political and epidemiological vocabulary. Any word about how people govern themselves or how diseases move through populations uses dem-.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>DEMAGOGUE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> DEH-muh-gahg\n<b>Spell it.</b> D · E · M · A · G · O · G · U · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> DEH-muh-gahg\n<b>Syllables.</b> deh · mah · gaa · g\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [DEM=DEM] [uh=A] [gog=GOGUE]\n<b>Exception.</b> demos = people + agogos = leader; -gogue not -gog; stress: DEM-uh-gog\n<b>Origin.</b> Greek\n<b>Root.</b> Greek demagogos = demos(people) + agogos(leader)","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Greek demos = people. Democracy (demos + kratos = rule) = rule by the people. Epidemic (epi- = upon + demos) = disease upon the people. Endemic (en- = within) = disease within the people (a specific region). Pandemic (pan- = all) = disease across all peoples worldwide. One root, from government to disease."},{"title":"Democratic Vocabulary","body":"Democracy = the people rule. Demagogue = demos + agogos (leader) = one who leads the people through emotion and manipulation rather than reason. Demotic = of or for ordinary people. Demographics = demos + graphein = writing/data about the people. Demography = the statistical study of human populations."},{"title":"Epidemic vs Endemic vs Pandemic","body":"Endemic (en- = within) = normally present within a specific population/area (malaria is endemic in some tropical regions). Epidemic (epi- = upon) = an outbreak spreading upon a population. Pandemic (pan- = all) = an epidemic that has spread to all (or most) peoples worldwide. Three prefixes, three precise meanings."},{"title":"Demiurge — the Craftsman God","body":"Demiurge (demi = people + urgos = worker) = \"the craftsman of the people\" = in Platonic philosophy, the force that creates the material world. A rare but high-value bee word that combines demos with ergon (work) — Greek compound vocabulary at its most sophisticated."},{"title":"Spelling dem- Words","body":"Democracy = D-E-M-O-C-R-A-C-Y (not -cracy with a k). Demagogue = D-E-M-A-G-O-G-U-E (-gogue not -gog — the French -ue ending). Epidemic = E-P-I-D-E-M-I-C (epi- + dem- + -ic). Demographics = D-E-M-O-G-R-A-P-H-I-C-S (-ph- Greek signal in -graphics)."}],"words":[{"w":"democracy","def":"the political orientation of those who favor government by the people or by their elected representatives","ex":"Students in the civics class debated whether a true democracy could survive when large portions of eligible voters chose not to participate in elections.","say":"dih-MAH-kruh-see","hook":"DEMOCRACY: DEMO the CRAZY idea that one person rules — demos + kratos, people power!"},{"w":"demagogue","def":"a political leader who seeks support by appealing to popular passions and prejudices","ex":"The historian warned that the fiery speaker was a demagogue who stirred up fear rather than offering real solutions.","say":"DEH-muh-gahg","hook":"A DEMAGOGUE has a silent OGUE at the end — like a rogue leader hiding behind the crowd: dem-a-GOGUE."},{"w":"epidemic","def":"a widespread outbreak of an infectious disease; many people are infected at the same time","ex":"an epidemic outbreak of influenza","say":"eh-puh-DEH-mihk","hook":"An EPIDEMic falls UPON the DEMO(cracy) — it spreads across all the people."},{"w":"endemic","def":"a disease that is constantly present to a greater or lesser degree in people of a certain class or in people living in a particular location","ex":"it is an endemic found only this island","say":"eh-NDEH-mihk","hook":"Endemic means IN the DEMO (people) of one place — en-DEM-ic, like a built-in local disease."},{"w":"pandemic","def":"an epidemic that is geographically widespread; occurring throughout a region or even throughout the world","ex":"a pandemic outbreak of malaria","say":"pa-NDEH-mihk","hook":"A panDEMic affects ALL the DEMOS — all the people — remember the 'dem' like democracy."},{"w":"demographics","def":"statistical data characterizing human populations broken down by factors such as age, sex, or income","ex":"The marketing team studied the demographics of the city to decide which neighborhoods would best receive their new product.","say":"deh-muh-GRA-fihks","hook":"DEMOgraphics studies the DEMO — the people of a place"},{"w":"demography","def":"the branch of sociology that studies the characteristics of human populations","ex":"Studying demography helped the students understand why some countries have aging populations while others are very young.","say":"dih-MAH-gruh-fee","hook":"DemoGRAPHy writes (GRAPHS) the story of the people — keep the PH."},{"w":"demotic","def":"a simplified cursive form of the ancient hieratic script","ex":"Demotic script was eventually replaced by Greek","say":"dih-MAH-tik","hook":"DEMOTIC script was for DEMO-cratic common people—both share 'demo' from demos."},{"w":"demiurge","def":"a subordinate deity, in some philosophies the creator of the universe","ex":"In ancient Gnostic belief, the demiurge was responsible for shaping the physical world from raw matter.","say":"DEM-ee-urj","hook":"The DEMI-URGE-d creator URGED matter into form — the DEMI-URGE worked for the people (demos)."},{"w":"democratize","def":"become (more) democratic; of nations","ex":"The internet has helped democratize information by making knowledge available to anyone with a connection.","say":"dih-MAH-kruh-teyez","hook":"To democratIZE, you let the people RISE with a Z."},{"w":"autocracy","def":"a political system governed by a single individual","ex":"The citizens grew frustrated living under an autocracy where a single ruler made every decision without question.","say":"aw-TAH-kruh-see","hook":"AUTO-CRACY: one ruler rules by themselves — C-R-A-C-Y, like democracy but with AUTO in front."},{"w":"plutocracy","def":"a political system governed by the wealthy people","ex":"Citizens protested what they called a plutocracy, where only the wealthiest had any real power.","say":"ploo-TOK-ruh-see","hook":"PLUTO (wealth god) + CRACY (rule) — rule by PLUTO's crowd: PLUTOCRACY."},{"w":"theocracy","def":"is a form of government in which a deity is recognized as the supreme civil ruler","ex":"In a theocracy, religious leaders make the laws of the land based on sacred texts and divine authority.","say":"th-ee-AH-k-r-uh-s-ee","hook":"THEOCRACY: THEO (God) + CRACY (rule) — like DEMOcracy but God's in charge, not the DEMO."}]},{"title":"aud (hear)","category":"Latin Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin audire = to hear. Everything about hearing and listening uses this root — from the audience that listens to audacious daring (a false friend: same letters, different root!).","method":"<div class='trick'><b>AUDITORIUM</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> aw-duh-TAW-ree-uhm\n<b>Spell it.</b> A · U · D · I · T · O · R · I · U · M\n<b>Say it again.</b> aw-duh-TAW-ree-uhm\n<b>Syllables.</b> ao · dah · tao · riy · ah · m\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [aw=AU] [dih=DI] [TOR=TOR] [ee=I] [um=UM]\n<b>Exception.</b> audire = to hear; -um = Latin neuter ending; 5 syllables; aw-dih-TOR-ee-um\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin auditorium = place for hearing","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Latin audire = to hear. Audible = able to be heard. Audience = those who come to hear. Auditorium = a place for hearing. Audit = originally an oral examination (hearing accounts). Audiovisual = combining sound and sight. All hearing-related — all from aud-."},{"title":"The Audacious Trap","body":"⚠️ Audacious shares aud- BUT comes from audere = to dare (different Latin root!). Audible (hearing) ≠ audacious (daring). Both share A-U-D at the start. The definition is the only way to know which root you are dealing with. This is a famous bee confusable."},{"title":"aud- in Legal/Formal Contexts","body":"Audit = an official hearing/examination of financial records. Auditor = one who audits. Judicial — NOT from aud-. Inaudible (in- + audible) = cannot be heard. Audition = a hearing/trial performance. Audiometry (aud- + -metry) = measurement of hearing."},{"title":"Subaudition","body":"A rare but beautiful word: subaudition (sub- + audit + -ion) = understanding something that is not explicitly stated — the meaning you \"hear under\" the words. Also: subaudible = below the threshold of hearing. These show how aud- combines with other prefixes."},{"title":"Spelling aud- Words","body":"All begin A-U-D — the au diphthong sounds like /aw/. Audacious ≠ from audire but still spelled A-U-D. Auditorium = A-U-D-I-T-O-R-I-U-M (note the -torium from auditor + -ium = place for). Audible = A-U-D-I-B-L-E (-ible not -able — Latin stem)."}],"words":[{"w":"audible","def":"a football play is changed orally after both teams have assumed their positions at the line of scrimmage","ex":"he spoke in an audible whisper","say":"AH-duh-buhl","hook":"AUDIBLE uses -IBLE not -ABLE: you need your EAR (AUD) to make it audIBLE — 'I' hear it!"},{"w":"audience","def":"a gathering of spectators or listeners at a (usually public) performance","ex":"The audience burst into applause when the young violinist finished her breathtaking performance.","say":"AH-dee-uhns","hook":"An AUDIence uses their ears — like an AUDIO system"},{"w":"auditorium","def":"the area of a theater or concert hall where the audience sits","ex":"The entire student body packed into the auditorium to watch the final spelling bee championship.","say":"aw-duh-TAW-ree-uhm","hook":"An audiTORIUM is a place where audiences hear — keep AUDI at the front, like listening."},{"w":"audit","def":"an inspection of the accounting procedures and records by a trained accountant or CPA","ex":"he made an audit of all the plants on his property","say":"AW-diht","hook":"An AUDIT is when the accountant 'hears' the books — Latin 'he heard': A-U-D-I-T, just five letters, one T."},{"w":"audition","def":"the ability to hear; the auditory faculty","ex":"his hearing was impaired","say":"ah-DIH-shuhn","hook":"An audITION is your chance to be heard — hear the word 'ITION' as you perform."},{"w":"audiometry","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"inaudible","def":"impossible to hear; imperceptible by the ear","ex":"an inaudible conversation","say":"ih-NAW-duh-buhl","hook":"Inaudible ends in -IBLE not -ABLE — AUD as in AUDIO cannot be heard here."},{"w":"audiovisual","def":"materials using sight or sound to present information","ex":"language tapes and videocassettes and other audiovisuals","say":"aw-dee-oh-VIH-zhoo-uhl","hook":"AUDIOVISUAL combines hearing AND seeing — AUDIO + VISUAL, both senses in one long word ending in -UAL."},{"w":"auditor","def":"someone who listens attentively","ex":"The auditor carefully reviewed every financial record to make sure there were no errors in the company's accounts.","say":"AW-dih-ter","hook":"An audiTOR is a person who listens and checks — TOR sounds like 'tore through the books'."},{"w":"subaudition","def":"The mental act of understanding or supplying something that is implied but not directly stated in speech or writing.","ex":"The reader used subaudition to fill in the missing word that the damaged manuscript had lost.","say":"sub-aw-DISH-un","hook":"SUB + AUDITION — hearing what's BELOW the text, mentally AUDITING what isn't said."}]},{"title":"dict / dic (say / speak)","category":"Latin Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin dicere = to say. One of the most productive roots in legal, political, and everyday English. Every time something is said officially, pronounced, or declared, dict- is likely present.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>MALEDICTION</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> mal-eh-DIK-shun\n<b>Spell it.</b> M · A · L · E · D · I · C · T · I · O · N\n<b>Say it again.</b> mal-eh-DIK-shun\n<b>Syllables.</b> male · dic · tion\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [mal=MAL] [uh=E] [DIK=DIC] [shun=TION]\n<b>Exception.</b> mal- = bad; -dict- = say; -ion = noun; contrast with benediction = good saying; stress: mal-uh-DIK-shun\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin: maledico (Latin)","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Latin dicere = to say. Diction = the way one says words = enunciation. Dictate = say officially. Edict (e- = out + dict) = what is said officially = a decree. Indict (in- + dict) = formally accuse (the c is silent in English: /in-DYTE/!). Verdict (ver = truth + dict) = what is truly said by a jury."},{"title":"Bene- and Male-diction","body":"Benediction (bene + dict + -ion) = a good saying = a blessing. Malediction (male + dict + -ion) = a bad saying = a curse. These are structural opposites built from the same dict- root. In a bee: benediction = B-E-N-E-D-I-C-T-I-O-N; malediction = M-A-L-E-D-I-C-T-I-O-N."},{"title":"Contradict & Predict","body":"Contradict (contra- = against + dict) = say against = dispute. Predict (pre- + dict) = say before = forecast. Interdict (inter- + dict) = say between/forbid. Valediction (vale = farewell + dict) = a farewell saying. Jurisdiction (juris = law + dict) = saying what the law is = legal authority."},{"title":"Abdicate vs Dedicate","body":"⚠️ Neither abdicate nor dedicate is from dicere = say. Abdicate comes from abdicare = renounce. Dedicate = dedicare = set apart for a purpose. These look like dict- words but use a different Latin root dicare (not dicere). The definition at the microphone resolves the confusion."},{"title":"Spelling dict- Words","body":"Indict = I-N-D-I-C-T (silent c — pronounced /in-DYTE/). Jurisdiction = J-U-R-I-S-D-I-C-T-I-O-N (note -juris- = law). Valediction = V-A-L-E-D-I-C-T-I-O-N (spoken at graduation). Malediction = M-A-L-E-D-I-C-T-I-O-N. The -dict- is always spelled the same: D-I-C-T."}],"words":[{"w":"diction","def":"the articulation of speech regarded from the point of view of its intelligibility to the audience","ex":"use concise military verbiage","say":"DIH-kshuhn","hook":"Good DICTION means saying each DICT-ion clearly — no mumbling allowed."},{"w":"dictate","def":"an authoritative rule","ex":"the dictates of reason","say":"dih-KTAYT","hook":"When you DICTATE, you say it — DICT sounds like 'dicked' out word by word."},{"w":"edict","def":"a formal or authoritative proclamation","ex":"a friend in New Mexico said that the order caused no trouble out there","say":"EE-dihkt","hook":"An EDICT is DICTATED outward — one 'd', like in DICTATE."},{"w":"indict","def":"accuse formally of a crime","ex":"The grand jury voted to indict the corrupt official on three counts of fraud and bribery.","say":"ih-NDEYET","hook":"You inDICT someone in DICT-ation — the C is silent but it's always there, hiding like evidence."},{"w":"verdict","def":"(law) the findings of a jury on issues of fact submitted to it for decision; can be used in formulating a judgment","ex":"The courtroom fell completely silent as the jury foreman rose to announce the long-awaited verdict.","say":"VUR-dihkt","hook":"A VERDICT is what is truly DICT-ated (said) by the jury — VERily DiCTated!"},{"w":"benediction","def":"the act of praying for divine protection","ex":"The priest offered a warm benediction at the end of the ceremony, sending the congregation home with words of peace and hope.","say":"beh-nuh-DIH-kshuhn","hook":"A BENEficial DICTION: a benediction is literally 'well-spoken' words of blessing."},{"w":"malediction","def":"the act of calling down a curse that invokes evil (and usually serves as an insult)","ex":"he suffered the imprecations of the mob","say":"mal-eh-DIK-shun","hook":"MALE (bad) + DICTION (words): bad words spoken as a curse — opposite of benediction."},{"w":"contradict","def":"To contradict a statement means to assert or express the opposite of what has been said.","ex":"The board opposed his motion","say":"kah-ntruh-DIHKT","hook":"To CONTRADICT is to say something AGAINST what was DICT-ated — contra + dict."},{"w":"predict","def":"make a prediction about; tell in advance","ex":"Call the outcome of an election","say":"prih-DIHKT","hook":"To preDICT is to DICT-ate the future before it happens — a DICTATOR tells you what will be."},{"w":"interdict","def":"an ecclesiastical censure by the Roman Catholic Church withdrawing certain sacraments and Christian burial from a person or all persons in a particular district","ex":"I forbid you to call me late at night","say":"IH-nter-dihkt","hook":"A DICT-ator steps INTER (between) you and your rights — interDICT contains 'dict' like dictate."},{"w":"valediction","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"jurisdiction","def":"(law) the right and power to interpret and apply the law","ex":"The local police explained that the crime had occurred just outside their jurisdiction and another department would handle it.","say":"juu-ruh-SDIH-kshuhn","hook":"Jurisdiction: the JURIS (law) DICTION (words) of authority."},{"w":"abdicate","def":"To formally give up or renounce a high office, throne, or position of power or responsibility.","ex":"When the king decided to abdicate his throne, the entire kingdom was stunned and uncertain about who would rule next.","say":"A-bduh-kayt","hook":"To abdicate is to 'declare away' your power—the 'dic' root means to declare."},{"w":"dedicating","def":"give entirely to a specific person, activity, or cause","ex":"She committed herself to the work of God","say":"DEH-dih-kay-tihng","hook":"Drop the E before adding -ING: DEDICATING, not dedicateing."}]},{"title":"duc / duct (lead)","category":"Latin Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin ducere = to lead. From education (leading out knowledge) to seduction (leading aside), this root describes every form of leading, guiding, and conducting.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>INDUCTION</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ih-NDUH-kshuhn\n<b>Spell it.</b> I · N · D · U · C · T · I · O · N\n<b>Say it again.</b> ih-NDUH-kshuhn\n<b>Syllables.</b> ih · ndah · kshah · n\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [in=IN] [DUK=DUC] [shun=TION]\n<b>Exception.</b> in- = into; -duct- = lead; -ion noun suffix; stress: in-DUK-shun\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin inductio = a leading in","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Latin ducere = to lead. Induct = lead into a position. Educate (e- = out + duc) = lead knowledge outward from within. Introduce (intro- = within + duce) = lead into the presence of. Conduct (con- = together + duct) = lead together. Reduce (re- = back + duce) = lead back = make smaller."},{"title":"Duke & Duchess","body":"Duke = dux = the leader. From ducere → dux → Old French duc → English duke. A duke is literally \"a leader.\" Aqueduct (aqua = water + ductus) = a structure that leads water. Viaduct (via = road + ductus) = a structure that leads a road across a valley. These compound words are architectural duc- words."},{"title":"Abduct, Deduct, Seduce","body":"Abduct (ab- = away) = lead away by force. Deduct (de- = from) = lead/take from the total. Seduce (se- = aside) = lead aside = lead astray. Traduce (tra- = across) = lead across = to slander. Adduce (ad- = toward) = lead toward = to cite as evidence. Each prefix changes the direction of leading."},{"title":"Conductor & Semiconductor","body":"Conductor = one who leads (an orchestra or electricity). Semiconductor (semi- = half) = a material that half-conducts electricity (silicon in computer chips). Nonconductor = does not conduct. Superconductor (super- = above) = conducts with zero resistance. The -conductor compound scales from music to physics."},{"title":"Spelling duc/duct Words","body":"The root appears as duc (before vowels: educate, reduce, seduce) and duct (before consonants: induction, conduction, abduction). Aqueduct = A-Q-U-E-D-U-C-T (Latin aqua = water). Viaduct = V-I-A-D-U-C-T (via = road). Educate = E-D-U-C-A-T-E (e- + duc + -ate)."}],"words":[{"w":"induction","def":"a formal entry into an organization or position or office","ex":"his initiation into the club","say":"ih-NDUH-kshuhn","hook":"INDUCTION has the word DUCT in it — like a duct leading you IN to a new role."},{"w":"educate","def":"give an education to","ex":"We must educate our youngsters better","say":"EH-juh-kayt","hook":"EDUCATE has a DUCK in the middle — a teacher leads ducklings out to learn."},{"w":"conduct","def":"manner of acting or controlling yourself","ex":"You cannot conduct business like this","say":"KAH-nduhkt","hook":"CONDUCT — a CONDUCTor LEADS the orchestra. CON+DUCT, no extra letters hidden inside."},{"w":"reduce","def":"cut down on; make a reduction in","ex":"reduce your daily fat intake","say":"ruh-DOOS","hook":"The DUKE led things BACK — reDUCE ends in DUCE, like a duke leading things down."},{"w":"introduce","def":"cause to come to know personally","ex":"permit me to acquaint you with my son","say":"ih-ntruh-DOOS","hook":"Introduce uses -duce like 'conduct' or 'deduce'—you LEAD someone IN."},{"w":"abduct","def":"To take someone away by force or illegally, such as in a kidnapping; also, in anatomy, to move a limb away from the body's midline.","ex":"The villain's plot to abduct the young princess was foiled by the brave knights who had been standing guard.","say":"a-BDUHKT","hook":"ab- (away) + duct (lead): to lead someone away against their will"},{"w":"deduct","def":"make a subtraction","ex":"subtract this amount from my paycheck","say":"dih-DUHKT","hook":"DE-DUCT: a DUCT leads water away — DEDUCT leads money away from your total."},{"w":"seduce","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"traduce","def":"means to slander or defame","ex":"She badmouths her husband everywhere","say":"truh-DYOOS","hook":"To TRADUCE someone is to lead their reputation across the mud — like PRODUCE but with TRA-, producing lies about someone."},{"w":"adduce","def":"advance evidence for","ex":"The defense attorney tried to adduce new witnesses and documents to support her client's alibi.","say":"ah-DOOS","hook":"To adduce evidence, you LEAD it forward — the double D leads duce right to the judge."},{"w":"aqueduct","def":"a conduit that resembles a bridge but carries water over a valley","ex":"The ancient Roman aqueduct still stretches across the valley, a testament to brilliant engineering.","say":"A-kwuh-duhkt","hook":"AquEDUCT not aquADUCT — the E is the bridge that carries water, just like the structure itself."},{"w":"viaduct","def":"bridge consisting of a series of arches supported by piers used to carry a road (or railroad) over a valley","ex":"The old stone viaduct carried the railroad across the deep valley for over a hundred years.","say":"VEYE-uh-duhkt","hook":"A VIAduct leads (DUCT) the road (VIA) over a valley — road + conduit = viaduct."},{"w":"conductor","def":"the person who leads a musical group","ex":"The conductor raised her baton and the entire orchestra fell into perfect silence.","say":"kuh-NDUH-kter","hook":"A conducTOR leads the orchestra — remember the -OR ending, because he's a leaDOR of sound."},{"w":"semiconductor","def":"a substance as germanium or silicon whose electrical conductivity is intermediate between that of a metal and an insulator; its conductivity increases with temperature and in the presence of impurities","ex":"Silicon, a widely used semiconductor, is the key ingredient in most modern computer chips.","say":"seh-mee-kuh-NDUH-kter","hook":"SEMICONDUCTOR ends in OR — the conductor leads the charge, so honor it with an O-R ending."},{"w":"ductile","def":"easily influenced","ex":"Gold is an extremely ductile metal, meaning skilled jewelers can hammer and stretch it into incredibly thin wires without the material cracking or breaking apart.","say":"DUH-ktuhl","hook":"A ductile wire can be DUCT-tiled flat — stretched into any tile shape you need."},{"w":"inductee","def":"a person inducted into an organization or social group","ex":"Ty Cobb and Babe Ruth were 1936 inductees in the National Baseball Hall of Fame","say":"ih-nduh-KTEE","hook":"The inductEE is the one being led IN — double E at the end like two open doors welcoming them."}]},{"title":"fer (carry / bear)","category":"Latin Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin ferre = to carry, to bear. One of the most productive Latin roots — it appears in scientific (conifer, fertile), legal (transfer), and everyday (prefer, suffer) vocabulary.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>EFFERVESCE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> —\n<b>Spell it.</b> E · F · F · E · R · V · E · S · C · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> —\n<b>Syllables.</b> e · f · f · e · r · v · e · s · c · e\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [ef=EF] [fer=FER] [VES=VES]\n<b>Exception.</b> ef- = ex- before f (assimilation); -ferv- = boil; -esce = becoming; stress: ef-er-VES\n<b>Origin.</b> —\n<b>Root.</b> —","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Latin ferre = to carry, bear. Transfer (trans- = across) = carry across. Confer (con- = together) = carry/bring together = discuss. Defer (de- = away) = carry away = postpone or show respect. Infer (in- = toward) = carry toward a conclusion. Prefer (pre- = before) = carry before others = like better."},{"title":"-fer Words in Science","body":"Aquifer (aqua + -fer) = carries/bears water underground. Conifer (conus = cone + -fer) = cone-bearing tree. Crucifer (crux = cross + -fer) = cross-bearing plant (broccoli, cabbage). Proliferate (proles + -ferare) = carry offspring = spread abundantly. Odoriferous (odor + -fer + -ous) = bearing a smell."},{"title":"Suffer & Offer","body":"Suffer (sub- + ferre) = carry under = endure. Offer (ob- + ferre) = carry toward = present for acceptance. Afferent (ad- + ferens) = carrying toward (nerves carrying signals TO the brain). Efferent (e- + ferens) = carrying outward (nerves carrying signals FROM the brain). A medical pair built on ferre."},{"title":"Fertile & Fertile","body":"Fertile (fertilis = bearing fruit) = producing abundantly. Fertility = the state of being productive. Fertilize = make fertile. Infertile (in- + fertile) = unable to bear/produce. Fertilizer = substance that makes soil more productive. All from ferre = to bear → fertilis = bearing."},{"title":"Spelling fer- Words","body":"The fer root can appear as fer- or -fer- or -ferr- (when stress causes doubling): prefer → preferring (double-r because stress is on the second syllable). Refer → referred (double-r). Transfer → transferring (double-r). Offer → offered (no double — stress on first syllable). The doubling rule for -fer- words follows the standard stress rule."}],"words":[{"w":"transfer","def":"the act of moving something from one location to another","ex":"the best student was a transfer from LSU","say":"tra-NSFUR","hook":"To transFER is to FERRY something across — FER sounds like FERRY, carrying goods over water."},{"w":"confer","def":"have a conference in order to talk something over","ex":"We conferred about a plan of action","say":"kuh-NFUR","hook":"When you conFER, you bring ideas toFERther — FER is the engine that carries meaning."},{"w":"defer","def":"hold back to a later time","ex":"let's postpone the exam","say":"dih-FUR","hook":"To deFER is to carry a decision FURther away — hear the FUR sound and picture pushing it away."},{"w":"infer","def":"reason by deduction; establish by deduction","ex":"He guessed the right number of beans in the jar and won the prize","say":"ih-NFUR","hook":"To inFER, you carry facts inward — FER means carry, like a ferry."},{"w":"prefer","def":"like better; value more highly","ex":"Some people prefer camping to staying in hotels","say":"pruh-FUR","hook":"You PREFER what you put beFORE — don't mix up the R and E: pre-FER, not per-fer."},{"w":"aquifer","def":"underground bed or layer yielding ground water for wells and springs etc","ex":"Farmers in the region depend on a deep underground aquifer to water their crops during dry summers.","say":"A-kwuh-fer","hook":"An aquiFER FERries water underground — the FER ending means 'to carry,' like a watery chauffeur."},{"w":"conifer","def":"any gymnospermous tree or shrub bearing cones","ex":"The tall conifer stood alone on the ridge, its dark green needles dusted with fresh snow.","say":"KAH-nuh-fer","hook":"A conifer BEARS CONES — 'fer' means bear, so a coniFER bears cones like a pine tree."},{"w":"proliferate","def":"grow rapidly","ex":"Pizza parlors proliferate in this area","say":"proh-LIH-fer-ayt","hook":"To proLIFERate is to fill with LIFE rapidly — LIFE is hiding right inside proLIFErate!"},{"w":"odoriferous","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"suffer","def":"undergo or be subjected to","ex":"He suffered the penalty","say":"SUH-fer","hook":"SUFFER has a double F — two F's like two blows of pain you must bear."},{"w":"offer","def":"the verbal act of offering","ex":"a generous offer of assistance","say":"AW-fer","hook":"OFFER — double F in the middle; you bring something OFfer to someone, carrying it toward them."},{"w":"afferent","def":"a nerve that passes impulses from receptors toward or to the central nervous system","ex":"The doctor explained that afferent nerve fibers carry sensory signals from the fingertips and skin all the way inward to the brain and spinal cord for processing.","say":"A-fer-uhnt","hook":"AFFERENT carries signals inward — think 'Arriving signals': A-F-FER-ENT, double F ferrying messages to the brain."},{"w":"efferent","def":"a nerve that conveys impulses toward or to muscles or glands","ex":"efferent nerves and impulses","say":"EH-fer-uhnt","hook":"EFfERENT carries signals EFFERently away from the center — EFF then 'rent' the path out."},{"w":"fertile","def":"capable of reproducing","ex":"The farmers were thrilled to discover that the valley soil was incredibly fertile, producing twice the expected harvest of corn and wheat in a single season.","say":"FUR-tuhl","hook":"FERTile land BEARS fruit — fertile ends in -ILE like 'agile' and 'docile,' smooth and productive."},{"w":"fertility","def":"the ratio of live births in an area to the population of that area; expressed per 1000 population per year","ex":"he praised the richness of the soil","say":"fer-TIH-luh-tee","hook":"FertilITY is the ability to bear — one L, then -ITY like ability and agility."},{"w":"fertilize","def":"provide with fertilizers or add nutrients to","ex":"We should fertilize soil if we want to grow healthy plants","say":"FUR-tuh-leyez","hook":"To fertilIZE is to make fertile — IZE it with American Z like a buzzing bee pollinating a flower."}]},{"title":"scrib / script (write)","category":"Latin Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin scribere = to write. Every form of official writing — prescriptions, descriptions, scripts, manuscripts — uses this root. It appears with the full range of Latin prefixes.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>CIRCUMSCRIBE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> sur-kuh-MSKREYEB\n<b>Spell it.</b> C · I · R · C · U · M · S · C · R · I · B · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> sur-kuh-MSKREYEB\n<b>Syllables.</b> cir · cum · scribe\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [sur=CIR] [kum=CUM] [SKRYB=SCRIBE]\n<b>Exception.</b> circum- = around; -scribe = write/draw; stress: sur-kum-SKRYB\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin circum (around) + scribere (to write/draw)","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Latin scribere = to write. Manuscript (manus = hand + script) = written by hand. Inscription (in- + script) = written on/into a surface. Prescription (pre- + script) = written before/in advance by a doctor. Description (de- + script) = written down = an account of. Transcription (trans- + script) = written across = a copy."},{"title":"Circumscribe & Inscribe","body":"Circumscribe (circum- = around + scribe) = draw a circle around = limit the scope of. Inscribe (in- + scribe) = write on or engrave into. Subscribe (sub- + scribe) = write under = sign your name below = agree to receive. Conscript (con- + script) = enrolled/written in together = drafted into military service."},{"title":"Prescribe vs Proscribe","body":"⚠️ Prescribe (pre- + scribe) = write in advance = a doctor writes a prescription. Proscribe (pro- = put forward publicly) = publicly ban = forbid. A doctor prescribes medicine; authorities proscribe illegal activities. Two different pro-/pre- prefixes, one -scribe root. Easy to confuse at the microphone."},{"title":"Script in Theater & Film","body":"Script = the written text of a play or film. Postscript (post- + script) = written after = P.S. Nondescript (non- + de- + script) = not written about distinctively = lacking distinctive character = dull. Scriptural = relating to sacred writings."},{"title":"Spelling scrib/script Words","body":"Root appears as -scrib- before vowels (subscribe, describe) and -script- before consonants (manuscript, inscription). Nondescript = N-O-N-D-E-S-C-R-I-P-T. Circumscribe = C-I-R-C-U-M-S-C-R-I-B-E. Conscript = C-O-N-S-C-R-I-P-T. The -sc- cluster at the start of -scribe/-script is the core spelling challenge."}],"words":[{"w":"manuscript","def":"the form of a literary work submitted for publication","ex":"The ancient manuscript, written entirely by hand, had survived five hundred years in the monastery's library.","say":"MA-nyuh-skrihpt","hook":"A MANU-SCRIPT was written by HAND — the SCRIPT is right there in the word!"},{"w":"inscription","def":"text that is written or otherwise marked upon an object so as to create a lasting or public record","ex":"The archaeologist carefully brushed away the dust to reveal the ancient inscription carved into the stone wall.","say":"ih-n-s-k-r-IH-p-sh-uh-n","hook":"An inSCRIPTion is like a SCRIPT carved in stone — drop the E from scribe and add -TION."},{"w":"prescription","def":"directions prescribed beforehand; the action of prescribing authoritative rules or directions","ex":"I tried to follow her prescription for success","say":"pruh-SKRIH-pshuhn","hook":"Don't PERvert the spelling — it's PRE not PER: PRE-SCRIP-TION, written before you're sick."},{"w":"description","def":"a statement that represents something in words","ex":"every description of book was there","say":"dih-SKRIH-pshuhn","hook":"A deSCRIPTion is a SCRIPT written about something — find SCRIPT hiding inside."},{"w":"transcription","def":"something written, especially copied from one medium to another, as a typewritten version of dictation","ex":"The court reporter's transcription of the entire three-hour trial filled more than two hundred pages.","say":"tra-NSKRIH-pshuhn","hook":"TRANS(fer) + SCRIPT: transferring what was scripted (written)"},{"w":"circumscribe","def":"draw a line around","ex":"The teacher used a compass to circumscribe a perfect circle around the triangle on the chalkboard.","say":"sur-kuh-MSKREYEB","hook":"CIRCUM means around + SCRIBE means write — to write a circle around something"},{"w":"inscribe","def":"carve, cut, or etch into a material or surface","ex":"The jeweler offered to inscribe a heartfelt message along the inner band of the ring, so the couple would always carry those meaningful words with them wherever they traveled.","say":"ih-NSKREYEB","hook":"To INSCRIBE is to write IN — a SCRIBE writes IN to stone, starts with IN not EN."},{"w":"subscribe","def":"offer to buy, as of stocks and shares","ex":"The broker subscribed 500 shares","say":"suh-BSKREYEB","hook":"To subSCRIBE is to write your name UNDER a publication — a SCRIBE signs below."},{"w":"conscript","def":"someone who is drafted into military service","ex":"The men were conscripted","say":"KAH-nskrihpt","hook":"A conSCRIPT is literally WRITTEN into military service — the script is the enlistment paper."},{"w":"prescribe","def":"issue commands or orders for","ex":"The doctor decided to prescribe a mild antibiotic to treat the stubborn infection.","say":"pruh-SKREYEB","hook":"A doctor PRESCRIBES by writing — PRE+SCRIBE — the SCRIBE writes the order before you take the pill."},{"w":"proscribe","def":"command against","ex":"I forbid you to call me late at night","say":"proh-SKREYEB","hook":"PROscribe PROHIBITS — both start with PRO; a doctor PREscribes (pre = before), but a ruler PROscribes (bans publicly)."},{"w":"postscript","def":"a note appended to a letter after the signature","ex":"In the postscript of her letter, she added a quick note reminding him to feed the cat.","say":"POH-skrihpt","hook":"A POSTSCRIPT is written (SCRIPT) after (POST) — don't forget the S in SCRIPT."},{"w":"nondescript","def":"lacking distinguishing characteristics or a distinctive character","ex":"women dressed in nondescript clothes","say":"n-AH-n-d-ih-s-k-r-IH-p-t","hook":"NONDESCRIPT has 'de' not 'di' — something nondescript is DE-void of description."},{"w":"scriptural","def":"of or pertaining to or contained in or in accordance with the Bible","ex":"The minister's sermon was filled with scriptural references, quoting passages from the Bible to support each point and helping the congregation connect ancient teachings to everyday modern life.","say":"SKRIH-pcher-uhl","hook":"SCRIPTURAL contains SCRIPT+URE+AL — holy writing wrapped in three layers of meaning."},{"w":"ascribe","def":"attribute or credit to","ex":"Many people ascribe the invention of the telephone to Alexander Graham Bell, though others believe different inventors deserve credit.","say":"uh-SKREYEB","hook":"aSCRIBE — a SCRIBE writes who deserves credit"}]},{"title":"port (carry)","category":"Latin Root Families","difficulty":"easy","concept":"Latin portare = to carry. One of the clearest-meaning roots in English — every port- word involves carrying, moving, or transporting something, physically or metaphorically.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>DEPORTMENT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> duh-PAW-rtmuhnt\n<b>Spell it.</b> D · E · P · O · R · T · M · E · N · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> duh-PAW-rtmuhnt\n<b>Syllables.</b> de · port · ment\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [dih=DE] [PORT=PORT] [ment=MENT]\n<b>Exception.</b> de- = completely; -port- = carry; -ment = noun; the way one carries oneself = manner; stress: dih-PORT-ment\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> French déporter = to conduct oneself, from Latin deportare = to carry","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Latin portare = to carry. Import (in- = in + port) = carry in from another country. Export (ex- = out) = carry out to another country. Transport (trans- = across) = carry across. Report (re- = back) = carry back (news). Support (sub- = under) = carry from under = hold up."},{"title":"Portfolio & Portmanteau","body":"Portfolio (port- + foglio = leaf/sheet) = something that carries papers/documents. Portmanteau (port- + manteau = cloak) = a large suitcase that carries cloaks. Also (Lewis Carroll): a portmanteau word = a word that carries two words inside it (smog = smoke + fog)."},{"title":"Deportment & Comport","body":"Deportment (de- + port- + -ment) = the way one carries oneself = bearing, posture, manner. Comport (com- = together) = carry together = behave in a certain way. Comportment = behavior and bearing. Disport (dis- = away) = carry oneself away in play = amuse oneself."},{"title":"Rapport — the Hidden port","body":"Rapport (re- + French apporter = bring back + port) = carrying feeling back = a sympathetic relationship. The -ort at the end shows the port- root through French. Rapport = R-A-P-P-O-R-T (double-p from French assimilation). A frequently misspelled word because the port root is not obvious."},{"title":"Spelling port- Words","body":"Transport = T-R-A-N-S-P-O-R-T. Deportment = D-E-P-O-R-T-M-E-N-T. Rapport = R-A-P-P-O-R-T (double-p, silent final t!). Portfolio = P-O-R-T-F-O-L-I-O. Portmanteau = P-O-R-T-M-A-N-T-E-A-U (the -eau French ending after the Latin port-). Root + French ending in one word."}],"words":[{"w":"import","def":"commodities (goods or services) bought from a foreign country","ex":"the lead role was played by an import from Sweden","say":"ih-MPAWRT","hook":"IMPORT — goods come IN through a PORT; IM replaces IN before 'p,' like goods docking at the harbor."},{"w":"export","def":"commodities (goods or services) sold to a foreign country","ex":"we export less than we import and have a negative trade balance","say":"EH-kspawrt","hook":"To EXport is to EXIT through the PORT with your goods."},{"w":"transport","def":"something that serves as a means of transportation","ex":"listening to sweet music in a perfect rapture","say":"tra-NSPAWRT","hook":"A PORT is where ships carry cargo — transPORT carries things across."},{"w":"report","def":"a written document describing the findings of some individual or group","ex":"this accords with the recent study by Hill and Dale","say":"ree-PAWRT","hook":"A reporter CARRIES news BACK to you — re+PORT like a porter carrying luggage back."},{"w":"support","def":"the activity of providing for or maintaining by supplying with money or necessities","ex":"his support kept the family together","say":"suh-PAWRT","hook":"A SUPPORTer carries you from under — like a PORT-er who lifts from below (SUB)."},{"w":"portfolio","def":"a large, flat, thin case for carrying loose papers or drawings or maps; usually leather","ex":"he remembered her because she was carrying a large portfolio","say":"paw-RTFOH-lee-oh","hook":"A portFOLIO carries your FOLIOs — sheets of paper you PORTA (carry) around to show your work."},{"w":"portmanteau","def":"a new word formed by joining two others and combining their meanings","ex":"Lewis Carroll was a master of the portmanteau, blending 'smoke' and 'fog' into the word 'smog.'","say":"PAW-rtmah-ntoh","hook":"A portmanteau CARRIES two words like a bag carries two halves"},{"w":"deportment","def":"the manner in which a person behaves toward others; conduct and bearing","ex":"The finishing school emphasized deportment, teaching students to walk with confidence and speak with courtesy.","say":"duh-PAW-rtmuhnt","hook":"dePORTment is about how you PORT or carry yourself in public"},{"w":"comport","def":"behave well or properly","ex":"The children must learn to behave","say":"kuh-MPAWRT","hook":"Comport yourself well — carry yourself together: 'port' like a porter who carries things with dignity."},{"w":"rapport","def":"is relation or connection","ex":"The teacher quickly built a warm rapport with her students by listening to their ideas.","say":"r-a-p-AW-r","hook":"Good RAPPORT carries a silent T at the end — like a French diplomat, elegantly quiet: R-A-P-P-O-R-T."},{"w":"disport","def":"occupy in an agreeable, entertaining or pleasant fashion","ex":"The children disport themselves gleefully at the beach, splashing and chasing waves all afternoon.","say":"dis-PORT","hook":"To disport is to carry yourself away for fun — think of a PORT where ships escape to play."},{"w":"portable","def":"a small light typewriter; usually with a case in which it can be carried","ex":"a portable television set","say":"PAW-rtuh-buhl","hook":"PORTABLE contains PORT — you can carry it to any PORT in the world; remember -able not -ible."},{"w":"porter","def":"a person employed to carry luggage and supplies","ex":"The helpful porter loaded all five suitcases onto his cart and led us swiftly to our hotel room.","say":"PAW-rter","hook":"A PORTER carries your bags at the PORT — the -ER at the end means he's the one doing the carrying."},{"w":"importation","def":"the commercial activity of buying and bringing in goods from a foreign country","ex":"The new trade policy restricted the importation of foreign steel to protect jobs in the domestic manufacturing industry.","say":"ih-mpaw-RTAY-shuhn","hook":"IMPORTATION — a NATION that does IMPORTATION brings goods IN through its ports; -ATION seals the deal."}]},{"title":"miss / mit (send)","category":"Latin Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin mittere = to send. It appears as -miss- in nouns and -mit in verbs — the same root, two faces. From mission to remit, dismiss to submit, sending is this root's business.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>INTERMISSION</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ih-nter-MIH-shuhn\n<b>Spell it.</b> I · N · T · E · R · M · I · S · S · I · O · N\n<b>Say it again.</b> ih-nter-MIH-shuhn\n<b>Syllables.</b> ih · nter · mih · shah · n\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [in=IN] [ter=TER] [MISH=MIS] [un=SION]\n<b>Exception.</b> inter- = between; -mission = a sending; -sion not -ssion here; stress: in-ter-MISH-un\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin inter = between + mittere = to send/let go","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Latin mittere = to send. Transmit (trans- = across) = send across. Omit (ob- = away) = send away = leave out. Emit (e- = out) = send out. Remit (re- = back) = send back (money). Submit (sub- = under) = send oneself under the authority of. Verb form = -mit."},{"title":"-mission = The Noun Form","body":"mittere → missio (noun). Permission (per- + mission) = sending through = official allowance. Intermission = a sending between acts = a break. Missionary = one sent on a mission. Emission = something sent out. Commission (com- + mission) = sent together = an official duty."},{"title":"Missile & Message","body":"Missile = missilis = something sent = a projectile. Message = missaticum = something sent = communication. Messenger = the person who sends/carries the message. All from mittere. Missive = a formal written message that is \"sent.\" Premise (pre- + mise) = something sent before = a proposition laid before argument."},{"title":"Dismiss & Remissive","body":"Dismiss (dis- + miss) = send apart = discharge. Remissive (re- + miss) = sending back = forgiving. Irremissible = cannot be sent away = unforgivable. Commissar = com- + miss- = official sent with a commission. Demise (de- + mise) = sent down = the end/death of something."},{"title":"Spelling -miss-/-mit-","body":"The verb always uses -mit: commit, submit, transmit, permit, admit. The noun always uses -mission or -missive: commission, permission, submission, admission. When -mit is stressed before -ing/-ed/-er, double the t: commit → committed, transmit → transmitting, permit → permitted."}],"words":[{"w":"transmit","def":"transfer to another","ex":"communicate a disease","say":"tra-NZMIHT","hook":"transMIT sends just one T when you MITt the signal — only double T when adding suffixes."},{"w":"omit","def":"prevent from being included or considered or accepted","ex":"The bad results were excluded from the report","say":"oh-MIHT","hook":"OMIT has just ONE 'm' — don't add an extra letter to a word that means to leave things out!"},{"w":"emit","def":"expel (gases or odors)","ex":"The ozone layer blocks some harmful rays which the sun emits","say":"ih-MIHT","hook":"To EMIT is to let it OUT — one m, like one exit door."},{"w":"remit","def":"the topic that a person, committee, or piece of research is expected to deal with or has authority to deal with","ex":"they set up a group with a remit to suggest ways for strengthening family life","say":"ree-MIHT","hook":"reMIT has one M — you send (MIT) something back RE-once, not twice."},{"w":"submit","def":"refer for judgment or consideration","ex":"The lawyers submitted the material to the court","say":"suh-BMIHT","hook":"subMIT: you SEND IT under the judge's authority."},{"w":"permission","def":"approval to do something","ex":"Before leaving campus for the field trip, every student had to have a signed permission slip from a parent.","say":"per-MIH-shuhn","hook":"perMISSion: you MISS your chance if you don't get it — double S like 'please, please'"},{"w":"intermission","def":"the act of suspending activity temporarily","ex":"During intermission, the audience rushed to the lobby to grab snacks before the second act began.","say":"ih-nter-MIH-shuhn","hook":"During intermISSION, the actress MISSED the stage — double S, double the break."},{"w":"missionary","def":"someone who attempts to convert others to a particular doctrine or program","ex":"The missionary learned the local language so she could better communicate with the community.","say":"MIH-shuh-neh-ree","hook":"A MISSIONARY carries a MISSION on their back—spell it just like mission, then add -ary."},{"w":"emission","def":"the act of emitting; causing to flow forth","ex":"the discharge of pus","say":"ih-MIH-shuhn","hook":"EMISSION has one M — gases EMIT with one burst, one M, flowing out."},{"w":"commission","def":"a special group delegated to consider some matter;  - Milton Berle","ex":"a committee is a group that keeps minutes and loses hours","say":"kuh-MIH-shuhn","hook":"A comMISSION sends (MISS = mittere) people on a MISSION — double M, double S!"},{"w":"missile","def":"a rocket carrying a warhead of conventional or nuclear explosives; may be ballistic or directed by remote control","ex":"The military launched a test missile that streaked across the sky at incredible speed.","say":"MIH-suhl","hook":"A missile is sent — MISS + ILE, like a projectile that misses nothing."},{"w":"message","def":"a communication (usually brief) that is written or spoken or signaled","ex":"he sent a three-word message","say":"MEH-suhj","hook":"MESSAGE ends in -AGE, not -EGE — think 'the messenger's AGE' to lock in that ending."},{"w":"dismiss","def":"bar from attention or consideration","ex":"She dismissed his advances","say":"dih-SMIHS","hook":"To disMISS is to send away — double the S at the end, because you're sending them away twice as fast."},{"w":"demise","def":"the time when something ends","ex":"it was the death of all his plans","say":"dih-MEYEZ","hook":"At her DEMISE, things were DE-placed and sent away — the 's' not 'z' keeps it French-elegant."},{"w":"commit","def":"perform an act, usually with a negative connotation","ex":"Every member of the science team had to commit to attending all weekend sessions in the lab, because missing even one meeting could delay the entire experiment by several important weeks.","say":"kuh-MIHT","hook":"To comMIT you must double up your M — two M's show you're doubly dedicated!"},{"w":"admittance","def":"the right to enter","ex":"the surgery was performed on his second admission to the clinic","say":"uh-DMIH-tuhns","hook":"ADMITTANCE doubles the T like a bouncer checking twice before letting you ENTER."}]},{"title":"vert / vers (turn)","category":"Latin Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin vertere = to turn. This root appears in personality words, scientific terms, and everyday vocabulary. It is one of the most versatile (from versatilis = turning easily!) roots in Latin.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>SUBVERT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> suh-BVURT\n<b>Spell it.</b> S · U · B · V · E · R · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> suh-BVURT\n<b>Syllables.</b> sah · bver · t\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [sub=SUB] [VURT=VERT]\n<b>Exception.</b> sub- = under; -vert = turn; stress: sub-VURT; noun form is subVERSION; adj form is subVERSIVE\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin sub = under + vertere = to turn","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Latin vertere = to turn. Invert (in- = into) = turn inside out. Divert (di- = away) = turn away. Revert (re- = back) = turn back to a previous state. Convert (con- = thoroughly) = turn completely = change. Subvert (sub- = under) = turn from under = undermine. Avert (a- = away) = turn away from = prevent."},{"title":"vers- Form (Noun/Adjective)","body":"The verb form uses -vert; the noun and adjective use -vers-. Subvert → subversion → subversive. Invert → inversion → inverse. Convert → conversion → conversive (rare). Diverse (di- + vers) = turned in many directions = varied. Universe (uni- + vers-) = turned into one = all things as one."},{"title":"Introvert & Extrovert","body":"Introvert (intro- = inward + vert) = one who turns inward. Extrovert (extra- = outward) = one who turns outward. Ambivert (ambi- = both) = turns both ways. Controvert = to turn against = to dispute. Inadvertent (in- + ad- + vert) = not turned toward = accidental/unintentional."},{"title":"Anniversary & Versatile","body":"Anniversary (annus = year + vers- = turning + -ary) = the turning of the year = yearly return. Versatile (versatilis = easily turning) = able to turn to many tasks. Adverse (ad- + vers-) = turned against = unfavorable. Traverse (tra- + vers-) = turn across = to cross."},{"title":"Spelling vert/vers Words","body":"The verb form always uses -vert: convert, subvert, invert. Nouns use -version: conversion, subversion, inversion. Anniversary = A-N-N-I-V-E-R-S-A-R-Y (double-n from annus). Universe = U-N-I-V-E-R-S-E. Versatile = V-E-R-S-A-T-I-L-E. Inadvertent = I-N-A-D-V-E-R-T-E-N-T."}],"words":[{"w":"invert","def":"make an inversion (in a musical composition)","ex":"here the theme is inverted","say":"ih-NVURT","hook":"To INVERT is to turn IN the VERT(ical) — flip it inside out, like an umbrella in wind."},{"w":"divert","def":"To divert something means to cause it to change direction or turn away from its original course.","ex":"The play amused the ladies","say":"deye-VURT","hook":"To diVERT is to turn a VERTical path sideways — the V turns the road."},{"w":"revert","def":"go back to a previous state","ex":"We reverted to the old rules","say":"rih-VURT","hook":"To reVERT is to turn (VERT) back again—a vertebra pivots just like this word."},{"w":"convert","def":"a person who has been converted to another religious or political belief","ex":"We converted from 220 to 110 Volt","say":"KAH-nvert","hook":"To CONVERT is to TURN — CON+VERT, where VERT means turn in Latin."},{"w":"subvert","def":"cause the downfall of; of rulers","ex":"The Czar was overthrown","say":"suh-BVURT","hook":"To subVERT is to turn something UNDER — VERT means turn, remember to spell it with E."},{"w":"versatile","def":"having great diversity or variety; able to adapt to many different functions or activities","ex":"The versatile athlete excelled at soccer, swimming, and gymnastics, making her the most valuable member of the school's sports program.","say":"VUR-suh-tuhl","hook":"verSATile people can SAT(isfy) many roles."},{"w":"anniversary","def":"the date on which an event occurred in some previous year (or the celebration of it)","ex":"The couple celebrated their silver anniversary with a romantic dinner at the restaurant where they had their first date.","say":"a-nuh-VUR-ser-ee","hook":"An anniversARY marks the year (anni) turning (vers) — end it with -ARY, like a diary marking the date."},{"w":"universe","def":"everything that exists anywhere","ex":"they study the evolution of the universe","say":"YOO-nuh-vurs","hook":"The UNIVERSE is one big VERSE — UNI-VERSE, spelled with a V not a C."},{"w":"controversy","def":"a contentious speech act; a dispute where there is strong disagreement","ex":"they were involved in a violent argument","say":"KAH-ntruh-vur-see","hook":"ContrOversy has an O — a contrOversy always ends with someone saying 'Oh, we disagree!'"},{"w":"introvert","def":"(psychology) a person who tends to shrink from social contacts and to become preoccupied with their own thoughts","ex":"some organs can invaginate","say":"IH-ntroh-vurt","hook":"An introvert TURNS (vert) INWARD (intro)—the spelling literally describes the personality."},{"w":"extrovert","def":"(psychology) a person concerned more with practical realities than with inner thoughts and feelings","ex":"As a natural extrovert, Marcus gained energy from being around people and would grow restless if he spent too much time alone.","say":"EH-kstruh-vurt","hook":"An EXTROVERT turns OUTWARD: EXTRO (out) + VERT (turn) — they face the world, not inward."},{"w":"ambivert","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"inadvertent","def":"happening by chance or unexpectedly or unintentionally","ex":"with an inadvertent gesture she swept the vase off the table","say":"ih-nuh-DVUR-tuhnt","hook":"inadVERTent — you didn't VERT (turn) your attention to it, so the mistake was accidental."},{"w":"adverse","def":"contrary to your interests or welfare","ex":"adverse circumstances","say":"a-DVURS","hook":"ADVERSE conditions turn AGAINST you — don't drop the AD: 'averse' is a different word, so keep the AD to turn it adverse."},{"w":"traverse","def":"to travel or pass across, over, or through; also a horizontal beam or barrier extending across something","ex":"The explorers had to traverse a rickety rope bridge to reach the waterfall on the other side of the jungle gorge.","say":"TRA-vers","hook":"TRAVERSE means to cross — think TRAVEL + VERSE, crossing a poem line by line."},{"w":"aversion","def":"a feeling of intense dislike","ex":"averting her gaze meant that she was angry","say":"uh-VUR-zhuhn","hook":"An aVERSION turns you AWAY — picture VERSing someone you hate and turning your back."}]},{"title":"spec / spect / spic (see / look)","category":"Latin Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin specere = to look. This root appears in vision words, philosophy words, and character words. The -spic- form is rarer and harder to recognize — making it a championship bee favorite.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>CIRCUMSPECT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> SUR-kuh-mspehkt\n<b>Spell it.</b> C · I · R · C · U · M · S · P · E · C · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> SUR-kuh-mspehkt\n<b>Syllables.</b> ser · kah · mspeh · kt\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [SUR=CIR] [kum=CUM] [spekt=SPECT]\n<b>Exception.</b> circum- = around; -spect = look; look around carefully before acting; stress: SUR-kum-spekt\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin circumspicere = to look around","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Latin specere = to look. Spectacle (spec- + -acle) = something to look at. Prospect (pro- = forward + spect) = looking forward = future possibility. Retrospect (retro- = backward + spect) = looking backward = hindsight. Circumspect (circum- = around) = looking around carefully = cautious. Inspect = look into."},{"title":"-spic- Form (harder)","body":"Conspicuous (con- + spicere) = looked at together = clearly visible. Perspicacious (per- + spic- + -acious) = looking thoroughly through = sharply insightful. Inauspicious (in- + auspicium = bird-watching) = not looking favorable. Auspicious (auspex = bird-watcher = Roman divination) = looking favorable."},{"title":"Species & Specimen","body":"Species = spec- = what is looked at/seen = a kind (as classified by sight). Specimen = spec- = something to be looked at = a sample. Specious = spec- = appearing good to the eye but actually wrong = superficially plausible. Specter = spec- = something seen = a ghost."},{"title":"Speculate & Respect","body":"Speculate = look at the possibilities = to consider or trade on uncertain outcomes. Respect (re- + spect) = look back upon = esteem. Suspect (sub- + spect) = look under = view with distrust. Disrespect = refuse to look upon with honor. Introspection (intro- + spect) = looking within = self-examination."},{"title":"Spelling spec/spect/spic","body":"Circumspect = C-I-R-C-U-M-S-P-E-C-T. Perspicacious = P-E-R-S-P-I-C-A-C-I-O-U-S (-spic- form). Conspicuous = C-O-N-S-P-I-C-U-O-U-S (-spic- form). Auspicious = A-U-S-P-I-C-I-O-U-S (from auspex = one who looks at birds). Specious = S-P-E-C-I-O-U-S. The -ic- in -spicious words is the key spelling cluster."}],"words":[{"w":"spectacle","def":"something or someone seen (especially a notable or unusual sight)","ex":"the tragic spectacle of cripples trying to escape","say":"SPEH-ktuh-kuhl","hook":"A SPECTACLE is something worth SPECTing (looking at) — spot the SPECT inside."},{"w":"prospect","def":"the possibility of future success","ex":"his prospects as a writer are excellent","say":"PRAH-spehkt","hook":"A PROSPECT is what you see when you look FORWARD—proSPECT, LOOK ahead."},{"w":"retrospect","def":"contemplation of things past","ex":"In retrospect, the team realized they should have practiced their presentation more carefully before standing in front of the judges, because several important points were left out entirely.","say":"REH-truh-spehkt","hook":"In RETROSPECT you look BACK — retro(back)+spect(look), like a spectator watching a replay."},{"w":"circumspect","def":"heedful of potential consequences","ex":"The new employee was circumspect about sharing her opinions at meetings until she better understood the company culture and felt confident that her ideas would be well received.","say":"SUR-kuh-mspehkt","hook":"CircumSPECT — INSPECT all around before acting — both end in -SPECT."},{"w":"inspect","def":"look over carefully","ex":"Please inspect your father's will carefully","say":"ih-NSPEHKT","hook":"inSPECT — a SPECK is tiny, but an inspector looks IN for every last speck."},{"w":"conspicuous","def":"obvious to the eye or mind","ex":"a tower conspicuous at a great distance","say":"kuh-NSPIH-kyoo-uhs","hook":"CONSpICUOUS has SPY in spirit — something so visible a spy could spot it instantly; don't forget the U before OUS."},{"w":"perspicacious","def":"acutely insightful and wise","ex":"The perspicacious young detective noticed a tiny mud stain on the suspect's shoe that everyone else had overlooked.","say":"per-spuh-KAY-shuhs","hook":"PER-SPIC-acious: someone who sees (SPIC) through everything"},{"w":"auspicious","def":"auguring favorable circumstances and good luck","ex":"an auspicious beginning for the campaign","say":"ah-SPIH-shuhs","hook":"Auspicious has a 'c' before '-ious' — think: the omen was speCial, so keep that 'c' in auspICious."},{"w":"inauspicious","def":"not auspicious; boding ill","ex":"adverse circumstances","say":"ih-now-SPIH-shihs","hook":"In an inauspicious start, the bird looked away — no good omen there."},{"w":"species","def":"(biology) taxonomic group whose members can interbreed","ex":"a species of molecule","say":"SPEE-sheez","hook":"SPECIES — SPECIal ES at the end, because every species is a special set."},{"w":"specimen","def":"an example regarded as typical of its class","ex":"The biology teacher passed around a perfectly preserved beetle specimen so that every student could examine its iridescent shell.","say":"SPEH-suh-muhn","hook":"specIMEN — the specimen is often studied by science MEN and women; ends in -MEN not -MAN"},{"w":"specious","def":"is apparently good or right though lacking real merit","ex":"The student's specious argument that studying during commercials counted as a full hour of homework review sounded convincing at first glance, but his parents quickly saw through the flawed and self-serving logic.","say":"s-p-EE-sh-uh-s","hook":"SPECIOus — it LOOKS good on the SURFACE (from species = appearance) but it's false"},{"w":"specter","def":"a mental representation of some haunting experience","ex":"he looked like he had seen a ghost","say":"SPEH-kter","hook":"A SPECTER appears before your eyes — SPECTer has SPECT like spectacle, and ghosts are quite a spectacle."},{"w":"speculate","def":"to believe especially on uncertain or tentative grounds","ex":"The detectives began to speculate about who had left muddy footprints across the museum floor.","say":"SPEH-kyuh-layt","hook":"SPECulate with a SPEC-ial telescope—you're just looking, not certain"},{"w":"respect","def":"(usually preceded by 'in') a detail or point","ex":"In every respect, the new student exceeded the teacher's expectations with her thoughtful essays.","say":"rih-SPEHKT","hook":"RESPECT — you look (SPECT) back at someone with admiration"},{"w":"introspection","def":"the contemplation of your own thoughts and desires and conduct","ex":"After the argument with her best friend, Maya spent the evening in quiet introspection, wondering if she had been too harsh.","say":"ih-ntruh-SPEH-kshuhn","hook":"Introspection is an internal inspection—spot INSPECTION hiding inside with an intro twist."}]},{"title":"ten / tain / tent (hold)","category":"Latin Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin tenere = to hold. This root appears as ten-, -tain-, and -tent- — three forms of the same root. From tenacious holding to detention, the idea of holding is constant.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PERTINACIOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> —\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · E · R · T · I · N · A · C · I · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> —\n<b>Syllables.</b> p · e · r · t · i · n · a · c · i · o · u · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [per=PER] [tih=TI] [NAY=NA] [shus=CIOUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> per- = thoroughly; -tenax- = holding; -ious suffix; per-tih-NAY-shus; related to pertinent and tenacious\n<b>Origin.</b> —\n<b>Root.</b> —","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Latin tenere = to hold → ten-, -tain-, -tent-. Tenacious = tenax = holding on firmly = not giving up. Detain (de- + tain) = hold away = keep from going. Retain (re- + tain) = hold back = keep. Contain (con- + tain) = hold together. Abstain (abs- + tain) = hold away from = refrain voluntarily."},{"title":"-tent- Form","body":"Content (con- + tent) = held together = what is inside/contained (noun) or satisfied (adj). Intent (in- + tent) = held inward = a purpose. Extent (ex- + tent) = held outward = the range/scope. Detention = the state of being held = kept from leaving. Attention (ad- + tent) = held toward = focused concentration."},{"title":"Tenure & Lieutenant","body":"Tenure (ten- + -ure) = the holding of a position = a period of holding office. Lieutenant (lieu = place + tenant = one who holds) = one who holds the place of the commander. Tenant (ten- + -ant) = one who holds a property = a renter. All from tenere = to hold."},{"title":"Pertinacious & Pertinent","body":"Pertinacious (per- + tenax) = holding on thoroughly = stubbornly persistent. Pertinent (per- + tinere) = held toward = directly relating to the matter. Both from per- + ten/tenax. Impertinent = im- + pertinent = not relating to the matter = rude (because you're NOT keeping to what's relevant)."},{"title":"Spelling ten/tain/tent Words","body":"Tenacious = T-E-N-A-C-I-O-U-S (-acious suffix). Pertinacious = P-E-R-T-I-N-A-C-I-O-U-S. Lieutenant = L-I-E-U-T-E-N-A-N-T (note the French lieu = place). Abstain = A-B-S-T-A-I-N (-ai- vowel pair). Detention = D-E-T-E-N-T-I-O-N. The three forms -ten-/-tain-/-tent- all mean \"hold\" but look different in words."}],"words":[{"w":"tenacious","def":"means holding fast","ex":"Despite failing her driving test twice, Leila remained tenacious in her determination to pass, practicing parallel parking every single evening until she could execute it smoothly, confidently, and without a single cone knocked over.","say":"t-uh-n-AY-sh-uh-s","hook":"Tenacious holds fast to every letter — especially that sneaky I before OUS: ten-A-CI-OUS."},{"w":"detain","def":"deprive of freedom; take into confinement","ex":"Please stay the bloodshed!","say":"dih-TAYN","hook":"To deTAIN is to hold someone in conTAINment — spot TAIN (hold) right in the middle."},{"w":"retain","def":"hold back within","ex":"This soil retains water","say":"rih-TAYN","hook":"RETAIN — re + TAIN, you hold TIGHT with a T, keeping everything in place."},{"w":"contain","def":"include or contain; have as a component","ex":"A totally new idea is comprised in this paper","say":"kuh-NTAYN","hook":"conTAIN — to CONTAIN is to TAIN (hold) things together inside."},{"w":"abstain","def":"refrain from voting","ex":"I abstain from alcohol","say":"uh-BSTAYN","hook":"AbsTAIN — hold yourself away, like a stain you refuse to make: ends in -a-i-n."},{"w":"intent","def":"an anticipated outcome that is intended or that guides your planned actions","ex":"his intent was to provide a new translation","say":"ih-NTEHNT","hook":"A TENT is pitched with inTENT — the word TENT is hiding inside inTENT."},{"w":"extent","def":"the point or degree to which something extends","ex":"the extent of the damage","say":"ih-KSTEHNT","hook":"A TENT stretches out — the exTENT of the campsite depends on how far the TENT reaches."},{"w":"detention","def":"a state of being confined (usually for a short time)","ex":"After talking during the fire drill, both students received after-school detention and had to write a one-page essay on campus safety rules.","say":"dih-TEH-nshuhn","hook":"DETENTION is when they DETAIN you—share the same root, TAIN/TEN = hold"},{"w":"attention","def":"the process whereby a person concentrates on some features of the environment to the (relative) exclusion of others","ex":"no medical care was required","say":"uh-TEH-nshuhn","hook":"Pay ATTENTION: it ends in '-tion' not '-sion' — TIONs of focus on that spelling!"},{"w":"tenure","def":"the term during which some position is held","ex":"She was tenured after she published her book","say":"TEH-nyer","hook":"TENURE lets you HOLD your job — one N, and it ends in -URE like SECURE."},{"w":"lieutenant","def":"is a military rank","ex":"The young lieutenant led his squad bravely through the difficult terrain, keeping everyone calm under pressure.","say":"l-oo-t-EH-n-uh-n-t","hook":"A LIEUTENANT holds the place — LIEU(place)+TENANT(holder); the TENANT holds the LIEU."},{"w":"tenant","def":"someone who pays rent to use land or a building or a car that is owned by someone else","ex":"the landlord can evict a tenant who doesn't pay the rent","say":"TEH-nuhnt","hook":"A tenant holds a single key — and tenant has a single N, not double."},{"w":"pertinacious","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"pertinent","def":"having precise or logical relevance to the matter at hand","ex":"a list of articles pertinent to the discussion","say":"PUR-tih-nihnt","hook":"PertinENT ends in -ent not -ant — ENTer only relevant facts."},{"w":"impertinent","def":"characterized by a lightly pert and exuberant quality","ex":"a certain irreverent gaiety and ease of manner","say":"ih-MPUR-tuh-nuhnt","hook":"An impertinent remark does NOT pertain — 'pertinent' hides right inside the word."},{"w":"abstinence","def":"the trait of abstaining (especially from alcohol)","ex":"The athlete's strict abstinence from sugary drinks helped her maintain peak performance throughout the entire season.","say":"A-bstuh-nuhns","hook":"Abstinence ends in -ence (not -ance) — remember: it takes diligENCE to practice abstinENCE."}]},{"title":"cred (believe)","category":"Latin Root Families","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Latin credere = to believe. One of the most humanly important roots — it creates vocabulary about trust, faith, and their betrayal. From credulous believers to incredible claims, cred- covers the full range.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>INCREDULOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ih-NKREH-juh-luhs\n<b>Spell it.</b> I · N · C · R · E · D · U · L · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> ih-NKREH-juh-luhs\n<b>Syllables.</b> ih · nkreh · jhah · lah · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [in=IN] [KREJ=CRED] [yuh=U] [lus=LOUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> in- = not; -cred- = believe; -ulous = full of (somewhat); in-KREJ-yuh-lus; 4 syllables\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin credulus = believing easily","cards":[{"title":"The Root","body":"Latin credere = to believe. Credulous = full of believing = too easily believing = gullible. Incredulous (in- + credulous) = not believing = deeply skeptical. Incredible (in- + credible) = not believable = extraordinary. Credibility = worthy of being believed. Discredit = remove believability."},{"title":"Creed & Credentials","body":"Creed = what one believes = a statement of beliefs. Credentials = evidence that establishes credibility = qualifications. Accredit (ac- = toward) = give official recognition = certify. Accredited = officially recognized and trusted. Credit = trust given before repayment. From religious belief to bank loans — the same root."},{"title":"Miscreant — the Villain Root","body":"Miscreant (mis- = wrongly + cred- = believe + -ant) = one who believes wrongly = a villain/criminal. Originally meant heretic (one who believes the wrong religion); now means a wrongdoer generally. The etymology is theological; the usage is now general. A surprisingly dark corner of the cred- family."},{"title":"Credence & Recreant","body":"Credence = the belief given to something = acceptance as true. Give credence to = treat as believable. Recreant (re- + cred- + -ant) = one who re-believes = surrendering to the enemy = cowardly traitor. Credo = a personal statement of beliefs. Credulity = the tendency to believe too easily."},{"title":"Spelling cred- Words","body":"Incredulous = I-N-C-R-E-D-U-L-O-U-S (-ulous not -ious). Credentials = C-R-E-D-E-N-T-I-A-L-S. Miscreant = M-I-S-C-R-E-A-N-T (-ean- not -een-). Recreant = R-E-C-R-E-A-N-T. Credence = C-R-E-D-E-N-C-E (-ence because from -ent adjective form). Incredible = I-N-C-R-E-D-I-B-L-E (-ible — Latin stem)."}],"words":[{"w":"credulous","def":"disposed to believe on little evidence","ex":"the gimmick would convince none but the most credulous","say":"KREH-juh-luhs","hook":"A CREDULOUS person believes too EASILY — the '-ulous' suffix stuffs them full of misplaced trust."},{"w":"incredulous","def":"not disposed or willing to believe; unbelieving","ex":"Mia was incredulous when her brother claimed he had finished a week's worth of homework in just twenty minutes.","say":"ih-NKREH-juh-luhs","hook":"An INCREDULOUS person is so full of doubt they raise their brow — remember the -ous ending."},{"w":"incredible","def":"beyond belief or understanding","ex":"It seemed incredible that a twelve-year-old girl had composed an entire symphony, but the audience rose to their feet in thunderous applause when she stood to take her bow.","say":"ih-NKREH-duh-buhl","hook":"INCREDIBLE ends in -ible, not -able: I can't believe the -ible ending either!"},{"w":"credibility","def":"the quality of being believable or trustworthy","ex":"The reporter lost credibility when it was discovered that she had made up several key facts in her story.","say":"kreh-duh-BIH-lih-tee","hook":"CREDIBILITY uses '-ibility' not '-ability' — I BELIEVE it, and 'i' comes before 'b.'"},{"w":"discredit","def":"the state of being held in low esteem","ex":"your actions will bring discredit to your name","say":"dih-SKREH-duht","hook":"disCREDIT destroys CREDIT — one D, one T, trust gone."},{"w":"creed","def":"any system of principles or beliefs","ex":"The school's creed emphasized honesty, respect, and responsibility in all actions.","say":"KREED","hook":"A CREED is what you HEED — both rhyme, and you live by what you believe."},{"w":"credentials","def":"a document attesting to the truth of certain stated facts","ex":"The journalist checked the scientist's credentials before including her quotes in the article.","say":"kruh-DEH-nshuhlz","hook":"Show your CREDENTIALS — the '-tials' ending signals official Latin authority."},{"w":"accredit","def":"grant credentials to","ex":"The Regents officially recognized the new educational institution","say":"uh-kreh-duht","hook":"acCREDIT contains CREDIT — double 'c' because you need twice the trust to be accredited."},{"w":"miscreant","def":"a person without moral scruples","ex":"The sheriff finally tracked down the miscreant who had been stealing from local farmers for months.","say":"MIH-skree-uhnt","hook":"A MISCREANT mis-CREATES chaos — spot CREATE in the middle; the villain CREATES misery."},{"w":"credence","def":"the mental attitude that something is believable and should be accepted as true","ex":"he gave credence to the gossip","say":"KREE-duhns","hook":"Give CREDENCE — end it with '-ence' just like 'evidence,' another word about proof."},{"w":"recreant","def":"an abject coward","ex":"some provinces had proved recreant","say":"REK-ree-unt","hook":"A RECREANT is a CREep who goes ANT-running away from a fight."},{"w":"credo","def":"any system of principles or beliefs","ex":"Her personal credo was simple: treat others the way you wish to be treated.","say":"KRAY-doh","hook":"CREDO means 'I believe' in Latin — one 'e,' one belief, simple and direct."},{"w":"credulity","def":"tendency to believe readily","ex":"The con artist relied on the credulity of his victims, who never thought to question his wild claims.","say":"krih-DOO-luh-tee","hook":"CREDULITY — a person full of credulity is CREDULOUS and gullible; hear 'credul' in both."},{"w":"credit","def":"recognition, acknowledgment.","ex":"give her recognition for trying","say":"KREH-duht","hook":"CREDIT starts with CRED — you need credibility to earn credit, and both start the same way."},{"w":"incredible","def":"beyond belief or understanding","ex":"It seemed incredible that a twelve-year-old girl had composed an entire symphony, but the audience rose to their feet in thunderous applause when she stood to take her bow.","say":"ih-NKREH-duh-buhl","hook":"INCREDIBLE ends in -ible, not -able: I can't believe the -ible ending either!"}]},{"title":"Silent kn- / gn- / wr- (Old English)","category":"Spelling Rules & Patterns","difficulty":"easy","concept":"These initial consonant clusters come from Old English and Norse. The first consonant was once pronounced — you can still hear it in German (Knabe = boy, schreiben = to write). English pronunciation shifted; spelling froze.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>WRAITH</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> RAYTH\n<b>Spell it.</b> W · R · A · I · T · H\n<b>Say it again.</b> RAYTH\n<b>Syllables.</b> w · r · a · i · t · h\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [r=WR] [ayth=AITH]\n<b>Exception.</b> wr- = /r/ only; w is completely silent; -ai- = /ay/; -th = /th/; Old English origin\n<b>Origin.</b> English\n<b>Root.</b> Scottish wraith = ghost, apparition (origin uncertain)","cards":[{"title":"WR- (silent W)","body":"wr- cluster from Old English: wraith (ghost), writhe (twist in pain), wrought (past of work), wrath (fury), wreak (inflict), wrest (twist away), wry (twisted/ironic), wring (twist tightly), wren (small bird). All start with a silent w — only the r is heard."},{"title":"KN- (silent K)","body":"Old Norse kn- cluster: knight, knave, kneel, knell (sound of a bell), knapsack, knack, knavish, knickers, knob, knoll (small hill), knot. The k was once pronounced — you can still hear it in German Knabe (boy) and Knie (knee)."},{"title":"GN- (silent G)","body":"Gnome (small creature), gnarled (twisted), gnash (grind teeth), gnu (wildebeest), gnostic (gnosis = knowledge — the g was always silent in Greek), gnaw (chew persistently), gnarl (twisted lump). The g was once pronounced in Old English — you can still hear it in Italian gnocchi."},{"title":"Why Spelling Froze","body":"English pronunciation shifted dramatically during the Great Vowel Shift (1400–1700), but printing was already standardizing spelling before the shift was complete. Spelling froze at a historical pronunciation moment; pronunciation kept moving. This is why English spelling preserves sounds that are no longer spoken."},{"title":"Bee Strategy","body":"When you hear a word starting with /r/ (like \"right\" or \"raith\") that seems literary or archaic, ask for the origin. Old English → consider wr-. When you hear /n/ at the start of a formal or medieval word, ask: could it be kn-? These two patterns explain dozens of common spelling bee words."}],"words":[{"w":"wraith","def":"a mental representation of some haunting experience","ex":"he looked like he had seen a ghost","say":"RAYTH","hook":"A wraith is like wrath made ghostly — silent, invisible anger haunting you."},{"w":"writhe","def":"to move in a twisting or contorted motion, (especially when struggling)","ex":"The prisoner writhed in discomfort","say":"RIHTH","hook":"WRITHE ends in -THE — think 'the snake writhes,' twisting its body into the shape of a TH."},{"w":"wrought","def":"exert oneself by doing mental or physical work for a purpose or out of necessity","ex":"I will work hard to improve my grades","say":"RAWT","hook":"WROUGHT iron is worked metal — remember the silent W and tricky -OUGHT by thinking 'Workers WROUGHT it.'"},{"w":"wrath","def":"intense anger (usually on an epic scale)","ex":"The coach's wrath was clear when the team showed up late to the championship game.","say":"RATH","hook":"WRATH rhymes with BATH — when someone's wrath boils over, they're steaming like a hot bath."},{"w":"wreak","def":"to inflict or execute as punishment or vengeance","ex":"I cannot work a miracle","say":"r-EE-k","hook":"WREAK havoc has a silent 'w' like WRECK — both 'wreak' and 'wreck' start with 'wr' and suggest destruction."},{"w":"wrest","def":"obtain by seizing forcibly or violently, also metaphorically","ex":"wrest the knife from his hands","say":"REHST","hook":"To WREST control you must first wrestle it away — WREST lives inside WRESTle."},{"w":"wry","def":"humorously sarcastic or mocking","ex":"With a wry smile, the comedian pointed out that the one day he forgot his umbrella was the day the city received its heaviest rainfall in decades.","say":"REYE","hook":"WRY humor is twisted — three letters, all twisted: silent W, consonant R, sneaky Y acting as a vowel."},{"w":"wring","def":"a twisting squeeze","ex":"gave the wet cloth a wring","say":"RIHNG","hook":"To WRING a towel, you need EXTRA force — that silent W is the extra effort you put in."},{"w":"wren","def":"English architect who designed more than fifty London churches (1632-1723)","ex":"A tiny wren perched on the fence post and filled the quiet morning with its surprisingly loud, melodious song.","say":"REHN","hook":"A WREN starts with a silent W — a tiny bird with a tiny hidden letter"},{"w":"knight","def":"is a mounted soldier in the Middle Ages","ex":"The Beatles were knighted","say":"n-AY-t","hook":"A KNIGHT rides into the NIGHT — both sound the same but KNIGHT wears armor spelled K-N-I-G-H-T with a hidden GH shield."},{"w":"knave","def":"a deceitful and unreliable scoundrel","ex":"The villagers warned each other not to trust the traveling merchant, calling him a knave and a cheat.","say":"NAYV","hook":"A KNAVE is a K-naughty rogue — the silent K hides his dishonesty just like he hides his tricks."},{"w":"knell","def":"the sound of a bell rung slowly to announce a death or a funeral or the end of something","ex":"As the old church bell sounded its deep, mournful knell across the foggy village, the mourners gathered at the cemetery gate and bowed their heads in solemn silence.","say":"NEHL","hook":"A KNELL sounds like a death bell — the silent K tolls like a ghostly gong before the NELL."},{"w":"knapsack","def":"a bag carried by a strap on your back or shoulder","ex":"She slung her knapsack over both shoulders and headed down the dusty path toward camp.","say":"NA-psak","hook":"A KNAPSACK snaps onto your back — keep the silent K at the front like the buckle."},{"w":"knavish","def":"marked by skill in deception","ex":"The knavish merchant short-changed every customer who wasn't paying close attention.","say":"NAY-vish","hook":"KNAVISH behavior is sneaky-ISH — the silent K sneaks in front just like a knave would."},{"w":"gnome","def":"a legendary creature resembling a tiny old man; lives in the depths of the earth and guards buried treasure","ex":"The old gardener placed a ceramic gnome beside the tulips for good luck.","say":"NOHM","hook":"A GNOME lives underground — the silent G hides like the gnome himself, buried beneath the earth with his treasure."},{"w":"gnarled","def":"twist into a state of deformity","ex":"The gnarled old oak at the edge of the field had twisted branches that looked like the fingers of a giant reaching toward the sky.","say":"NAHRLD","hook":"The silent 'gn' is like a knot you can't untangle"},{"w":"gnash","def":"is to grind or strike the teeth together","ex":"The trapped wolf would gnash its teeth whenever a stranger came too close.","say":"n-A-sh","hook":"The silent 'gn' bites hard: you GNASH your teeth starting with a letter you never hear — G is there, gnashing silently."},{"w":"gnu","def":"large African antelope having a head with horns like an ox and a long tufted tail","ex":"The documentary showed a gnu charging across the savanna to escape a pursuing lion.","say":"NOO","hook":"A GNU is a new antelope to many — it sounds like 'new' but is spelled gnu, where the G silently stampedes ahead of the n-u."},{"w":"gnostic","def":"an advocate of Gnosticism","ex":"The professor explained that a gnostic believes salvation comes through secret spiritual knowledge rather than faith alone, and that these ancient thinkers often clashed sharply with the mainstream religious authorities of their time.","say":"NOS-tik","hook":"A GNOSTIC seeks hidden knowledge — that silent G hides the secret just as Gnostic wisdom was hidden from ordinary people."}]},{"title":"Silent -gh- Patterns","category":"Spelling Rules & Patterns","difficulty":"medium","concept":"The -gh- cluster is Old English's most complex legacy. It was once pronounced as a guttural /kh/ sound (like German Bach). As that sound disappeared, the gh became silent — but stayed in the spelling, creating six different pronunciations for -ough alone.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>DISTRAUGHT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> d-ih-s-t-r-AW-t\n<b>Spell it.</b> D · I · S · T · R · A · U · G · H · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> d-ih-s-t-r-AW-t\n<b>Syllables.</b> d · i · s · t · r · a · u · g · h · t\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [dis=DIS] [TRAWT=TRAUGHT]\n<b>Exception.</b> -aught = /awt/ sound; gh is completely silent; from Old English trahtion = pulled; stress: dis-TRAWT\n<b>Origin.</b> English\n<b>Root.</b> Latin distractus = pulled apart, past participle of distrahere","cards":[{"title":"-igh- = /eye/ sound","body":"Night, knight, blight, flight, right, sight, tight, light, might, slight, fright, plight, bright. The -igh- sequence always = /eye/. The gh is completely silent. This is the most regular of the -gh- patterns."},{"title":"-ough = 6 pronunciations (memorize as groups)","body":"- /oh/: though, although, dough, furlough - /oo/: through, slough (a swamp) - /uf/: rough, tough, enough, slough (shed skin) - /of/: cough, trough - /aw/: thought, bought, fought, ought, nought, distraught, wrought - /up/: hiccough (= hiccup) Learn by pronunciation group, not individual words."},{"title":"-aught = /awt/ sound","body":"Distraught (pulled apart = extremely upset), onslaught (sudden violent attack), slaughter, naught (nothing), naughty, daughter, caught, taught, fraught (filled with anxiety). All use -aught = /awt/. This group is the most consistent."},{"title":"-ight vs -ite","body":"Night (Old English, -ight) vs site (Latin, -ite). Might (power) vs mite (a tiny creature). Right vs write vs rite — three spellings of one /rīt/ sound. When the /eye/ + /t/ sound appears in a word with Old English feel, the spelling is likely -ight."},{"title":"Bee Strategy for -gh-","body":"Ask for origin and definition. Old English origin + /awt/ sound → -aught. Old English + /eye/ sound → -ight. The /uf/ sound in a short word → likely -ough (rough, tough). The /oh/ sound in a word → could be -ough (though) or -ow (low) — definition distinguishes."}],"words":[{"w":"distraught","def":"means deeply agitated","ex":"distraught with grief","say":"d-ih-s-t-r-AW-t","hook":"DISTRAUGHT — the GH is silent but the emotion is not; the AU combination sounds like AW in 'awful.'"},{"w":"onslaught","def":"a sudden and severe onset of trouble","ex":"the attack began at dawn","say":"AW-nslawt","hook":"ONSLAUGHT — remember the AUGHT at the end like 'caught' or 'taught'; the attack CAUGHT everyone off guard."},{"w":"slaughter","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"naught","def":"a quantity of no importance","ex":"it looked like nothing I had ever seen before","say":"NAWT","hook":"NAUGHT has the AUGH pattern — think 'All Ugh, I got nothing!'"},{"w":"naughty","def":"suggestive of sexual impropriety","ex":"The comedian's naughty jokes made some adults in the audience blush, though they tried to hide their laughter behind their programs.","say":"NAW-tee","hook":"NAUGHTY has NAUGHT inside — a naughty child has naught (no) good behavior."},{"w":"daughter","def":"a female human offspring","ex":"My grandmother beamed with pride as her daughter—my mother—walked across the stage to receive her college diploma.","say":"DAW-ter","hook":"DAUGHTER has a silent GH in the middle—think AUGHT like 'taught'"},{"w":"fraught","def":"means full of or accompanied by","ex":"a fraught mother-daughter relationship","say":"f-r-AW-t","hook":"FRAUGHT rhymes with CAUGHT—you get caught in a fraught situation"},{"w":"wrought","def":"exert oneself by doing mental or physical work for a purpose or out of necessity","ex":"I will work hard to improve my grades","say":"RAWT","hook":"WROUGHT iron is worked metal — remember the silent W and tricky -OUGHT by thinking 'Workers WROUGHT it.'"},{"w":"thought","def":"the content of cognition; the main thing you are thinking about","ex":"it was not a good idea","say":"THAWT","hook":"THOUGHT contains 'ought' — you OUGHT to think (thought) before you speak."},{"w":"bought","def":"obtain by purchase; acquire by means of a financial transaction","ex":"The family purchased a new car","say":"BAHT","hook":"You BOUGHT it with cash and got a silent 'ugh' deal — no 'a', just 'ou' like you 'ought' to remember."},{"w":"knight","def":"is a mounted soldier in the Middle Ages","ex":"The Beatles were knighted","say":"n-AY-t","hook":"A KNIGHT rides into the NIGHT — both sound the same but KNIGHT wears armor spelled K-N-I-G-H-T with a hidden GH shield."},{"w":"blight","def":"a state or condition being blighted","ex":"Too much rain may blight the garden with mold","say":"BLEYET","hook":"A BLIGHT makes crops look SLIGHT — both end in -IGHT: B-L-I-G-H-T."},{"w":"plough","def":"a group of seven bright stars in the constellation Ursa Major","ex":"The ship plowed through the water","say":"PLOW","hook":"The British PLOUGH hides OUGH like THROUGH—think of the plow CUTTING THROUGH the soil."},{"w":"though","def":"(postpositive) however","ex":"it might be unpleasant, though","say":"THOH","hook":"'Though' looks like 'through' lost its 'r' — it's a long spelling for a word that means 'even so.'"},{"w":"through","def":"having finished or arrived at completion","ex":"certain to make history before he's done","say":"THROO","hook":"THROUGH is TOUGH to spell — just remember: THR + OUGH, like ROUGH but with a TH in front."},{"w":"rough","def":"the part of a golf course bordering the fairway where the grass is not cut short","ex":"trees with rough bark","say":"RUHF","hook":"ROUGH has a tricky OUGH that sounds like UFF — think 'it's ROUGH enough to trip you up with that spelling.'"},{"w":"cough","def":"is to expel air through the lungs harshly often violently","ex":"The smoker coughs all day","say":"k-AH-f","hook":"A ROUGH cough is TOUGH enough — all three share the '-ough' that sounds like '-uff'."}]},{"title":"ie / ei Rule and Exceptions","category":"Spelling Rules & Patterns","difficulty":"easy","concept":"The classic rhyme: \"i before e, except after c, or when sounding like /ay/ as in neighbor and weigh.\" This covers 80% of cases. The other 20% — the exceptions — are the ones that appear in spelling bees.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>SERENDIPITY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> s-eh-r-uh-n-d-IH-p-ih-t-ee\n<b>Spell it.</b> S · E · R · E · N · D · I · P · I · T · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> s-eh-r-uh-n-d-IH-p-ih-t-ee\n<b>Syllables.</b> s · e · r · e · n · d · i · p · i · t · y\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [ser=SER] [en=EN] [DIP=DIP] [ih=I] [tee=TY]\n<b>Exception.</b> -i- before -p- here; no ie/ei issue in this word — but seize, weird, leisure all break the ie/ei rule\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> Persian Serendip = old name for Sri Lanka","cards":[{"title":"The Rule — i before e","body":"After most consonants, ie = /ee/: believe, achieve, relieve, reprieve, grieve, retrieve, mischief, piece, niece. The mnemonic: \"i before e\" — the i comes first in most /ee/ sounds."},{"title":"After c — e before i","body":"After the letter c, the order reverses: ceiling, receive, perceive, deceive, conceive, deceit, conceit, receipt. The c flips the order. Mnemonic: the c is selfish — it pushes e in front of i."},{"title":"When Sounding /ay/ — e before i","body":"Vein, reign, rein, sleigh, weigh, beige, feign, feint, freight, neighbor, eight. When the vowel combination sounds like /ay/, e comes before i. The sound /ay/ overrides the normal order."},{"title":"The Exceptions — Memorize These","body":"Seize (not sieze), weird (not wierd), either (not iether), neither, leisure (not liesure), forfeit (not forfiet), foreign (not foriegn), height (not hieght), protein, caffeine, kaleidoscope, zeitgeist, species. These break the rule and must be memorized individually."},{"title":"Why the Rule Has Exceptions","body":"The rule was invented in 1866 to describe English spelling — English spelling was not invented to follow the rule. Words borrowed from German (zeitgeist, stein), French (beige, feign), and science (protein, caffeine) follow their source languages' spelling, not an English mnemonic invented centuries later."}],"words":[{"w":"believe","def":"accept as true; take to be true","ex":"I believed his report","say":"bih-LEEV","hook":"Never beLIEve a LIE — the word 'believe' hides the word LIE right in the middle!"},{"w":"achieve","def":"to gain with effort","ex":"she achieved her goal despite setbacks","say":"uh-CHEEV","hook":"The CHIEF leads the team — aCHIEve has CHIEF hidden inside: a-CHIE-ve."},{"w":"relieve","def":"is to ease or alleviate pain distress or anxiety","ex":"This pill will relieve your headaches","say":"r-ih-l-EE-v","hook":"RELIEVE: I before E — reLIEve the pain by letting it LIE down first."},{"w":"ceiling","def":"the overhead upper surface of a covered space","ex":"he hated painting the ceiling","say":"SEE-lihng","hook":"The CEILING follows the 'I before E' rule's exception — remember: you CEIl the room, and the ceiling is above you."},{"w":"receive","def":"get something; come into possession of","ex":"At the end-of-year ceremony, every student who completed the reading challenge would receive a personalized certificate and a gift card to the local bookstore as a reward for their efforts.","say":"ruh-SEEV","hook":"Break the I-before-E rule: reCEIVE — think 'CEIling' to remember CEI, not CIE."},{"w":"perceive","def":"is to become aware of","ex":"I could perceive the ship coming over the horizon","say":"p-ur-s-EE-v","hook":"Remember: I before E except after C — perCEIVE has C-E-I-V-E, not C-I-E."},{"w":"deceive","def":"is to mislead by a false appearance or statement","ex":"The insurance company deceived me when they told me they were covering my house","say":"d-ih-s-EE-v","hook":"deCEIVE — the E comes before I here: 'CEI' not 'CIE' — the deceiver puts E before I to trick you!"},{"w":"vein","def":"a blood vessel that carries blood from the capillaries toward the heart","ex":"all veins except the pulmonary vein carry unaerated blood","say":"VAYN","hook":"A VEIN carries blood — E before I: 'thE blood In a VEIN flows to the heart.'"},{"w":"reign","def":"a period during which something or somebody is dominant or powerful","ex":"he was helpless under the reign of his egotism","say":"RAYN","hook":"REIGN contains a silent G-N — the KING's REIGN has a silent G like the silent power of royalty; R-E-I-G-N."},{"w":"feign","def":"is to represent fictitiously","ex":"He feigned that he was ill","say":"f-AY-n","hook":"FEIGN has a hidden GN — you feign ignorance by hiding the G like a silent secret."},{"w":"seize","def":"take hold of; grab","ex":"The detective moved quickly to seize the evidence before it could be destroyed.","say":"SEEZ","hook":"SEIZE breaks the 'i before e' rule — remember: weird SEIZURE"},{"w":"weird","def":"is unearthly or uncanny","ex":"It felt truly weird to walk through the empty school hallways on a Tuesday afternoon when every student and teacher had left early for a surprise snow day.","say":"w-IH-r-d","hook":"WEIRD breaks the 'i before e' rule — it's so WEIRD that E comes before I!"},{"w":"neither","def":"not either; not one or the other","ex":"Neither the rain nor the cold could keep the determined runners from finishing the marathon.","say":"NEE-ther","hook":"Neither follows the E-I rule exception: N-E-I-T-H-E-R — think 'not either' shrunk to one word."},{"w":"leisure","def":"is freedom from the demands of work","ex":"his job left him little leisure","say":"l-EH-zh-ur","hook":"LEIsure — think of LEI (a flower necklace): relaxing on a Hawaiian vacation is leisure!"},{"w":"forfeit","def":"something that is lost or surrendered as a penalty","ex":"Because three players missed the mandatory practice, the team had to forfeit their spot in the championship tournament.","say":"FAW-rfiht","hook":"FORFEIT: remember E before I here—it's one of the exceptions to 'i before e'"},{"w":"foreign","def":"of concern to or concerning the affairs of other nations (other than your own)","ex":"Learning a foreign language can open doors to new cultures, friendships, and opportunities that most people in your hometown never get the chance to experience.","say":"FAW-ruhn","hook":"FOREIGN hides a REIGN inside — a foreign king has a reign far away; remember i before e except after c, but here it's E-I-G-N."},{"w":"height","def":"the vertical dimension of extension; distance from the base of something to the top","ex":"his landscapes were deemed the acme of beauty","say":"HEYET","hook":"HEIGHT has a silent GH — think 'High Enormous Incredible Giant Huge Thing.'"},{"w":"protein","def":"any of a large group of nitrogenous organic compounds that are essential constituents of living cells; consist of polymers of amino acids; essential in the diet of animals for growth and for repair of tissues; can be obtained from meat and eggs and milk and legumes","ex":"a diet high in protein","say":"PROH-teen","hook":"Remember: E before I — 'prote-IN,' not 'proti-EN' — protein comes FIRST (protos) in your diet."},{"w":"caffeine","def":"a bitter alkaloid found in coffee and tea that is responsible for their stimulating effects","ex":"Maya limited herself to one cup of tea in the morning because too much caffeine made her hands jittery during her violin recital.","say":"ka-FEEN","hook":"Caffeine has DOUBLE F — two shots of espresso, two F's."}]},{"title":"Double Consonant Rules","category":"Spelling Rules & Patterns","difficulty":"medium","concept":"English doubles a final consonant before suffixes that begin with a vowel (-ing, -ed, -er, -est) under specific conditions. The rule is completely systematic — stress is the key.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>COMMITTED</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> kuh-MIH-tihd\n<b>Spell it.</b> C · O · M · M · I · T · T · E · D\n<b>Say it again.</b> kuh-MIH-tihd\n<b>Syllables.</b> kah · mih · tah · d\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [kuh=COM] [MIT=MIT] [ed=TED]\n<b>Exception.</b> stress on -MIT so double T before -ed; commit + ted → committed; single-T would give /KOM-ih-ted/\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin committere = to send or put together","cards":[{"title":"The One-Syllable Rule (CVC)","body":"Double the final consonant when a one-syllable word ends in consonant-vowel-consonant: run→running, stop→stopped, sit→sitting, cut→cutting, big→bigger. The doubling keeps the vowel short. Without it: runing would rhyme with tuning."},{"title":"The Two-Syllable Stress Rule","body":"For two-syllable words, double only if stress falls on the LAST syllable: begin→beginning (stress on BEGIN), occur→occurred (stress on OCCUR), commit→committed (stress on COMMIT), prefer→preferred (stress on preFER). Do NOT double if stress falls on the FIRST syllable: open→opening, happen→happened."},{"title":"Test — Tap the Syllable","body":"Tap your desk on each syllable and feel which one is louder. Travel: TRAV-el (first syllable louder) → traveled (no double). Control: con-TROL (second syllable louder) → controlled (double-l). Offer: OF-fer (first) → offered (no double). Occur: oc-CUR (second) → occurred (double-r)."},{"title":"American vs British Doubling","body":"Americans: traveled, modeled, canceled. British: travelled, modelled, cancelled — they double whenever the final l is preceded by a single vowel, regardless of stress. For US spelling bees (Merriam-Webster): American conventions apply. Know which dictionary the bee uses."},{"title":"Always-Doubled Words","body":"Some words have inherited double consonants that are not about suffixes — they must be memorized: accommodate (double-c + double-m), embarrass (double-r + double-s), millennium (double-l + double-n), necessary (one-c + double-s), occasion (double-c + one-s), recommend (one-c + double-m), satellite (one-t + double-l)."}],"words":[{"w":"committed","def":"perform an act, usually with a negative connotation","ex":"The detective announced that a crime had been committed sometime between midnight and dawn, and that all residents of the building were considered potential witnesses.","say":"kuh-MIH-tihd","hook":"comMITTED doubles the T in past tense — you were so committed you gave it two T's!"},{"w":"occurred","def":"come to pass","ex":"A tremendous thunderstorm occurred overnight, knocking out the power and leaving the entire neighborhood in darkness until repair crews arrived early the next morning.","say":"uh-KURD","hook":"It OCCURRed to me: double 'c', double 'r' — two pairs, like two things running into each other."},{"w":"beginning","def":"the event consisting of the start of something","ex":"the beginning of the war","say":"bih-GIH-nihng","hook":"Beginning has two n's — you need two feet to take your first step."},{"w":"preferred","def":"like better; value more highly","ex":"Some people prefer camping to staying in hotels","say":"pruh-FURD","hook":"PREFERRED doubles the R because the stress falls on -FER — you really, REALLY prefer it, so add an extra R."},{"w":"controlled","def":"exercise authoritative control or power over","ex":"The experienced pilot controlled the small aircraft smoothly through the sudden turbulence, keeping the passengers calm by maintaining a steady altitude and speaking reassuringly over the intercom throughout the bumpy flight.","say":"kuh-NTROHLD","hook":"CONTROLLED doubles the L — it takes two strong Ls to hold everything under control."},{"w":"traveled","def":"change location; move, travel, or proceed, also metaphorically","ex":"How fast does your new car go?","say":"TRA-vuhld","hook":"American TRAVELED uses one L — one L for one continent crossed."},{"w":"canceled","def":"postpone indefinitely or annul something that was scheduled","ex":"Call off the engagement","say":"KA-nsuhld","hook":"In American English, one L is CANCELED — the second L got crossed out, just like the event!"},{"w":"accommodate","def":"is to do a kindness or a favor to oblige","ex":"The hotel staff worked hard to accommodate every guest's special request, arranging extra pillows, dietary meals, and late checkout times to ensure that everyone left feeling comfortable and well cared for.","say":"uh-k-AH-m-uh-d-ay-t","hook":"ACCOMModate needs double C and double M — it takes TWO of each to fit everyone in."},{"w":"embarrass","def":"is to cause confusion and shame to","ex":"His brother blocked him at every turn","say":"ih-m-b-EH-r-uh-s","hook":"I'm Really Really Awkward — embaRRASS has a double R and double S to make you squirm."},{"w":"millennium","def":"is a period of 1000 years","ex":"Scientists predicted it would take a millennium for the ancient forest to fully recover from the fire.","say":"m-uh-l-EH-n-ee-uh-m","hook":"MILLENNIUM: double L, double N, -ium at the end—two pairs for two thousand years of confusion."},{"w":"necessary","def":"is being essential indispensable","ex":"food and shelter are necessities of life","say":"n-EH-s-uh-s-eh-r-ee","hook":"NECESSARY: one Collar, two Socks — one 'c' and two 's's, like a shirt needs."},{"w":"occasion","def":"an event that occurs at a critical time","ex":"at such junctures he always had an impulse to leave","say":"uh-KAY-zhuhn","hook":"One Collar, one Suitcase: oc-ca-sion — double C, single S, for a special event."},{"w":"recommend","def":"is to present as worthy of confidence or acceptance","ex":"The travel agent recommended strongly that we not travel on Thanksgiving Day","say":"r-eh-k-uh-m-EH-n-d","hook":"RECOMMEND has one 'c' and two 'm's — think: I'd COMMEND it again, so one 'c', double 'm'."},{"w":"satellite","def":"a man-made object placed in orbit around the Earth or another celestial body to collect data or aid communication","ex":"a city and its satellite communities","say":"s-A-t-uh-l-ay-t","hook":"SATellite has one T then double L — it SITS in orbit like a steady attendant"},{"w":"parallel","def":"is extending in the same direction but never converging","ex":"parallels never meet","say":"p-EH-r-uh-l-eh-l","hook":"PARALLEL has two L's in the middle and two L's at the end — like two parallel lines running side by side: para-L-L-e-L-L."},{"w":"committee","def":"a special group delegated to consider some matter;  - Milton Berle","ex":"a committee is a group that keeps minutes and loses hours","say":"kuh-MIH-tee","hook":"A comMITTEE has double M, double T, double E — three pairs, like three pairs of people on the committee!"}]},{"title":"c = /s/ Before e / i / y","category":"Spelling Rules & Patterns","difficulty":"easy","concept":"The letter c has two sounds: /k/ (hard) before a, o, u, and /s/ (soft) before e, i, y. Knowing this rule explains dozens of spelling patterns and helps decode words you've never seen.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>IRIDESCENT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ih-r-uh-d-EH-s-uh-n-t\n<b>Spell it.</b> I · R · I · D · E · S · C · E · N · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> ih-r-uh-d-EH-s-uh-n-t\n<b>Syllables.</b> i · r · i · d · e · s · c · e · n · t\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [ir=IR] [ih=I] [DES=DES] [ent=CENT]\n<b>Exception.</b> -sc- = /s/ because c before e; -escent = becoming; -ir- not -irr-; stress: ir-ih-DES-ent\n<b>Origin.</b> English\n<b>Root.</b> Greek iris = rainbow + Latin -escent(becoming)","cards":[{"title":"The Rule","body":"c = /k/ before a, o, u, and consonants: cat, cold, cup, craft. c = /s/ before e, i, y: ceiling, city, cycle. This explains why cell starts with /s/ and call starts with /k/ — same letter, different vowel following it."},{"title":"-sc- = /s/ Before e/i","body":"The cluster -sc- before e or i also = /s/: iridescent (sc + e = /s/), adolescent, luminescent, quiescent, convalescent, effervescent, incandescent. The s in -sc- is redundant to the /s/ sound of c — but both letters must be spelled."},{"title":"-ce and -ci- Inside Words","body":"Susceptible (sus- + cep- + -ible) — the c before e → susceptible not susceptable. Conceit (con- + ceit) — c before e. Luscious — c before i. Precious — c before i. Spacious — c before i. Recognizing -ci- as /sh/ in suffixes like -cious, -cial, -cient is a major spelling pattern."},{"title":"Acquiesce — the c/qu Combination","body":"Acquiesce (ac- + quiescere = rest) — the qu keeps its /kw/ sound; the -esce has c before e = /s/. The word has two different c sounds: /kw/ (in qu) and /s/ (in -sc-). Spelling: A-C-Q-U-I-E-S-C-E."},{"title":"Soft c vs Hard c in the Same Word","body":"Circle = cir (soft c before i) + -cle (hard c before l). Circus = cir (soft c before i) + -cus (hard c before u). Concede = con (hard c) + -cede (soft c before e). The position of the vowel following the c tells you which sound it makes — every time."}],"words":[{"w":"iridescent","def":"is displaying a play of bright colors like a rainbow","ex":"The hummingbird hovered just inches from the flower, its iridescent throat feathers shifting from deep emerald to brilliant violet as it tilted its tiny head, catching the afternoon sunlight at a slightly different angle.","say":"ih-r-uh-d-EH-s-uh-n-t","hook":"Iridescent — one R, like a single rainbow arc over the word."},{"w":"adolescent","def":"a juvenile between the onset of puberty and maturity","ex":"As an adolescent, Theo struggled to balance the pressures of middle school friendships, growing responsibilities at home, and his own rapidly changing feelings about who he wanted to become.","say":"a-duh-LEH-suhnt","hook":"An ADOLESCENT grows — spell the SCENT of growth: a-d-o-l-e-S-C-E-N-T."},{"w":"luminescent","def":"emitting light not caused by heat","ex":"The luminescent stickers on her ceiling glowed softly after the lights went out.","say":"loo-muh-NEH-suhnt","hook":"LUMINESCENT ends in '-ent' like a glowing agent — only an '-ent' student spells it right."},{"w":"quiescent","def":"is being at rest quiet inactive","ex":"the quiescent level of centimeter wave-length solar radiation","say":"k-w-ay-EH-s-uh-n-t","hook":"QUIESCENT ends in -SCENT: imagine a quiet, still room with a faint scent — perfectly at rest."},{"w":"effervescent","def":"used of wines and waters; charged naturally or artificially with carbon dioxide","ex":"The effervescent new student bubbled with energy from the very first day, cracking jokes, complimenting everyone's artwork, and making the entire classroom feel lighter and more fun simply by walking through the door each morning.","say":"eh-f-ur-v-EH-s-uh-n-t","hook":"EFFERVescent = bubbles FERVOR-ing out — think of a soda bottle fizzing over."},{"w":"incandescent","def":"strikingly bright radiant or clear","ex":"an incandescent bulb","say":"ih-n-k-uh-n-d-EH-s-uh-n-t","hook":"An incanDESCENT bulb glows as it DESCENDS into heat — spell the SCENT of hot wax: -s-c-e-n-t."},{"w":"luscious","def":"is highly pleasing to the taste or smell","ex":"The baker arranged a luscious display of ripe strawberries, glazed pastries, and cream-filled tarts that made every customer stop and stare hungrily through the window.","say":"l-UH-sh-ih-s","hook":"LUSCIOUS has no H—it's lus-CIOUS, like delicious without the deli, packed with flavor."},{"w":"precious","def":"is of high price or great value","ex":"The locket passed down through four generations was precious not because of its gold casing but because of the tiny photographs it held inside.","say":"p-r-EH-sh-uh-s","hook":"PRECIOUS gems have a PRICE — preci+ous, don't drop the 'i' that spells 'pricei' inside."},{"w":"spacious","def":"affording much room not narrow or constricted roomy","ex":"After years of sharing a tiny bedroom with two siblings, moving into a spacious room with her own desk, bookshelf, and window seat felt like an absolute luxury to Maya.","say":"s-p-AY-sh-uh-s","hook":"A SPACIOUS room has SPACE — keep the I before OUS: spac-I-ous, because you need an 'I' to see all that space."},{"w":"susceptible","def":"(often followed by `of' or `to') yielding readily to or capable of","ex":"susceptible to colds","say":"suh-SEH-ptuh-buhl","hook":"susceptIBLE — end in -ible not -able; think 'I'll Be LEt in easily' — I-B-L-E for things easily taken up."},{"w":"acquiesce","def":"to agree or express agreement","ex":"After hours of debate, Marcus finally decided to acquiesce to his teammates' plan even though he still had doubts about it.","say":"a-kwee-EHS","hook":"ACQUIesce — QUIET agreement; when you acquiesce, you quietly give in"},{"w":"conceit","def":"is an excessively favorable opinion of oneself","ex":"he could always come up with some inspired off-the-wall conceit","say":"k-uh-n-s-EE-t","hook":"conCEIT — someone full of conceit thinks they're the ELITE"},{"w":"scintillating","def":"Brilliantly clever, lively, and stimulating; sparkling with wit, energy, or dazzling light.","ex":"the substance scintillated sparks and flashes","say":"SIN-tih-lay-ting","hook":"SCINTILLATING has TILLA inside — imagine a caterpillar named TILLA who sparkles and glitters as she walks."},{"w":"nascent","def":"is beginning to exist or develop","ex":"The nascent robotics club at Jefferson Middle School had only four members and one broken motor, but their enthusiasm and creativity suggested something truly exciting was just beginning to take shape.","say":"n-AY-s-uh-n-t","hook":"NASCent — NASCar is a newly born racing sport; things that are NASC-ent are just being born"},{"w":"obsolescent","def":"means passing out of use as a word","ex":"With smartphones everywhere, the pay phone has become an obsolescent relic of a previous generation.","say":"ah-b-s-uh-l-EH-s-uh-n-t","hook":"An obsoleSCENT thing is fading from the SCENE — keep the S-C in the middle!"}]},{"title":"ph = /f/ Sound (Greek Signal)","category":"Spelling Rules & Patterns","difficulty":"medium","concept":"ph = /f/ is the most reliable Greek origin signal in English. It appears ONLY in Greek-origin words (or words modeled on Greek). Hearing /f/ in a learned, scientific, or literary word = look for ph, not f.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>DIAPHANOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> d-ay-A-f-uh-n-ih-s\n<b>Spell it.</b> D · I · A · P · H · A · N · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> d-ay-A-f-uh-n-ih-s\n<b>Syllables.</b> d · i · a · p · h · a · n · o · u · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [die=DI] [AF=APH] [uh=A] [nus=NOUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> -ph- = /f/ (Greek!); dia- = through; phanein = show; -ous suffix; die-AF-uh-nus\n<b>Origin.</b> English\n<b>Root.</b> Greek diaphainein = to show through","cards":[{"title":"The Golden Rule","body":"If you hear /f/ in a learned, scientific, or literary word — write ph not f. Phenomenon, ephemeral, diphtheria, phosphorus, sycophant, sophistry, metaphor, diaphanous, asphyxia, phlegm. The ph is Greek phi (φ), and it entered English with the Greek vocabulary."},{"title":"The Exception","body":"Common everyday English words use f not ph: fun, fish, finger, fly, fog, flat. The rule only applies to borrowed learned words. Fahrenheit = German, uses f. Fan = Old English, uses f. If it is a short, everyday word you knew as a child → probably f. If it is a learned word you encountered in books → probably ph."},{"title":"ph in the Middle of Words","body":"Elephant (elephas = Greek) — ph in the middle. Orphan (orphanos = Greek) — ph in the middle. Emphasis (emphasis = Greek) — ph in the middle. Amphitheater — ph inside. Epiphany — ph inside. Morphine — ph inside. The ph appears anywhere in the word, not just at the start."},{"title":"The Hardest ph Clusters","body":"Diphthong = di- + phthongos = two sounds merged — has -phth- cluster (two silent-seeming letters working together). Ophthalmology = -phth- cluster inside. Phthisis (tuberculosis) starts with pht- — P-H-T-H-I-S-I-S. These are the most extreme Greek ph spellings."},{"title":"Building ph Word Families","body":"-phage (eating): sarcophagus (flesh eater). -phor (carrying): metaphor, phosphor. -phyte (plant): lithophyte, epiphyte. -phon (sound): microphone, saxophone. -phil (loving): bibliophile, anglophile. One pattern — the ph — unlocks them all."}],"words":[{"w":"diaphanous","def":"means very sheer and light","ex":"a hat with a diaphanous veil","say":"d-ay-A-f-uh-n-ih-s","hook":"DIAphanous fabric is so sheer you could see a DIAMOND through it."},{"w":"phenomenon","def":"is a fact or occurrence observed or observable","ex":"The sudden appearance of the northern lights over the city was a spectacular natural phenomenon.","say":"f-uh-n-AH-m-uh-n-ah-n","hook":"PHENOMENON ends in -ON not -IN — one phENOMENon, many phenomENA."},{"w":"ephemeral","def":"is lasting a very short time","ex":"the ephemeral joys of childhood","say":"ih-f-EH-m-ur-uh-l","hook":"EPHEMERAL: 'Every Petal Has Every Morning Erased, Really A Loss' — beauty gone by dawn."},{"w":"sycophant","def":"a person who tries to please someone in order to gain a personal advantage","ex":"The new employee was such a sycophant that he laughed loudly at every one of the boss's jokes, no matter how unfunny.","say":"SIK-uh-fant","hook":"A SYCOphant is SICK with flattery to get what they want"},{"w":"metaphor","def":"is a figure of speech in which a term is applied to something to which it isn't literally applicable","ex":"When the poet wrote that life is a rollercoaster, she was using a metaphor to describe its unpredictable ups and downs.","say":"m-EH-t-uh-f-aw-r","hook":"A metaPHOR carries meaning across — it PHORwarded an idea to a new place."},{"w":"asphyxia","def":"a condition in which insufficient or no oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged on a ventilatory basis; caused by choking or drowning or electric shock or poison gas","ex":"The doctor explained that asphyxia occurs when the body is deprived of the oxygen it needs to survive.","say":"as-FIK-see-uh","hook":"ASPHYXIA has a Y after SPH — you gasp 'WHY?' when you can't breathe, and Y is right there in the middle."},{"w":"phlegm","def":"apathy demonstrated by an absence of emotional reactions","ex":"the general appearance of sluggishness alarmed his friends","say":"FLEHM","hook":"PHLEGM hides a silent G — the G gets stuck in your throat just like phlegm does."},{"w":"diphthong","def":"is an unsegmented gliding speech sound","ex":"The speech teacher explained that the word 'coin' contains a diphthong because two vowel sounds blend together smoothly.","say":"d-IH-p-th-aw-ng","hook":"A DIPHTHONG has TWO sounds — and two silent letters ph and th, making it doubly tricky."},{"w":"ophthalmology","def":"is the branch of medicine dealing with anatomy functions and diseases of the eye","ex":"She chose to specialize in ophthalmology because she wanted to help patients who were losing their sight.","say":"ah-p-th-uh-m-AH-l-uh-j-ee","hook":"OPHTHALMOLOGY — the word itself needs an eye exam; spot the OPHTHALM hiding before -OLOGY."},{"w":"phosphorus","def":"a multivalent nonmetallic element of the nitrogen family that occurs commonly in inorganic phosphate rocks and as organic phosphates in all living cells; is highly reactive and occurs in several allotropic forms","ex":"Phosphorus is an essential element found in our bones and teeth, and it plays a key role in producing energy in our cells.","say":"FAH-sfer-uhs","hook":"PHOSPHORUS the element ends in -US like NUCLEUS — it's the glowing nucleus of fertilizers and matches."},{"w":"diphtheria","def":"acute contagious infection caused by the bacterium Corynebacterium diphtheriae; marked by the formation of a false membrane in the throat and other air passages causing difficulty in breathing","ex":"Before vaccines were available, diphtheria swept through schools and claimed the lives of many young children.","say":"dih-FTHIH-ree-ah","hook":"DIPHTHERIA has a PH like PHarynx — it attacks your throat; remember the silent P in diPHtheria."},{"w":"emphatic","def":"spoken with emphasis","ex":"The coach gave an emphatic thumbs-up when her team scored the winning goal in the final seconds of the game.","say":"eh-MFA-tihk","hook":"An EMPHATIC statement puts EMPHASIS on every word"},{"w":"orphan","def":"a child who has lost both parents","ex":"The kind couple decided to adopt the orphan after meeting her at the community shelter.","say":"AW-rfuhn","hook":"ORPHan: think of ORPH rhyming with MORPH — an orphan morphs into independence alone."},{"w":"elephant","def":"five-toed pachyderm","ex":"The elephant raised its enormous trunk and sprayed water over its dusty back.","say":"EH-luh-fuhnt","hook":"An ELEPHANT is ELEPH-ANT — imagine a giant ant named Eleph carrying a trunk."},{"w":"amphitheater","def":"is an oval or round building with an open central area","ex":"The students sat in the grassy amphitheater and watched the outdoor Shakespeare performance under the stars.","say":"A-m-f-uh-th-ee-uh-t-ur","hook":"AMPHITHEATER = AMPHI + THEATER — seats go AROUND (amphi) the THEATER, so just add 'amphi' to a word you know!"},{"w":"epiphany","def":"is a Christian festival","ex":"Beyond its religious meaning, Maya used the word epiphany to describe the sudden moment she realized the solution to the math problem.","say":"ih-p-IH-f-uh-n-ee","hook":"An EPIPHAny is when truth APPEARS (PHANy = phainein = show) — one 'n,' one shining moment of clarity."}]},{"title":"qu- Combination (q Always Followed by u)","category":"Spelling Rules & Patterns","difficulty":"easy","concept":"In English, the letter q is almost always followed by u. The combination qu represents two different sounds: /kw/ in most English words, and /k/ in French-origin words ending in -que.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>ELOQUENT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> EH-luh-kwuhnt\n<b>Spell it.</b> E · L · O · Q · U · E · N · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> EH-luh-kwuhnt\n<b>Syllables.</b> eh · lah · kwah · nt\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [EL=EL] [uh=O] [kwent=QUENT]\n<b>Exception.</b> -oqu- = /uh-kw/; eloqui = speak out; -ent suffix; stress: EL-uh-kwent\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin eloqui = to speak out","cards":[{"title":"The Rule","body":"In English, q is almost always followed by u. The qu cluster represents /kw/ in most words: queen, quick, question, quiet, quorum, quandary, quarrel, quarrel, querulous, quorum. There is almost never a q without a u in a standard English word."},{"title":"qu = /k/ (French-origin words)","body":"In French-origin words ending in -que, the qu = /k/ not /kw/: bouquet (boo-KAY), clique (kleek), opaque (oh-PAYK), unique (yoo-NEEK), oblique (oh-BLEEK), technique (tek-NEEK), antique (an-TEEK). The -que ending signals French origin and /k/ sound."},{"title":"qu Inside Latin Words","body":"Eloquent (e- + loqui = speak) — the qu = /kw/. Soliloquy — qu = /kw/. Colloquy — qu = /kw/. Ventriloquist — qu = /kw/. In Latin-derived words, qu almost always = /kw/. In French-derived words ending in -que, it = /k*."},{"title":"Exceptions — q Without u","body":"Rare borrowed words have q without u: qi (Chinese life-force), qigong (Chinese breathing practice), qanat (Persian underground waterway), qoph (Hebrew letter). These come from languages where q represents a different sound than in Latin/Greek/French. At a bee: ask for origin."},{"title":"Soliloquy vs Colloquy","body":"Soliloquy = S-O-L-I-L-O-Q-U-Y (speaking alone — the qu before y). Colloquy = C-O-L-L-O-Q-U-Y. Ventriloquist = V-E-N-T-R-I-L-O-Q-U-I-S-T. In all three, the qu is followed by a vowel (y or u or i). The q always needs its u — and then another vowel follows to complete the syllable."}],"words":[{"w":"eloquent","def":"expressing yourself readily, clearly, effectively","ex":"able to dazzle with his facile tongue","say":"EH-luh-kwuhnt","hook":"An ELOquent speaker lets words FLOW out beautifully."},{"w":"soliloquy","def":"is a discourse by a person who is talking to himself","ex":"The actor delivered Hamlet's famous soliloquy so powerfully that the entire audience held their breath.","say":"s-uh-l-IH-l-uh-k-w-ee","hook":"A soliloquy is a SOLO speech — SOL-I-LOQU-Y: alone + speak, with a Q-U-Y ending like obloquy."},{"w":"colloquy","def":"a conversation especially a formal one","ex":"The two diplomats held a private colloquy before the official summit began.","say":"KAH-luh-kwee","hook":"A COLLOQUY is a TALK — col-LOQUY has LOQUACIOUS buried inside it."},{"w":"ventriloquist","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"quandary","def":"a situation from which extrication is difficult especially an unpleasant or trying one","ex":"Maya was in a quandary when both her best friend and her science partner needed help at exactly the same time.","say":"KWAH-nder-ee","hook":"You wander (quandary) in circles when you can't decide."},{"w":"querulous","def":"means full of complaints","ex":"The querulous passenger in seat 14B complained loudly about the air conditioning, the seat cushion, the snack selection, and the angle of the sun through the window during the entire two-hour flight.","say":"k-w-EH-r-uh-l-uh-s","hook":"Someone querulous is always querying why things are so bad."},{"w":"quorum","def":"a gathering of the minimal number of members of an organization to conduct business","ex":"The school board could not vote on the new policy because not enough members arrived to form a quorum.","say":"KWAW-ruhm","hook":"QUORUM ends in -UM like 'forum' — you need a quorum to hold a forum, and both end the same way."},{"w":"bouquet","def":"an arrangement of flowers that is usually given as a present","ex":"The groom's hands trembled as he presented the bride with a bouquet of red roses and white lilies tied with a silk ribbon.","say":"b-oo-k-AY","hook":"BOUQUET ends in -QUET but sounds like -KAY—picture a bouquet at a boutiQUE"},{"w":"clique","def":"an exclusive circle of people with a common purpose","ex":"The tight-knit clique of artists always sat together at lunch and rarely welcomed new members.","say":"KLEEK","hook":"A CLIQUE ends in -QUE like UNIQUE — exclusive people think they're uniquely special."},{"w":"opaque","def":"is not allowing light to pass through","ex":"opaque windows of the jail","say":"oh-p-AY-k","hook":"OPAQUE ends in '-que' like unique — both words end in a quirky silent 'ue' that blocks easy reading."},{"w":"unique","def":"radically distinctive and without equal","ex":"he is alone in the field of microbiology","say":"yoo-NEEK","hook":"UNIQUE ends with QUE — it's the one word that uses Q without a U after it... wait, it does! That's unique."},{"w":"oblique","def":"any grammatical case other than the nominative","ex":"the oblique rays of the winter sun","say":"uh-b-l-EE-k","hook":"OBLIQUe — think of a slanted line that is not quite EQUAL to straight."},{"w":"technique","def":"is the manner in which the technical skills of a particular art are used","ex":"practice greatly improves proficiency","say":"t-eh-k-n-EE-k","hook":"TECHNIQUE ends in -IQUE like UNIQUE — a unique technique needs that silent QUE: T-E-C-H-N-I-Q-U-E."},{"w":"antique","def":"an elderly man","ex":"We went antiquing on Saturday","say":"a-NTEEK","hook":"An ANTIQUE always ends in -QUE — it's a uniquely old piece, and UNIQUE ends in -QUE too!"},{"w":"torque","def":"is something that produces rotation","ex":"The mechanic used a special wrench to apply the correct torque when tightening the engine bolts.","say":"t-AW-r-k","hook":"TORQUE has a silent QUE — think: it QUEERLY twists, so keep the QUE."},{"w":"plaque","def":"is a tablet or plate of metal intended for use as an ornament","ex":"A bronze plaque on the library wall honored the generous donor who funded its construction.","say":"p-l-A-k","hook":"A plAQUE hangs on the wall—it has a QUEUE of letters: Q-U-E at the end."}]},{"title":"y as Vowel (Greek Words)","category":"Spelling Rules & Patterns","difficulty":"medium","concept":"In English words of Greek origin, y functions as a vowel, sounding like /i/ or /ee/. This is Greek letter upsilon (Υ), which became y when Greek words entered Latin and then English.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>LABYRINTH</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> l-A-b-ur-ih-n-th\n<b>Spell it.</b> L · A · B · Y · R · I · N · T · H\n<b>Say it again.</b> l-A-b-ur-ih-n-th\n<b>Syllables.</b> l · a · b · y · r · i · n · t · h\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [LAB=LAB] [uh=Y] [rinth=RINTH]\n<b>Exception.</b> y = /uh/ here (as vowel, not consonant); -th = /th/ from Greek theta; Greek origin; LAB-uh-rinth\n<b>Origin.</b> English\n<b>Root.</b> Greek labyrinthos = maze, possibly from labrys = double-headed axe","cards":[{"title":"The Pattern","body":"When y appears in the MIDDLE of a word (not at the end), it is usually Greek and functions as a vowel, sounding like /i/ or /uh/: rhythm, crypt, lymph, nymph, gymnasium, typhoon, oxygen, labyrinth, syllable, symbol, cyst, gypsum, myth, myrtle."},{"title":"Y Clusters — Middle of Word","body":"-yn-: synonym, syntax, synthesis, synapse. -ym-: symbol, symmetry, sympathy, symphony. -yr-: pyramid, lyric, lyre, myrtle, tyranny, myrrh. -ys-: system, mystery, crystalline. -yp-: typical, type, typhoon, hypnosis."},{"title":"Y at the End = /ee/","body":"When y ends a word, it sounds like /ee/ in Greek-derived words: harmony, melody, euphony, biology, geography. This is the -y from Greek -ia or -eia. Different sound, same Greek origin. End = /ee/. Middle = /i/ or /uh/."},{"title":"Medical Y Words","body":"Psych- words: psychology, psychiatry, psyche — the p is silent AND y is a vowel. Gymn- words: gymnasium, gymnast, gymnastics — y is a vowel. Crypt- words: cryptic, cryptogram — y is a vowel. Cyst, lymph, glyph — all single-syllable medical words with y as the only vowel."},{"title":"Why y?* Greek letter upsilon (Υ, υ) was a vowel in Greek. When Romans transcribed Greek words, they wrote y for upsilon (because they had no upsilon in Latin). English inherited this Roman convention. So every English word with a vowel-sounding y in the middle is a direct descendant of a Greek upsilon*. **Word Bank","body":"labyrinth · rhythm · lymph · nymph · gymnasium · typhoon · oxygen · syllable · symbol · crypt · mystery · synonym · synthesis · pyramid · lyric · tyranny · gypsum · crystalline ---"}],"words":[{"w":"labyrinth","def":"is an intricate combination of paths","ex":"The ancient labyrinth beneath the castle had so many twisting passages that explorers often got lost.","say":"l-A-b-ur-ih-n-th","hook":"LABYrinth has a BABY inside it — even a baby would get lost in a maze!"},{"w":"rhythm","def":"is movement with uniform recurrence of a beat or accent","ex":"the piece has a fast rhythm","say":"r-IH-th-uh-m","hook":"'Rhythm Helps Your Two Hips Move' — the first letter of each word spells RHYTHM."},{"w":"lymph","def":"a thin coagulable fluid (similar to plasma but) containing white blood cells (lymphocytes) and chyle; is conveyed to the blood stream by lymphatic vessels","ex":"The nurse explained that lymph travels through the body's vessels and plays a key role in fighting infection.","say":"LIHMF","hook":"LYMPH flows clear like water — Latin lympha = water, and the PH makes it scientifically proper."},{"w":"nymph","def":"(classical mythology) a minor nature goddess usually depicted as a beautiful maiden","ex":"the ancient Greeks believed that nymphs inhabited forests and bodies of water","say":"NIHMF","hook":"A NYMPH hides a Y — think 'mYsterious nature maiden' with that hidden Y."},{"w":"gymnasium","def":"a school for students intermediate between elementary school and college; usually grades 9 to 12","ex":"The students at the gymnasium spent long hours studying Latin, mathematics, and philosophy.","say":"jih-MNAY-zee-uhm","hook":"GymnasIUM — the -IUM ending like a grand auditorium where athletes perform."},{"w":"typhoon","def":"a tropical cyclone occurring in the western Pacific or Indian oceans","ex":"The fishermen rushed back to shore when the weather radar showed a typhoon building strength over the Pacific.","say":"teye-FOON","hook":"A TYPHOON hits with a BOOM — hear that OON at the end like the howling wind."},{"w":"oxygen","def":"a nonmetallic bivalent element that is normally a colorless odorless tasteless nonflammable diatomic gas; constitutes 21 percent of the atmosphere by volume; the most abundant element in the earth's crust","ex":"The deep-sea diver carefully checked her oxygen tank before descending into the dark ocean waters.","say":"AH-ksuh-juhn","hook":"OXYGEN was named 'acid producer' — OXY-GEN, where GEN means to generate; it generates life."},{"w":"syllable","def":"a unit of spoken language larger than a phoneme","ex":"the word `pocket' has two syllables","say":"SIH-luh-buhl","hook":"A sylLABle is a LAB where sounds combine — double L, then -able at the end."},{"w":"symbol","def":"an arbitrary sign (written or printed) that has acquired a conventional significance","ex":"the eagle is a symbol of the United States","say":"SIH-mbuhl","hook":"SYMBol — SYM sounds like 'seem,' and a symbol SEEMS to mean more than it shows; end in -bol not -bel."},{"w":"crypt","def":"is a subterranean chamber or vault","ex":"Archaeologists carefully descended into the ancient crypt beneath the cathedral, hoping to find inscriptions on the stone walls.","say":"k-r-IH-p-t","hook":"A CRYPT is a hidden underground vault — the Y is buried in the middle, just like bodies are buried inside."},{"w":"mystery","def":"something that baffles understanding and cannot be explained","ex":"how it got out is a mystery","say":"MIH-ster-ee","hook":"MYSTERY starts with MY — it is MY secret to keep; never swap the Y for an I at the start."},{"w":"synonym","def":"is a word having nearly the same meaning as another","ex":"The teacher asked us to find a synonym for the word happy, and most students wrote joyful.","say":"s-IH-n-uh-n-ih-m","hook":"A SYNonym gives a word a NEW NAME (onym) that means the SAME thing."},{"w":"synthesis","def":"the process of producing a chemical compound (usually by the union of simpler chemical compounds)","ex":"The lab report explained the synthesis of aspirin by combining salicylic acid with acetic anhydride.","say":"SIH-nthuh-suhs","hook":"SynthESIS — think of placing pieces TOGETHER; remember the ending is -ESIS like 'thesis.'"},{"w":"pyramid","def":"a polyhedron having a polygonal base and triangular sides with a common vertex","ex":"Our class built a cardboard pyramid as part of our project on ancient Egyptian architecture.","say":"PIH-ruh-mihd","hook":"A PYRAMID has one A in the middle holding up the triangle — PYR-A-MID."},{"w":"lyric","def":"the text of a popular song or musical-comedy number","ex":"his compositions always started with the lyrics","say":"LIH-rihk","hook":"A LYRIC is sung to a LYRE — keep the Y from lyre to remember the musical connection."},{"w":"tyranny","def":"a form of government in which the ruler is an absolute dictator (not restricted by a constitution or laws or opposition etc.)","ex":"The students read about how citizens eventually rebelled against the tyranny of the cruel king who taxed them into poverty.","say":"TIH-ruh-nee","hook":"TYRANNY has double N and double Y energy — two N's hold the people down, -Y seals their fate."},{"w":"gypsum","def":"is a common mineral","ex":"The workers mixed powdered gypsum with water to create the smooth plaster finish on the walls.","say":"j-IH-p-s-uh-m","hook":"GYpsum starts with GY — like a GYmnasium floor made of plaster."},{"w":"crystalline","def":"consisting of or containing or of the nature of crystals","ex":"granite is crystalline","say":"KRIH-stuh-leyen","hook":"CRYSTALline has DOUBLE L — the crystal structure is so perfect it needs two L's standing in line."}]},{"title":"-ough: Six Pronunciations","category":"Spelling Rules & Patterns","difficulty":"hard","concept":"The most notoriously irregular spelling pattern in English: -ough represents six distinct sounds with no sound-based rule for which applies. Memorizing the words by sound group is the only reliable strategy.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>THOROUGH</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> THUR-oh\n<b>Spell it.</b> T · H · O · R · O · U · G · H\n<b>Say it again.</b> THUR-oh\n<b>Syllables.</b> ther · ow\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [THUR=THOR] [oh=OUGH]\n<b>Exception.</b> -ough = /oh/ here (the thorough/borough group); -th = /th/; silent gh; stress: THUR-oh\n<b>Origin.</b> Old English\n<b>Root.</b> Old English þuruh = through, complete","cards":[{"title":"Group 1 — /oh/ (rhymes with \"go\")","body":"Though (conjunction), although, dough (bread dough), furlough (temporary leave), thorough (complete — also pronounced /thur-oh/). Mnemonic: though the dough rises, the soldier on furlough is thorough."},{"title":"Group 2 — /oo/ and /uf/","body":"/oo/ (rhymes with \"true\"): through (from one side to the other), slough (a swamp in American English). /uf/ (rhymes with \"stuff\"): rough, tough, enough, slough (to shed skin). ⚠️ Slough has TWO pronunciations with TWO meanings — /sloo/ = swamp, /sluf/ = shed skin."},{"title":"Group 3 — /aw/ and /of/","body":"/aw/ (rhymes with \"law\"): thought, bought, fought, ought, nought (zero), wrought (shaped by work), distraught (extremely upset), onslaught. /of/ (rhymes with \"off\"): cough, trough (a feeding container). The /aw/ group is the largest."},{"title":"Group 4 — /up/ and Outliers","body":"/up/: hiccough = an old spelling of hiccup — the -ough is historically irregular even here. Borough = /BUR-oh/. Thorough = /THUR-oh/. These end in -ough but sound like -oh. They share the /oh/ group pronunciation but are worth noting separately because of spelling-pronunciation mismatch."},{"title":"Bee Strategy for -ough Words","body":"When you hear a word and suspect -ough, ask for the definition and origin. Old English origin + /aw/ sound → almost certainly -ough (thought, bought). /uf/ sound in a short word → -ough (rough, tough). /oh/ sound → could be -ough (though) or -ow (low). Definition distinguishes. Spell the gh — it is always there, always silent."}],"words":[{"w":"thought","def":"the content of cognition; the main thing you are thinking about","ex":"it was not a good idea","say":"THAWT","hook":"THOUGHT contains 'ought' — you OUGHT to think (thought) before you speak."},{"w":"bought","def":"obtain by purchase; acquire by means of a financial transaction","ex":"The family purchased a new car","say":"BAHT","hook":"You BOUGHT it with cash and got a silent 'ugh' deal — no 'a', just 'ou' like you 'ought' to remember."},{"w":"fought","def":"be engaged in a fight; carry on a fight","ex":"the tribesmen fought each other","say":"FAWT","hook":"He FOUGHT and OUGHT to have won — FOUGHT rhymes with OUGHT, spelling it right."},{"w":"ought","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"wrought","def":"exert oneself by doing mental or physical work for a purpose or out of necessity","ex":"I will work hard to improve my grades","say":"RAWT","hook":"WROUGHT iron is worked metal — remember the silent W and tricky -OUGHT by thinking 'Workers WROUGHT it.'"},{"w":"distraught","def":"means deeply agitated","ex":"distraught with grief","say":"d-ih-s-t-r-AW-t","hook":"DISTRAUGHT — the GH is silent but the emotion is not; the AU combination sounds like AW in 'awful.'"},{"w":"onslaught","def":"a sudden and severe onset of trouble","ex":"the attack began at dawn","say":"AW-nslawt","hook":"ONSLAUGHT — remember the AUGHT at the end like 'caught' or 'taught'; the attack CAUGHT everyone off guard."},{"w":"rough","def":"the part of a golf course bordering the fairway where the grass is not cut short","ex":"trees with rough bark","say":"RUHF","hook":"ROUGH has a tricky OUGH that sounds like UFF — think 'it's ROUGH enough to trip you up with that spelling.'"},{"w":"tough","def":"someone who learned to fight in the streets rather than being formally trained in the sport of boxing","ex":"The tough from the rougher side of the city swaggered into the gym, but the experienced boxing coach recognized immediately that real skill, not street fighting, would be needed to win any match.","say":"TUHF","hook":"TOUGH has a silent GH — even its spelling puts up a fight."},{"w":"enough","def":"an adequate quantity; a quantity that is large enough to achieve a purpose","ex":"enough is as good as a feast","say":"ih-NUHF","hook":"ENOUGH ends in OUGH — say 'ee-NUFF' but write the tricky -ough like 'tough.'"},{"w":"through","def":"having finished or arrived at completion","ex":"certain to make history before he's done","say":"THROO","hook":"THROUGH is TOUGH to spell — just remember: THR + OUGH, like ROUGH but with a TH in front."},{"w":"though","def":"(postpositive) however","ex":"it might be unpleasant, though","say":"THOH","hook":"'Though' looks like 'through' lost its 'r' — it's a long spelling for a word that means 'even so.'"},{"w":"although","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"dough","def":"a flour mixture stiff enough to knead or roll","ex":"She punched and folded the springy dough on the floured countertop until it was perfectly smooth.","say":"DOH","hook":"DOUGH ends in -OUGH and rhymes with 'go' — think: 'I knead DOUGH, though it's tough to spell.'"},{"w":"furlough","def":"is a leave of absence granted to an enlisted person","ex":"She was laid off together with hundreds of other workers when the company downsized","say":"f-UR-l-oh","hook":"FURLOUGH has a tricky -ough ending — think of a soldier saying 'enough! I need a leave!' (-ough like 'enough')."},{"w":"cough","def":"is to expel air through the lungs harshly often violently","ex":"The smoker coughs all day","say":"k-AH-f","hook":"A ROUGH cough is TOUGH enough — all three share the '-ough' that sounds like '-uff'."},{"w":"trough","def":"a narrow depression (as in the earth or between ocean waves or in the ocean bed)","ex":"The farmer filled the wooden trough with fresh water so the horses could drink after their long ride.","say":"TRAWF","hook":"TROUGH sounds like TROFF but is spelled with -OUGH — think of a ROUGH wooden TROUGH: rOUGH/trOUGH."},{"w":"thorough","def":"painstakingly careful and accurate","ex":"our accountant is thorough","say":"THUR-oh","hook":"'Thorough' hides 'though' inside — you must go THROUGH the whole word: t-h-o-r-o-u-g-h."},{"w":"borough","def":"one of the administrative divisions of a large city","ex":"Brooklyn is one of the five boroughs that make up New York City.","say":"BUR-oh","hook":"BOROUGH has a tricky -OUGH ending — a BOROUGH is a BURROW of citizens dug into city government."}]},{"title":"Medical Body Systems Vocabulary","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Medical vocabulary follows a strict pattern: Greek or Latin body-part root + Greek suffix = a medical term. Once you know the six major body-system roots and the handful of suffixes, you can decode any medical word.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>GASTROINTESTINAL</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ga-stroh-ih-NTEH-stuh-nuhl\n<b>Spell it.</b> G · A · S · T · R · O · I · N · T · E · S · T · I · N · A · L\n<b>Say it again.</b> ga-stroh-ih-NTEH-stuh-nuhl\n<b>Syllables.</b> gae · strow · ih · nteh · stah · nah · l\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [gas=GAS] [troh=TRO] [in=IN] [TES=TES] [tuh=TI] [nul=NAL]\n<b>Exception.</b> gastro- = stomach; intestin- = intestines; -al = adjective suffix; 6 syllables; gas-troh-in-TES-tuh-nul\n<b>Origin.</b> Greek\n<b>Root.</b> Greek gaster = stomach + Latin intestinum = intestine","cards":[{"title":"Cardio (Heart)","body":"Cardiovascular = heart + blood vessels. Myocardial (myo- = muscle) = relating to the heart muscle. Pericarditis = inflammation of the membrane around the heart. Electrocardiogram (EKG) = electro- + cardio- + -gram = 17 letters that all follow Greek spelling rules perfectly."},{"title":"Neuro (Brain/Nerve)","body":"Neurological = relating to the nervous system. Neurotransmitter = chemical messenger between nerves. Encephalitis (encephalo- = brain) = brain inflammation. Meningitis (meninges = membranes around brain) = inflammation of brain membranes. Every -itis = inflammation; every neuro- = nerve."},{"title":"Gastro (Stomach/Gut)","body":"Gastrointestinal = stomach + intestines. Gastroenterology = gastro- + entero- (intestine) + -logy = the study of the digestive system. Esophagus (oisophagos = food carrier) = the food tube. Peristalsis (peri- = around + stalsis = contraction) = the wave motion of the gut."},{"title":"Pulmo (Lung) & Hema (Blood)","body":"Pulmonary (pulmo = lung) = relating to the lungs. Pneumonia (pneumon = lung) = lung inflammation. Hematopoiesis (hemato- = blood + poiesis = making) = making blood cells in the bone marrow. Hemoglobin = the oxygen-carrying blood protein. ⚠️ Pneumonia has a silent p — P-N-E-U-M-O-N-I-A."},{"title":"The Spell-It System","body":"Every medical term = [body part] + [what is happening]. Hepatitis (hepato- = liver + -itis) = liver inflammation. Nephrology (nephro- = kidney + -logy) = study of kidneys. Ophthalmoscopy (ophthalmos- + -scopy) = examination of the eye. Learn the part + the suffix = decode any medical word."}],"words":[{"w":"cardiovascular","def":"of or pertaining to or involving the heart and blood vessels","ex":"cardiovascular conditioning","say":"kah-rdee-oh-VA-skyuh-ler","hook":"CARDIOVASCULAR — your heart pumps through VASCUlar tubes; no extra A sneaks into VASCUL."},{"w":"myocardial","def":"of or relating to the myocardium","ex":"The doctor explained that a myocardial infarction is the medical term for what most people call a heart attack.","say":"meye-uh-KAH-rdee-uhl","hook":"A MYOCARDIAL event targets the heart muscle — end it with -IAL like 'trial of the heart.'"},{"w":"electrocardiogram","def":"a graphical recording of the cardiac cycle produced by an electrocardiograph","ex":"The doctor studied the electrocardiogram carefully to check whether the patient's heartbeat was regular.","say":"ih-leh-ktroh-KAH-rdee-uh-gram","hook":"An ELECTROCARDIOGRAM is an ELECTRO-CARDIO-GRAM: electricity + heart + graph — three Greek parts, one life-saving word."},{"w":"neurological","def":"of or relating to or used in or practicing neurology","ex":"neurological evidence","say":"nuu-ruh-LAH-jih-kuhl","hook":"A NEUROn's LOGICal path through the brain makes it NEUROLOGICAl."},{"w":"neurotransmitter","def":"a neurochemical that transmits nerve impulses across a synapse","ex":"Dopamine is a neurotransmitter that plays a key role in how we feel pleasure and stay motivated.","say":"nyoor-oh-TRANZ-mit-er","hook":"NEURO + TRANSMITTER: a TRANSMITTER sends signals — a NEUROTRANSMITTER sends signals between nerve cells, spelled by joining both."},{"w":"encephalitis","def":"inflammation of the brain usually caused by a virus; symptoms include headache and neck pain and drowsiness and nausea and fever (`phrenitis' is no longer in scientific use)","ex":"After contracting the mosquito-borne virus, the hiker was hospitalized with encephalitis, which caused severe headaches and confusion.","say":"eh-nseh-fuh-LEYE-tuhs","hook":"Think 'en-CEPH-al' — the cephalopod uses its brain, and this is brain inflammation"},{"w":"meningitis","def":"infectious disease characterized by inflammation of the meninges (the tissues that surround the brain or spinal cord) usually caused by a bacterial infection; symptoms include headache and stiff neck and fever and nausea","ex":"The school nurse urged all parents to vaccinate their children against meningitis before the new semester began.","say":"meh-nuh-NJEYE-tuhs","hook":"MEN-IN-GI-TIS: the inflammation that gets INTO the brain's membrane IS serious."},{"w":"gastrointestinal","def":"of or relating to the stomach and intestines","ex":"a gastrointestinal disorder","say":"ga-stroh-ih-NTEH-stuh-nuhl","hook":"GASTRO+INTESTINAL: your GASTRO tract leads INTO your INTESTINES — the word maps the journey."},{"w":"gastroenterology","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"esophagus","def":"the passage between the pharynx and the stomach","ex":"When you swallow food, it travels down the esophagus and into your stomach within just a few seconds.","say":"ih-SAH-fuh-guhs","hook":"Your ESOPHAGUS carries food—ESO(inside)+PHAG(eat)+US; it ends in -US not -OUS, because one tube, not an adjective."},{"w":"peristalsis","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"pulmonary","def":"relating to or affecting the lungs","ex":"After the doctor reviewed the X-rays, she explained that the pulmonary infection had spread to both lungs and would require a full course of strong antibiotics to treat.","say":"PUU-lmuh-neh-ree","hook":"PULMOnary: your PULMOn (lung) needs air — don't leave out the 'o' before '-ary'."},{"w":"pneumonia","def":"is inflammation of the lungs with congestion","ex":"After being caught in the freezing rain for hours, she developed pneumonia and had to be hospitalized.","say":"n-oo-m-OH-n-y-uh","hook":"PNEUMonia attacks the lungs — the silent P-N-E-U-M is the hardest part; picture a PNEUMATIC pump filling diseased lungs."},{"w":"hematopoiesis","def":"the formation of blood cells in the living body (especially in the bone marrow)","ex":"Doctors studied the patient's hematopoiesis to understand why his red blood cell count was so low.","say":"hee-mat-oh-poy-EE-sis","hook":"HEMATO (blood) + POIESIS (making) — your bones MAKE blood through hematopoiESIS."},{"w":"hemoglobin","def":"a hemoprotein composed of globin and heme that gives red blood cells their characteristic color; function primarily to transport oxygen from the lungs to the body tissues","ex":"fish have simpler hemoglobin than mammals","say":"hee-muh-GLOH-buhn","hook":"HEMOGLOBin: a GLOBe of iron in your blood that grabs oxygen — end it with -IN like a protein."},{"w":"hepatitis","def":"inflammation of the liver caused by a virus or a toxin","ex":"The doctor explained that hepatitis can damage the liver if it is not treated quickly.","say":"heh-puh-TEYE-tuhs","hook":"HepaTITIS ends in -ITIS like all inflammations — the liver is on FIRE, and ITIS is the alarm."},{"w":"nephrology","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""}]},{"title":"Natural Science Vocabulary","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Science vocabulary is systematically built from Greek and Latin roots. Every term follows the pattern: process + modifier + suffix. Once you know the roots, science words spell themselves.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PHOTOSYNTHESIS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> f-oh-t-oh-s-IH-n-th-uh-s-ih-s\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · H · O · T · O · S · Y · N · T · H · E · S · I · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> f-oh-t-oh-s-IH-n-th-uh-s-ih-s\n<b>Syllables.</b> p · h · o · t · o · s · y · n · t · h · e · s · i · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [foh=PHO] [toh=TO] [SIN=SYN] [thuh=THE] [sis=SIS]\n<b>Exception.</b> photo- = light; syn- = together; -thesis = placing; -th- = /th/; ALL components Greek; 5 syllables\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Greek photos = light + synthesis = putting together","cards":[{"title":"Biology Words","body":"Photosynthesis = light + together + placing = plants converting light to food. Metamorphosis = change of form. Symbiosis = living together mutually. Mitosis (mitos = thread) = cell division where chromosomes thread through. Meiosis (meioun = to lessen) = cell division that halves chromosomes. Osmosis = passage through a membrane."},{"title":"Chemistry Words","body":"Catalysis (katalysis = dissolution) = chemical reaction facilitated by a catalyst. Electrolysis (electro- + lysis = breaking) = breaking chemical bonds with electricity. Stoichiometry (stoikheion = element + metry) = measuring chemical proportions. Exothermic = releases heat. Endothermic = absorbs heat. Covalent (co- + valent) = sharing electrons."},{"title":"Physics Words","body":"Electromagnetic = electric + magnetic fields together. Thermodynamics = thermo- + dynamis (power) = science of heat and energy. Centrifugal (centri- + fuga = flight) = fleeing from center. Centripetal (centri- + petere = seek) = seeking the center. Note: these two are opposites — fuga (flee) vs petere (seek)."},{"title":"Geology Words","body":"Sedimentary (sedimentum = settling) = rock formed from settled particles. Igneous (ignis = fire) = rock formed from volcanic fire. Metamorphic = rock changed in form by heat/pressure. Stratigraphic (stratum + graphos) = the written record of rock layers. Tectonic (tektonikos = of a builder) = relating to earth's structural plates."},{"title":"Spelling Science Words","body":"The key: always ask which language. Greek words use ph, y as vowel, ch = /k/. Latin words use -tion, -al, -ous. Photosynthesis has five Greek elements all spelled predictably. Stoichiometry = S-T-O-I-C-H-I-O-M-E-T-R-Y — break it: stoikheion + -metry. Long science words are long because they are built from multiple roots, each spelled by its own rules."}],"words":[{"w":"photosynthesis","def":"the formation of carbohydrates from carbon dioxide and a source of hydrogen in chlorophyll-containing cells","ex":"During photosynthesis, the leaves of the sunflower convert sunlight into the energy it needs to grow.","say":"f-oh-t-oh-s-IH-n-th-uh-s-ih-s","hook":"PHOTO-SYN-THE-SIS: plants use PHOTO (light) to SYN-THE-SIZE food — end it with -SIS like 'crisis.'"},{"w":"metamorphosis","def":"the marked and rapid transformation of a larva into an adult that occurs in some animals","ex":"the metamorphosis of the old house into something new and exciting","say":"meh-tuh-MAW-rfuh-suhs","hook":"metaMORPHosis: the caterpillar MORPHs through a process (-osis), not an 'a'."},{"w":"symbiosis","def":"the relation between two different species of organisms that are interdependent; each gains benefits from the other","ex":"The clownfish and the sea anemone demonstrate a classic example of symbiosis, each protecting and benefiting the other in the ocean.","say":"sih-mbeye-OH-suhs","hook":"SYMBIOsis — SYM + BIO: two species sharing one BIO(logy) class together, the perfect partnership."},{"w":"mitosis","def":"cell division in which the nucleus divides into nuclei containing the same number of chromosomes","ex":"During biology class, we watched a time-lapse video of mitosis showing one cell splitting perfectly into two identical daughter cells.","say":"my-TOH-sis","hook":"MITOSIS splits the cell — picture chromosomes as THREADS (mitos) being pulled apart: MI-TO-SIS."},{"w":"meiosis","def":"(genetics) cell division that produces reproductive cells in sexually reproducing organisms; the nucleus divides into four nuclei each containing half the chromosome number (leading to gametes in animals and spores in plants)","ex":"During the unit on genetics, the class studied how meiosis produces four unique sex cells from a single parent cell, each with half the original chromosomes.","say":"meye-OH-suhs","hook":"MEIOsis — MEIosis MEIns less; it REDUCES chromosome numbers in half like a sale cutting prices"},{"w":"osmosis","def":"(biology, chemistry) diffusion of molecules through a semipermeable membrane from a place of higher concentration to a place of lower concentration until the concentration on both sides is equal","ex":"During the science experiment, we watched osmosis pull water through the membrane into the saltier solution, causing the bag to swell.","say":"aw-ZMOH-sihs","hook":"OSMOsis — molecules are PUSHED (osmo) through a membrane"},{"w":"catalysis","def":"acceleration of a chemical reaction induced the presence of material that is chemically unchanged at the end of the reaction","ex":"of the top 50 commodity chemicals, 30 are created directly by catalysis and another 6 are made from raw materials that are catalytically produced","say":"kuh-TAL-uh-sis","hook":"CataLYSIS ends in '-lysis' like analysis — both involve breaking things DOWN systematically."},{"w":"electrolysis","def":"(chemistry) a chemical decomposition reaction produced by passing an electric current through a solution containing ions","ex":"In chemistry class, we used electrolysis to split water into hydrogen and oxygen gases.","say":"ih-leh-KTRAH-luh-suhs","hook":"ELECTROLYSIS ends in '-lysis' like ANALYSIS — both involve breaking something apart; electricity breaks down the solution."},{"w":"stoichiometry","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"electromagnetic","def":"pertaining to or exhibiting magnetism produced by electric charge in motion","ex":"electromagnetic energy","say":"ih-leh-ktroh-ma-GNEH-tihk","hook":"ELECTROMAGNETIC — the 'r' in 'electro' stays strong before 'magnetic'; electricity and magnetism are inseparable partners."},{"w":"thermodynamics","def":"the branch of physics concerned with the conversion of different forms of energy","ex":"Understanding thermodynamics helped the engineering students explain why a car engine produces so much waste heat.","say":"thur-moh-deye-NA-mihks","hook":"THERMO-DYNAM-ICS: the science (-ICS) of heat-power — no K, just a clean C before S."},{"w":"centrifugal","def":"tending to move away from a center","ex":"When the washing machine spun at full speed, the centrifugal force pushed the wet clothes outward against the drum wall, squeezing out most of the water.","say":"SEH-ntrih-fyoo-guhl","hook":"CENTRIFUGAL force FLEES the center — fugere means 'to flee,' so it FUGes away."},{"w":"centripetal","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"sedimentary","def":"resembling or containing or formed by the accumulation of sediment","ex":"sedimentary deposits","say":"seh-duh-MEH-nter-ee","hook":"Sediment settles at the bottom — remember '-ary' like 'library' where things are stored layer by layer."},{"w":"igneous","def":"produced under conditions involving intense heat","ex":"igneous rock is rock formed by solidification from a molten state; especially from molten magma","say":"IH-gnee-uhs","hook":"IGNEous rock is full of fire — IGNite and IGNEous both start with that fiery IGN."},{"w":"stratigraphic","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"tectonic","def":"of or relating to the structure, movement, and deformation of the earth's crust","ex":"The tectonic shift of the Pacific Plate occurs so slowly that humans cannot feel it, yet it reshapes continents over millions of years.","say":"teh-KTAH-nihk","hook":"TECTONic — TECT the structure of the earth's TONE layers"}]},{"title":"Fine Arts & Music Vocabulary","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Arts vocabulary draws from Italian (music), French (dance and visual arts), and Greek (theory). Knowing the language of origin immediately suggests the spelling pattern.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>CHIAROSCURO</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> —\n<b>Spell it.</b> C · H · I · A · R · O · S · C · U · R · O\n<b>Say it again.</b> —\n<b>Syllables.</b> c · h · i · a · r · o · s · c · u · r · o\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [kyar=CHIAR] [oh=O] [SKOOR=SCUR] [oh=O]\n<b>Exception.</b> Italian: chiaro = clear + oscuro = dark; -ch- = /ky/ in Italian; 4 syllables; kyar-oh-SKOOR-oh\n<b>Origin.</b> —\n<b>Root.</b> —","cards":[{"title":"Italian Music Dynamics","body":"Already covered in C47 — the key spelling pattern here is the -issimo superlative (pianissimo, fortissimo) with double-s, and the -etto/-etta diminutive (allegretto). Crescendo = C-R-E-S-C-E-N-D-O (-sc- before e = /s/). Diminuendo = D-I-M-I-N-U-E-N-D-O (from diminuere = lessen)."},{"title":"Dance Vocabulary (French)","body":"Arabesque (Arab + -esque) = in the Arabic style = a ballet position. Pirouette = a spinning turn. Plié (plier = to bend) = a bending movement. Jeté (jeter = to throw) = a leap. Pas de deux (pas = step + de + deux = two) = a dance for two. Entrechat (entre = between + chat = cat) = a jumping step crossing the legs."},{"title":"Visual Arts Terms","body":"Chiaroscuro (Italian) = light and dark contrast in painting. Impasto (Italian: impastare = to knead) = thick paint texture. Sfumato (Italian: sfumare = evaporate) = soft, hazy outlines. Pointillism (point = dot) = painting with dots of pure color. Trompe-l'oeil (French: trick the eye) = hyper-realistic painting."},{"title":"Music Theory Terms","body":"Syncopation (syn- + koptein = cut) = rhythmic emphasis on normally unaccented beats. Counterpoint (contra- + punctus = point) = independent melodic lines sounding together. Cadenza (Italian, from cadere = fall) = an elaborate solo passage near a concerto's end. Leitmotif (German: leit- = leading + Motiv) = a recurring musical theme."},{"title":"Architecture Terms","body":"Colonnade (colonna = column) = a row of columns. Corinthian, Doric, Ionic = the three Greek orders of columns. Tympanum (tympanon = drum) = the triangular space above a doorway. Buttress (French bouter = to push) = a structure built against a wall. Fenestration (fenestra = window) = the arrangement of windows in a building."}],"words":[{"w":"chiaroscuro","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"impasto","def":"painting that applies the pigment thickly so that brush or palette knife marks are visible","ex":"Van Gogh's masterful use of impasto makes his paintings look almost three-dimensional, with swirling ridges of paint you want to reach out and touch.","say":"im-PAH-stoh","hook":"IMPASTo: thick paint like thick PASTE pressed onto canvas"},{"w":"sfumato","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"pointillism","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"arabesque","def":"position in which the dancer has one leg raised behind and arms outstretched in a conventional pose","ex":"The ballerina held a flawless arabesque for several breathtaking seconds, her back leg perfectly parallel to the stage.","say":"ar-ah-BESK","hook":"Arabesque ends in -ESQUE like 'picturesque' — a beautifully posed, picture-like position."},{"w":"pirouette","def":"is a whirling about on one foot as in ballet dancing","ex":"The ballerina completed a flawless pirouette at center stage, spinning so fast she seemed to blur.","say":"p-ih-r-oo-EH","hook":"PIROUETTE has FOUR vowels in a row (ouet) — the dancer spins four times before sticking the landing."},{"w":"syncopation","def":"(phonology) the loss of sounds from within a word (as in `fo'c'sle' for `forecastle')","ex":"The jazz drummer's use of syncopation gave the music an exciting, unpredictable rhythm that made everyone want to dance.","say":"SIH-ngkuh-pay-shuhn","hook":"SYNCOPation is a COP cutting syllables — the COP in synCOPation is always on duty."},{"w":"counterpoint","def":"a musical form involving the simultaneous sound of two or more melodies","ex":"the students contrast considerably in their artistic abilities","say":"KOW-nter-poynt","hook":"Counter-POINT makes a musical POINT — POINT is spelled normally, because two melodies both make their point clearly."},{"w":"cadenza","def":"a brilliant solo passage occurring near the end of a piece of music","ex":"The violinist's cadenza left the audience breathless with its dizzying speed and breathtaking emotion.","say":"kah-DEN-zah","hook":"A cadENZA is an Italian FRENZY of solo notes — remember the Z like the zing of a violin."},{"w":"leitmotif","def":"a melodic phrase that accompanies the reappearance of a person or situation (as in Wagner's operas)","ex":"The villain's leitmotif, a low rumbling brass theme, played every time he appeared on screen.","say":"LEYE-tmoh-teef","hook":"A LEITMOTIF LEADS the motif — LEIT means 'leading,' so lead with L-E-I-T then motif."},{"w":"colonnade","def":"a series of regularly spaced columns","ex":"The tourists walked through the shaded colonnade of the ancient temple, marveling at each towering marble column.","say":"k-ah-l-uh-n-AY-d","hook":"A colonnade has double 'n'—picture two columns standing side by side, just like the double 'n'."},{"w":"tympanum","def":"the main cavity of the ear; between the eardrum and the inner ear","ex":"The doctor explained that the infection had spread to the tympanum, affecting the patient's hearing.","say":"TIH-mpuh-nuhm","hook":"TYMPANUM is the eardrum — TYM-PAN-UM, your ear is a pan that UM-plifies sound."},{"w":"buttress","def":"a support usually of stone or brick; supports the wall of a building","ex":"The medieval cathedral's stone buttress stretched outward from the tall wall like a sturdy arm, preventing the massive structure from crumbling under the enormous weight of its own roof.","say":"BUH-truhs","hook":"A BUTTRESS has a double T because it takes TWO supports to hold a wall up—and an -ess ending like 'fortress.'"},{"w":"fenestration","def":"the arrangement of windows in a building","ex":"The judge admired the fenestration of the old courthouse, where arched windows flooded every courtroom with golden afternoon light.","say":"fen-es-TRAY-shun","hook":"FENESTRA + TION — Latin fenestra means window; the -TION ending makes it the arrangement of windows."},{"w":"diminuendo","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"crescendo","def":"(music) a gradual increase in loudness","ex":"The music crescendoes here","say":"krih-SHEH-ndoh","hook":"A cresCENDO builds to CENTER stage — find the SCENE growing louder inside it."}]},{"title":"Culinary Vocabulary","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Food vocabulary is international — French dominates professional cooking, Italian contributes pasta and cheese terms, Spanish adds chili and spice words, Japanese contributes specific techniques. The spelling signals follow language of origin.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>JULIENNE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> joo-lee-EN\n<b>Spell it.</b> J · U · L · I · E · N · N · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> joo-lee-EN\n<b>Syllables.</b> ju · li · enne\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [joo=JU] [lee=LI] [EN=ENNE]\n<b>Exception.</b> French: from Julien (a proper name); -enne = French feminine ending; silent final -e; stress: joo-lee-EN\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> Named after the French given name Julien or Julie; origin of the culin","cards":[{"title":"French Cooking Terms (Professional)","body":"Julienne = vegetables cut in thin matchsticks. Brunoise = vegetables cut in tiny cubes. Mirepoix = diced onion, celery, carrot base (-oi- = /wah/ French pattern). Beurre blanc = beurre (butter) + blanc (white) = a white butter sauce. Roux (roux = reddish-brown) = a flour-butter thickening base — R-O-U-X (silent x)."},{"title":"French Pastry & Restaurant Terms","body":"Crème brûlée (brûler = burn) = burned cream. Amuse-bouche (amuser = to amuse + bouche = mouth) = a tiny appetizer. Mise en place = mise (put) + en (in) + place (place) = everything in its place before cooking. Soufflé (souffler = to blow) = a dish that puffs up. Velouté (velours = velvet) = a velvety sauce."},{"title":"Italian Food Terms","body":"Bruschetta = B-R-U-S-C-H-E-T-T-A (-sch- = /sk/ in Italian; -tt- double). Prosciutto = P-R-O-S-C-I-U-T-T-O (-sci- = /sh/ in Italian; -tt-). Ossobuco (osso = bone + buco = hole) = braised veal shanks. Risotto (riso = rice + -otto = slightly enlarged) = creamy rice dish. Carpaccio = thinly sliced raw meat."},{"title":"Spice & Ingredient Words","body":"Saffron (Arabic za'faran) = saf- → S-A-F-F-R-O-N (double-f). Turmeric = T-U-R-M-E-R-I-C (not tumeric — the first r is often omitted in speech). Cardamom = C-A-R-D-A-M-O-M (not cardamon). Worcestershire = WOO-ster-sheer (the spelling is radically longer than the pronunciation)."},{"title":"Japanese Food Terms","body":"Teriyaki (teri = gloss + yaki = grilled) = T-E-R-I-Y-A-K-I (the CV syllable pattern: no consonant clusters). Edamame (eda = branch + mame = bean) = E-D-A-M-A-M-E. Tempura = T-E-M-P-U-R-A (Portuguese origin, adopted into Japanese). Miso = M-I-S-O. Wasabi = W-A-S-A-B-I. Japanese loanwords follow the clean CV pattern."}],"words":[{"w":"julienne","def":"a vegetable cut into thin strips (usually used as a garnish)","ex":"The chef julienned the carrots and zucchini into perfectly uniform strips before arranging them in a colorful fan across the plate.","say":"joo-lee-EN","hook":"JULIENne: JULIEN the French chef cuts everything into thin strips"},{"w":"brunoise","def":"A culinary technique in which vegetables or other foods are cut into very small, uniform cubes approximately one to three millimeters on each side, used to create fine garnishes or flavor bases.","ex":"The chef's brunoise of carrots and celery was so perfectly uniform it looked machine-cut.","say":"broo-NWAZ","hook":"BRUNOISE: think 'brew noise in tiny cubes'—say bru-NWAZ, a French tiny-dice cut."},{"w":"mirepoix","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"roux","def":"a mixture of fat and flour heated and used as a basis for sauces","ex":"She whisked the roux carefully over low heat until it turned a deep golden brown before adding the broth.","say":"ROO","hook":"A ROUX sounds like 'roo' but hides an X at the end — think of a kangaroo chef making a sauce, signing with an X."},{"w":"bruschetta","def":"toasted bread rubbed with garlic and topped with olive oil, tomatoes, and herbs","ex":"At the Italian restaurant, we started with crispy bruschetta topped with fresh tomatoes and basil.","say":"broo-SKEH-tah","hook":"BRUSCHETTA has no SH — it's broo-SKET-ta; the SC makes a K sound, like a knife scraping toast."},{"w":"prosciutto","def":"Italian salt-cured ham usually sliced paper thin","ex":"The chef draped thin slices of prosciutto over the ripe melon for a classic Italian appetizer.","say":"pruh-SHOO-toh","hook":"Say it like 'pruh-SHOO-toh' — this Italian ham makes you shout SHOO as you chase people away from your plate; spell the silent C: proSCIutto."},{"w":"ossobuco","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"risotto","def":"rice cooked with broth and sprinkled with grated cheese","ex":"The chef stirred the creamy mushroom risotto slowly for twenty minutes until every grain of rice was perfectly tender.","say":"ree-SAW-toh","hook":"RISOTTO has a double T — Two stirs to cook the rice just right."},{"w":"carpaccio","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"saffron","def":"is a crocus having showy purple flowers","ex":"The chef added a pinch of saffron to the rice, turning it a beautiful golden yellow color.","say":"s-A-f-r-uh-n","hook":"SAFFRON is double 'f', single 'r' — two 'f's for the two stigmas you need to make this expensive spice."},{"w":"turmeric","def":"widely cultivated tropical plant of India having yellow flowers and a large aromatic deep yellow rhizome; source of a condiment and a yellow dye","ex":"My grandmother stirred a teaspoon of golden turmeric into the simmering soup, filling the kitchen with a warm, earthy fragrance.","say":"TUR-muh-rihk","hook":"Remember the hidden 'r': tur-MER-ic, not tu-MER-ic — there's an 'r' in the middle."},{"w":"cardamom","def":"rhizomatous herb of India having aromatic seeds used as seasoning","ex":"The warm chai tea was fragrant with cardamom, cinnamon, and ginger, filling the whole kitchen with spice.","say":"KAH-rduh-muhm","hook":"CardaMOM — your MOM puts cardaMOM in her chai; remember MOM at the end."},{"w":"worcestershire","def":"a savory sauce of vinegar and soy sauce and spices","ex":"She splashed a generous dash of Worcestershire sauce into the stew to give it a deep, tangy flavor.","say":"WUU-ster-sher","hook":"Spell WORCESTERSHIRE by parts: WORCESTER + SHIRE — the sauce is complex, so is the spelling."},{"w":"teriyaki","def":"beef or chicken or seafood marinated in spicy soy sauce and grilled or broiled","ex":"The tangy, sweet smell of teriyaki chicken sizzling on the grill drew hungry customers to the restaurant from half a block away.","say":"teh-rih-YAH-kee","hook":"TERIYAKI has one R — the glaze shines bright enough without doubling up."},{"w":"edamame","def":"young soybeans harvested while still green and tender, typically served steamed in their pods and lightly salted, popular as a snack especially in Japanese cuisine","ex":"At the Japanese restaurant, they snacked on lightly salted edamame while waiting for their sushi to arrive.","say":"ed-uh-MAH-may","hook":"EDAmame: EDA sounds like 'eat-a' — eat a bean right off the branch!"},{"w":"soufflé","def":"light fluffy dish of egg yolks and stiffly beaten egg whites mixed with e.g. cheese or fish or fruit","ex":"The chef warned us not to slam the oven door or the delicate chocolate souffle would collapse.","say":"soo-FLAY","hook":"A SOUFFLE puffs up like blowing air — it's SOUL+FLAY without the accent, light as breath."},{"w":"amuse-bouche","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""}]},{"title":"Geography & Place Words","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"easy","concept":"Geographical vocabulary draws from multiple languages — Greek for landform concepts, Spanish and Portuguese for the Americas, Arabic for Middle Eastern geography, and Old Norse for Scandinavian features. Origin signals spelling.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>ARCHIPELAGO</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ah-rkuh-PEH-luh-goh\n<b>Spell it.</b> A · R · C · H · I · P · E · L · A · G · O\n<b>Say it again.</b> ah-rkuh-PEH-luh-goh\n<b>Syllables.</b> aa · rkah · peh · lah · gow\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [ar=AR] [kih=CHI] [PEL=PEL] [uh=A] [goh=GO]\n<b>Exception.</b> Italian/Greek: arkhi- = chief + pelagos = sea; -ch- = /k/; stress: ar-kih-PEL-uh-goh\n<b>Origin.</b> Italian\n<b>Root.</b> Greek arkhi-(chief) + pelagos(sea) = chief sea (the Aegean)","cards":[{"title":"Landform Words","body":"Archipelago (arkhi- + pelagos = sea) = a group of islands in a sea. Peninsula (paene = almost + insula = island) = a land almost surrounded by water. Isthmus (isthmos = neck) = a narrow land connection = I-S-T-H-M-U-S (the th and m cluster). Escarpment = a steep slope at the edge of a plateau."},{"title":"Water Words","body":"Estuary (aestus = tide) = a tidal river mouth where fresh and salt water meet. Lagoon (Italian laguna from Latin lacuna = pool) = a shallow body of water. Fjord (Norwegian) = a narrow sea inlet between cliffs — F-J-O-R-D (the fj- cluster is pure Norse). Bayou (Native American bayuk) = a slow-moving body of water."},{"title":"Climate Zone Words","body":"Savanna (Spanish sabana from Taino) = a tropical grassland with scattered trees. Tundra (Russian from Finnish tunturi = treeless plain) = the Arctic treeless plain. Chaparral (Spanish chaparro = dwarf evergreen oak) = dense shrubby vegetation in dry climates. Taiga (Russian, from Turkic) = the vast boreal forest."},{"title":"Spanish/Portuguese Americas Words","body":"Canyon (cañón = large tube/pipe) = a deep gorge. Mesa (mesa = table) = a flat-topped hill. Arroyo (arroyo = stream) = a dry gully. Laguna = a lagoon. Pampa (Quechua pampa = plain) = the South American grassland. Many American landscape words are Spanish because Spanish explorers named them first."},{"title":"Bee Strategy for Geography","body":"Landform words from Spanish keep -ll- (armadillo, guerrilla, vanilla) or -rr- (arroyo, sierra). Norse words may have fj- or -rd endings. Greek geography words use -graph-, -scope-, -meter-. The definition + origin together point to the right spelling pattern every time."}],"words":[{"w":"archipelago","def":"a group of many islands in a large body of water","ex":"The sailors navigated carefully through the archipelago, weaving between dozens of rocky islands.","say":"ah-rkuh-PEH-luh-goh","hook":"ARCHipelago: the ARCH chief of the SEA holds many islands — spell out arch-i-pel-a-go like stepping stones between islands."},{"w":"peninsula","def":"a large mass of land projecting into a body of water","ex":"The small fishing village sat at the tip of a rocky peninsula surrounded by crashing waves on three sides.","say":"puh-NIH-nsuh-luh","hook":"A peninsula is 'almost an island' — pen+insula, one 'n', like a pen pointing into water."},{"w":"isthmus","def":"is a narrow strip of land with water on both sides","ex":"The narrow isthmus of Panama connects North America and South America by a thin strip of land.","say":"IH-s-m-uh-s","hook":"An isTHMus has a silent TH—think of it as the thin, quiet strip of land squeezed between two seas."},{"w":"escarpment","def":"a long steep slope or cliff at the edge of a plateau or ridge; usually formed by erosion","ex":"The hikers paused at the top of the escarpment to gaze over the vast valley hundreds of feet below.","say":"eh-SKAH-rpmuhnt","hook":"An esCARP ment has a CARP-shaped sharp drop — imagine a fish leaping off a cliff"},{"w":"estuary","def":"the wide part of a river where it nears the sea; fresh and salt water mix","ex":"The biology class traveled to the estuary to observe the unique mix of plants and animals that thrive where the river meets the ocean.","say":"EH-schoo-eh-ree","hook":"An ESTUary is where the ESTUS (tide) meets the river — it's a tidal mixing zone."},{"w":"lagoon","def":"is an area of shallow water separated from the sea by sandy dunes","ex":"The children snorkeled in the calm, crystal-clear lagoon sheltered by a ring of white sand.","say":"l-uh-g-OO-n","hook":"A LAGOON has double O like the two round eyes of a calm, enclosed pool of water."},{"w":"fjord","def":"a long narrow inlet of the sea between steep cliffs; common in Norway","ex":"The cruise ship sailed slowly through the majestic fjord, its towering cliffs rising straight out of the icy water.","say":"FYAWRD","hook":"FJORD starts with FJ — imagine a Freeze of ice + waves of water forming the Norwegian inlet — FJ-ORD."},{"w":"bayou","def":"is a marshy arm of a river usually sluggish or stagnant","ex":"Spanish moss hung from the cypress trees along the murky, still bayou at the edge of town.","say":"b-AY-oo","hook":"A BAYOU ends in -OU like the sound of surprise when you sink into that murky water: 'BAY-oo!'"},{"w":"savanna","def":"a flat grassland in tropical or subtropical regions","ex":"A lone cheetah sprinted across the golden savanna as a herd of zebras scattered in every direction.","say":"suh-VA-nuh","hook":"A savanna has one 'n' in the middle — one vast, open plain with nothing to crowd it."},{"w":"tundra","def":"a vast treeless plain in the Arctic regions where the subsoil is permanently frozen","ex":"The caribou migrated across the frozen tundra in a massive herd that stretched as far as the eye could see.","say":"TUH-ndruh","hook":"The TUNDRA is UNDER a frozen sky — TUNDRA hides UNDER in its letters."},{"w":"chaparral","def":"is a dense growth of shrubs or trees","ex":"The hikers pushed through dense chaparral, their legs scratched by the tough, wiry shrubs on the hillside.","say":"sh-a-p-ur-A-l","hook":"ChaPARRal has a PARR in the middle — think of PARR as a tangled thicket of letters."},{"w":"taiga","def":"The vast boreal forest biome found across northern regions of Russia, Canada, and Scandinavia, characterized by dense coniferous trees such as spruce, fir, and pine. It is the world's largest terrestrial biome and endures extremely cold winters.","ex":"The taiga stretches across northern Russia, filled with dense spruce and pine forests.","say":"TY-guh","hook":"The taiga is a vast forest — spell it T-A-I-G-A, like a tiger's cold home."},{"w":"canyon","def":"a ravine formed by a river in an area with little rainfall","ex":"Standing at the rim of the canyon, she marveled at the layers of red and orange rock carved by the river below.","say":"KA-nyuhn","hook":"A CANYON has one N in the middle — one deep groove carved by one mighty river."},{"w":"mesa","def":"flat tableland with steep edges","ex":"the tribe was relatively safe on the mesa but they had to descend into the valley for water","say":"MAY-suh","hook":"A MESA is a TABLE in Spanish — flat on top like a dining table, one 's' keeps it sleek and level."},{"w":"arroyo","def":"a stream or brook","ex":"After the desert rainstorm, the dry arroyo quickly filled with rushing water.","say":"er-OY-oh","hook":"An ARROYO has double R like a rushing river roaring through a ravine."},{"w":"pampa","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"veldt","def":"elevated open grassland in southern Africa","ex":"Lions roamed freely across the golden veldt as the African sun dipped below the hills.","say":"VELT","hook":"VELDT has a silent T at the end — like the quiet grassland itself: V-E-L-D-T."}]},{"title":"Law & Government Vocabulary","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","concept":"Legal and governmental vocabulary draws almost entirely from Latin — English law was conducted in Latin for centuries. These words follow strict Latin spelling rules and appear frequently in championship bees.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>JURISPRUDENCE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> juu-ruh-SPROO-duhns\n<b>Spell it.</b> J · U · R · I · S · P · R · U · D · E · N · C · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> juu-ruh-SPROO-duhns\n<b>Syllables.</b> jhuh · rah · spruw · dah · ns\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [joor=JU] [is=RIS] [PROO=PRU] [dens=DENCE]\n<b>Exception.</b> juris = of law + prudentia = foresight; -ence suffix; stress: joor-is-PROO-dens\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin jurisprudentia = knowledge of law, from jus = law + prudentia =","cards":[{"title":"Core Legal Latin","body":"Habeas corpus (habeas = you should have + corpus = body) = the right to appear before a court. Subpoena (sub- + poena = penalty) = under penalty = a legal demand to appear. Jurisprudence (juris = of law + prudentia) = the philosophy of law. Plenipotentiary (plenus = full + potens = powerful) = having full diplomatic power."},{"title":"Types of Government","body":"Oligarchy (oligos = few + arkhein = rule) = rule by a few. Plutocracy (ploutos = wealth + kratos) = rule by the wealthy. Theocracy (theos = god + kratos) = rule by divine authority. Kleptocracy (kleptein = steal + kratos) = rule by thieves = corrupt government. Meritocracy (meritum = earned) = rule by merit."},{"title":"Legal Process Words","body":"Adjudicate (ad- + judex = judge) = to give a judicial ruling. Promulgate (pro- + vulgare = publish) = to make known officially. Ratify (ratus + -fy) = to formally approve. Filibuster (Spanish filibustero = pirate) = obstructing legislation through extended speech. Gerrymander (from Governor Gerry + salamander) = redrawing districts for political advantage."},{"title":"Constitutional Words","body":"Plenipotentiary = a diplomat with full powers. Extraterritoriality = exemption from local law. Abrogation (ab- + rogare = ask) = repeal of a law. Promulgation = official public announcement. Bicameral (bi- + camera = chamber) = having two legislative chambers. Bicameral is the standard for most democracies."},{"title":"Spelling Legal Words","body":"Habeas corpus = H-A-B-E-A-S · C-O-R-P-U-S (two-word Latin phrase). Subpoena = S-U-B-P-O-E-N-A (sub- + poena). Jurisprudence = J-U-R-I-S-P-R-U-D-E-N-C-E (-ence). Plenipotentiary = P-L-E-N-I-P-O-T-E-N-T-I-A-R-Y. These long Latin compounds spell correctly when broken into their component roots."}],"words":[{"w":"jurisprudence","def":"the branch of philosophy concerned with the law and the principles that lead courts to make the decisions they do","ex":"civilization presupposes respect for the law","say":"juu-ruh-SPROO-duhns","hook":"JURISPRUDENCE ends in -ENCE not -ANCE — it takes PRUDENCE (wisdom) to practice jurisPRUDENCE."},{"w":"habeas corpus","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"subpoena","def":"is the usual writ for the summoning of witnesses","ex":"The witness and her records were subpoenaed","say":"s-uh-p-EE-n-uh","hook":"subPOENA has POEtic justice — the OE together means penalty is hiding in plain sight."},{"w":"plenipotentiary","def":"a diplomat who is fully authorized to represent his or her government","ex":"The plenipotentiary arrived in the capital city with the authority to sign the peace treaty on behalf of her entire nation.","say":"plen-ih-puh-TEN-shee-ehr-ee","hook":"PLENI (full) + POTENT (powerful): someone with FULL POWER to negotiate"},{"w":"adjudicate","def":"put on trial or hear a case and sit as the judge at the trial of; to make a formal judgment","ex":"The experienced judge was asked to adjudicate the dispute between the two competing robotics teams at the regional competition.","say":"uh-JOO-dih-kayt","hook":"A JUDGE adjudicates — both share judic"},{"w":"promulgate","def":"state or announce","ex":"The school board voted to promulgate new guidelines about technology use in classrooms before the new semester began.","say":"proh-MUH-lgayt","hook":"PRO-mulgators speak FORTH to make laws public"},{"w":"ratify","def":"approve and express assent, responsibility, or obligation","ex":"All parties ratified the peace treaty","say":"RA-tuh-feye","hook":"RATIFY: one T — to make (fy) something fixed (rati), r-a-t-i-f-y."},{"w":"filibuster","def":"a legislator who gives long speeches in an effort to delay or obstruct legislation that he (or she) opposes","ex":"The senator launched a filibuster that lasted nearly twelve hours, reading recipes aloud to stall the vote.","say":"FIH-luh-buh-ster","hook":"A FILIbuster BUSTS the Senate schedule — one L, like one senator talking forever."},{"w":"gerrymander","def":"is dividing election districts to suit one group or party","ex":"Critics accused the legislature of trying to gerrymander the district boundaries to guarantee their party's victory in the next election.","say":"j-EH-r-ee-m-a-n-d-ur","hook":"Governor GERRY drew a district shaped like a SALAMANDER — GERRY+mander = GERRYMANDER."},{"w":"oligarchy","def":"a political system governed by a few people","ex":"The revolution was sparked by citizens who were tired of living under an oligarchy where three wealthy families made all the laws.","say":"AH-luh-gah-rkee","hook":"OLIGARCHy — an OLIGARCH rules with FEW (oligos) in an ARCH of power."},{"w":"plutocracy","def":"a political system governed by the wealthy people","ex":"Citizens protested what they called a plutocracy, where only the wealthiest had any real power.","say":"ploo-TOK-ruh-see","hook":"PLUTO (wealth god) + CRACY (rule) — rule by PLUTO's crowd: PLUTOCRACY."},{"w":"theocracy","def":"is a form of government in which a deity is recognized as the supreme civil ruler","ex":"In a theocracy, religious leaders make the laws of the land based on sacred texts and divine authority.","say":"th-ee-AH-k-r-uh-s-ee","hook":"THEOCRACY: THEO (God) + CRACY (rule) — like DEMOcracy but God's in charge, not the DEMO."},{"w":"kleptocracy","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"meritocracy","def":"a form of social system in which power goes to those with superior intellects","ex":"In a true meritocracy, the hardest-working and most talented people rise to the top.","say":"meh-rih-TAW-kruh-see","hook":"MERITOCRACY = MERIT + OCRACY (like democracy) — those who EARN it RULE it, spelled just as it sounds."},{"w":"abrogation","def":"the act of abrogating; an official or legal cancellation","ex":"The abrogation of the old trade agreement sent shock waves through the economies of both countries.","say":"a-bruh-GAY-shuhn","hook":"Abrogation cancels laws — it's an AB-ROG-ATION, with ROG like 'rogue' tossing the law aside."},{"w":"bicameral","def":"composed of two legislative bodies","ex":"the bicameral heart of a fish","say":"by-KAM-er-ul","hook":"BICAMERAL: TWO CAMERAs in one legislature — BI + CAMERA + L, one C not two."}]},{"title":"Arabic Loanwords","category":"Loanword Language Groups","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Arabic gave English the al- prefix (Arabic \"the\") and a cluster of mathematics, astronomy, and science words. The al- is one of the most recognizable loanword signals in English.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>ALGORITHM</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> A-l-g-ur-ih-th-uh-m\n<b>Spell it.</b> A · L · G · O · R · I · T · H · M\n<b>Say it again.</b> A-l-g-ur-ih-th-uh-m\n<b>Syllables.</b> a · l · g · o · r · i · t · h · m\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [AL=AL] [guh=GO] [rith=RITHM]\n<b>Exception.</b> Arabic al- = the; al-Khwarizmi = the mathematician's name; -rithm not -rhythm; stress: AL-guh-rith-um\n<b>Origin.</b> English\n<b>Root.</b> Arabic Al-Khwarizmi = surname of 9th-century mathematician","cards":[{"title":"The al- Signal (Arabic \"the\")","body":"Arabic al- = \"the\" was absorbed with the word into English. Algebra (al-jabr = reunion of broken parts). Algorithm (al-Khwarizmi = name of mathematician). Alchemy (al-kimiya = the transformation). Almanac (al-manakh = the calendar). Alcove (al-qubba = the vault). The al- beginning = almost certainly Arabic origin."},{"title":"Mathematics from Arabic","body":"Algebra, algorithm, cipher (sifr = zero), zero (sifr through Italian zefiro). Arabs preserved and advanced Greek mathematics when Europe had lost it. When Europe rediscovered math through Arabic texts in the 12th century, it absorbed Arabic mathematical vocabulary wholesale."},{"title":"Astronomy from Arabic","body":"Zenith (samt = direction overhead). Nadir (nazir = opposite). Azimuth (al-samt) = a compass bearing. Aldebaran, Algol, Altair, Betelgeuse — many star names begin with Al- (= \"the star of...\"). Arabic astronomers named the stars and the names stuck."},{"title":"Chemistry & Trade from Arabic","body":"Elixir (al-iksir = the philosopher's stone). Tariff (ta'rifa = notification of price). Hazard (az-zahr = the dice). Magazine (makhazin = storehouses). Safari (safara = to travel). Assassin (hashishin = hashish users = a medieval sect). Etymology reveals medieval history."},{"title":"Spelling Arabic Loanwords","body":"The al- prefix may appear as al-, el-, or absorbed: algebra, alchemy, alcohol (al + kohl). Some lost the al-: chemistry (from alchemy), cotton (Arabic qutn). When you see al- at the start of a learned word — especially in math, astronomy, or science — consider Arabic origin and check if the al- = \"the.\""}],"words":[{"w":"algebra","def":"the mathematics of generalized arithmetical operations","ex":"Once she understood how to solve for x, algebra suddenly seemed far less frightening than it had before.","say":"A-ljuh-bruh","hook":"AL-GE-BRA: algebra reunites broken numbers — spell it straight: a-l-g-e-b-r-a, no extra 'e'."},{"w":"algorithm","def":"is a set of rules for solving a problem","ex":"The computer scientist designed an algorithm that could sort thousands of names in less than a second.","say":"A-l-g-ur-ih-th-uh-m","hook":"ALGORITHm contains ARITH as in ARITHmetic — a math rule has math in its spelling!"},{"w":"alchemy","def":"the way two individuals relate to each other","ex":"their chemistry was wrong from the beginning -- they hated each other","say":"A-lkuh-mee","hook":"ALCHemy has an ITCH in the middle — transforming metals is an itchy business."},{"w":"almanac","def":"an annual publication including weather forecasts and other miscellaneous information arranged according to the calendar of a given year","ex":"Farmer Greta checked the almanac every January to plan which crops to plant each month.","say":"AH-lmuh-nak","hook":"AL-MA-NAC: 'ALL MAN needs A Calendar' — an almanac tells everyone the dates."},{"w":"alcove","def":"a small recess opening off a larger room","ex":"She curled up in the cozy alcove with a book while the storm raged outside.","say":"A-lkohv","hook":"An ALCOVe is like a COVE tucked inside a room — end it with a silent E like a cave."},{"w":"zenith","def":"the point above the observer that is directly opposite the nadir on the imaginary sphere against which celestial bodies appear to be projected","ex":"At noon in midsummer, the blazing sun hung near its zenith, casting almost no shadow on the ground below.","say":"ZEE-nuhth","hook":"At the ZENITH, the sun shines on your ZEN forehead — Z-E-N-I-T-H, straight overhead."},{"w":"nadir","def":"an extreme state of adversity; the lowest point of anything","ex":"Failing the championship match felt like the nadir of his athletic career, but he vowed to come back stronger.","say":"NAY-der","hook":"NADIR — the lowest point; NADiR, think 'NADir Is Rock-bottom,' ends in -ir not -ier."},{"w":"azimuth","def":"is the angle of horizontal deviation of a bearing","ex":"The navigator carefully calculated the azimuth to ensure the ship was heading in the correct direction across the open sea.","say":"AZ-uh-muth","hook":"AZIMUTH ends in -UTH like 'truth' — the TRUE horizontal angle to your target."},{"w":"elixir","def":"a sweet flavored liquid (usually containing a small amount of alcohol) used in compounding medicines to be taken by mouth in order to mask an unpleasant taste","ex":"The old herbalist claimed his elixir could cure a cold in just one day.","say":"ih-LIH-kser","hook":"An ELIXIR ends in '-ir' not '-er' — remember: it's a magic liquid, and magic words end in '-ir' like 'flair'."},{"w":"tariff","def":"is a list showing duties imposed on imports or exports","ex":"they signed a treaty to lower duties on trade between their countries","say":"t-EH-r-uh-f","hook":"A tarIFF has one R and double F—the government takes a FiFth with two F's."},{"w":"hazard","def":"a source of danger; a possibility of incurring loss or misfortune","ex":"drinking alcohol is a health hazard","say":"HA-zerd","hook":"A HAZard is a DANGER—there's only one Z in hazard, just as one bad roll of the dice is enough."},{"w":"magazine","def":"a periodic publication containing pictures and stories and articles of interest to those who purchase it or subscribe to it","ex":"it takes several years before a magazine starts to break even or make money","say":"MA-guh-zeen","hook":"A MAGAZINE is a storehouse of stories — remember it's MAGA-ZINE, not maga-ZINE with an I."},{"w":"safari","def":"an overland journey by hunters (especially in Africa)","ex":"On their African safari, the family spotted a pride of lions resting under an acacia tree.","say":"suh-FAH-ree","hook":"On SAFARI you travel FAR — the word 'FAR' hides inside sAFARi, reminding you it's one 'f', not two."},{"w":"assassin","def":"is a murderer especially in politics","ex":"his assassins were hunted down like animals","say":"uh-s-A-s-uh-n","hook":"ASSASSIN has two double-S pairs — remember: ASS-ASS-IN, with two 'donkeys' charging in!"},{"w":"alcohol","def":"a liquor or brew containing alcohol as the active agent","ex":"alcohol (or drink) ruined him","say":"A-lkuh-hahl","hook":"ALCOHOL: remember AL always COHabits with OL — al-co-hol."},{"w":"cipher","def":"a message written in a secret code","ex":"it looked like nothing I had ever seen before","say":"SEYE-fer","hook":"CIPHER starts with 'ci' not 'cy' — the secret code hides an 'i,' not a 'y'."}]},{"title":"Spanish Loanwords","category":"Loanword Language Groups","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Spanish gave English its American landscape vocabulary, animal names, and food words. The signature patterns: -illo/-illa diminutives, ll = /y/ sound, and j = /h/ sound.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>GUERRILLA</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ger-IH-luh\n<b>Spell it.</b> G · U · E · R · R · I · L · L · A\n<b>Say it again.</b> ger-IH-luh\n<b>Syllables.</b> guer · ril · la\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [guh=GUER] [RIL=RIL] [uh=LA]\n<b>Exception.</b> Spanish guerra = war + -illa = little; double-R AND double-L; stress: guh-RIL-uh\n<b>Origin.</b> Spanish\n<b>Root.</b> Spanish guerra = war + diminutive -illa (little war)","cards":[{"title":"The -illo/-illa Diminutive","body":"Spanish -illo/-illa = small version (diminutive). Armadillo (armado = armored + -illo = small armored one). Guerrilla (guerra = war + -illa = small war = irregular warfare). Vanilla (vaina = pod + -illa = small pod). Peccadillo (pecado = sin + -illo = small sin = a minor fault). Sarsaparilla = the long drink name."},{"title":"American Landscape & Animals","body":"Canyon (from cañón = large tube). Armadillo = the armored animal. Alligator (from el lagarto = the lizard). Mosquito (mosca = fly + -ito = small fly). Cockroach (cucaracha). Tornado (tornada = thunderstorm). Hacienda = a large estate. Sierra = a jagged mountain range. Rodeo = rodear = to go around."},{"title":"Food from Spanish","body":"Chocolate (from Nahuatl xocolatl through Spanish). Tomato (from Nahuatl tomatl). Avocado (from Nahuatl ahuacatl). Chili (chilli in Nahuatl). Tortilla (torta = cake + -illa = small cake). These passed through Spanish from indigenous American languages — double linguistic heritage."},{"title":"ll = /y/ and Other Sounds","body":"In Spanish, ll = /y/ sound: tortilla = /tor-TEE-yuh/. Guerrilla = /guh-RIL-uh/ (in English, the double-l sounds as /l/). The j = /h/ in Spanish: jalapeño = /hah-luh-PAY-nyoh/. Junta = /HUN-tuh or /JUN-tuh in English. These original Spanish sounds change as words enter English."},{"title":"Spelling Spanish Loanwords","body":"Guerrilla = G-U-E-R-R-I-L-L-A (double-r AND double-l). Armadillo = A-R-M-A-D-I-L-L-O (double-l). Sarsaparilla = S-A-R-S-A-P-A-R-I-L-L-A (double-l). Mosquito = M-O-S-Q-U-I-T-O (qu = /k/ before i). Vanilla = V-A-N-I-L-L-A (double-l). The double-ll is the most consistent Spanish spelling signal in English loanwords."}],"words":[{"w":"guerrilla","def":"a member of an irregular armed force that fights a stronger force by sabotage and harassment","ex":"The guerrilla fighters used their knowledge of the jungle terrain to launch surprise raids and then vanish before the larger army could respond.","say":"ger-IH-luh","hook":"Two r's and two l's—guerrilla warfare is doubly intense"},{"w":"armadillo","def":"burrowing chiefly nocturnal mammal with body covered with strong horny plates","ex":"The armadillo curled into a tight ball when it sensed danger, relying on its tough armored shell for protection.","say":"ah-rmuh-DIH-loh","hook":"armaDILLo — the armored animal that DRILLS into dirt"},{"w":"vanilla","def":"is as in the flavor","ex":"he liked vanilla ice cream","say":"v-uh-n-IH-l-uh","hook":"VaNILLa has two L's, just like the TALL vanilla bean pods standing side by side."},{"w":"peccadillo","def":"is a very minor or slight sin or offense","ex":"Forgetting to return a library book on time is a peccadillo, not a crime worth losing sleep over.","say":"peh-kuh-DIL-oh","hook":"A PECCADILLO is a little sin — it ends in DILLO like an armaDILLO, a small creature just like a small offense."},{"w":"sarsaparilla","def":"is a soft drink made from the extract of a root","ex":"The old-fashioned soda shop served a frothy glass of sarsaparilla that tasted like something from another era.","say":"sas-puh-RIL-uh","hook":"SARSaparilla: think 'SARS-a-pa-RILLA' — four punchy syllables like a drum roll on a soda fountain counter."},{"w":"canyon","def":"a ravine formed by a river in an area with little rainfall","ex":"Standing at the rim of the canyon, she marveled at the layers of red and orange rock carved by the river below.","say":"KA-nyuhn","hook":"A CANYON has one N in the middle — one deep groove carved by one mighty river."},{"w":"mosquito","def":"two-winged insect whose female has a long proboscis to pierce the skin and suck the blood of humans and animals","ex":"One mosquito sneaked through the torn screen and kept the whole cabin awake with its whining buzz.","say":"m-uh-s-k-EE-t-oh","hook":"A mosquito has a QUI in the middle — quite annoying!"},{"w":"tornado","def":"a localized and violently destructive windstorm occurring over land characterized by a funnel-shaped cloud extending toward the ground","ex":"The tornado tore through the small town in minutes, uprooting trees and flipping cars like toys.","say":"taw-RNAY-doh","hook":"A torNADO makes you say 'NO!' — spell it with an A: tornAdo, not tornEdo."},{"w":"hacienda","def":"a large estate in Spanish-speaking countries","ex":"The old hacienda had whitewashed walls, a central courtyard fountain, and orange trees that scented the evening air.","say":"ha-see-EH-nduh","hook":"A hacienda has a C in the middle: ha-CI-enda — the big C stands for the Central estate."},{"w":"sierra","def":"a range of mountains (usually with jagged peaks and irregular outline)","ex":"The hikers gazed up at the jagged sierra silhouetted against the deep orange sky at sunset.","say":"see-EH-ruh","hook":"A SIERRA has jagged peaks like a saw — double R like two sharp teeth cutting the skyline."},{"w":"rodeo","def":"an exhibition of cowboy skills","ex":"The crowd cheered wildly at the rodeo when the cowboy stayed on the bucking bronco for eight seconds.","say":"ROH-dee-oh","hook":"RODEO ends in -eo like VIDEO — watch the cowboy video at the rodeo."},{"w":"alligator","def":"leather made from alligator's hide","ex":"The alligator slid silently off the muddy bank and disappeared beneath the surface of the swamp.","say":"A-luh-gay-ter","hook":"An ALLIGATOR ends in -OR like a predatOR — not -er!"},{"w":"chocolate","def":"a beverage made from cocoa powder and milk and sugar; usually drunk hot","ex":"After building a snowman, the children rushed inside for mugs of steaming hot chocolate topped with marshmallows.","say":"CHAW-kluht","hook":"CHOCO-LATE: you stayed up LATE eating CHOCO — spell out all three syllables: CHOC-O-LATE."},{"w":"tomato","def":"mildly acid red or yellow pulpy fruit eaten as a vegetable","ex":"She sliced a sun-warmed tomato from her garden and layered it onto the sandwich with fresh basil.","say":"tuh-MAY-toh","hook":"A tomATO ends in A-T-O — no E, it's not a potato!"},{"w":"avocado","def":"a pear-shaped tropical fruit with green or blackish skin and rich yellowish pulp enclosing a single large seed","ex":"She mashed a ripe avocado with lime juice and salt to make a creamy guacamole.","say":"a-vuh-KAH-doh","hook":"AVOcado: the 'o' comes BEFORE the 'a' — think AVO, not AVA."},{"w":"tortilla","def":"thin unleavened pancake made from cornmeal or wheat flour","ex":"She warmed each corn tortilla directly over the gas flame until it blistered with small charred spots.","say":"taw-RTEE-uh","hook":"A tortILLA has a double L — two flat rounds, just like two tortillas stacked together."},{"w":"jalapeño","def":"plant bearing very hot and finely tapering long peppers; usually red","ex":"She sliced a fresh jalapeno for the salsa, then accidentally touched her eye and spent the next ten minutes at the sink.","say":"ha-luh-PEE-nyoh","hook":"A JALAPENO makes you go 'AH' — J-A-L-A-P-E-N-O, scream each letter with heat."}]},{"title":"Japanese Loanwords","category":"Loanword Language Groups","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Japanese loanwords in English are recognizable by their clean alternating consonant-vowel (CV) syllable structure — no consonant clusters, always ending in a vowel (or n). They look and sound completely unlike Latin or Greek words.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>TSUNAMI</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> tsoo-NAH-mee\n<b>Spell it.</b> T · S · U · N · A · M · I\n<b>Say it again.</b> tsoo-NAH-mee\n<b>Syllables.</b> tsuw · naa · miy\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [tsoo=TSU] [NAH=NA] [mee=MI]\n<b>Exception.</b> Japanese: tsu = harbor + nami = wave; ts- cluster unusual in English; stress: tsoo-NAH-mee\n<b>Origin.</b> Japanese\n<b>Root.</b> Japanese tsu = harbor + nami = wave","cards":[{"title":"The CV Pattern","body":"Japanese syllables are consonant + vowel: ka, ki, ku, ke, ko; sa, si, su.... English loanwords from Japanese keep this structure: karate = ka·ra·te (3 CV syllables). origami = o·ri·ga·mi (4 CV syllables). tsunami = tsu·na·mi (the ts- is unusual in English — it is a single Japanese sound tsu)."},{"title":"Nature & Disaster Words","body":"Tsunami (tsu = harbor + nami = wave) = a harbor wave = a large seismic ocean wave. Typhoon (taifu = big wind, itself from Chinese taifeng) = T-Y-P-H-O-O-N (ph here is from Greek influence via English, NOT the original Japanese). Futon (futo = thick + ton = a roll) = a rolled sleeping mat."},{"title":"Arts & Culture Words","body":"Haiku (hai = amusement + ku = verse) = H-A-I-K-U (4 letters, 2 syllables). Origami (ori = fold + kami = paper) = O-R-I-G-A-M-I. Karaoke (kara = empty + oke = orchestra) = empty orchestra = K-A-R-A-O-K-E (4 syllables: ka·ra·o·ke). Manga (man = comic + ga = images) = M-A-N-G-A."},{"title":"Martial Arts & Food","body":"Karate (kara = empty + te = hand) = K-A-R-A-T-E. Judo (ju = gentle + do = way) = J-U-D-O. Samurai (saburau = to serve) = S-A-M-U-R-A-I. Sushi = S-U-S-H-I. Teriyaki = T-E-R-I-Y-A-K-I. Wasabi = W-A-S-A-B-I. All end in a vowel; all follow the CV pattern."},{"title":"Bee Strategy for Japanese","body":"When the pronunciation has clean alternating vowels and consonants with no clusters (except possibly ts-), and the word relates to Japanese culture, martial arts, food, or nature — spell it phonetically by CV syllable. Japanese loanwords are almost perfectly phonetic in English: what you hear is what you spell."}],"words":[{"w":"tsunami","def":"a cataclysm resulting from a destructive sea wave caused by an earthquake or volcanic eruption","ex":"a colossal tsunami destroyed the Minoan civilization in minutes","say":"tsoo-NAH-mee","hook":"TSUNAMI: the silent T hides like a wave gathering underwater — T-S-U-N-A-M-I, harbor wave."},{"w":"typhoon","def":"a tropical cyclone occurring in the western Pacific or Indian oceans","ex":"The fishermen rushed back to shore when the weather radar showed a typhoon building strength over the Pacific.","say":"teye-FOON","hook":"A TYPHOON hits with a BOOM — hear that OON at the end like the howling wind."},{"w":"origami","def":"the Japanese art of folding paper into shapes representing objects (e.g., flowers or birds)","ex":"With careful folds and creases, she transformed a single square of paper into an origami crane.","say":"aw-ree-GAH-mee","hook":"ORIGAMI: ORI folds the GAMI paper — one M only, as delicate as a paper crane."},{"w":"haiku","def":"an epigrammatic Japanese verse form of three short lines","ex":"For her class assignment, Maya wrote a haiku about the first snowfall, capturing the quiet beauty of winter in just seventeen syllables.","say":"HEYE-koo","hook":"HAIKU ends in KU — think of counting syllables: five, seven, five — KU sounds like 'coo' of a peaceful dove."},{"w":"karaoke","def":"singing popular songs accompanied by a recording of an orchestra (usually in bars or nightclubs)","ex":"Everyone cheered when Marcus grabbed the microphone at karaoke night and belted out a pop anthem.","say":"keh-ree-OH-kee","hook":"KARAOKE: an EMPTY (kara) ORCHESTRA (oke) — you fill in the singing! K-A-R-A-O-K-E."},{"w":"manga","def":"A style of Japanese comic books and graphic novels featuring distinctive artwork with expressive characters, dramatic panel layouts, and stories covering a wide range of genres for all ages.","ex":"She read three volumes of her favorite manga series before bed every Friday night.","say":"MA-ngguh","hook":"MANGA: 'MAN with a GA(p) in his comic book' — Japanese comics with dramatic panels."},{"w":"karate","def":"is a method of self-defense","ex":"After years of practice, Maya earned her black belt in karate and could break a wooden board with her hand.","say":"k-ur-AH-t-ee","hook":"KARATE = empty hand (kara+te) — your bare HAND is your weapon; ends in -te like 'tay.'"},{"w":"judo","def":"a sport adapted from jujitsu (using principles of not resisting) and similar to wrestling; developed in Japan","ex":"She earned her black belt in judo after years of dedicated practice and competition.","say":"JOO-doh","hook":"The 'gentle way' needs just two syllables: JU-DO, as smooth as a throw."},{"w":"samurai","def":"a Japanese warrior who was a member of the feudal military aristocracy","ex":"The samurai lived by a strict code of honor called bushido, which valued loyalty and bravery above all else.","say":"SA-muu-reye","hook":"SAMURAI ends in U-R-A-I — remember SAM-U-RAI: Sam, You Raise Arms Instantly."},{"w":"sushi","def":"rice (with raw fish) wrapped in seaweed","ex":"At the Japanese restaurant, Marcus tried sushi for the first time and was surprised by how fresh the salmon tasted.","say":"SOO-shee","hook":"SUSHI ends with a simple I — as clean and simple as the dish itself; no extra E needed."},{"w":"teriyaki","def":"beef or chicken or seafood marinated in spicy soy sauce and grilled or broiled","ex":"The tangy, sweet smell of teriyaki chicken sizzling on the grill drew hungry customers to the restaurant from half a block away.","say":"teh-rih-YAH-kee","hook":"TERIYAKI has one R — the glaze shines bright enough without doubling up."},{"w":"wasabi","def":"a Japanese plant of the family Cruciferae with a thick green root","ex":"The sushi chef warned that the bright green wasabi paste would clear my sinuses instantly.","say":"wuh-SAH-bee","hook":"WASABI ends in I — it makes your eyes water, so I cry!"},{"w":"futon","def":"mattress consisting of a pad of cotton batting that is used for sleeping on the floor or on a raised frame","ex":"My college dorm room had just enough space for a futon that folded into a sofa during the day.","say":"FOO-tah-n","hook":"A FUTON has one T—it's a flat bed, not a fat one, so keep it thin with one T."},{"w":"kimono","def":"a loose robe; imitated from robes originally worn by Japanese","ex":"She slipped on a silk kimono embroidered with golden cranes before sitting down to write in her journal.","say":"kuh-MOH-nuh","hook":"A KIMONO ends in O, not A — remember: you put it ON, and it ends in O!"},{"w":"tofu","def":"cheeselike food made of curdled soybean milk","ex":"She cubed the silken tofu and added it to the bubbling miso broth.","say":"TOH-foo","hook":"TOfu: TO the store for FOOd that starts with just four letters — T-O-F-U."},{"w":"ninja","def":"a member of the ninja who were trained in martial arts and hired for espionage or sabotage or assassinations; a person skilled in ninjutsu","ex":"Moving silently through the shadows, the ninja slipped past the guards and retrieved the stolen scroll.","say":"NIH-njuh","hook":"A NINJA sneaks silently — the j is the silent shadow between nin and a: n-i-n-j-a."},{"w":"anime","def":"a hard copal derived from an African tree","ex":"The craftsman used anime resin as a key ingredient in the glossy varnish he applied to the wooden cabinet.","say":"a-nih-MAY","hook":"Anime ends with just one 'e' — like a single spark of life, not two."}]},{"title":"German Loanwords","category":"Loanword Language Groups","difficulty":"hard","concept":"German words in English are often philosophical, psychological, or cultural compound nouns. They keep their German spelling completely — making them some of the most distinctive-looking words in English.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>SCHADENFREUDE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> SHA-dih-nfroyd\n<b>Spell it.</b> S · C · H · A · D · E · N · F · R · E · U · D · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> SHA-dih-nfroyd\n<b>Syllables.</b> shah · dihn · froyd\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [SHAH=SCHA] [den=DEN] [froyd=FREUDE]\n<b>Exception.</b> German: Schaden = harm + Freude = joy; -sch- = /sh/; -eu- = /oy/; silent final -e; stress: SHAH-den-froyd\n<b>Origin.</b> German\n<b>Root.</b> German Schaden=damage/harm + Freude=joy","cards":[{"title":"The -sch- Signal","body":"German sch = /sh/ sound. Words with -sch-: schadenfreude (Schaden = harm + Freude = joy = joy at another's misfortune), schnitzel (schnitt = cut = a thin breaded cutlet), kindergarten (Kinder = children + Garten = garden), schmaltz (Schmalz = rendered fat = excessively sentimental). Always sch never sh in German-origin words."},{"title":"German Compound Words","body":"German forms nouns by joining words. Zeitgeist (Zeit = time + Geist = spirit) = spirit of the age. Wanderlust (wandern = to wander + Lust = desire) = desire to travel. Weltanschauung (Welt = world + Anschauung = view) = a worldview. Doppelganger (doppel = double + Gänger = walker) = one's double/ghostly twin."},{"title":"Psychology from German","body":"Freud was Viennese (German-speaking), so psychology gives us: Angst = anxiety or dread. Gestalt (Gestalt = shape/whole) = a pattern that is more than the sum of its parts. Poltergeist (poltern = clatter + Geist = ghost) = a noisy ghost. Kitsch (Kitsch = something cheap/gaudy) = art that is sentimentally tasteless."},{"title":"Other German Words","body":"Rucksack (Rücken = back + Sack = bag) = a backpack. Pretzel (Brezel from Latin bracellus = little arms) = P-R-E-T-Z-E-L. Leitmotif (leit- = leading + Motiv) = a recurring musical theme. Hamburger = from Hamburg (the German city). Frankfurter = from Frankfurt."},{"title":"Spelling German Loanwords","body":"Schadenfreude = S-C-H-A-D-E-N-F-R-E-U-D-E. Zeitgeist = Z-E-I-T-G-E-I-S-T (-ei- = /eye/ in German). Wanderlust = W-A-N-D-E-R-L-U-S-T. Doppelganger = D-O-P-P-E-L-G-A-N-G-E-R (double-p). Poltergeist = P-O-L-T-E-R-G-E-I-S-T. Ask for origin: if German, look for sch, ei, eu, or compound-noun structure."}],"words":[{"w":"schadenfreude","def":"delight in another person's misfortune","ex":"He felt a guilty schadenfreude when his rival tripped on the way to accept the award.","say":"SHA-dih-nfroyd","hook":"SCHADEN looks like 'shaken'—you feel a shameful joy when someone else gets shaken up."},{"w":"zeitgeist","def":"the defining spirit or mood of a particular period in history as shown by the ideas and beliefs of the time","ex":"Social media, constant connectivity, and a hunger for viral fame seemed to perfectly capture the zeitgeist of the early twenty-first century.","say":"TSEYE-tgeyest","hook":"ZEITgeist: ZEIT (time) + GEIST (ghost/spirit) — the ghost of the era"},{"w":"wanderlust","def":"very strong or irresistible impulse to travel","ex":"Her wanderlust drove her to book a flight to a new country every summer.","say":"WAH-nder-luhst","hook":"WANDERlust: you LUST to WANDER — both full words hidden inside, no letters lost."},{"w":"weltanschauung","def":"a comprehensive view of the world and human life","ex":"Her travels through six continents completely changed her weltanschauung, giving her a truly global perspective.","say":"VELT-ahn-show-oong","hook":"WELTANSCHAUUNG = WELT (world) + AN + SCHAU (look) + UNG — 'world-look-ing,' your whole worldview."},{"w":"doppelganger","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"angst","def":"an acute but unspecific feeling of anxiety; usually reserved for philosophical anxiety about the world or about personal freedom","ex":"His journal was filled with teenage angst, every page heavy with worry about the future and his place in the world.","say":"AHNGKST","hook":"ANGST hides a tight cluster: A-N-G-S-T — five letters squeezed together, just like anxiety squeezes your chest."},{"w":"gestalt","def":"a configuration or pattern of elements so unified as a whole that it cannot be described merely as a sum of its parts","ex":"The artist understood that the gestalt of the mural was more powerful than any single painted figure within it.","say":"geh-SHTALT","hook":"GESTALT ends in '-alt' — ALTogether, the whole is greater than its parts: gest-ALT."},{"w":"poltergeist","def":"a ghost that announces its presence with rapping and the creation of disorder","ex":"The family blamed a poltergeist when books flew off shelves and doors slammed shut in the middle of the night.","say":"POH-lter-geyest","hook":"A POLTER-GEIST knocks and RATTLES — polter means rattle, geist means ghost; no 'ou', just ol."},{"w":"kitsch","def":"excessively garish or sentimental art; usually considered in bad taste","ex":"The souvenir shop was filled with kitsch — plastic flamingos, glittery snow globes, and neon-painted seashells.","say":"KIHCH","hook":"KITSCH has a hidden SCH at the end—German for cheap art, so picture a tacky gnome wearing a KITSCH sash."},{"w":"rucksack","def":"a bag carried by a strap on your back or shoulder","ex":"He stuffed his rucksack with trail mix, a water bottle, and a rain jacket before the hike.","say":"RUH-ksak","hook":"A RUCKSACK is a BACK-SACK — RUCK means BACK in German, so you carry it on your BACK in a SACK."},{"w":"leitmotif","def":"a melodic phrase that accompanies the reappearance of a person or situation (as in Wagner's operas)","ex":"The villain's leitmotif, a low rumbling brass theme, played every time he appeared on screen.","say":"LEYE-tmoh-teef","hook":"A LEITMOTIF LEADS the motif — LEIT means 'leading,' so lead with L-E-I-T then motif."},{"w":"kindergarten","def":"a preschool for children age 4 to 6 to prepare them for primary school","ex":"On her first day of kindergarten, Maria nervously clutched her backpack but soon joined a group building blocks.","say":"KIH-nder-gah-rtuhn","hook":"KinderGARTEN is a GARDEN for children — not a 'garden' spelled wrong!"},{"w":"schnitzel","def":"deep-fried breaded veal cutlets","ex":"During our class's cultural food day, Maya brought a platter of golden schnitzel that disappeared within minutes.","say":"SHNIT-sul","hook":"SCHNITZEL: the SCH makes a SH sound—think of SHHH it's delicious"},{"w":"schmaltz","def":"(Yiddish) excessive sentimentality in art or music","ex":"The movie was full of schmaltz, with tearful reunions and swelling violins in nearly every scene.","say":"SHMAHLTS","hook":"SCHMALTZ is greasy sentimentality—the 'sch' is slippery fat before the sappy '-maltz.'"},{"w":"pretzel","def":"glazed and salted cracker typically in the shape of a loose knot","ex":"She twisted the warm dough into the familiar knot shape before baking it into a golden, salted pretzel.","say":"PREH-tzuhl","hook":"A PRETZEL is twisted like the Z in its spelling — preTZel has a Z just like the knot's shape."},{"w":"hamburger","def":"a sandwich consisting of a fried cake of minced beef served on a bun, often with other ingredients","ex":"After the game, the whole team celebrated with a juicy hamburger and a tall glass of lemonade.","say":"HA-mber-ger","hook":"A HAMBURGER came from HAMBURG — add -ER to the city name and you get the sandwich."}]},{"title":"Sanskrit & Hindi Loanwords","category":"Loanword Language Groups","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Sanskrit gave English spiritual and philosophical vocabulary; Hindi gave everyday household words. Both tend to end in -a and use vowel-rich spellings. Many came through Portuguese or British colonial contact.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>NIRVANA</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> nih-RVAH-nuh\n<b>Spell it.</b> N · I · R · V · A · N · A\n<b>Say it again.</b> nih-RVAH-nuh\n<b>Syllables.</b> nih · rvaa · nah\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [nir=NIR] [VAH=VA] [nuh=NA]\n<b>Exception.</b> Sanskrit nir- = out + vana = blowing = the blowing out of desire; -ir- not -er-; stress: nir-VAH-nuh\n<b>Origin.</b> Sanskrit\n<b>Root.</b> Sanskrit nirvana = blowing out, extinction (of desire)","cards":[{"title":"Sanskrit Spiritual Words","body":"Nirvana = extinction of desire = liberation. Karma (karman = action) = what you do comes back. Avatar (ava = down + tara = crossing) = a deity's earthly form. Mantra (man = think + tra = tool) = sacred sound or phrase. Yoga (yuj = to unite) = union of body and mind. Dharma = cosmic law and duty."},{"title":"Hindi Everyday Words","body":"Shampoo (champo = press/massage). Bungalow (bangla = Bengali-style house with a veranda). Jungle (jangal = forest, wilderness). Thug (thag = swindler — originally a member of a criminal cult). Bandana (bandhana = tying). Loot (lut = to plunder). Dinghy (dingi = a small boat)."},{"title":"The -a Ending Pattern","body":"Sanskrit words often end in -a = /uh/: yoga, karma, mantra, dharma, chakra, mandala, nirvana. The final -a is pronounced clearly in Sanskrit — as /ah/ — but reduced to /uh/ in English. Never add -h: it is karma not karmah. The spelling is clean and phonetic."},{"title":"Juggernaut — the Dramatic Story","body":"Juggernaut = from Sanskrit Jagannatha (Jagat = world + natha = lord = Lord of the Universe). A temple cart so enormous it crushed everything before it — and people supposedly threw themselves under it. Now means any huge unstoppable force. Spelling: J-U-G-G-E-R-N-A-U-T (double-g from Anglicization)."},{"title":"Yoga Vocabulary in Bees","body":"Chakra (cakra = wheel) = C-H-A-K-R-A. Mandala (mandala = circle) = M-A-N-D-A-L-A. Pranayama (prana = breath + ayama = extension) = P-R-A-N-A-Y-A-M-A. Samsara (sam = together + sara = flowing) = the cycle of rebirth. These Sanskrit competition words follow the phonetic -a ending pattern consistently."}],"words":[{"w":"nirvana","def":"(Hinduism and Buddhism) the beatitude that transcends the cycle of reincarnation; characterized by the extinction of desire and suffering and individual consciousness","ex":"After weeks of stressful exams, sinking into a hammock with a good book felt like pure nirvana.","say":"nih-RVAH-nuh","hook":"NIRVANA starts with NIR not NER — think 'Near vana' is peace, but spell it NI-R-V-A-N-A."},{"w":"karma","def":"(Hinduism and Buddhism) the effects of a person's actions that determine his destiny in his next incarnation","ex":"When the bully tripped over his own shoelace right after knocking down someone's lunch tray, his classmates whispered, 'karma.'","say":"KAH-rmuh","hook":"KARMA starts with K — Kind Actions Revisit Me Always — K-A-R-M-A."},{"w":"avatar","def":"a new personification of a familiar idea","ex":"the embodiment of hope","say":"A-vuh-tahr","hook":"AVATAR: A Very Awesome Terrestrial Appearance Reborn — and only one A in the middle: AV-A-TAR."},{"w":"mantra","def":"a commonly repeated word or phrase","ex":"she repeated `So pleased with how its going' at intervals like a mantra","say":"MA-ntruh","hook":"A MANTRA is a tool for the MIND — M-A-N-T-R-A, no E sneaking in after the T."},{"w":"yoga","def":"Hindu discipline aimed at training the consciousness for a state of perfect spiritual insight and tranquility that is achieved through the three paths of actions and knowledge and devotion","ex":"Every morning before school, she practiced yoga in the backyard to calm her mind and stretch her muscles.","say":"YOH-guh","hook":"YOGA unites body and mind — YOke your body and soul toGether with yOGA"},{"w":"dharma","def":"basic principles of the cosmos; also: an ancient sage in Hindu mythology worshipped as a god by some lower castes","ex":"The monk spent decades studying dharma, seeking to understand the universal laws that govern all existence.","say":"DAH-rmuh","hook":"DHARMA holds the cosmos together — hold onto that 'h' right after the 'D'."},{"w":"chakra","def":"In Hindu and yogic tradition, a chakra is one of seven centers of spiritual energy believed to exist in the human body, each associated with specific physical and emotional functions.","ex":"The yoga instructor explained that focusing on each chakra can help bring the body into balance.","say":"CHUK-ruh","hook":"Chakra sounds like 'circle' — both begin with CH and a chakra is an energy circle in the body."},{"w":"mandala","def":"any of various geometric designs (usually circular) symbolizing the universe; used chiefly in Hinduism and Buddhism as an aid to meditation","ex":"The monk spent three weeks carefully arranging colored sand into an intricate mandala.","say":"MAH-duh-luh","hook":"A MANDALA is a circle: picture one 'a' at each end wrapping the word like a circular design."},{"w":"shampoo","def":"cleansing agent consisting of soaps or detergents used for washing the hair","ex":"After playing in the muddy field, he needed two rounds of shampoo to get all the dirt out of his hair.","say":"sha-MPOO","hook":"SHAMPOO ends with double-o like the two bubbles it makes — sha-m-p-o-o."},{"w":"bungalow","def":"a small house with a single story","ex":"The elderly couple retired to a cozy bungalow near the beach where they could watch sunsets from the porch.","say":"BUH-ngguh-loh","hook":"A bungalow has ONE floor and ONE L — not two L's, just one low level."},{"w":"jungle","def":"a location marked by an intense competition and struggle for survival","ex":"The explorers hacked through dense jungle for two days before spotting the ancient stone temple.","say":"JUH-ngguhl","hook":"JUNGLE ends in GLE — the vines TANGLE and MINGLE in the junGLE."},{"w":"thug","def":"an aggressive and violent young criminal","ex":"The thug lurking in the alley made the shopkeeper nervous enough to call the police.","say":"THUHG","hook":"A THUG grabs you — four letters, as short and blunt as the criminal himself: T-H-U-G."},{"w":"bandana","def":"large and brightly colored handkerchief; often used as a neckerchief","ex":"The cowboy tied a red bandana around his neck to keep the trail dust out of his mouth.","say":"ba-NDA-nuh","hook":"A BANDANA ties around your head with one N — one knot, one N."},{"w":"dinghy","def":"is a small boat designed as a lifeboat","ex":"When the sailboat began taking on water, the crew quickly lowered the dinghy and rowed toward shore.","say":"d-IH-ng-ee","hook":"A DINGHY has a hidden H like a hidden oar — D-I-N-G-H-Y, not the adjective DINGY."},{"w":"juggernaut","def":"a massive inexorable force that seems to crush everything in its way","ex":"The championship team rolled through the playoffs like a juggernaut, crushing every opponent without breaking a sweat.","say":"JUH-ger-nawt","hook":"A JUGGERnaut JUGGLES enormous power — double G for the double force crushing everything."},{"w":"pundit","def":"someone who has been admitted to membership in a scholarly field","ex":"The political pundit on television confidently predicted the election results, though he was wrong about half the time.","say":"PUH-nduht","hook":"A PUNDIT is a PUN-DIT — someone so learned they can DIT-ate on any topic!"},{"w":"loot","def":"goods or money obtained illegally","ex":"This writer plundered from famous authors","say":"LOOT","hook":"LOOT has two O's like two eyes—a thief's wide greedy eyes spotting treasure."},{"w":"samsara","def":"(Hinduism and Buddhism) the endless cycle of birth and suffering and death and rebirth","ex":"The monk spent years meditating on how to break free from the cycle of samsara.","say":"suh-MSAH-ruh","hook":"SAMSARA: SAM keeps SARA in an endless cycle — SAM-SARA, around and around forever."}]},{"title":"Norse & Old Norse Loanwords","category":"Loanword Language Groups","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Old Norse (the language of the Vikings) gave English its basic vocabulary of law, seafaring, and everyday life. Norse words often have the sk- cluster, the -th ending, and short powerful structures.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>BERSERK</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ber-SURK\n<b>Spell it.</b> B · E · R · S · E · R · K\n<b>Say it again.</b> ber-SURK\n<b>Syllables.</b> ber · ser · k\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [bur=BER] [SURK=SERK]\n<b>Exception.</b> Old Norse ber = bear + serkr = shirt = a bear-shirt warrior; -er- not -ar-; stress: bur-SURK\n<b>Origin.</b> Norse\n<b>Root.</b> Old Norse berserkr = bear-shirt warrior, from ber = bear + serkr = shi","cards":[{"title":"The sk- Signal","body":"Old Norse favored the sk- cluster where Old English used sc-: skill (skil = distinction), sky (sky = cloud), skin (skinn), skull (skalli), skirt (skyrta = shirt — related to English shirt!), skit, skate, ski. The sk- cluster is a reliable Norse signal."},{"title":"Law & Society Words from Norse","body":"Law itself is from Norse lag = that which is laid down. Outlaw (ût-lagi = outside the law). Berserk (ber = bear + serkr = shirt) = wearing a bear skin = a frenzied Viking warrior — now means wildly out of control. Ransack (rann = house + saka = seek) = search a house violently."},{"title":"Seafaring Words","body":"Starboard (stjórn = steering + borð = side) = the right side of a ship (where the steering oar was). Keel (kjölr) = the bottom spine of a ship. Gust (gustr = a cold blast). Fjord (fjörðr) = F-J-O-R-D. Sleet (slētr). Dregs (dregg). Norse sailors named the features of the sea that mattered."},{"title":"Days of the Week","body":"Tuesday (Tyr, Norse god of war), Wednesday (Wóden/Wotan, chief Norse god), Thursday (Thor, god of thunder), Friday (Frigg, goddess of love). Four of seven weekday names are Old Norse/Old English deity names. Thursday = THURS-day — Þórsdagr = Thor's day."},{"title":"Everyday Norse in Modern English","body":"Take, get, give, they, their, them — these basic pronouns came from Norse (Old English had hie, hiera, him). Egg (Norse egg, Old English had ǣg). Bag, leg, gap, odd, ugly, wrong, dirt, knife — Norse won over Old English equivalents for many everyday words."}],"words":[{"w":"berserk","def":"one of the ancient Norse warriors legendary for working themselves into a frenzy before a battle and fighting with reckless savagery and insane fury","ex":"the soldier was completely amuck","say":"ber-SURK","hook":"BERSERK — no 'z'! Norse bear-warriors wore bear-SHIRTS (serk), so spell it ber-SERK, not bez-erk."},{"w":"ransack","def":"steal goods; take as spoils","ex":"During the earthquake people looted the stores that were deserted by their owners","say":"RA-nsak","hook":"To RANSACK a room is to SCAN it with a SACK—note the double C-K at the end: R-A-N-S-A-C-K."},{"w":"outlaw","def":"someone who has committed a crime or has been legally convicted of a crime","ex":"Marijuana is criminalized in the U.S.","say":"OW-tlaw","hook":"An OUTLAW lives OUTSIDE the LAW — both words are hiding right inside."},{"w":"starboard","def":"the right side of a ship or aircraft to someone who is aboard and facing the bow or nose","ex":"The captain ordered the crew to look off the starboard side where a pod of dolphins was leaping.","say":"STAH-rberd","hook":"STAR-BOARD: the right side where sailors once steered, using a board like a rudder — steer a BOARD to the stars."},{"w":"fjord","def":"a long narrow inlet of the sea between steep cliffs; common in Norway","ex":"The cruise ship sailed slowly through the majestic fjord, its towering cliffs rising straight out of the icy water.","say":"FYAWRD","hook":"FJORD starts with FJ — imagine a Freeze of ice + waves of water forming the Norwegian inlet — FJ-ORD."},{"w":"sleet","def":"partially melted snow (or a mixture of rain and snow)","ex":"If the temperature rises above freezing, it will probably sleet","say":"SLEET","hook":"SLEET rhymes with FLEET and MEET — they all share -EET, cold and sharp like icy rain."},{"w":"dregs","def":"sediment that has settled at the bottom of a liquid","ex":"After pouring the last of the coffee, only bitter dregs remained swirling at the bottom of the pot.","say":"DREHGZ","hook":"DREGS — the bottom of the barrel has one G, not two; don't double the GG in the dregs."},{"w":"skill","def":"an ability that has been acquired by training","ex":"the skill of a well-trained boxer","say":"SKIHL","hook":"A skilled player always has two l's in their drill — skill ends in double-L."},{"w":"sky","def":"the space surrounding the earth","ex":"flip me the beachball","say":"s-k-AY","hook":"SKY is simply S-K-Y — three letters, as short and open as the sky itself."},{"w":"skull","def":"the bony skeleton of the head of vertebrates","ex":"The biology class carefully examined a model of a human skull to learn the names of each bone.","say":"SKUHL","hook":"A SKULL has two eye sockets side by side — just like the double-L at the end."},{"w":"skirt","def":"cloth covering that forms the part of a garment below the waist","ex":"She wore a flowing floral skirt that swirled around her ankles as she danced at the festival.","say":"SKURT","hook":"A SKIRT has 'irt' just like 'shirt'—they're related garments, spelled with the same ending."},{"w":"law","def":"the collection of rules imposed by authority","ex":"civilization presupposes respect for the law","say":"LAW","hook":"LAW — three letters, L-A-W, like the three branches that make it: simple and unbreakable."},{"w":"they","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"their","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"them","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"egg","def":"animal reproductive body consisting of an ovum or embryo together with nutritive and protective envelopes; especially the thin-shelled reproductive body laid by e.g. female birds","ex":"she kicked him in the balls and got away","say":"EHG","hook":"An EGG has a double G in the middle, as round and paired as two yolks."},{"w":"ugly","def":"displeasing to the senses","ex":"The beautiful mural had been painted over with a messy, ugly scrawl of graffiti that made everyone in the neighborhood feel disappointed and frustrated.","say":"UH-glee","hook":"UGLY ends in LY like most ly-words but it's an adjective — the UGly bug has a Y tail."},{"w":"wrong","def":"that which is contrary to the principles of justice or law","ex":"he feels that you are in the wrong","say":"RAWNG","hook":"It's WRONG to forget the silent W — that sneaky W is the crooked thing hiding at the start."}]},{"title":"Words About Lying & Deception (Rhetorical Terms)","category":"Advanced Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","concept":"Rhetorical vocabulary describes the techniques of persuasion, deception, and argument. From Aristotle through modern debate, these terms appear in championship bees and are built from Greek and Latin roots.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>DISSIMULATION</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> dih-sim-yoo-LAY-shun\n<b>Spell it.</b> D · I · S · S · I · M · U · L · A · T · I · O · N\n<b>Say it again.</b> dih-sim-yoo-LAY-shun\n<b>Syllables.</b> dis · sim · u · la · tion\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [dis=DIS] [sim=SIM] [yuh=U] [LAY=LA] [shun=TION]\n<b>Exception.</b> dis- + simulare = to pretend; -ation noun; dissimulate = hide true feelings; stress: dis-sim-yuh-LAY-shun\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin: atus (Latin)","cards":[{"title":"Deception Techniques","body":"Prevarication (pre- + varicare = straddle) = evasive speech. Equivocation (equi- + vox = equal voice) = deliberately ambiguous language. Dissimulation (dis- + simulare = pretend) = concealing true feelings. Obfuscation (ob- + fuscare = to darken) = deliberately making things unclear. Dissembling = disguising true motives."},{"title":"Rhetorical Figures — Saying by Not Saying","body":"Apophasis (apo- = away + phasis = speech) = mentioning something by saying you will not mention it (\"I won't mention his criminal record...\"). Litotes (litos = plain) = understatement by negation (\"not bad\" = very good). Meiosis (meioun = to lessen) = deliberate understatement."},{"title":"Figures of Emphasis","body":"Anaphora (ana- = back + phora = carrying) = repetition at the start of successive clauses. Epistrophe (epi- + strephein = turn) = repetition at the end of clauses. Chiasmus (khiasmos = diagonal arrangement) = ABBA inversion: \"Ask not what your country can do for you; ask what you can do for your country.\" Zeugma (zeugma = yoke) = one verb governing two different objects."},{"title":"Logical Fallacies","body":"Sophistry = clever but misleading argument. Solecism (Soloi = a Greek colony with bad Greek) = a grammatical error or social blunder. Malapropism = using the wrong word for a similar-sounding one. Pleonasm (pleon = more) = using more words than necessary (\"free gift,\" \"ATM machine\"). Tautology (tauto = same) = needlessly repeating the same idea."},{"title":"High-Value Bee Rhetorical Words","body":"Apophasis = A-P-O-P-H-A-S-I-S (-ph- Greek signal). Chiasmus = C-H-I-A-S-M-U-S (-ch- = /k/). Zeugma = Z-E-U-G-M-A (-eu- diphthong). Tmesis (tmesis = cutting) = inserting a word inside another word (\"what-SO-ever\") = T-M-E-S-I-S (starts with tm- — unusual cluster). Anacoluthon = a sentence that starts one way and ends another."}],"words":[{"w":"prevarication","def":"a statement that deviates from or perverts the truth","ex":"The judge grew impatient with the witness's prevarication and demanded a direct, honest answer to the question.","say":"pruh-veh-ruh-KAY-shuhn","hook":"PreVARIcation contains a VARIATION of the truth — remember VARI and -ation."},{"w":"equivocation","def":"a statement that is not literally false but that cleverly avoids an unpleasant truth","ex":"The politician's equivocation on the tax question frustrated voters who wanted a clear yes or no.","say":"ih-kwih-vuh-KAY-shuhn","hook":"EQUIVOCATION is a VOCal trick of equal deception—V-O-C sits right in the middle."},{"w":"dissimulation","def":"the act of deceiving","ex":"The spy's dissimulation was so perfect that even his closest friends suspected nothing.","say":"dih-sim-yoo-LAY-shun","hook":"DIS-SIMUL-ATION: SIMUL like simulate — simulating false feelings to deceive."},{"w":"obfuscation","def":"confusion resulting from failure to understand","ex":"The politician's obfuscation made it nearly impossible to understand his actual position on the issue.","say":"ah-bfuh-SKAY-shuhn","hook":"OBFUSCATION: the 'sc' in the middle is deliberately murky — the word itself obscures with a cloudy 'sc' combo."},{"w":"dissembling","def":"pretending with intention to deceive","ex":"He feigned that he was ill","say":"dih-SEH-mblihng","hook":"disSEMbling means hiding what you SEEM to be — double S conceals the truth just like the word conceals its meaning."},{"w":"apophasis","def":"mentioning something by saying it will not be mentioned","ex":"The politician used apophasis cleverly, saying 'I won't even bring up my opponent's tax problems' to plant the idea anyway.","say":"uh-POF-uh-sis","hook":"APO-PHASIS: 'I won't PHASE you with this — it's spelled with PH, not F, and ends in -IS.'"},{"w":"litotes","def":"understatement for rhetorical effect (especially when expressing an affirmative by negating its contrary)","ex":"saying `I was not a little upset' when you mean `I was very upset' is an example of litotes","say":"LY-tuh-teez","hook":"'Not bad at all!' — LITOTES uses a LIGHT TOUCH (lito-) to say a lot by saying less."},{"w":"chiasmus","def":"inversion in the second of two parallel phrases","ex":"The famous line 'ask not what your country can do for you' is a classic example of chiasmus.","say":"ky-AZ-mus","hook":"'Ask not what chiasmus IS, but what IS chiasmus' — the word itself inverts, starting with 'chi' like an X."},{"w":"zeugma","def":"use of a word to govern two or more words though appropriate to only one","ex":"`Mr. Pickwick took his hat and his leave' is an example of zeugma","say":"ZOOG-muh","hook":"ZEUGMA yokes two ideas — remember the U after ZE, like a yoke connecting: Z-E-U-G-M-A."},{"w":"anaphora","def":"using a pronoun or similar word instead of repeating a word used earlier","ex":"The poet used anaphora brilliantly, beginning each stanza with the same powerful phrase to build emotion.","say":"uh-NA-fer-uh","hook":"ANAPHORA carries a word back again — ana(again)+phora(carry) — like a rhetorical boomerang."},{"w":"epistrophe","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"sophistry","def":"a deliberately invalid argument displaying ingenuity in reasoning in the hope of deceiving someone","ex":"The debate judge warned that clever sophistry would not substitute for real evidence and honest reasoning.","say":"SAW-fih-stree","hook":"A SOPHIST tries to TRY to trick you with clever-sounding lies—sophisTRY ends in -TRY, not -TERY."},{"w":"solecism","def":"is a nonstandard or ungrammatical usage","ex":"Interrupting the guest speaker mid-sentence was considered a glaring solecism that made the entire audience cringe with embarrassment.","say":"SOL-ih-siz-um","hook":"A SOLECISM is a SOLE mistake in etiquette—you stand alone in your awkwardness."},{"w":"pleonasm","def":"using more words than necessary","ex":"The writing teacher circled the phrase 'free gift' on the student's essay and wrote 'pleonasm' in the margin, explaining that the word 'free' was completely unnecessary since all gifts are free.","say":"PLEE-uh-na-zuhm","hook":"PLEONASM uses more letters than needed — just like a pleonasm uses more WORDS than needed."},{"w":"tautology","def":"(logic) a statement that is necessarily true","ex":"The phrase 'a bachelor who has never been married' is a tautology, since the definition of bachelor already includes that meaning.","say":"taw-TOL-uh-jee","hook":"TAUTO means SAME so a TAUTOlogy says the same thing twice"},{"w":"tmesis","def":"A rhetorical figure in which a word or phrase is split by the insertion of another word, often for emphasis or humorous effect, as in 'abso-blooming-lutely.'","ex":"When Marcus said 'un-flipping-believable,' his English teacher recognized it as a perfect example of tmesis used for comic effect.","say":"TMEE-sis","hook":"Tmesis CUTs a word in two—just as the 't' and 'm' are unusually cut together."},{"w":"anacoluthon","def":"an abrupt change within a sentence from one syntactic structure to another","ex":"The nervous speaker used an anacoluthon mid-sentence, starting with 'When I was young—actually, forget it, the point is courage.'","say":"an-ah-koh-LOO-thon","hook":"ANACOLUTHON: ANA (not) + ACOLUTHON (following) — the sentence stops FOLLOWING its own grammatical path."}]},{"title":"Homophones (Same Sound, Different Spelling)","category":"Word Formation","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Homophones are words that sound identical but are spelled differently and mean different things. They cannot be decoded from sound alone — etymology and context are the only guides.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PRINCIPLE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> PRIH-nsuh-puhl\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · R · I · N · C · I · P · L · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> PRIH-nsuh-puhl\n<b>Syllables.</b> prih · nsah · pah · l\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [PRIN=PRIN] [suh=CI] [pul=PLE]\n<b>Exception.</b> principal vs principle: both /PRIN-suh-pul/; -al = adjective/noun (a person); -le = abstract (a rule)\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> Latin principium = beginning, foundation","cards":[{"title":"The Core Pairs","body":"Principal (the head of a school, or primary) vs Principle (a fundamental rule). Memory trick: the principal is your pal; a principle is a learned rule. Complement (complete something) vs Compliment (praise). Stationary (not moving) vs Stationery (paper products — the er in stationery = paper)."},{"title":"More Critical Pairs","body":"Affect (verb = to influence) vs Effect (noun = the result). Accept (to receive) vs Except (excluding). Elicit (to draw out) vs Illicit (not permitted). Eminent (famous, prominent) vs Imminent (about to happen). Allude (hint at) vs Elude (escape from)."},{"title":"Triple Homophones","body":"Their (belonging to them) / There (a place) / They're (they are). To (preposition) / Two (the number) / Too (also/excessively). Bare (uncovered) / Bear (the animal, or to carry). Three spellings, one sound — context is everything."},{"title":"Etymology Resolves Homophones","body":"Stationary comes from Latin stationarius = standing still. Stationery comes from stationer = a bookshop owner who had a fixed station (shop). The -er at the end of stationery comes from the stationer who sold paper. Knowing the origin makes the spelling logical."},{"title":"Disinterested vs Uninterested","body":"Disinterested = having no personal stake = impartial (a dis- = away from interest judge). Uninterested = not interested = bored (un- = simply not). These are not homophones — they sound different and mean different things — but they are the most commonly confused pair in educated writing."}],"words":[{"w":"principal","def":"the original amount of a debt on which interest is calculated","ex":"she sent unruly pupils to see the principal","say":"PRIH-nsuh-puhl","hook":"Your school PRINCIPAL is your PAL — principAL ends in A-L like PAL."},{"w":"principle","def":"a basic generalization that is accepted as true and that can be used as a basis for reasoning or conduct","ex":"their principles of composition characterized all their works","say":"PRIH-nsuh-puhl","hook":"A PRINCIPLE is a RULE — principLE ends in L-E like RULE reversed... and rules end things."},{"w":"complement","def":"a word or phrase used to complete a grammatical construction","ex":"The bright orange scarf was a perfect complement to her navy blue coat, and the grammar teacher also noted that a predicate adjective functions as a complement to the subject of a sentence.","say":"KAH-mpluh-muhnt","hook":"A complEment makEs things complEte — both have an E."},{"w":"compliment","def":"a remark (or act) expressing praise and admiration","ex":"He complimented her on her last physics paper","say":"KAH-mpluh-mehnt","hook":"A compliment is something nice said to I — remember 'complIment' has an I, because it's about ME feeling good."},{"w":"stationary","def":"standing still","ex":"the car remained stationary with the engine running","say":"STAY-shuh-neh-ree","hook":"StationARY means stAying — both have 'A'; you stAy in one plAce."},{"w":"stationery","def":"is writing paper","ex":"She chose elegant floral stationery to write her thank-you notes after the party.","say":"s-t-AY-sh-uh-n-eh-r-ee","hook":"StationERy is for lettERs — both have 'ER'; you write a lettER on stationERy."},{"w":"affect","def":"the conscious subjective aspect of feeling or emotion","ex":"Will the new rules affect me?","say":"uh-FEHKT","hook":"AFFECT starts with A — the Action word; double F, then ECT, like 'acted.'"},{"w":"effect","def":"a phenomenon that follows and is caused by some previous phenomenon","ex":"the magnetic effect was greater when the rod was lengthwise","say":"ih-FEHKT","hook":"To remember EFFECT vs AFFECT: EFFECT is the End result — both start with E."},{"w":"accept","def":"consider or hold as true","ex":"I cannot accept the dogma of this church","say":"a-KSEHPT","hook":"ACCEPT has two C's — you must take BOTH C's to accept it fully."},{"w":"except","def":"take exception to","ex":"he demurred at my suggestion to work on Saturday","say":"ih-KSEHPT","hook":"ExCEPT takes something out — the C and P are both stops, shutting things out."},{"w":"elicit","def":"call forth (emotions, feelings, and responses)","ex":"The teacher asked a surprising, thought-provoking question designed to elicit a genuine, emotional response from every student sitting quietly in the classroom.","say":"ih-LIH-siht","hook":"To ELICIT a response, you lure it out — don't confuse it with ILLICIT (illegal), which starts with two L's like 'law'."},{"w":"illicit","def":"is not legally permitted","ex":"an illicit association with his secretary","say":"ih-l-IH-s-uh-t","hook":"ILLICIT has two L's — doubly forbidden; find LICIT (permitted) inside and slap IL- in front."},{"w":"eminent","def":"standing above others in quality or position","ex":"The eminent scientist was invited to speak at universities all over the world because of her groundbreaking research.","say":"EH-muh-nuhnt","hook":"An EMINENT person stands out like a mountain EMINENCE on the horizon"},{"w":"imminent","def":"close in time; about to occur","ex":"Dark clouds gathered overhead, warning hikers that a thunderstorm was imminent.","say":"IH-muh-nuhnt","hook":"IMMINENt danger is IN MINutes away."},{"w":"allude","def":"make a more or less disguised reference to","ex":"He alluded to the problem but did not mention it","say":"uh-LOOD","hook":"To allude is to playfully hint — think of a court JESTER who PLAYS (ludere) at the truth with double l's."},{"w":"elude","def":"escape, either physically or mentally","ex":"The thief eluded the police","say":"ih-LOOD","hook":"To ELUDE is toLUDE away — slip out like a player ducking the game."},{"w":"disinterested","def":"unaffected by self-interest","ex":"A disinterested judge who had no connection to either side was chosen to resolve the dispute.","say":"dih-SIH-ntrih-stihd","hook":"DIS-INTEREST-ED means having no personal stake — only ONE 'r', unlike uninterested's twin."},{"w":"uninterested","def":"not having or showing interest","ex":"an uninterested spectator","say":"uh-NIH-ntruh-stihd","hook":"UNINterested has INTEREST in the middle — find the word 'interest' and add un- and -ed around it."}]},{"title":"Contronyms (Same Word, Opposite Meanings)","category":"Word Formation","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Contronyms (also called autoantonyms) are words with two opposite meanings. Context determines which meaning applies. English has dozens of these from centuries of word-meaning drift.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>SANCTION</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> SA-ngkshuhn\n<b>Spell it.</b> S · A · N · C · T · I · O · N\n<b>Say it again.</b> SA-ngkshuhn\n<b>Syllables.</b> sae · ngkshah · n\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [SANK=SANC] [shun=TION]\n<b>Exception.</b> Latin sancire = to make sacred; sanction = to approve OR to penalize — opposite meanings; stress: SANK-shun\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> Latin sanctio = a decree making something sacred (sanctus=holy)","cards":[{"title":"Classic Contronyms","body":"Sanction = to officially approve OR to penalize with restrictions. Cleave = to split apart OR to stick closely together. Oversight = careful supervision OR a failure to notice. Buckle = to fasten firmly OR to bend and collapse. Dust = to add dust (dusting crops) OR to remove dust (dusting furniture)."},{"title":"More Contronyms","body":"Screen = to show (screen a film) OR to hide (screen from view). Weather = to withstand (weather a storm) OR to erode (rock weathers over time). Trip = to stumble and fall OR to take a journey. Off = active (the alarm went off) OR inactive (the alarm is off). Fast = moving quickly OR stuck firmly in place."},{"title":"Contronyms in Legal Language","body":"Enjoin = to order someone to do something OR to prohibit someone from doing something. Cleave appears in wedding vows: \"cleave unto\" = hold closely together. In cooking: \"cleave the meat\" = split apart. The same word, used centuries apart, accumulated both meanings."},{"title":"Why Contronyms Exist","body":"Some developed from different etymological paths meeting in the same spelling. Sanction comes from Latin sanctio = a decree — a decree can authorize or prohibit. Cleave has TWO Old English roots: cleofan (to split) and clifian (to stick). They merged in spelling but kept opposite meanings."},{"title":"Contronyms in Spelling Bees (Vocabulary Rounds)","body":"Inflammable = can catch fire (NOT fireproof) — in- here means \"into flames\" not \"not.\" Invaluable = so valuable it cannot be valued = priceless (NOT worthless). These are the most dangerous contronyms because the in- prefix appears to negate the meaning but does not."}],"words":[{"w":"sanction","def":"formal and explicit approval","ex":"a Democrat usually gets the union's endorsement","say":"SA-ngkshuhn","hook":"SANCTION: SANCT+ION — a decree so holy it charges like an ION, either approving or punishing."},{"w":"cleave","def":"separate or cut with a tool, such as a sharp instrument","ex":"Using a single powerful stroke, the butcher was able to cleave the thick piece of beef in two, his sharp blade passing cleanly through bone and sinew without any hesitation.","say":"KLEEV","hook":"To CLEAVE is to split — the EA in the middle is itself split between C-L and V-E, mirroring the action."},{"w":"oversight","def":"an unintentional omission resulting from failure to notice something","ex":"Forgetting to include the bibliography was a simple oversight that the student quickly corrected.","say":"OH-ver-seyet","hook":"An OVERSIGHT means you looked right OVER something — the SIGHT was there, you just missed it."},{"w":"buckle","def":"fastener that fastens together two ends of a belt or strap; often has loose prong","ex":"Maya carefully fastened the buckle on her worn leather backpack before rushing out the door and sprinting three whole blocks to catch the school bus in time.","say":"BUH-kuhl","hook":"BUCKLE your belt with a U and an LE at the end — bU-ckLE cinches it together."},{"w":"dust","def":"fine powdery material such as dry earth or pollen that can be blown about in the air","ex":"the furniture was covered with dust","say":"DUHST","hook":"DUST: Dirt Under Shelves Today — four letters, fine and simple."},{"w":"screen","def":"a white or silvered surface where pictures can be projected for viewing","ex":"they had just moved in and had not put up blinds yet","say":"SKREEN","hook":"SCREEN contains GREEN — movie screens often show lush green landscapes."},{"w":"weather","def":"the atmospheric conditions at a particular place and time, including temperature, wind, clouds, and precipitation","ex":"The weather forecast predicted sunny skies for the outdoor graduation ceremony, and for once the meteorologist was exactly right.","say":"WEH-ther","hook":"WEATHER: WE AT HER mercy — watch for the silent 'a'"},{"w":"enjoin","def":"issue an injunction","ex":"I said to him to go home","say":"eh-NJOYN","hook":"A judge ENJOINs — they JOIN an order ONTO you."},{"w":"fast","def":"abstaining from food","ex":"Catholics sometimes fast during Lent","say":"FAST","hook":"FAST is short and firm — just four letters, as solid as its meaning."},{"w":"trip","def":"a journey for some purpose (usually including the return)","ex":"he took a trip to the shopping center","say":"TRIHP","hook":"A TRIP is one journey — just one p, one path there and back."},{"w":"inflammable","def":"is capable of being set on fire","ex":"The chemist placed a large warning label on the bottle because the liquid inside was highly inflammable and could ignite from a small spark.","say":"ih-n-f-l-A-m-uh-b-uh-l","hook":"inFLAMmable: full of FLAME — confusingly same meaning as flammable"},{"w":"invaluable","def":"having incalculable monetary, intellectual, or spiritual worth","ex":"The mentor's guidance proved invaluable to Marco as he prepared his science fair project and eventually won first place.","say":"ih-NVA-lyuh-buhl","hook":"inVALUABLE is so valuable it CANNOT be valued — paradoxically, in means beyond value here."},{"w":"off","def":"kill intentionally and with premeditation","ex":"The mafia boss ordered his enemies murdered","say":"AWF","hook":"To OFF someone is to send them FAR OFF — double the F to finish them off completely."},{"w":"rent","def":"a payment or series of payments made by the lessee to an owner for use of some property, facility, equipment, or service","ex":"there was a rip in his pants","say":"REHNT","hook":"RENT is short and blunt — you pay it or you're out on the street."},{"w":"transparent","def":"transmitting light; able to be seen through with clarity","ex":"the cold crystalline water of melted snow","say":"tra-NSPEH-ruhnt","hook":"A transPARENt parent shows everything clearly — PARENT is hiding inside, ending in ENT."}]},{"title":"Eponyms (Words from People's Names)","category":"Word Formation","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Eponyms are words derived from people's names — real or legendary. English has hundreds of them, from boycott to algorithm. Knowing the story behind an eponym makes the spelling unforgettable.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>BOYCOTT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> BOY-kaht\n<b>Spell it.</b> B · O · Y · C · O · T · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> BOY-kaht\n<b>Syllables.</b> boy · cott\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [BOY=BOY] [kot=COTT]\n<b>Exception.</b> From Captain Charles Boycott (Irish land agent, 1880); double-T not single; stress: BOY-kot\n<b>Origin.</b> Other\n<b>Root.</b> Named after Captain Charles Boycott (1832–1897), a land agent in Irela","cards":[{"title":"Classic Eponyms","body":"Boycott = from Captain Charles Boycott, an Irish land agent who was socially ostracized. Sandwich = from the Earl of Sandwich who ate bread around his food so he could keep gambling. Cardigan = from Lord Cardigan who wore a knitted jacket at the Battle of Balaclava. Wellington (boot) = from the Duke of Wellington."},{"title":"Scientific Eponyms","body":"Watt (unit of power) = from James Watt, inventor. Fahrenheit = from Daniel Fahrenheit. Celsius = from Anders Celsius. Pasteurize = from Louis Pasteur. Galvanize = from Luigi Galvani (electricity). Algorithm = from Al-Khwarizmi, the Arab mathematician. Jacuzzi = from Candido Jacuzzi."},{"title":"Literary Eponyms","body":"Malapropism = from Mrs. Malaprop in Sheridan's play The Rivals (1775). Quixotic = from Don Quixote, Cervantes' idealistic knight. Odyssey = from Odysseus (Ulysses) and his long journey. Mentor = from Mentor, Odysseus's trusted advisor. Panic = from Pan, the Greek god who caused sudden irrational terror."},{"title":"Words from Mythology as Eponyms","body":"Narcissism = from Narcissus. Tantalize = from Tantalus (in the underworld, food and water always out of reach). Herculean = from Hercules. Jovial = from Jove/Jupiter (those born under Jupiter were thought cheerful). Mercurial = from Mercury (quick-moving, unpredictable)."},{"title":"Spelling Eponyms","body":"They generally keep the capitalized person's spelling, then lowercased: Boycott = two t's because the name Boycott has two t's. Cardigan = no e before -an because the name is Cardigan. Machiavellian = M-A-C-H-I-A-V-E-L-L-I-A-N (double-l from Machiavelli's name). Quixotic = Q-U-I-X-O-T-I-C (x from Spanish Quixote)."}],"words":[{"w":"boycott","def":"a group's refusal to have commercial dealings with some organization in protest against its policies","ex":"Students organized a boycott of the cafeteria's new menu until the school agreed to bring back the beloved pizza Fridays.","say":"BOY-kaht","hook":"BOYCOTT—a BOY named COTT refused to cooperate"},{"w":"sandwich","def":"two (or more) slices of bread with a filling between them","ex":"She was sandwiched in her airplane seat between two fat men","say":"SA-ndwihch","hook":"No W sneaks into SANDWICH — think SAND + WITCH without the T, and drop the W everyone wants to add."},{"w":"cardigan","def":"knitted jacket that is fastened up the front with buttons or a zipper","ex":"She wrapped herself in a cozy cardigan and settled into the armchair with a good book.","say":"KAH-rdih-guhn","hook":"A cardIGAN is a snuGAN sweater — remember the -IGAN ending, like Michigan in a cozy sweater."},{"w":"malapropism","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"quixotic","def":"not sensible about practical matters; idealistic and unrealistic","ex":"as quixotic as a restoration of medieval knighthood","say":"kwih-KSAH-tihk","hook":"QuiXOTic has an X because the hero crossed out reality with impossible dreams."},{"w":"odyssey","def":"a long wandering and eventful journey","ex":"Her solo backpacking trip across three continents became a true odyssey of self-discovery.","say":"AH-duh-see","hook":"An odyssey has ONE 'd' and double 's' — 'od-YS-sey': one d, two s letters... wait, no: O-D-Y-S-S-E-Y — the double 's' is in the middle of the adventure."},{"w":"mentor","def":"a wise and trusted guide and advisor","ex":"The famous professor mentored him during his years in graduate school","say":"MEH-ntawr","hook":"A MENTOR ends in '-or' like a doctOR or profesOR — a title for one who guides."},{"w":"narcissism","def":"is excessive self-love vanity","ex":"self-love that shut out everyone else","say":"n-AH-r-s-ih-s-ih-z-uh-m","hook":"NARCISSISM has double-s twice — so self-obsessed it even doubles its letters twice."},{"w":"tantalize","def":"To tantalize someone means to torment them by keeping something desirable just out of their reach.","ex":"The children teased the new teacher","say":"t-A-n-t-uh-l-ay-z","hook":"TANTALIZE contains TANTALUS — the king who could never reach his food tantalizes YOU to remember the A."},{"w":"herculean","def":"displaying superhuman strength or power","ex":"Moving all those waterlogged sandbags before the flood arrived was a herculean task that left the volunteers exhausted but proud.","say":"her-KYOO-lee-uhn","hook":"Think of HERCULES — herculEAN comes straight from his name."},{"w":"jovial","def":"full of or showing high-spirited merriment; ; - Wordsworth","ex":"when hearts were young and gay","say":"JOH-vee-uhl","hook":"JOVIAL comes from JOVE (Jupiter) — those born under his lucky star were cheerful, so keep 'Jov' at the heart."},{"w":"mercurial","def":"liable to sudden unpredictable change","ex":"The mercurial artist could shift from joyful and talkative to withdrawn and sullen within a single afternoon, making it difficult for his students to predict his mood.","say":"mer-KYUU-ree-uhl","hook":"MERCURIAL people change like liquid MERCURY—end it in -AL like the metAL mercury itself."},{"w":"pasteurize","def":"heat food in order to kill harmful microorganisms","ex":"Health officials require dairy farmers to pasteurize their milk by heating it to a specific temperature in order to kill dangerous bacteria before it reaches grocery shelves.","say":"PA-scher-eyez","hook":"To PASTEURIZE is to use PASTEUR's method — keep his name spelled perfectly inside the verb."},{"w":"galvanize","def":"to stimulate to action","ex":"The coach's passionate halftime speech galvanized the team, and they came back from twelve points down to win the championship.","say":"GAL-vuh-nyz","hook":"GALVANize — like Galvani's electric shock, it jolts people to act"},{"w":"algorithm","def":"is a set of rules for solving a problem","ex":"The computer scientist designed an algorithm that could sort thousands of names in less than a second.","say":"A-l-g-ur-ih-th-uh-m","hook":"ALGORITHm contains ARITH as in ARITHmetic — a math rule has math in its spelling!"},{"w":"machiavellian","def":"a follower of Machiavelli's principles","ex":"The Machiavellian class president promised everyone free pizza, knowing he had no intention of ever keeping that promise.","say":"mah-kee-uh-VEH-lee-uhn","hook":"MACHI-a-VELLI: remember the Italian name with two L's like a villain"}]},{"title":"Words from Greek & Roman Mythology","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Mythology generated hundreds of English words through the names of gods, heroes, and places. These words often have unusual spellings — because they come from Greek or Latin proper names, not from common roots.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PROMETHEAN</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> pruh-MEE-thee-un\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · R · O · M · E · T · H · E · A · N\n<b>Say it again.</b> pruh-MEE-thee-un\n<b>Syllables.</b> pruh · mee · thee · un\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [pruh=PRO] [MEE=ME] [thee=THE] [un=AN]\n<b>Exception.</b> from Prometheus (Greek Titan who stole fire); -th- = /th/ Greek theta; -ean suffix = relating to; stress: pruh-MEE-thee-un\n<b>Origin.</b> Greek\n<b>Root.</b> Greek Prometheus = forethought (pro = before + methos = thought)","cards":[{"title":"Gods → Common Nouns","body":"Panic = from Pan (Greek goat-god who caused sudden terror). Volcano = from Vulcan (Roman god of fire). Cereal = from Ceres (Roman goddess of grain). Music = from the Muses (nine Greek goddesses of arts). Ocean = from Oceanus (the Titan who surrounded the world). Chaos = from Chaos (the first primordial state)."},{"title":"Heroes → Adjectives","body":"Herculean = of Hercules = requiring enormous strength. Promethean = of Prometheus = boldly creative, fire-stealing. Quixotic = of Don Quixote (literary, not mythological) = impractically idealistic. Odyssean = of Odysseus = involving a long, difficult journey. Siren = from the Sirens = irresistibly attractive but dangerous."},{"title":"Places → Words","body":"Labyrinth = from the Labyrinth of the Minotaur in Crete. Marathon = from the town of Marathon (the messenger ran 26 miles to Athens). Laconic = from Laconia/Sparta (Spartans were famous for brief speech). Draconian = from Draco (Athenian lawmaker famous for harsh laws). Tantalize = from Tantalus (forever reaching for unreachable food)."},{"title":"Planets & Elements","body":"Mercury (planet + element) = from Mercury, messenger god. Venus = from Venus, goddess of love. Mars = from Mars, god of war. Plutonium = from Pluto, god of the underworld. Titanium = from the Titans. Helium = from Helios, god of the sun (discovered in the sun's spectrum first)."},{"title":"Spelling Mythology Words","body":"Promethean = P-R-O-M-E-T-H-E-A-N (-th- Greek theta). Herculean = H-E-R-C-U-L-E-A-N (-ean suffix). Labyrinth = L-A-B-Y-R-I-N-T-H (y as vowel, Greek). Draconian = D-R-A-C-O-N-I-A-N (from Drakōn). Siren = S-I-R-E-N (ei from Greek Seirēn). The Greek -th- and y-as-vowel signals appear repeatedly in mythology words."}],"words":[{"w":"promethean","def":"Daringly original and creative, or relating to a bold, rebellious spirit; inspired by the Greek Titan Prometheus who defied the gods.","ex":"Her Promethean drive to invent new technologies changed the way millions of people communicate.","say":"pruh-MEE-thee-un","hook":"Prometheus stole fire — spell his name with EAN at the end, like a heroic LEAN forward into flames."},{"w":"herculean","def":"displaying superhuman strength or power","ex":"Moving all those waterlogged sandbags before the flood arrived was a herculean task that left the volunteers exhausted but proud.","say":"her-KYOO-lee-uhn","hook":"Think of HERCULES — herculEAN comes straight from his name."},{"w":"quixotic","def":"not sensible about practical matters; idealistic and unrealistic","ex":"as quixotic as a restoration of medieval knighthood","say":"kwih-KSAH-tihk","hook":"QuiXOTic has an X because the hero crossed out reality with impossible dreams."},{"w":"labyrinth","def":"is an intricate combination of paths","ex":"The ancient labyrinth beneath the castle had so many twisting passages that explorers often got lost.","say":"l-A-b-ur-ih-n-th","hook":"LABYrinth has a BABY inside it — even a baby would get lost in a maze!"},{"w":"marathon","def":"any long and arduous undertaking","ex":"Studying for finals felt like a marathon as Jaylen sat at his desk for six straight hours reviewing every chapter.","say":"MEH-ruh-thahn","hook":"MARAthon — a MARA-vel of endurance; think of the messenger who ran from MARA-thon to Athens"},{"w":"laconic","def":"is using few words being concise","ex":"Coach Rivera was famously laconic before big games, offering her team nothing more than a quiet nod and the words 'You know what to do,' yet somehow those five words inspired more confidence than any long speech ever could.","say":"l-ah-k-AH-n-ih-k","hook":"Spartans from LACONIA said little — laconic means little talk."},{"w":"draconian","def":"of or relating to Draco or his harsh code of laws","ex":"The principal's draconian rule that students could not speak at all during lunch made the cafeteria feel like a prison.","say":"dray-KOH-nee-uhn","hook":"DRAConian laws DRAG you down with their harshness"},{"w":"tantalize","def":"To tantalize someone means to torment them by keeping something desirable just out of their reach.","ex":"The children teased the new teacher","say":"t-A-n-t-uh-l-ay-z","hook":"TANTALIZE contains TANTALUS — the king who could never reach his food tantalizes YOU to remember the A."},{"w":"siren","def":"a sea nymph (part woman and part bird) supposed to lure sailors to destruction on the rocks where the nymphs lived","ex":"Odysseus ordered his crew to plug their ears so they would not hear the Siren's fatal song","say":"SEYE-ruhn","hook":"A SIREN lures with her voice—the 'i' in the middle is the eye that hypnotizes sailors."},{"w":"volcano","def":"a fissure in the earth's crust (or in the surface of some other planet) through which molten lava and gases erupt","ex":"Lava poured down the volcano's slope, glowing orange against the dark night sky.","say":"vah-LKAY-noh","hook":"VOL-CA-NO: think 'VOLatile CANon of lava NO one can stop' — it opens with VOL, not VUL."},{"w":"cereal","def":"a prepared food of grain such as oatmeal or cornflakes eaten especially for breakfast","ex":"Before the big exam, Daria poured herself a bowl of whole-grain cereal, knowing that a nutritious breakfast would help her stay alert and focused throughout the long morning.","say":"s-IH-r-ee-uh-l","hook":"CEREAL comes from CERES the grain goddess — it starts with CE like the goddess, not SE like a TV serial."},{"w":"music","def":"vocal or instrumental sounds having rhythm, melody, or harmony.","ex":"he fell asleep to the music of the wind chimes","say":"MYOO-zihk","hook":"MUSIC comes from the MUSE — the muse inspires art, so keep the C, not a K."},{"w":"ocean","def":"a large body of water constituting a principal part of the hydrosphere","ex":"Standing at the cliff's edge, she stared out at the vast ocean stretching endlessly to the horizon.","say":"OH-shuhn","hook":"The OCEAN ends in '-ean' — think 'the sea can' hold the spelling o-c-e-a-n."},{"w":"chaos","def":"a state of extreme confusion and disorder","ex":"When the fire alarm went off during lunch, the cafeteria erupted into complete chaos as students scrambled for the exits.","say":"KAY-ahs","hook":"CHAOS starts with CH not K — remember: Complete Havoc And Overwhelming Scramble."},{"w":"mercurial","def":"liable to sudden unpredictable change","ex":"The mercurial artist could shift from joyful and talkative to withdrawn and sullen within a single afternoon, making it difficult for his students to predict his mood.","say":"mer-KYUU-ree-uhl","hook":"MERCURIAL people change like liquid MERCURY—end it in -AL like the metAL mercury itself."},{"w":"jovial","def":"full of or showing high-spirited merriment; ; - Wordsworth","ex":"when hearts were young and gay","say":"JOH-vee-uhl","hook":"JOVIAL comes from JOVE (Jupiter) — those born under his lucky star were cheerful, so keep 'Jov' at the heart."},{"w":"narcissism","def":"is excessive self-love vanity","ex":"self-love that shut out everyone else","say":"n-AH-r-s-ih-s-ih-z-uh-m","hook":"NARCISSISM has double-s twice — so self-obsessed it even doubles its letters twice."}]},{"title":"Words About Time (Beyond chron-)","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Time vocabulary extends far beyond chron-. Latin tempus, Greek aion, and hora all generate time words — plus poetic and philosophical time concepts that appear in advanced vocabulary rounds.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>EPHEMERAL</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ih-f-EH-m-ur-uh-l\n<b>Spell it.</b> E · P · H · E · M · E · R · A · L\n<b>Say it again.</b> ih-f-EH-m-ur-uh-l\n<b>Syllables.</b> e · p · h · e · m · e · r · a · l\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [ih=E] [FEM=PHEM] [ur=ER] [ul=AL]\n<b>Exception.</b> Greek epi- = upon + hemera = day = lasting only a day; -ph- = /f/ Greek signal; stress: ih-FEM-ur-ul\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Greek ephemeros = lasting a day, from epi (on) + hemera (day)","cards":[{"title":"ephemeral & transient","body":"Ephemeral (epi- + hemera = day) = lasting only a day = short-lived. Transient (trans- + ire = go across) = passing across quickly = temporary. Fleeting (Old English fleon = to flee) = passing quickly. Momentary (momentum = movement) = lasting only a moment. All describe brevity of time."},{"title":"tempus (Latin time)","body":"Temporal (tempus = time) = relating to time (vs spiritual). Temporary = lasting for a limited time. Contemporary (con- + tempus) = existing at the same time. Extemporaneous (ex tempore = out of the moment) = spoken without preparation. Tempest (tempus in the sense of a storm's time = a violent storm)."},{"title":"aion / aevum (age/era)","body":"Aeon (Greek aion) = an immeasurably long period. Medieval (medi- = middle + aevum = age) = of the middle ages. Primeval (prim- = first + aevum) = of the earliest age. Coeval (co- + aevum) = of the same age/period. Longevity (longus = long + aevum = age) = long life."},{"title":"hora (hour/season)","body":"Horology (hora + -logy) = the study and making of clocks. Horoscope (hora + -scope) = looking at the birth hour. Ephemeral blends epi- (upon) + hemera (day, from Greek goddess Hemera of daylight). Diurnal (diurnus from dies = day) = occurring during the day or daily. Nocturnal (nox = night) = occurring at night."},{"title":"Spelling Time Words","body":"Ephemeral = E-P-H-E-M-E-R-A-L (-ph- Greek signal; -er- not -or-). Extemporaneous = E-X-T-E-M-P-O-R-A-N-E-O-U-S (from ex tempore). Contemporary = C-O-N-T-E-M-P-O-R-A-R-Y (con + tempor + -ary). Medieval = M-E-D-I-E-V-A-L (-ie- not -ei- — the e comes from aevum, not from the ie/ei rule)."}],"words":[{"w":"ephemeral","def":"is lasting a very short time","ex":"the ephemeral joys of childhood","say":"ih-f-EH-m-ur-uh-l","hook":"EPHEMERAL: 'Every Petal Has Every Morning Erased, Really A Loss' — beauty gone by dawn."},{"w":"transient","def":"means not lasting or enduring","ex":"The joy of winning the spelling bee was intense but transient, quickly replaced by the nervous excitement of preparing for the next, far more difficult round of competition.","say":"t-r-A-n-zh-uh-n-t","hook":"TRANS-I-ENT: a transient is briefly going across — remember the I before ENT, like a tiny visitor passing through."},{"w":"momentary","def":"lasting for a markedly brief time","ex":"The momentary flash of lightning lit up the entire night sky so brilliantly that everyone standing on the porch gasped in surprise before darkness returned.","say":"MOH-muh-nteh-ree","hook":"A MOMENTARY thing relates to a MOMENT — keep the -ARY ending like 'temporary.'"},{"w":"temporal","def":"the semantic role of the noun phrase that designates the time of the state or action denoted by the verb","ex":"temporal matters of but fleeting moment","say":"TEH-mper-uhl","hook":"TEMPORAL relates to time — it holds TEMPOR(ary) inside, reminding you that time is always fleeting."},{"w":"temporary","def":"a worker (especially in an office) hired on a temporary basis","ex":"politics is an impermanent factor of life","say":"TEH-mper-eh-ree","hook":"Temporary has an A before the R — think 'A temp works A while' to remember the -ary ending."},{"w":"contemporary","def":"a person of nearly the same age as another","ex":"contemporary trends in design","say":"kuh-NTEH-mper-eh-ree","hook":"A CONTEMPORARY shares your TIME — find TEMPOR (time) hiding inside, then add '-ary'."},{"w":"extemporaneous","def":"is done without special preparation","ex":"his ad-lib comments showed poor judgment","say":"ek-stem-puh-RAY-nee-us","hook":"EX TEMPORE means 'out of the moment'—no prep time!"},{"w":"aeon","def":"(Gnosticism) a divine power or nature emanating from the Supreme Being and playing various roles in the operation of the universe","ex":"oh, that happened eons ago","say":"EE-on","hook":"AEON has the fancy AE at the start — the extra A stretches the word out, just like an aeon stretches out time."},{"w":"medieval","def":"relating to or belonging to the Middle Ages","ex":"The students built a medieval castle replica complete with a drawbridge and turrets for their history class project on the feudal system.","say":"mih-DEE-vuhl","hook":"MEDIEval — MEDI means MIDDLE; the MEDIEval era is the MIDDLE age of history"},{"w":"primeval","def":"having existed from the beginning; in an earliest or original stage or state","ex":"The hikers stood in silence at the edge of the primeval forest, awed by the towering ancient trees whose roots had spread through the dark soil for thousands of uninterrupted years.","say":"preye-MEE-vuhl","hook":"PRIMEVAL = PRIME + EVAL(uation of the first age) — think 'prime evil' ancient darkness."},{"w":"coeval","def":"a person of nearly the same age as another","ex":"Shakespeare and Galileo were nearly coeval, both shaping history during the remarkable late sixteenth century.","say":"koh-EE-vuhl","hook":"COEVAL = same AGE (aevum) — two people are coeval when they share the same era, spelled co-EV-AL."},{"w":"longevity","def":"duration of service","ex":"her longevity as a star","say":"law-NJEH-vuh-tee","hook":"LONGEVITY means a LONG life with VITALITY — spot the word VITA (life) hiding inside: long-VITY."},{"w":"horology","def":"the art of designing and making clocks","ex":"She studied horology at a Swiss institute before opening her own clock-repair shop.","say":"hoh-ROL-oh-jee","hook":"HOROLOGY = study of HOURS — one R, like one hand on the clock face."},{"w":"diurnal","def":"of or belonging to or active during the day","ex":"Unlike owls, which are nocturnal hunters, eagles are diurnal birds that soar and hunt only while the sun is shining.","say":"deye-UR-nuhl","hook":"diURNal — contains URN; think of the sun as an URN pouring light during the DAY."},{"w":"nocturnal","def":"is of or pertaining to the night","ex":"nocturnal animals are active at night","say":"n-ah-k-t-UR-n-uh-l","hook":"NOCTURNal — think NOCTURNE, the night music; both start with NOCTUR-"},{"w":"evanescent","def":"tending to vanish like vapor; quickly fading or disappearing","ex":"The evanescent rainbow disappeared just moments after the storm clouds parted, leaving only a grey sky behind.","say":"eh-vuh-NEH-suhnt","hook":"EVANESCent — it EVANishes like an effervESCEnt bubble"}]},{"title":"Words About Size & Quantity","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Size and quantity vocabulary comes from both number prefixes (already covered) and from Latin and Greek roots for big/small, many/few. These combine with other roots to make precise measurement words.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>MINUSCULE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> m-IH-n-uh-s-k-y-oo-l\n<b>Spell it.</b> M · I · N · U · S · C · U · L · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> m-IH-n-uh-s-k-y-oo-l\n<b>Syllables.</b> m · i · n · u · s · c · u · l · e\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [MIN=MIN] [uh=US] [skyool=CULE]\n<b>Exception.</b> Latin minusculus = rather small; -us- not -i- in middle; NOT miniscule — a very common misspelling\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> Latin minusculus = rather small, from minus = less","cards":[{"title":"Tiny Words","body":"Minuscule (minusculus = rather small) = tiny — NOT miniscule (a misspelling caused by confusing with mini-). Infinitesimal (infinitus = without end + -esimal = fraction) = immeasurably tiny. Diminutive (diminuere = lessen) = very small. Microscopic = visible only under a microscope. Infinitesimal is used in calculus for quantities approaching zero."},{"title":"Large Words","body":"Colossal (from the Colossus of Rhodes) = enormous. Titanic (from the Titans) = of enormous size and power. Gargantuan (from Gargantua, Rabelais' giant character) = enormously large. Prodigious (prodigium = omen) = remarkably large in extent. Elephantine = of elephant-like size = enormous and unwieldy."},{"title":"Many & Few","body":"Multitudinous (multitudo = great number) = very numerous. Myriad (myrioi = ten thousand) = a very large but indefinite number (technically 10,000 in Greek). Plethora (plethora = fullness) = an excessive amount. Paucity (paucus = few) = a small number. Dearth (Old English deore = dear/scarce) = a scarcity."},{"title":"Measurement Words","body":"Infinitesimal = approaching zero. Exponential = growing by multiplication of itself. Logarithmic = growing by addition to the exponent. Negligible (neglegere = to disregard) = too small to matter. Incommensurable (in- + com- + mensura = measure) = not able to be measured against each other."},{"title":"Spelling Size Words","body":"Minuscule = M-I-N-U-S-C-U-L-E (-us- not -is-). Infinitesimal = I-N-F-I-N-I-T-E-S-I-M-A-L (-esimal). Gargantuan = G-A-R-G-A-N-T-U-A-N. Multitudinous = M-U-L-T-I-T-U-D-I-N-O-U-S. Myriad = M-Y-R-I-A-D (y as vowel — Greek!)."}],"words":[{"w":"minuscule","def":"the characters that were once kept in bottom half of a compositor's type case; also means extremely small","ex":"The scientist examined a minuscule speck of dust under the powerful microscope, astonished that something so incredibly tiny could contain thousands of microscopic organisms.","say":"m-IH-n-uh-s-k-y-oo-l","hook":"Think MINUS — minuscule means less than tiny; don't spell it with an I like 'mini'"},{"w":"infinitesimal","def":"(mathematics) a variable that has zero as its limit","ex":"two minute whiplike threads of protoplasm","say":"ih-nfih-nih-TEH-sih-muhl","hook":"INFINITESIMAl: spot FINITE inside, then add ESIMAL — an infinitely tiny ending for a tiny thing."},{"w":"diminutive","def":"a word that is formed with a suffix (such as -let or -kin) to indicate smallness","ex":"diminutive in stature","say":"dih-MIH-nyuh-tihv","hook":"A diMINutive thing is so MINI it fits in a tiny suffix like -let or -kin."},{"w":"microscopic","def":"of or relating to or used in microscopy","ex":"microscopic analysis","say":"meye-kruh-SKAH-pihk","hook":"MICROSCOPIC ends in '-ic' like 'atomic'—no 'k', just micro+scop+ic."},{"w":"colossal","def":"so great in size or force or extent as to elicit awe","ex":"colossal crumbling ruins of an ancient temple","say":"kuh-LAH-suhl","hook":"The coLOSSal Colossus had one L but a LOSS of balance — one L, double S: coLOSSal."},{"w":"titanic","def":"of great force or power","ex":"The titanic storm uprooted century-old trees and tore rooftops from houses across the county.","say":"teye-TA-nihk","hook":"TITANIC means colossal — the great ship TITANIC had one 'n' yet still sank enormously."},{"w":"gargantuan","def":"of great mass; huge and bulky","ex":"The gargantuan sandwich at the deli was so tall that you needed two hands just to hold it up.","say":"gah-RGA-nchoo-uhn","hook":"GARGANTuan — a GIANT name for a GIANT size"},{"w":"prodigious","def":"so great in size or force or extent as to elicit awe","ex":"The young pianist displayed a prodigious talent, performing a full concerto from memory at age nine.","say":"pruh-DIH-juhs","hook":"A PRODIGY has PRODIGIOUS talent — both share the root!"},{"w":"elephantine","def":"of great mass; huge and bulky","ex":"The elephantine boulders that blocked the mountain trail had been carried there by a glacier thousands of years ago and were far too massive for any crew to move.","say":"eh-luh-FA-nteen","hook":"ELEPHANTINE ends in -INE like a magazine — imagine a magazine called 'Elephant INE' for giant things."},{"w":"multitudinous","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"myriad","def":"is a very great or indefinitely great number","ex":"he faced a myriad of details","say":"m-IH-r-ee-uh-d","hook":"A MYRIAD of stars: MY Reliable Infinite Array of Dots — M-Y-R-I-A-D."},{"w":"plethora","def":"extreme excess","ex":"There was a plethora of science fair projects on volcanoes, so the judges decided to award a special prize for the most original topic.","say":"PLEH-ther-uh","hook":"PLETH-ORA: think of PLENTY of things OVERFLOWING into a PLETH-ora!"},{"w":"paucity","def":"the presence of something in only small or insufficient quantities","ex":"Because of the paucity of rain that summer, the reservoir dropped to dangerously low levels and water rationing began.","say":"PAW-suh-tee","hook":"PAUCITY: PAUSE and think how LITTLE (paucus) there is—a PAUSE means something is missing"},{"w":"dearth","def":"an acute insufficiency","ex":"There was such a dearth of rain that summer that the farmers feared their crops would completely wither.","say":"DURTH","hook":"A DEARTH of ideas? Picture the EAR in dEARth — you can't HEAR any ideas because there are so few."},{"w":"negligible","def":"so small as to be meaningless; insignificant","ex":"the effect was negligible","say":"NEH-gluh-juh-buhl","hook":"A negligIBLE amount can be neglIgIBly ignored — use '-ible' like 'possible.'"},{"w":"incommensurable","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""}]},{"title":"Personality: Words About Talkers, Thinkers & Liars","category":"Advanced Vocabulary — Word Power","difficulty":"hard","concept":"Advanced personality vocabulary for the competition stage. These are Word Power Made Easy's highest-level words — the ones that separate contestants who have studied from those who have just read a list.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PUSILLANIMOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> pyoo-suh-LA-nuh-muhs\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · U · S · I · L · L · A · N · I · M · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> pyoo-suh-LA-nuh-muhs\n<b>Syllables.</b> pu · sil · lan · i · mous\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [pyoo=PU] [sih=SIL] [LAN=LAN] [uh=I] [mus=MOUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> Latin pusillus = very small + animus = spirit = very small-spirited = cowardly; stress: pyoo-sih-LAN-uh-mus\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin pusillus = very small + animus = spirit or soul","cards":[{"title":"Cowardice Words","body":"Pusillanimous (pusillus = tiny + animus = spirit) = tiny-spirited = cowardly. Craven (Old French cravant = crushed) = contemptibly lacking courage. Timorous = full of fear. Recreant (re- + credere = surrendering belief) = a cowardly traitor. Poltroon (Italian poltrone = lazy person) = a complete coward."},{"title":"Arrogance Words","body":"Supercilious (super- + cilium = eyebrow) = raising the eyebrow above others = contemptuous. Imperious (imperium = command) = domineering, expecting obedience. Insolent (in- + solere = be accustomed) = rudely disrespectful. Bumptious = offensively self-assertive. Truculent (truculentus = fierce) = aggressively defiant."},{"title":"Intelligence Extreme Words","body":"Perspicacious (sharp insight) vs obtuse (blunt understanding). Sagacious (experienced wisdom) vs fatuous (smug foolishness). Precocious (mature before time) vs puerile (childishly silly). Sapient (truly wise) vs vacuous (empty). These contrasting pairs create precision in describing minds."},{"title":"Moral Character Words","body":"Probity (probus = honest) = complete honesty and strong moral principles. Rectitude (rectus = straight) = moral straightness. Turpitude (turpis = base/ugly) = depravity, wickedness. Iniquity (in- + aequus = equal) = gross injustice, wickedness. Scrupulous (scrupulus = small sharp stone = a troubled conscience) = careful about morality."},{"title":"Rare but Powerful","body":"Pusillanimous = P-U-S-I-L-L-A-N-I-M-O-U-S (double-l from pusillus). Supercilious = S-U-P-E-R-C-I-L-I-O-U-S. Truculent = T-R-U-C-U-L-E-N-T. Turpitude = T-U-R-P-I-T-U-D-E. Probity = P-R-O-B-I-T-Y. Rectitude = R-E-C-T-I-T-U-D-E. These are the words that win rounds."}],"words":[{"w":"pusillanimous","def":"lacking in courage and manly strength and resolution; contemptibly fearful","ex":"The pusillanimous bully always backed down the moment anyone stood up to him with calm confidence.","say":"pyoo-suh-LA-nuh-muhs","hook":"pusill-ANIM-ous: tiny ANIMUS (spirit) — a very small-spirited person"},{"w":"craven","def":"an abject coward","ex":"the craven fellow turned and ran","say":"KRAY-vuhn","hook":"A CRAVEN coward has a hidden RAVEN in the word—even the dark bird is braver than this coward."},{"w":"timorous","def":"timid by nature or revealing timidity","ex":"timorous little mouse","say":"TIH-mer-uhs","hook":"A TIMOROUS person is full of TIMOR (fear) — spot the Latin root hiding inside."},{"w":"recreant","def":"an abject coward","ex":"some provinces had proved recreant","say":"REK-ree-unt","hook":"A RECREANT is a CREep who goes ANT-running away from a fight."},{"w":"poltroon","def":"an abject coward","ex":"When the bully finally faced someone his own size, everyone saw what a poltroon he truly was.","say":"pol-TROON","hook":"A poltroon swoons instead of fighting — troon rhymes with swoon"},{"w":"supercilious","def":"having or showing arrogant superiority and disdain toward those one views as unworthy","ex":"The supercilious student rolled her eyes every time a classmate asked the teacher to slow down, as if the question were beneath her.","say":"soo-per-SIH-lee-uhs","hook":"SUPERCILIOUS people raise their SUPERCILIA (eyebrows) at others — one L, not two!"},{"w":"imperious","def":"having or showing arrogant superiority and disdain toward those one views as unworthy","ex":"The imperious duchess swept into the room and ordered everyone to bow before she would speak.","say":"ih-MPIH-ree-uhs","hook":"IMPERIOus: the EMPEROR is always imperious."},{"w":"insolent","def":"haughty and contemptuous or brutal in behavior or language","ex":"a flip answer to serious question","say":"IH-n-s-uh-l-uh-n-t","hook":"An insolENT person is not the lENienT type — end both words with E-N-T."},{"w":"truculent","def":"is fierce or savagely brutal","ex":"a truculent speech against the new government","say":"t-r-UH-k-y-uh-l-uh-n-t","hook":"A TRUCULENT person is full of TROUBLE — spell the END as -LENT, like he lent you his fury: T-R-U-C-U-L-E-N-T."},{"w":"probity","def":"complete and confirmed integrity; having strong moral principles","ex":"in a world where financial probity may not be widespread","say":"PROH-buh-tee","hook":"proBITY — a person of probity won't bite you dishonestly; -ITY signals a quality."},{"w":"rectitude","def":"righteousness as a consequence of being honorable and honest","ex":"The judge was admired throughout the city for her unwavering rectitude and fair treatment of every case.","say":"REH-ktih-tood","hook":"RECT-itude — a CORRECT attitude makes one righteous."},{"w":"turpitude","def":"a corrupt or depraved or degenerate act or practice","ex":"The judge declared that the politician's crimes showed such moral turpitude that he was unfit to ever hold public office again.","say":"TUR-pih-tood","hook":"TURPitude = TURP (disgusting, like TWERP) + -itude: a state of being disgraceful."},{"w":"iniquity","def":"absence of moral or spiritual values","ex":"the powers of darkness","say":"ih-NIH-kwih-tee","hook":"InIQUITy — spot QUIT in the middle; sinners never QUIT their iniquity."},{"w":"scrupulous","def":"having scruples; arising from a sense of right and wrong; principled","ex":"less scrupulous producers sent bundles that were deceptive in appearance","say":"SKROO-pyuh-luhs","hook":"A SCRUPULOUS person carefully picks every sharp scrUPULous stone out of the path — U-P-U-L spells careful attention."},{"w":"bumptious","def":"offensively self-assertive","ex":"The bumptious new student interrupted the teacher three times in the first period, loudly announcing that he already knew everything being taught.","say":"BUMP-shus","hook":"BUMPing into others with his ego: BUMPtious"},{"w":"perspicacious","def":"acutely insightful and wise","ex":"The perspicacious young detective noticed a tiny mud stain on the suspect's shoe that everyone else had overlooked.","say":"per-spuh-KAY-shuhs","hook":"PER-SPIC-acious: someone who sees (SPIC) through everything"},{"w":"sagacious","def":"showing acute mental discernment or being shrewd","ex":"much too perspicacious to be taken in by such a spurious argument","say":"suh-GAY-shus","hook":"A SAGE is wise; sagaCIOUS has SAGE inside it"}]},{"title":"The Schwa Problem & Unstressed Vowels","category":"Advanced Spelling Strategy","difficulty":"hard","concept":"The schwa — the unstressed /uh/ sound — is the most common vowel sound in English and can be spelled with any of the five vowels. Solving the schwa is the single biggest challenge in advanced spelling.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>SEPARATE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> SEH-per-ayt\n<b>Spell it.</b> S · E · P · A · R · A · T · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> SEH-per-ayt\n<b>Syllables.</b> seh · per · ey · t\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [SEP=SEP] [ur=AR] [ut=ATE]\n<b>Exception.</b> middle syllable = /ur/ schwa spelled -ar-; common error is seperate with -er-; stress: SEP-ur-ut\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin separare = to pull apart (se=apart + parare=prepare/arrange)","cards":[{"title":"What is the Schwa? The schwa (ə) is the neutral, unstressed /uh/ sound. It can be spelled: a (about), e (the), i (pencil), o (lemon), u (circus). Separate* has a schwa in the middle: sep-ar-ate — the ar is reduced to /ur/. Common error: seperate (using e instead of a*). 🃏 Card 2 — **Strategy 1 — Stress the Related Word","body":"Find a related word where the unstressed syllable BECOMES stressed: Competition → stress the compete → /com-PETE/ shows the e in pet. Explanation → explain → /ex-PLAIN/ shows the a. Definition → define → /de-FINE/ shows the i. The stressed form reveals the correct vowel."},{"title":"Strategy 2 — Know the Suffix","body":"Suffix patterns are reliable: -ant words use -ance: important → importance. -ent words use -ence: evident → evidence. -ary vs -ery: secretary (Latin origin → -ary) vs stationery (from stationer → -ery). The suffix rule beats guessing the schwa sound."},{"title":"Strategy 3 — Know the Origin","body":"Latin words use -or not -er for agents: senator, elevator, narrator. French words use -eur not -er: entrepreneur, chauffeur. Greek words use -is not -us for some nouns: thesis, crisis, basis (but plural -es: theses, crises). Origin predicts the unstressed vowel."},{"title":"The Most-Misspelled Schwa Words","body":"Separate (-ar-), definitely (-ite- not -ate-), environment (-ron-), government (-rn-), February (-ru-), library (-ra-), necessary (-ess-), privilege (-leg-), restaurant (-au-). Each has a schwa that is a misspelling trap. The strategy: stress the root to reveal the vowel, or memorize the origin."}],"words":[{"w":"separate","def":"a separately printed article that originally appeared in a larger publication","ex":"The mountain range divides the two countries","say":"SEH-per-ayt","hook":"There's 'a rat' in sep-A-RAT-e — the rat separates the two e's."},{"w":"competition","def":"a business relation in which two parties compete to gain customers","ex":"business competition can be fiendish at times","say":"kah-mpuh-TIH-shuhn","hook":"A COMPETITION has a 'petit' in the middle — petit means small, and small differences decide winners."},{"w":"explanation","def":"a statement that makes something comprehensible by describing the relevant structure or operation or circumstances etc.","ex":"the explanation was very simple","say":"eh-kspluh-NAY-shuhn","hook":"An EXPLANATION makes things PLAIN — drop the I: ex-PLAIN-ation, no extra I needed."},{"w":"definite","def":"precise; explicit and clearly defined","ex":"I want a definite answer","say":"DEH-fuh-nuht","hook":"Definite ends in -ite not -ate — remember 'finite' hides inside definITE."},{"w":"environment","def":"the totality of surrounding conditions","ex":"he longed for the comfortable environment of his living room","say":"ih-NVEYE-ruh-nmuhnt","hook":"Remember the N before MENT: your envirON-MENT surrounds you on every side."},{"w":"government","def":"the organization that is the governing authority of a political unit","ex":"the government reduced taxes","say":"GUH-ver-muhnt","hook":"GOVERNMENT has an N before MENT — GOVERN+MENT, never drop the N."},{"w":"february","def":"the month following January and preceding March","ex":"February is the shortest month, yet it always seems packed with holidays, snowstorms, and Valentine's Day cards.","say":"FEH-byuh-weh-ree","hook":"Feb-RU-ary: remember the hidden R — 'bRr, it's cold in febRUary!'"},{"w":"library","def":"a room where books are kept","ex":"they had brandy in the library","say":"LEYE-breh-ree","hook":"LIB-RAR-Y: there are two R's because you Read Regularly at the library."},{"w":"necessary","def":"is being essential indispensable","ex":"food and shelter are necessities of life","say":"n-EH-s-uh-s-eh-r-ee","hook":"NECESSARY: one Collar, two Socks — one 'c' and two 's's, like a shirt needs."},{"w":"privilege","def":"a right granted as a peculiar benefit advantage or favor","ex":"suffrage was the prerogative of white adult males","say":"p-r-IH-v-l-uh-j","hook":"There is NO 'D' in privilege — it's a private law, not a private ledge."},{"w":"restaurant","def":"a building where people go to eat","ex":"After the school play, our whole family walked to the Italian restaurant on Main Street to celebrate with pasta and garlic bread.","say":"REH-ster-ahnt","hook":"A reSTAUrant helps you reSTORe your energy — remember the AU in the middle."},{"w":"temperature","def":"the degree of hotness or coldness of a body or environment (corresponding to its molecular activity)","ex":"The nurse checked the child's temperature and confirmed he had a mild fever that would need monitoring overnight.","say":"TEH-mpruh-cher","hook":"TEMPERATURE hides TEMPER — a high fever makes you lose your temper! Spell temper-A-ture."},{"w":"relevant","def":"having a bearing on or connection with the subject at issue","ex":"the scientist corresponds with colleagues in order to learn about matters relevant to her own research","say":"REH-luh-vuhnt","hook":"RELEVANT ends in -ANT: an ANT that LIFTS things above the rest is always relevant."},{"w":"category","def":"a collection of things sharing a common attribute","ex":"there are two classes of detergents","say":"KA-tuh-gaw-ree","hook":"CATEGORY: a CAT in a GORE-y story belongs in its own — spell it catEGORY, hiding GORE in the middle."},{"w":"mathematics","def":"a science (or group of related sciences) dealing with the logic of quantity and shape and arrangement","ex":"She discovered a love of mathematics when she realized that solving equations felt like cracking secret codes.","say":"ma-thuh-MA-tihks","hook":"MATHEMATICS hides the word THEM in the middle: ma-THEM-atics — they all love numbers."}]},{"title":"Words About Knowledge & Learning","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","concept":"The vocabulary of learning, knowledge, and ignorance draws from Greek mathein (learn), Latin docere (teach), and scire (know). These words describe the pursuit of understanding itself.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>ERUDITE</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> EH-ruh-deyet\n<b>Spell it.</b> E · R · U · D · I · T · E\n<b>Say it again.</b> EH-ruh-deyet\n<b>Syllables.</b> eh · rah · day · t\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [ER=ER] [yoo=U] [dyt=DITE]\n<b>Exception.</b> Latin e- + rudis = rough = polished out of roughness = learned; -ite not -ight; stress: ER-yoo-dyt\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin erudire = to polish, instruct (e-out + rudis-rough)","cards":[{"title":"The Teaching Roots","body":"Erudite (e- + rudis = rough = polished by learning). Pedagogy (pais = child + agein = lead) = the science of teaching. Didactic (didaskein = to teach) = intended to teach or instruct. Edification (e- + aedificare = build) = mental or moral improvement. Heuristic (heuriskein = to find) = learning by discovering for oneself."},{"title":"Knowledge vs Ignorance","body":"Omniscient = knows everything. Prescient = knows in advance. Nescient (ne- = not + scire) = lacking knowledge. Obtuse = slow to understand. Ignoramus (Latin legal term = \"we do not know\") = an ignorant person. Troglodyte (trogle = cave + dytes = one who enters) = one who is behind the times."},{"title":"Academic Vocabulary","body":"Dissertation (dis- + serere = to join = a connected argument) = a scholarly essay. Exegesis (exegeisthai = to lead out the meaning) = scholarly interpretation of a text. Hermeneutics (from Hermes, the interpreter) = the theory of interpretation. Elucidation (e- + lucidus = clear) = making something clear."},{"title":"Learning Methods","body":"Autodidact (auto- + didakt-) = self-taught. Empirical (empeiria = experience) = based on evidence and experience. Deductive = reasoning from general principles to specific cases. Inductive = reasoning from specific cases to general principles. Syllogism (syllogismos = conclusion) = a formal logical argument."},{"title":"Spelling Knowledge Words","body":"Erudite = E-R-U-D-I-T-E (-ite not -ight). Pedagogy = P-E-D-A-G-O-G-Y. Didactic = D-I-D-A-C-T-I-C. Heuristic = H-E-U-R-I-S-T-I-C (-eu- diphthong). Exegesis = E-X-E-G-E-S-I-S (-esis Greek suffix). Hermeneutics = H-E-R-M-E-N-E-U-T-I-C-S (-eu- twice)."}],"words":[{"w":"erudite","def":"having or showing profound knowledge","ex":"The erudite professor could speak fluently about ancient languages, modern physics, and Renaissance art all within a single lecture, leaving her students both deeply inspired and slightly overwhelmed.","say":"EH-ruh-deyet","hook":"An ERUdite scholar is polished OUT of being RUDE and RAW—refined by knowledge."},{"w":"pedagogy","def":"the principles and methods of instruction","ex":"he prepared for teaching while still in college","say":"PEH-duh-goh-jee","hook":"PEDAGOGY is the art of leading children to knowledge — PED+AGOG+Y; don't double the GO, one is enough."},{"w":"didactic","def":"instructive (especially excessively)","ex":"Although the novel had an important moral lesson, its tone was so didactic that many readers felt they were being lectured rather than entertained.","say":"deye-DA-ktihk","hook":"DIDACTIC teaching DID ACT on students — the teacher DID ACT to instruct them."},{"w":"edification","def":"uplifting enlightenment","ex":"The principal posted inspirational quotes in the hallway for the edification of every student who passed by.","say":"eh-duh-fuh-KAY-shuhn","hook":"EDIFication EDIFIES — like building an EDIFICE, it builds up your mind."},{"w":"heuristic","def":"a commonsense rule (or set of rules) intended to increase the probability of solving some problem","ex":"The teacher gave students a heuristic for estimating answers — always round to the nearest ten before calculating — to help them catch big mistakes.","say":"hyuu-RIH-stihk","hook":"HEURistic — Eureka! It shares roots with the word EUREKA (I found it!)."},{"w":"omniscient","def":"infinitely wise","ex":"In many fantasy novels, the narrator is omniscient, able to reveal the secret thoughts of every character in the story.","say":"ah-MNIH-shuhnt","hook":"OMNI + SCIENT: SCIENT relates to SCIENCE (knowing) — omniscient knows ALL sciences"},{"w":"prescient","def":"perceiving the significance of events before they occur","ex":"Her prescient warning about the bridge's weak supports was ignored for years before the structure finally collapsed.","say":"PREH-see-uhnt","hook":"PRESCIENT people have pre-SCIENCE — they know things before they happen"},{"w":"nescient","def":"holding that only material phenomena can be known and knowledge of spiritual matters or ultimate causes is impossible","ex":"The philosopher argued that a nescient person, unaware of spiritual truths beyond physical evidence, could still live a moral life guided entirely by reason and observable facts.","say":"NESH-ee-ent","hook":"NESCIENT sounds like 'not-science' — someone ignorant of what science knows."},{"w":"ignoramus","def":"an ignorant person","ex":"The professor called his rude student an ignoramus for confidently declaring that the Earth was only a few thousand years old.","say":"ih-gner-AY-muhs","hook":"An ignorAMUS is a real AMUS-ing dummy — no silent e, just a blunt Latin 'we do not know.'"},{"w":"dissertation","def":"a treatise advancing a new point of view resulting from research; usually a requirement for an advanced academic degree","ex":"After years of research, Maya finally submitted her dissertation on climate change to the university committee.","say":"dih-ser-TAY-shuhn","hook":"A disSERTation takes a SERT-ain topic apart — double 's' because you must work doubly hard to write one."},{"w":"exegesis","def":"an explanation or critical interpretation (especially of the Bible)","ex":"Her careful exegesis of the parable revealed layers of meaning that most readers had overlooked.","say":"ek-sih-JEE-sis","hook":"EXEGESIS leads meaning OUT of text — spell it like it sounds: ex-e-GE-sis, no double letters."},{"w":"hermeneutics","def":"the branch of theology that deals with principles of exegesis","ex":"Her course in hermeneutics taught her how to interpret ancient texts with both precision and imagination.","say":"her-meh-NOO-tiks","hook":"HERMES the messenger had to INTERPRET the gods' words — herMENEUtics is the art of interpretation."},{"w":"elucidation","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"autodidact","def":"a person who has taught himself","ex":"The famous inventor was a proud autodidact who had never attended college yet revolutionized electrical engineering.","say":"aw-toh-DY-dakt","hook":"AUTO (self) + DIDACT (teach) = self-taught person."},{"w":"empirical","def":"derived from experiment and observation rather than theory","ex":"The scientists gathered empirical evidence by conducting hundreds of experiments before publishing their findings.","say":"eh-MPIH-rih-kuhl","hook":"EMPIRIcal knowledge comes from EXPERIMENTS in the real world"},{"w":"syllogism","def":"deductive reasoning in which a conclusion is derived from two premises","ex":"The philosopher used a syllogism to prove that all humans are mortal.","say":"SIL-uh-jiz-um","hook":"SylLOGIsm — there's LOGIC inside sylLOGIsm, because it's all about logical reasoning."}]},{"title":"The 44 Phonemes — Sound-to-Spelling Mastery","category":"Advanced Spelling Strategy","difficulty":"hard","concept":"English has 26 letters but 44 distinct sounds (phonemes). The Spellbound Sound Trick works by mapping sounds to letters. This concept covers the hardest sound-spelling mismatches — the ones where one sound has multiple possible spellings.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>ONOMATOPOEIA</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> on-oh-mat-oh-PEE-uh\n<b>Spell it.</b> O · N · O · M · A · T · O · P · O · E · I · A\n<b>Say it again.</b> on-oh-mat-oh-PEE-uh\n<b>Syllables.</b> on · o · mat · o · poe · ia\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [on=ON] [oh=O] [mat=MAT] [oh=O] [PEE=POE] [uh=IA]\n<b>Exception.</b> Greek onoma = name + poiein = make = naming by sound; -eia = Greek feminine ending; 6 syllables\n<b>Origin.</b> Greek\n<b>Root.</b> Greek onoma = name + poiein = to make","cards":[{"title":"The /f/ Sound — 4 Spellings","body":"f = fun, fish (everyday words). ph = phone, graph (Greek words). ff = off, cliff, staff (after short vowel at end). gh = enough, rough, tough (Old English). Rule: single everyday word → f; Greek origin → ph; after short vowel at end → ff; Old English + vowel before → gh. Origin + position = correct spelling."},{"title":"The /k/ Sound — 5 Spellings","body":"k = king, kind (before e/i). c = cat, cup, cold (before a/o/u). ck = lack, brick, deck (after short vowel at end of syllable). ch = chemistry, echo (Greek). que = unique, clique (French). Rule: before e/i → k; before a/o/u → c; after short vowel → ck; Greek → ch; French end → que. Origin and position decide."},{"title":"The /sh/ Sound — 7 Spellings","body":"sh = ship, wish (Old English). ti = nation, patience (Latin -tio). ci = special, musician (Latin). ssi = mission, session (Latin). ch = champagne, chef (French). s = sugar, sure. xi = anxious. ⚠️ Most common: -tion, -sion, -cian suffixes all produce /sh/ from the ti/ci/ssi patterns."},{"title":"The Schwa /uh/ — Any Vowel","body":"The schwa can be spelled a (about), e (the), i (pencil), o (lemon), u (circus), ai (certain). The only solution: stress the related word to reveal the hidden vowel, know the suffix rules, or know the etymology. No shortcut exists — but patterns narrow the options dramatically."},{"title":"Onomatopoeia — Words That Sound Like What They Mean","body":"Onomatopoeia (onoma + poiein = make a name) = naming by imitation of sound: buzz, hiss, crash, murmur, babble, cackle, sizzle, thud. These are words where the sound IS the meaning. Onomatopoeia itself = O-N-O-M-A-T-O-P-O-E-I-A — one of the longest words with multiple repeated vowel pairs."}],"words":[{"w":"onomatopoeia","def":"using words that imitate the sound they denote","ex":"The poet used onomatopoeia brilliantly, filling the stanza with words like buzz, crash, and sizzle to bring the kitchen scene alive.","say":"on-oh-mat-oh-PEE-uh","hook":"ON-O-MAT-O-POE-IA — sounds like what it means, just like the device itself"},{"w":"phenomenon","def":"is a fact or occurrence observed or observable","ex":"The sudden appearance of the northern lights over the city was a spectacular natural phenomenon.","say":"f-uh-n-AH-m-uh-n-ah-n","hook":"PHENOMENON ends in -ON not -IN — one phENOMENon, many phenomENA."},{"w":"knight","def":"is a mounted soldier in the Middle Ages","ex":"The Beatles were knighted","say":"n-AY-t","hook":"A KNIGHT rides into the NIGHT — both sound the same but KNIGHT wears armor spelled K-N-I-G-H-T with a hidden GH shield."},{"w":"enough","def":"an adequate quantity; a quantity that is large enough to achieve a purpose","ex":"enough is as good as a feast","say":"ih-NUHF","hook":"ENOUGH ends in OUGH — say 'ee-NUFF' but write the tricky -ough like 'tough.'"},{"w":"rough","def":"the part of a golf course bordering the fairway where the grass is not cut short","ex":"trees with rough bark","say":"RUHF","hook":"ROUGH has a tricky OUGH that sounds like UFF — think 'it's ROUGH enough to trip you up with that spelling.'"},{"w":"technique","def":"is the manner in which the technical skills of a particular art are used","ex":"practice greatly improves proficiency","say":"t-eh-k-n-EE-k","hook":"TECHNIQUE ends in -IQUE like UNIQUE — a unique technique needs that silent QUE: T-E-C-H-N-I-Q-U-E."},{"w":"unique","def":"radically distinctive and without equal","ex":"he is alone in the field of microbiology","say":"yoo-NEEK","hook":"UNIQUE ends with QUE — it's the one word that uses Q without a U after it... wait, it does! That's unique."},{"w":"special","def":"a special offering, usually temporary and at a reduced price, that is featured in advertising","ex":"The pizza restaurant ran a Tuesday special that let families order two large pizzas for the price of one.","say":"SPEH-shuhl","hook":"SPEcial — SPEll it carefully; the C comes before the I"},{"w":"musician","def":"someone who plays a musical instrument (as a profession)","ex":"The talented musician played her violin so beautifully that several audience members were moved to tears.","say":"myoo-ZIH-shuhn","hook":"A MUSIC-IAN practices MUSIC — the suffix is -IAN like a librarian or comedian."},{"w":"nation","def":"a politically organized body of people under a single government","ex":"the state has elected a new president","say":"NAY-shuhn","hook":"A NATION is born — the word itself contains 'nati' from Latin 'birth,' so a nation is a people born together."},{"w":"patience","def":"the capacity to accept or tolerate delay, trouble, or suffering without becoming angry or upset","ex":"It took enormous patience for the sculptor to carve every tiny feather into the marble bird over the course of three years.","say":"p-AY-sh-uh-n-s","hook":"PATIENCE has TIENCE—Take It Easy, Nothing Changes Everything"},{"w":"separate","def":"a separately printed article that originally appeared in a larger publication","ex":"The mountain range divides the two countries","say":"SEH-per-ayt","hook":"There's 'a rat' in sep-A-RAT-e — the rat separates the two e's."},{"w":"definite","def":"precise; explicit and clearly defined","ex":"I want a definite answer","say":"DEH-fuh-nuht","hook":"Definite ends in -ite not -ate — remember 'finite' hides inside definITE."},{"w":"environment","def":"the totality of surrounding conditions","ex":"he longed for the comfortable environment of his living room","say":"ih-NVEYE-ruh-nmuhnt","hook":"Remember the N before MENT: your envirON-MENT surrounds you on every side."},{"w":"necessary","def":"is being essential indispensable","ex":"food and shelter are necessities of life","say":"n-EH-s-uh-s-eh-r-ee","hook":"NECESSARY: one Collar, two Socks — one 'c' and two 's's, like a shirt needs."},{"w":"privilege","def":"a right granted as a peculiar benefit advantage or favor","ex":"suffrage was the prerogative of white adult males","say":"p-r-IH-v-l-uh-j","hook":"There is NO 'D' in privilege — it's a private law, not a private ledge."}]},{"title":"Championship Vocabulary: The Final 10","category":"Championship Level","difficulty":"hard","concept":"The highest-level competition words — chosen because they combine unusual spelling patterns, rare etymology, and rich meaning. These are the words that decide championships.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PLENIPOTENTIARY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> plen-ih-puh-TEN-shee-ehr-ee\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · L · E · N · I · P · O · T · E · N · T · I · A · R · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> plen-ih-puh-TEN-shee-ehr-ee\n<b>Syllables.</b> plen · i · po · ten · ti · ar · y\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [plen=PLEN] [ih=I] [puh=PO] [TEN=TEN] [shee=TIA] [ree=RY]\n<b>Exception.</b> Latin: plenus = full + potens = powerful + -iary suffix; stress: plen-ih-puh-TEN-shee-air-ee\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin plenus = full + potentia = power","cards":[{"title":"plenipotentiary, perspicacious, pusillanimous","body":"Three words that appear in championship rounds because they are long, built from multiple Latin parts, and have tricky stress patterns. Plenipotentiary = full power (diplomatic). Perspicacious = sharply insightful. Pusillanimous = tiny-spirited = cowardly. All follow their Latin roots perfectly."},{"title":"onomatopoeia, ophthalmologist, triskaidekaphobia","body":"Three Greek compounds. Onomatopoeia = naming by sound (6 syllables). Ophthalmologist = eye doctor (5 syllables, -phth- cluster). Triskaidekaphobia = fear of 13 (triskaideka = 13 in Greek + phobia) — one of the longest common fear words. All decode perfectly from their Greek roots."},{"title":"entrepreneur, restaurateur, connoisseur","body":"Three French-origin words that break English intuitions. Entrepreneur = 12 letters, four syllables, no double letters despite the complexity. Restaurateur = no n before -eur. Connoisseur = double-n AND double-s AND French -eur. Three words; three common misspellings; three French patterns."},{"title":"weltanschauung, schadenfreude","body":"Two German philosophical compounds. Weltanschauung = W-E-L-T-A-N-S-C-H-A-U-U-N-G (note uu from compound junction). Schadenfreude = S-C-H-A-D-E-N-F-R-E-U-D-E. Both follow German spelling exactly. Both decoded by knowing: sch = /sh/, au = /ow/, eu = /oy/."},{"title":"The Championship Strategy","body":"At the microphone — ask for origin FIRST. Then apply the rule set for that language. The winner is not the person who has memorized the most words — it is the person whose pattern-recognition fires fastest under pressure. Everything in this library builds that recognition. Say it. Spell it. Say it again."}],"words":[{"w":"plenipotentiary","def":"a diplomat who is fully authorized to represent his or her government","ex":"The plenipotentiary arrived in the capital city with the authority to sign the peace treaty on behalf of her entire nation.","say":"plen-ih-puh-TEN-shee-ehr-ee","hook":"PLENI (full) + POTENT (powerful): someone with FULL POWER to negotiate"},{"w":"perspicacious","def":"acutely insightful and wise","ex":"The perspicacious young detective noticed a tiny mud stain on the suspect's shoe that everyone else had overlooked.","say":"per-spuh-KAY-shuhs","hook":"PER-SPIC-acious: someone who sees (SPIC) through everything"},{"w":"pusillanimous","def":"lacking in courage and manly strength and resolution; contemptibly fearful","ex":"The pusillanimous bully always backed down the moment anyone stood up to him with calm confidence.","say":"pyoo-suh-LA-nuh-muhs","hook":"pusill-ANIM-ous: tiny ANIMUS (spirit) — a very small-spirited person"},{"w":"onomatopoeia","def":"using words that imitate the sound they denote","ex":"The poet used onomatopoeia brilliantly, filling the stanza with words like buzz, crash, and sizzle to bring the kitchen scene alive.","say":"on-oh-mat-oh-PEE-uh","hook":"ON-O-MAT-O-POE-IA — sounds like what it means, just like the device itself"},{"w":"ophthalmologist","def":"a medical doctor specializing in the diagnosis and treatment of diseases of the eye","ex":"After noticing blurry vision, Marcus visited an ophthalmologist who discovered he needed glasses for the first time.","say":"ah-pthuh-MAH-luh-jihst","hook":"An OPHTHALMOLOGIST studies the EYE — hide OPHTHALM (eye) at the start and -OLOGIST at the end."},{"w":"triskaidekaphobia","def":"is a fear of the number 13","ex":"Because of his triskaidekaphobia, he refused to stay in room 13 at any hotel he ever visited.","say":"tris-ky-dek-uh-FOH-bee-uh","hook":"TRISKAIDEKA spells out 3+and+10=13—fear the KAI in the middle!"},{"w":"entrepreneur","def":"is a person who organizes or manages an enterprise","ex":"At just fourteen, the young entrepreneur launched her own custom jewelry business and sold her designs online.","say":"ah-n-t-r-uh-p-r-uh-n-UR","hook":"Remember the unusual 'eur' ending — the French entrepreneur ends like 'connoisseur'"},{"w":"restaurateur","def":"the proprietor of a restaurant","ex":"The celebrated restaurateur opened her fifth dining establishment downtown, promising a menu inspired by her grandmother's recipes.","say":"reh-ster-uh-TUR","hook":"A restauraTEUR has no N — unlike restaurant, the owner drops the N and gains -EUR elegantly."},{"w":"connoisseur","def":"is a person competent to pass critical judgment","ex":"The art museum hired a connoisseur of Renaissance paintings to authenticate the newly discovered canvas.","say":"k-ah-n-uh-s-UR","hook":"A connoisseur KNOWS their stuff — double n, double s"},{"w":"weltanschauung","def":"a comprehensive view of the world and human life","ex":"Her travels through six continents completely changed her weltanschauung, giving her a truly global perspective.","say":"VELT-ahn-show-oong","hook":"WELTANSCHAUUNG = WELT (world) + AN + SCHAU (look) + UNG — 'world-look-ing,' your whole worldview."},{"w":"schadenfreude","def":"delight in another person's misfortune","ex":"He felt a guilty schadenfreude when his rival tripped on the way to accept the award.","say":"SHA-dih-nfroyd","hook":"SCHADEN looks like 'shaken'—you feel a shameful joy when someone else gets shaken up."},{"w":"perspicacity","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"irrefutable","def":"impossible to deny or disprove","ex":"incontrovertible proof of the defendant's innocence","say":"ih-ruh-FYOO-tuh-buhl","hook":"IRREFUTable: no E before -able. The argument is so strong you cannot REFUTE it — ir+REFUT+able."},{"w":"magniloquent","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"dendrochronology","def":"the science of dating events and variations in environment in former periods by study of the rings of growth in trees and aged wood.","ex":"Through dendrochronology, researchers determined that the ancient timber beam had been cut from a tree felled in 1347.","say":"deh-ndroh-kruh-NAH-luh-jee","hook":"DENDRO (tree) + CHRONO (time) + LOGY (study): scientists study tree rings to time-travel through history."}]},{"title":"Personality: Generosity & Miserliness","category":"Advanced Vocabulary — Word Power","difficulty":"medium","concept":"From magnanimous givers to parsimonious hoarders, this cluster of words describes attitudes toward sharing, spending, and keeping. Built primarily on Latin roots of giving and withholding.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>MUNIFICENT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> myoo-NIF-ih-sent\n<b>Spell it.</b> M · U · N · I · F · I · C · E · N · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> myoo-NIF-ih-sent\n<b>Syllables.</b> m · u · n · i · f · i · c · e · n · t\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [myoo=MU] [NIF=NIF] [ih=I] [sent=CENT]\n<b>Exception.</b> Latin munificus = gift-making; munus = gift + facere = make; -ent not -ant; stress: myoo-NIF-ih-sent\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin munificus = generous, from munus=gift + facere=make","cards":[{"title":"Generous Words","body":"Munificent (munus = gift + facere = make) = extremely generous. Magnanimous (magna = great + animus = soul) = great-souled generosity. Beneficent (bene + facere) = actively doing good. Bountiful = providing generously. Openhanded = giving freely. Philanthropic = motivated by love of humanity."},{"title":"Miserly Words","body":"Parsimonious (parsimonia = sparingness) = excessively frugal. Penurious (penuria = want) = extremely poor OR excessively mean with money. Niggardly (Old Norse hngurr = miser) = miserly. Avaricious (avarus = greedy) = extremely greedy for wealth. Rapacious (rapax = seizing) = greedily seizing more than needed."},{"title":"The munificent-parsimony Scale","body":"From most to least generous: munificent → magnanimous → beneficent → generous → thrifty → frugal → parsimonious → miserly → avaricious → rapacious. Knowing these distinctions wins vocabulary rounds."},{"title":"Spending Attitudes","body":"Prodigal (prodigere = drive forward wastefully) = recklessly extravagant. Profligate (profligare = strike down) = wildly wasteful. Spendthrift = spending recklessly. Lavish = spending in large amounts. These describe too much generosity, not virtue."},{"title":"Spelling These Words","body":"Munificent = M-U-N-I-F-I-C-E-N-T. Parsimonious = P-A-R-S-I-M-O-N-I-O-U-S. Avaricious = A-V-A-R-I-C-I-O-U-S (-cious suffix). Rapacious = R-A-P-A-C-I-O-U-S. Penurious = P-E-N-U-R-I-O-U-S. All end in -ious — the pattern from -acious/-icious family."}],"words":[{"w":"munificent","def":"means one who is very generous","ex":"distributed gifts with a lavish hand","say":"myoo-NIF-ih-sent","hook":"MUNIFICENT: a MUNIficent giver makes gifts (fic=make)—no extra I, just muNIFICENT."},{"w":"magnanimous","def":"is generous in forgiving insult or injury","ex":"a greathearted general","say":"m-a-g-n-A-n-uh-m-uh-s","hook":"A magnANIMous person has a GREAT ANIMAL spirit — big-souled and forgiving."},{"w":"beneficent","def":"doing or producing good","ex":"The beneficent billionaire donated millions of dollars to build new schools and hospitals in impoverished communities around the world.","say":"beh-nuh-FIH-shuhnt","hook":"BENE (good) + FICENT — bene-FICENT does good things, like magnificent but good"},{"w":"philanthropic","def":"generous in assistance to the poor","ex":"a benevolent contributor","say":"fih-luh-NTHRAH-pihk","hook":"PHILanthropic people PHIL the world with love for ANTHROP-os (humankind)."},{"w":"parsimonious","def":"excessively unwilling to spend","ex":"parsimonious thrift relieved by few generous impulses","say":"pah-rsuh-MOH-nee-uhs","hook":"A parsimonious person spares every MONI (money) — par-si-MON-i-ous."},{"w":"penurious","def":"not having enough money to pay for necessities","ex":"The penurious family could barely afford bread, so the neighbors quietly left groceries on their porch each week.","say":"peh-NYOO-ree-uhs","hook":"PENURIOUS people have PENURY — a penny-poor existence."},{"w":"avaricious","def":"immoderately desirous of acquiring e.g. wealth","ex":"they are avaricious and will do anything for money","say":"av-uh-RISH-us","hook":"AVAR + ICIOUS — think 'a very icious (vicious) desire for money' — greed can be vicious."},{"w":"rapacious","def":"living by preying on other animals especially by catching living prey","ex":"The rapacious hawk swooped down from the sky with terrifying speed, seizing the small rabbit in its talons before the creature could escape into the underbrush.","say":"ruh-PA-shihs","hook":"A RAPACIOUS creature RAPS and SEIZES — remember RAP+ACIOUS, it grabs everything including extra syllables."},{"w":"prodigal","def":"a recklessly extravagant consumer","ex":"prodigal in their expenditures","say":"PRAH-dih-guhl","hook":"A PRODIGal spends a prodiGious amount — note the A before L: prodig-A-L; the prodigal son needed that A(id) to return home."},{"w":"profligate","def":"a dissolute man in fashionable society","ex":"prodigal in their expenditures","say":"PRAW-flih-gayt","hook":"A profliGATE person flung open the GATE to ruin — remember the hidden 'gate' at the end."},{"w":"niggardly","def":"petty or reluctant in giving or spending","ex":"The niggardly landlord refused to turn up the heat even in the coldest weeks of January, spending as little as possible on his tenants' comfort.","say":"NIH-ger-dlee","hook":"NIGGARDLY: the NIGGARD spells his name with two g's and guards the 'a' in the middle."},{"w":"bountiful","def":"given or giving freely","ex":"After months of rain and sunshine, the farmers enjoyed a bountiful harvest that filled every barn to the rafters.","say":"BOW-ntih-fuhl","hook":"BOUNTIFUL is FULL of BOUNTY—plenty of goodness"},{"w":"openhanded","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"miserly","def":"(used of persons or behavior) characterized by or indicative of lack of generosity","ex":"The miserly old landlord refused to fix the leaking roof or replace the broken heater, hoarding every coin so tightly that his tenants suffered through the bitter cold winter months.","say":"MEYE-zer-lee","hook":"A miserly person acts just like a MISER — tack -ly on miser and you've got miserly."},{"w":"frugal","def":"avoiding waste","ex":"By being consistently frugal throughout the year — clipping coupons, cooking at home, and skipping unnecessary purchases — Marcus saved enough money to fund an entire summer road trip.","say":"FROO-guhl","hook":"A FRUGAL person saves money — notice the word ends in 'gal,' and a thrifty gal never wastes a penny."}]},{"title":"Words About Movement & Direction","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Movement vocabulary draws from Latin roots cedere (go), venire (come), ferre (carry), and vertere (turn). Directional prefixes combine with these roots to create a precise vocabulary of motion.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>PERIPATETIC</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> peh-ruh-puh-TEH-tihk\n<b>Spell it.</b> P · E · R · I · P · A · T · E · T · I · C\n<b>Say it again.</b> peh-ruh-puh-TEH-tihk\n<b>Syllables.</b> peh · rah · pah · teh · tih · k\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [per=PER] [ih=I] [puh=PA] [TET=TET] [ik=IC]\n<b>Exception.</b> Greek peri- = around + patein = walk; Aristotle taught while walking around; stress: per-ih-puh-TET-ik\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Greek peripatein = to walk around, patein = to walk","cards":[{"title":"cedere (go) compounds","body":"Precede = go before. Recede = go back. Concede = go together with = yield. Accede = go toward = agree. Secede (se- = apart) = go apart = formally withdraw from. Supersede = sit above = replace. Note: supersede ends in -sede (from sedere = sit), not -cede — the only common word that does."},{"title":"venire (come) compounds","body":"Convene (con- + venire) = come together. Intervene = come between. Circumvent = come around = avoid or outwit. Prevent = come before = stop from happening. Adventure (ad- + ventura = thing about to come) = something coming toward you = an exciting event."},{"title":"Walking Words","body":"Peripatetic = walking around = traveling from place to place. Perambulate (per- + ambulare = walk) = walk through. Itinerant (itinerare = to travel) = traveling from place to place. Ambulatory = able to walk. Somnambulist (somnus = sleep + ambulare) = a sleepwalker."},{"title":"Directional Prefixes Review","body":"Every movement word has a directional prefix + a movement root: pre- (before) + cedere = precede. re- (back) + cedere = recede. con- (together) + venire = convene. inter- (between) + venire = intervene. Knowing the prefix + knowing the root = knowing the word."},{"title":"Spelling Movement Words","body":"Peripatetic = P-E-R-I-P-A-T-E-T-I-C. Perambulate = P-E-R-A-M-B-U-L-A-T-E. Somnambulist = S-O-M-N-A-M-B-U-L-I-S-T. Circumvent = C-I-R-C-U-M-V-E-N-T. Supersede = S-U-P-E-R-S-E-D-E (-sede not -cede). Movement words spell correctly when you know the root and count the prefix."}],"words":[{"w":"peripatetic","def":"a person who walks from place to place","ex":"The peripatetic journalist traveled from city to city interviewing ordinary people, never staying in one place longer than a week as she gathered stories for her upcoming book about everyday heroes.","say":"peh-ruh-puh-TEH-tihk","hook":"A PERIPATETIC person PATters their feet walking around — peri (around) + PAT (walk) + etic."},{"w":"perambulate","def":"make an official inspection on foot of (the bounds of a property)","ex":"Selectmen are required by law to perambulate the bounds every five years","say":"per-AM-byoo-layt","hook":"PER + AMBULATE — ambulance moves people; to perambulate is to walk all the way through an area."},{"w":"itinerant","def":"a laborer who moves from place to place as demanded by employment","ex":"The itinerant musician traveled from town to town throughout the summer, setting up his guitar case on busy street corners and playing folk songs for passersby in exchange for spare change.","say":"eye-TIH-ner-uhnt","hook":"An itinerANT is an ANT that wanders the road — remember the 'ant' at the end who keeps moving."},{"w":"somnambulist","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"precede","def":"is to go before","ex":"Stone tools precede bronze tools","say":"p-r-ih-s-EE-d","hook":"To preCEDE is to go before — remember: cede ends in E not EE."},{"w":"recede","def":"to move back or away to withdraw","ex":"After three days of heavy rainfall, the townspeople anxiously watched the floodwaters finally begin to recede, slowly pulling back from the streets and leaving a thick layer of mud behind.","say":"r-ih-s-EE-d","hook":"When waters RECEDE, they go back — re-(back) + CEDE (give way), ending neatly in E-D-E like 'concede.'"},{"w":"concede","def":"admit (to a wrongdoing)","ex":"She confessed that she had taken the money","say":"kuh-NSEED","hook":"To conCEDE is to let others proCEED — both share -CEDE meaning to go or yield."},{"w":"accede","def":"yield to another's wish or opinion","ex":"The government bowed to the military pressure","say":"a-KSEED","hook":"To accEDE, you yield like a ceding nation — double 'c', then end with 'ede' like 'cede'."},{"w":"secede","def":"is to withdraw formally from an alliance","ex":"After the break up of the Soviet Union, many republics broke away","say":"s-ih-s-EE-d","hook":"To seCEDE is to CEDE yourself apart—the South ceded to secede."},{"w":"supersede","def":"is to replace in power or acceptance","ex":"Smith replaced Miller as CEO after Miller left","say":"s-oo-p-ur-s-EE-d","hook":"To supersEDE is to sit above — remember the SEDE comes from 'sedere' (to sit), not 'cede.'"},{"w":"convene","def":"meet formally","ex":"The council convened last week","say":"kuh-NVEEN","hook":"To conVENE is to COME together — VENue is where people convene."},{"w":"intervene","def":"get involved, so as to alter or hinder an action, or through force or threat of force","ex":"Why did the U.S. not intervene earlier in WW II?","say":"ih-nter-VEEN","hook":"InterVENE: someone who interVENEs COMES BETWEEN — the VEIN of a rescuer runs between two fighters."},{"w":"circumvent","def":"surround so as to force to give up","ex":"The Turks besieged Vienna","say":"sur-kuh-MVEHNT","hook":"CircumVENT — you VENT air around an obstacle to bypass it — VENT is the way out."},{"w":"prevent","def":"keep from happening or arising; make impossible","ex":"My sense of tact forbids an honest answer","say":"prih-VEHNT","hook":"To preVENT is to COME before the event and stop it — pre + VENT (air comes out before the fire starts)."},{"w":"ambulatory","def":"a covered walkway (as in a cloister)","ex":"it has an ambulatory and seven chapels","say":"A-mbyuh-luh-taw-ree","hook":"An AMBULATORY is a walking corridor — remember AMBULate + -ORY (like a dormitory, a place for doing something)."}]},{"title":"Literary & Poetic Devices","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","concept":"Literary vocabulary describes the tools of writers and poets. These Greek and Latin terms appear in both vocabulary rounds and are the kind of advanced knowledge that separates competition levels.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>SYZYGY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> SIZ-ih-jee\n<b>Spell it.</b> S · Y · Z · Y · G · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> SIZ-ih-jee\n<b>Syllables.</b> syz · y · gy\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [SIZ=SYZ] [uh=Y] [jee=GY]\n<b>Exception.</b> Greek syzygos = yoked together; in astronomy = alignment of three bodies; -y- twice as vowel; SIZ-uh-jee\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Greek suzugia = yoked together, from syn-(together) + zugon(yoke)","cards":[{"title":"Sound Devices","body":"Alliteration (al- + litera = letter) = repeated initial consonant sounds. Assonance (assonare = to correspond in sound) = repeated vowel sounds. Onomatopoeia = words that sound like what they mean. Cacophony = harsh discordant sounds. Euphony = pleasant harmonious sounds. Sibilance = repeated s sounds creating a hissing effect."},{"title":"Imagery Devices","body":"Metaphor (meta- + pherein = carry) = a comparison without like or as. Simile (similis = like) = a comparison using like or as. Synecdoche (synekdoche = taking up together) = a part representing the whole (\"wheels\" for a car). Metonymy (metonymy = change of name) = a related thing replacing the thing itself (\"the crown\" for monarchy)."},{"title":"Structure Devices","body":"Chiasmus = ABBA inversion structure. Anaphora = repetition at the start. Epistrophe = repetition at the end. Anadiplosis (ana- = back + diplous = double) = ending one clause with a word, starting the next with it. Symploce (symploce = interweaving) = combining anaphora and epistrophe."},{"title":"Rare Literary Terms","body":"Syzygy (syzygos = yoked) = in poetry, two feet joined together; in astronomy, three bodies aligned. S-Y-Z-Y-G-Y = six letters, three of which are y (all vowels). Tmesis (tmesis = cutting) = inserting a word inside another: \"what-SO-ever.\" Hapax legomenon = a word appearing only once in a body of literature."},{"title":"Spelling Literary Terms","body":"Syzygy = S-Y-Z-Y-G-Y (three y's as vowels — a Greek vowel festival!). Synecdoche = S-Y-N-E-C-D-O-C-H-E (-ch- = /k/ Greek). Metonymy = M-E-T-O-N-Y-M-Y (-nym- from onoma = name). Anadiplosis = A-N-A-D-I-P-L-O-S-I-S. Chiasmus = C-H-I-A-S-M-U-S. Literary terms all follow Greek spelling rules."}],"words":[{"w":"syzygy","def":"the straight line configuration of 3 celestial bodies (as the sun and earth and moon) in a gravitational system","ex":"During a total solar eclipse, the sun, moon, and earth achieve a perfect syzygy that briefly turns day into night.","say":"SIZ-ih-jee","hook":"SYZYGY: no vowels except Y—three bodies lined up like three Y's"},{"w":"synecdoche","def":"substituting a more inclusive term for a less inclusive one or vice versa","ex":"When the coach shouted 'All hands on deck!' she used a synecdoche, referring to the whole team by just one body part.","say":"sih-NEK-duh-kee","hook":"synECDoche — ECD sounds like 'a piece' standing for the whole"},{"w":"metonymy","def":"substituting the name of an attribute or feature for the name of the thing itself (as in `they counted heads')","ex":"The poet used metonymy when he wrote 'the crown decided' to mean the king decided.","say":"meh-TON-uh-mee","hook":"metoNYMY — the NY in the middle is like New York called 'the Crown' — a perfect metonymy hiding in the spelling."},{"w":"chiasmus","def":"inversion in the second of two parallel phrases","ex":"The famous line 'ask not what your country can do for you' is a classic example of chiasmus.","say":"ky-AZ-mus","hook":"'Ask not what chiasmus IS, but what IS chiasmus' — the word itself inverts, starting with 'chi' like an X."},{"w":"anaphora","def":"using a pronoun or similar word instead of repeating a word used earlier","ex":"The poet used anaphora brilliantly, beginning each stanza with the same powerful phrase to build emotion.","say":"uh-NA-fer-uh","hook":"ANAPHORA carries a word back again — ana(again)+phora(carry) — like a rhetorical boomerang."},{"w":"epistrophe","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"anadiplosis","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"alliteration","def":"use of the same consonant at the beginning of each stressed syllable in a line of verse","ex":"around the rock the ragged rascal ran","say":"uh-LIH-ter-ay-shuhn","hook":"ALLITERATION: notice the double L and -LITER- inside — letters loving letters together!"},{"w":"assonance","def":"the repetition of similar vowels in the stressed syllables of successive words","ex":"The poet used assonance brilliantly, repeating the long 'o' sound in 'slow golden glow.'","say":"AS-oh-nance","hook":"ASSONANCE is about SOUND — find SON (sound) in the middle: as-SON-ance ends in -ANCE, not -ENCE."},{"w":"onomatopoeia","def":"using words that imitate the sound they denote","ex":"The poet used onomatopoeia brilliantly, filling the stanza with words like buzz, crash, and sizzle to bring the kitchen scene alive.","say":"on-oh-mat-oh-PEE-uh","hook":"ON-O-MAT-O-POE-IA — sounds like what it means, just like the device itself"},{"w":"sibilance","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"metaphor","def":"is a figure of speech in which a term is applied to something to which it isn't literally applicable","ex":"When the poet wrote that life is a rollercoaster, she was using a metaphor to describe its unpredictable ups and downs.","say":"m-EH-t-uh-f-aw-r","hook":"A metaPHOR carries meaning across — it PHORwarded an idea to a new place."},{"w":"simile","def":"is a figure of speech in which two unlike things are compared","ex":"The poet used a vivid simile, writing that her smile was like the first ray of morning sunlight.","say":"SIM-ih-lee","hook":"A SIMILE ends in E — like a SMILE on the page when you compare two things cleverly."},{"w":"tmesis","def":"A rhetorical figure in which a word or phrase is split by the insertion of another word, often for emphasis or humorous effect, as in 'abso-blooming-lutely.'","ex":"When Marcus said 'un-flipping-believable,' his English teacher recognized it as a perfect example of tmesis used for comic effect.","say":"TMEE-sis","hook":"Tmesis CUTs a word in two—just as the 't' and 'm' are unusually cut together."},{"w":"hapax","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""}]},{"title":"Color, Light & Perception Words","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Color and light vocabulary comes from Latin lux/lucis (light), Greek khroma (color), and Old English for basic color terms. These words appear in science, art, and literature.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>IRIDESCENT</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> ih-r-uh-d-EH-s-uh-n-t\n<b>Spell it.</b> I · R · I · D · E · S · C · E · N · T\n<b>Say it again.</b> ih-r-uh-d-EH-s-uh-n-t\n<b>Syllables.</b> i · r · i · d · e · s · c · e · n · t\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [ir=IR] [ih=I] [DES=DES] [ent=CENT]\n<b>Exception.</b> Latin: iris = rainbow + -escent = becoming; -sc- before e = /s/; stress: ir-ih-DES-ent\n<b>Origin.</b> English\n<b>Root.</b> Greek iris = rainbow + Latin -escent(becoming)","cards":[{"title":"Light Words","body":"Iridescent (iris = rainbow + -escent) = shimmering with rainbow colors. Luminescent (lumen = light + -escent) = emitting light not from heat. Incandescent (in- + candere = glow white) = glowing from high heat. Phosphorescent = glowing in the dark after absorbing light. Translucent = allowing light through diffusely. Opalescent = showing shifting rainbow colors (like an opal)."},{"title":"Color Words","body":"Chromatic (khroma = color) = relating to color. Monochromatic = one color only. Polychromatic = many colors. Achromatic (a- + khroma) = without color = black, white, and grey only. Chiaroscuro = light and dark in art. Tenebrism (tenebra = darkness) = use of deep shadow in painting."},{"title":"Perception & Vision Words","body":"Diaphanous (dia- = through + phainein = show) = so thin as to allow light through = gossamer. Pellucid (per- + lucidus) = translucently clear. Opaque = no light passes through. Scintillating (scintilla = spark) = sparkling brilliantly. Resplendent (re- + splendere = shine) = shining brilliantly."},{"title":"Aurora Words","body":"Aurora (Latin goddess of dawn) = the northern/southern lights. Aurora borealis (borealis = northern) = northern lights. Aurora australis (australis = southern) = southern lights. Crepuscular (crepusculum = twilight) = relating to twilight. Diurnal vs nocturnal = day vs night. Vespertine (vesper = evening star) = relating to the evening."},{"title":"Spelling Light Words","body":"Iridescent = I-R-I-D-E-S-C-E-N-T (-sc- before e = /s/). Luminescent = L-U-M-I-N-E-S-C-E-N-T. Incandescent = I-N-C-A-N-D-E-S-C-E-N-T. Phosphorescent = P-H-O-S-P-H-O-R-E-S-C-E-N-T (two -ph- Greek signals!). Diaphanous = D-I-A-P-H-A-N-O-U-S. Pellucid = P-E-L-L-U-C-I-D (double-l)."}],"words":[{"w":"iridescent","def":"is displaying a play of bright colors like a rainbow","ex":"The hummingbird hovered just inches from the flower, its iridescent throat feathers shifting from deep emerald to brilliant violet as it tilted its tiny head, catching the afternoon sunlight at a slightly different angle.","say":"ih-r-uh-d-EH-s-uh-n-t","hook":"Iridescent — one R, like a single rainbow arc over the word."},{"w":"luminescent","def":"emitting light not caused by heat","ex":"The luminescent stickers on her ceiling glowed softly after the lights went out.","say":"loo-muh-NEH-suhnt","hook":"LUMINESCENT ends in '-ent' like a glowing agent — only an '-ent' student spells it right."},{"w":"incandescent","def":"strikingly bright radiant or clear","ex":"an incandescent bulb","say":"ih-n-k-uh-n-d-EH-s-uh-n-t","hook":"An incanDESCENT bulb glows as it DESCENDS into heat — spell the SCENT of hot wax: -s-c-e-n-t."},{"w":"phosphorescent","def":"emitting light without appreciable heat as by slow oxidation of phosphorous","ex":"The phosphorescent jellyfish drifted silently through the dark ocean water, glowing an eerie blue-green that lit up the waves around them.","say":"fos-fuh-RES-unt","hook":"PHOSPHORUS + ESCENT: like PHOSPHORUS glowing in the dark"},{"w":"translucent","def":"is letting pass through but not clearly","ex":"The translucent curtains let soft morning light filter gently into the room, casting pale golden shadows across the floor without revealing the private details of the space inside.","say":"t-r-a-n-s-l-OO-s-uh-n-t","hook":"transLUCent lets LUCY the light shine through — LUC holds the light, no extra S."},{"w":"opalescent","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"diaphanous","def":"means very sheer and light","ex":"a hat with a diaphanous veil","say":"d-ay-A-f-uh-n-ih-s","hook":"DIAphanous fabric is so sheer you could see a DIAMOND through it."},{"w":"pellucid","def":"transmitting light; able to be seen through with clarity","ex":"The pellucid water of the mountain spring revealed every pebble glinting on the streambed below.","say":"peh-LOO-sid","hook":"PELLUCID has LUCID inside it — double 'l' then LUCID, because clear light shines through LUCIDLY."},{"w":"scintillating","def":"Brilliantly clever, lively, and stimulating; sparkling with wit, energy, or dazzling light.","ex":"the substance scintillated sparks and flashes","say":"SIN-tih-lay-ting","hook":"SCINTILLATING has TILLA inside — imagine a caterpillar named TILLA who sparkles and glitters as she walks."},{"w":"resplendent","def":"having great beauty and splendor","ex":"a glorious spring morning","say":"ree-SPLEH-nduhnt","hook":"resPLENDent — PLEND sounds like SPLENDID; it's so shiny it nearly spells splendid inside."},{"w":"chromatic","def":"able to refract light without spectral color separation","ex":"The music teacher introduced the chromatic scale to her students, explaining that it includes every half step between notes and covers the full range of pitches.","say":"kroh-MAT-ik","hook":"CHROMATIC scales have all the colors of sound—CHROMA + TIC, the clock TICs through every hue."},{"w":"polychromatic","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"achromatic","def":"having no hue","ex":"The photographer converted the colorful image into an achromatic print, leaving only shades of gray from pure white to deep black.","say":"ay-kroh-MAT-ik","hook":"Achromatic = a (without) + chromatic (color) — like a black-and-white TV without any chroma."},{"w":"tenebrism","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"crepuscular","def":"like twilight; dim","ex":"Deer are crepuscular animals, so hikers are most likely to spot them just after sunrise or right before sunset.","say":"krih-PUS-kyoo-ler","hook":"CREPUSCular creatures CREEP out at dusk"},{"w":"vespertine","def":"of, relating to, or occurring in the evening; used in biology to describe animals or plants that are most active or open during the evening hours","ex":"The vespertine chorus of crickets and frogs began each evening just as the sun dipped below the horizon.","say":"VES-per-tyn","hook":"VESPER-tine: vespers are evening prayers, so vespertine means 'of the evening' — the -tine ending is fine, like 'fine' evenings."}]},{"title":"Sound, Music & Language Theory","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","concept":"Advanced sound and language vocabulary from Greek linguistics and music theory. These terms appear in championship rounds and are built from well-known Greek roots in new combinations.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>MELLIFLUOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> meh-LIF-loo-us\n<b>Spell it.</b> M · E · L · L · I · F · L · U · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> meh-LIF-loo-us\n<b>Syllables.</b> m · e · l · l · i · f · l · u · o · u · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [meh=MEL] [LIF=LIF] [loo=LU] [us=OUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> Latin mel = honey + fluere = flow = flowing with honey = sweetly smooth; stress: meh-LIF-loo-us\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin mel = honey + fluere = to flow","cards":[{"title":"Sweet Sound Words","body":"Mellifluous (mel = honey + fluere = flow) = sweetly smooth sounding. Dulcet (dulcis = sweet) = sweet and soothing. Sonorous (sonorus = resonant) = deep and rich in sound. Resonant = reinforced or prolonged by vibration. Euphonious = pleasant in sound. Melismatic (melos = song) = one syllable sung across many notes."},{"title":"Harsh Sound Words","body":"Cacophonous = harsh and discordant. Strident (stridere = to creak) = loud and harsh. Raucous (raucus = hoarse) = harsh and loud. Discordant = without harmony. Dissonant = clashing in sound. Grating = irritatingly harsh. Stentorian (from Stentor, a Greek herald with a huge voice) = very loud."},{"title":"Language Theory Words","body":"Polysemy (poly- + sema = meaning) = a word having multiple meanings. Homophony = same sound. Synonymy = same meaning. Antonymy = opposite meaning. Pragmatics (pragma = action) = how context affects meaning. Semantics (sema = sign) = the study of meaning. Morphology = the study of word forms."},{"title":"Poetry Sound Terms","body":"Sibilance = repeated /s/ sounds. Assonance = repeated vowel sounds. Consonance = repeated consonant sounds. Enjambment (enjamber = to stride over) = a line of poetry that continues without pause into the next. Caesura (caedere = to cut) = a pause within a line of verse."},{"title":"Spelling Sound Words","body":"Mellifluous = M-E-L-L-I-F-L-U-O-U-S (double-l). Dulcet = D-U-L-C-E-T. Sonorous = S-O-N-O-R-O-U-S. Stentorian = S-T-E-N-T-O-R-I-A-N. Polysemy = P-O-L-Y-S-E-M-Y (y as Greek vowel). Enjambment = E-N-J-A-M-B-M-E-N-T (mb cluster). Caesura = C-A-E-S-U-R-A (ae diphthong)."}],"words":[{"w":"mellifluous","def":"is sweetly or smoothly flowing","ex":"the dulcet tones of the cello","say":"meh-LIF-loo-us","hook":"MELLI-fluous sounds like MELLOW and flows like honey"},{"w":"dulcet","def":"extremely pleasant in a gentle way","ex":"the most dulcet swimming on the most beautiful and remote beaches","say":"DUH-lsuht","hook":"DULCET tones are sweetly DULC-et — think of the dulcimer, a sweet instrument sharing the same root."},{"w":"sonorous","def":"full and loud and deep","ex":"The orchestra's cellos filled the grand concert hall with a sonorous, resonant hum that vibrated in the listeners' chests and seemed to make the very walls tremble with its depth and beauty.","say":"SAH-ner-uhs","hook":"A SONOROUS voice is full of SONO-rous SOUND — the O's roll like deep bass notes."},{"w":"resonant","def":"characterized by resonance","ex":"The speaker's resonant voice filled every corner of the enormous auditorium without a microphone, captivating the entire audience from the very first word.","say":"REH-zuh-nuhnt","hook":"A reSON-ANT voice has a SON ringing through it — full and echoing."},{"w":"euphonious","def":"having a pleasant sound","ex":"The euphonious melody drifting from the open window made every passerby slow their pace and smile.","say":"yoo-FOH-nee-us","hook":"EUPHONious — the EUPHON-y makes it sound good"},{"w":"cacophonous","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"strident","def":"conspicuously and offensively loud; given to vehement outcry","ex":"The debate moderator asked the strident protestors outside to lower their voices, but their vehement chanting only grew louder as the vote approached.","say":"STREYE-duhnt","hook":"STRIDENT ends in -ENT not -ANT — a strident voice is insistENT and urgENT."},{"w":"raucous","def":"is harsh or strident","ex":"The raucous celebration that erupted in the gymnasium after the championship win was so loud that teachers two hallways away could clearly hear the cheering, stomping, and joyful screaming through the thick walls.","say":"r-AW-k-uh-s","hook":"RAW + COUS — a raucous noise sounds raw and rough."},{"w":"stentorian","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"polysemy","def":"the ambiguity of an individual word or phrase that can be used (in different contexts) to express two or more different meanings","ex":"The word 'bank' is a perfect example of polysemy because it can mean a financial institution or the edge of a river.","say":"puh-LIS-uh-mee","hook":"Polysemy: poly means many, semy means meanings"},{"w":"semantics","def":"the study of language meaning","ex":"a petty argument about semantics","say":"sih-MA-ntihks","hook":"SEMANTICS — find the MANTIC inside, like a MANTRA of meaning — se-MANT-ics."},{"w":"morphology","def":"the branch of biology that deals with the structure of animals and plants","ex":"In science class, we studied the morphology of insects, comparing the body structures of beetles and butterflies.","say":"maw-RFAH-luh-jee","hook":"MORPHOLOGY: the study of form — keep the PH because Greek PHilosophers loved studying PHorms."},{"w":"sibilance","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"assonance","def":"the repetition of similar vowels in the stressed syllables of successive words","ex":"The poet used assonance brilliantly, repeating the long 'o' sound in 'slow golden glow.'","say":"AS-oh-nance","hook":"ASSONANCE is about SOUND — find SON (sound) in the middle: as-SON-ance ends in -ANCE, not -ENCE."},{"w":"enjambment","def":"the continuation of a syntactic unit from one line of verse into the next line without a pause","ex":"The poet used enjambment so skillfully that readers were swept from one line to the next without pausing.","say":"en-JAM-ment","hook":"ENJAMBMENT has 'jamb' — like a door jamb, the line doesn't stop but keeps going through the frame."},{"w":"caesura","def":"a pause or interruption (as in a conversation)","ex":"after an ominous caesura the preacher continued","say":"sih-ZHUR-uh","hook":"A caesura CUTS a poetic line in two — the CAES comes from the Latin word for cutting."}]},{"title":"Architecture & Urban Vocabulary","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Architecture vocabulary combines Latin, Greek, Italian, and French. Architectural terms describe both the physical elements of buildings and the philosophical concepts behind their design.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>FENESTRATION</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> fen-es-TRAY-shun\n<b>Spell it.</b> F · E · N · E · S · T · R · A · T · I · O · N\n<b>Say it again.</b> fen-es-TRAY-shun\n<b>Syllables.</b> fen · es · tra · tion\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [fen=FEN] [uh=ES] [TRAY=TRA] [shun=TION]\n<b>Exception.</b> Latin fenestra = window; -ation noun suffix; the arrangement of windows in a building; stress: fen-uh-STRAY-shun\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin: fenestratio (Latin)","cards":[{"title":"Structural Elements","body":"Buttress (Old French bouter = to push) = a structure supporting a wall. Colonnade (colonna = column) = a row of columns. Balustrade (balustre = a pillar) = a railing supported by small pillars. Crenellation (crena = notch) = the notched parapet of a castle. Pediment = the triangular gable above a classical portico."},{"title":"Space & Form Words","body":"Fenestration (fenestra = window) = the arrangement of windows. Atrium (atrium = the main hall) = a central open space. Clerestory (cler- = clear + -story) = high windows above the main roof. Nave (navis = ship) = the central body of a church. Apse (apsis = arch) = a semicircular recess at the end of a church."},{"title":"Classical Architecture","body":"Corinthian = the most ornate of the three Greek orders (with elaborate acanthus leaf capitals). Doric = the simplest order. Ionic = the middle order (with scroll capitals). Entablature = the horizontal structure above columns. Architrave (archi- = chief + trabs = beam) = the main beam resting on columns."},{"title":"Urban Planning Words","body":"Agora (Greek) = a public gathering place. Forum (Latin) = a public square. Boulevard (French from German Bollwerk = bulwark) = a wide tree-lined road. Cul-de-sac (French = bottom of the sack) = a dead-end road. Esplanade (explanare = to flatten) = a long, flat open promenade."},{"title":"Spelling Architecture Words","body":"Fenestration = F-E-N-E-S-T-R-A-T-I-O-N. Balustrade = B-A-L-U-S-T-R-A-D-E. Crenellation = C-R-E-N-E-L-L-A-T-I-O-N (double-l). Clerestory = C-L-E-R-E-S-T-O-R-Y. Entablature = E-N-T-A-B-L-A-T-U-R-E. Boulevard = B-O-U-L-E-V-A-R-D (-ou- French vowel)."}],"words":[{"w":"fenestration","def":"the arrangement of windows in a building","ex":"The judge admired the fenestration of the old courthouse, where arched windows flooded every courtroom with golden afternoon light.","say":"fen-es-TRAY-shun","hook":"FENESTRA + TION — Latin fenestra means window; the -TION ending makes it the arrangement of windows."},{"w":"buttress","def":"a support usually of stone or brick; supports the wall of a building","ex":"The medieval cathedral's stone buttress stretched outward from the tall wall like a sturdy arm, preventing the massive structure from crumbling under the enormous weight of its own roof.","say":"BUH-truhs","hook":"A BUTTRESS has a double T because it takes TWO supports to hold a wall up—and an -ess ending like 'fortress.'"},{"w":"colonnade","def":"a series of regularly spaced columns","ex":"The tourists walked through the shaded colonnade of the ancient temple, marveling at each towering marble column.","say":"k-ah-l-uh-n-AY-d","hook":"A colonnade has double 'n'—picture two columns standing side by side, just like the double 'n'."},{"w":"balustrade","def":"a railing at the side of a staircase or balcony to prevent people from falling","ex":"She gripped the marble balustrade tightly as she climbed the steep staircase inside the old palace.","say":"BAL-us-trayd","hook":"BALUSTRADE: 'BALance USing a TRADE-mark railing' — the railing helps you balance; end it with -RADE like lemonade."},{"w":"crenellation","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"pediment","def":"a triangular gable between a horizontal entablature and a sloping roof","ex":"The ancient Greek temple's pediment was carved with scenes of gods battling giants.","say":"PED-ih-ment","hook":"A pediMENT is the triMENTgular hat on top of a Greek temple — a pointy crown resting on stone feet."},{"w":"atrium","def":"is the central room of an ancient Roman house","ex":"Sunlight poured through the open roof of the Roman villa's atrium, filling the space with golden warmth.","say":"AY-t-r-ee-uh-m","hook":"ATRIUM: the grand AT-RIUM entrance — keep the 'i' before 'u' and 'm', like a skylit Roman room: a-t-r-i-u-m."},{"w":"clerestory","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"nave","def":"the central area of a church","ex":"Rows of wooden pews lined the nave of the old cathedral, filling the long central aisle with quiet reverence.","say":"NAYV","hook":"The NAVE of a church looks like an upside-down ship — navis means ship in Latin."},{"w":"apse","def":"a domed or vaulted recess or projection on a building especially the east end of a church; usually contains the altar","ex":"The ancient cathedral's apse was decorated with glittering golden mosaics that caught the morning light.","say":"APS","hook":"An APSE is a curved niche — four letters curving like the arch itself: A-P-S-E."},{"w":"corinthian","def":"a man devoted to the pursuit of pleasure","ex":"The temple featured tall Corinthian columns decorated with elaborate carvings of leaves at the top.","say":"ker-IH-nthee-uhn","hook":"A CORINTHIAN loves luxury — the word ends in -IAN not -EAN, like a polished column capital."},{"w":"doric","def":"the dialect of Ancient Greek spoken in Doris","ex":"The ruins featured thick columns built in the Doric style, sturdy and unadorned at the top.","say":"DAW-rihk","hook":"DORIC columns are plain and simple — so is the spelling: just D-O-R-I-C, no fuss."},{"w":"ionic","def":"the dialect of Ancient Greek spoken and written in Attica and Athens and Ionia","ex":"The ancient ruins featured tall ionic columns with intricately carved capitals, reflecting the elegant architectural style developed in the Greek region of Ionia thousands of years ago.","say":"eye-AH-nihk","hook":"IONIC columns come from IONIA — end it with IC like 'classic,' a classic Greek style."},{"w":"entablature","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"architrave","def":"the molding around a door or window","ex":"The carpenter carefully carved an ornate architrave to frame the grand entrance of the Victorian mansion.","say":"AH-rkuh-trayv","hook":"An ARCHITRAVe is the CHIEF BEAM (trave) over a door — arch over, then TRAVE like 'travel' over the top."},{"w":"agora","def":"100 agorot equal 1 shekel in Israel","ex":"In ancient Athens, citizens gathered in the agora to debate politics, trade goods, and share news.","say":"A-ger-uh","hook":"The AGORA was where people gathered — one G, open like an open marketplace."},{"w":"esplanade","def":"a long stretch of open level ground (paved or grassy) for walking beside the seashore","ex":"Families gathered along the esplanade on Sunday afternoons, strolling past ice cream vendors while watching the sailboats drift across the harbor.","say":"eh-spluh-NAHD","hook":"An ESPLAnade is a PLAIN (flat) PROMENADE — flat ground for pleasant walking."}]},{"title":"The Natural World — Flora & Fauna Vocabulary","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"medium","concept":"Scientific names for plants and animals come from Latin and Greek, following the Linnaean classification system. These vocabulary words appear in science bee rounds and general championship vocabulary.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>DECIDUOUS</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> dih-SIH-joo-uhs\n<b>Spell it.</b> D · E · C · I · D · U · O · U · S\n<b>Say it again.</b> dih-SIH-joo-uhs\n<b>Syllables.</b> dih · sih · jhuw · ah · s\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [dih=DE] [SIJ=CID] [yoo=U] [us=OUS]\n<b>Exception.</b> Latin deciduus = falling off; de- + cadere = fall; -uous suffix; -cid- not -cid-; stress: dih-SIJ-yoo-us\n<b>Origin.</b> Latin\n<b>Root.</b> Latin deciduus = falling off (de-+cadere=to fall)","cards":[{"title":"Tree & Plant Words","body":"Deciduous (de- + cadere = fall) = losing leaves annually. Coniferous (conus = cone + ferre = bear) = cone-bearing = evergreen. Arboreal (arbor = tree) = relating to trees or living in trees. Sylvan (silva = forest) = relating to forests. Herbaceous (herba = grass/herb) = a plant with no woody stem."},{"title":"Animal Behavior","body":"Diurnal = active during the day. Nocturnal = active at night. Crepuscular = active at twilight. Migratory (migrare = to move) = moving seasonally. Hibernation (hibernare = to winter) = dormancy in winter. Estivation (aestivare = to spend summer) = dormancy in summer."},{"title":"Classification Words","body":"Taxonomy (taxis = arrangement + nomos = law) = the science of classification. Phylogeny (phylon = tribe + genos) = evolutionary history. Morphology = study of form. Genus (genos) = a classification group. Species (specere = to look) = the fundamental classification unit. Subspecies = a division within a species."},{"title":"Ecological Words","body":"Symbiosis (sym- + bios) = mutually beneficial relationship. Mutualism = both organisms benefit. Commensalism (com- + mensa = table) = one benefits, other is unaffected. Parasitism = one benefits, other is harmed. Predation (praedari = to plunder) = one organism killing another for food."},{"title":"Spelling Nature Words","body":"Deciduous = D-E-C-I-D-U-O-U-S (-uous suffix). Coniferous = C-O-N-I-F-E-R-O-U-S. Arboreal = A-R-B-O-R-E-A-L. Herbaceous = H-E-R-B-A-C-E-O-U-S (-eous suffix). Taxonomy = T-A-X-O-N-O-M-Y. Phylogeny = P-H-Y-L-O-G-E-N-Y (ph = Greek; y = vowel twice)."}],"words":[{"w":"deciduous","def":"(of plants and shrubs) shedding foliage at the end of the growing season","ex":"Every October, the deciduous trees lining our street put on a spectacular show of red, orange, and gold before dropping their leaves entirely and standing bare throughout the long winter months.","say":"dih-SIH-joo-uhs","hook":"DecidUOUS trees lose leaves — remember the U-O-U-S ending like the leaves falling: U-O-U-S, down, down, down."},{"w":"coniferous","def":"of or relating to or part of trees or shrubs bearing cones and evergreen leaves","ex":"The hikers walked through a dense coniferous forest where towering pines blocked out most of the sunlight.","say":"kuh-NIH-fer-uhs","hook":"Coniferous trees are FAMOUS for their cones — remember 'coni-FER-ous' has FER in the middle, like itFERS (bears) cones."},{"w":"arboreal","def":"of or relating to or formed by trees","ex":"The red-eyed tree frog is a remarkably arboreal creature, spending nearly its entire life clinging to leaves and branches high above the rain forest floor.","say":"ah-RBAW-ree-uhl","hook":"A squirrel is arborEAL — it EAts Acorns up in trees; spot E-A-L at the end."},{"w":"sylvan","def":"a spirit that lives in or frequents the woods","ex":"a shady sylvan glade","say":"SIH-lvuhn","hook":"SYLVan — think of Sylvester the cat hiding in SYLVan woods, spelled with a Y like 'mystery.'"},{"w":"herbaceous","def":"characteristic of a nonwoody herb or plant part","ex":"The gardener pointed out that the herbaceous border along the fence needed to be cut back before the first frost.","say":"er-BAY-shuhs","hook":"HERBaceous plants are full of HERBS — soft stems, not woody"},{"w":"diurnal","def":"of or belonging to or active during the day","ex":"Unlike owls, which are nocturnal hunters, eagles are diurnal birds that soar and hunt only while the sun is shining.","say":"deye-UR-nuhl","hook":"diURNal — contains URN; think of the sun as an URN pouring light during the DAY."},{"w":"nocturnal","def":"is of or pertaining to the night","ex":"nocturnal animals are active at night","say":"n-ah-k-t-UR-n-uh-l","hook":"NOCTURNal — think NOCTURNE, the night music; both start with NOCTUR-"},{"w":"crepuscular","def":"like twilight; dim","ex":"Deer are crepuscular animals, so hikers are most likely to spot them just after sunrise or right before sunset.","say":"krih-PUS-kyoo-ler","hook":"CREPUSCular creatures CREEP out at dusk"},{"w":"hibernation","def":"the torpid or resting state in which some animals pass the winter","ex":"he emerged from his hibernation to make his first appearance in several years","say":"heye-ber-NAY-shuhn","hook":"HibernATION — the bear's winter NATION of sleep; always starts with HI not HY, like hibernate."},{"w":"estivation","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"taxonomy","def":"a classification of organisms into groups based on similarities of structure or origin etc","ex":"In biology class, we learned about the taxonomy that organizes all living things from kingdoms down to individual species.","say":"ta-KSAW-nuh-mee","hook":"TAXONOMy: think TAX + GNOME + Y — the gnome who organizes all living things by law."},{"w":"phylogeny","def":"(biology) the sequence of events involved in the evolutionary development of a species or taxonomic group of organisms","ex":"By studying phylogeny, scientists can trace how modern whales evolved from land-dwelling ancestors millions of years ago.","say":"feye-LAH-juh-nee","hook":"PHYLOGENY traces your species' family tree — PHYLo + GENY, like PHYLosophically examining GENeration."},{"w":"symbiosis","def":"the relation between two different species of organisms that are interdependent; each gains benefits from the other","ex":"The clownfish and the sea anemone demonstrate a classic example of symbiosis, each protecting and benefiting the other in the ocean.","say":"sih-mbeye-OH-suhs","hook":"SYMBIOsis — SYM + BIO: two species sharing one BIO(logy) class together, the perfect partnership."},{"w":"mutualism","def":"the relation between two different species of organisms that are interdependent; each gains benefits from the other","ex":"The relationship between clownfish and sea anemones is a classic example of mutualism, where both species benefit.","say":"MYOO-choo-uh-lih-zuhm","hook":"Mutualism ends in -ism because it's a system where both sides benefit — remember i-s-m not i-z-m."},{"w":"commensalism","def":"the relation between two different kinds of organisms when one receives benefits from the other without damaging it","ex":"The biologist explained that the relationship between barnacles and whales is an example of commensalism, since barnacles benefit while whales are unaffected.","say":"kuh-MEN-suh-liz-um","hook":"COMMENSAL (sharing a table) + ISM = commensalism; one guest eats well at the table, the host doesn't notice."},{"w":"parasitism","def":"The relationship between two different organisms in which one organism (the parasite) benefits by living on or in the other (the host) and typically causes harm to the host in the process.","ex":"The science teacher explained parasitism using the example of a flea living on a dog.","say":"PAIR-uh-sih-tiz-um","hook":"ParaSITISM — one creature SITS on another and takes what it needs."},{"w":"predation","def":"an act of plundering and pillaging and marauding","ex":"The wildlife documentary showed dramatic footage of predation as a hawk dove from the sky to snatch a field mouse.","say":"pruh-DAY-shuhn","hook":"PredATION is the ACTION of one animal hunting another — spot the word ACTION inside."}]},{"title":"Philosophical & Religious Vocabulary","category":"Subject-Area Vocabulary","difficulty":"hard","concept":"Philosophy and religion vocabulary is built almost entirely from Greek — theos (god), logos (reason), psyche (soul), kosmos (order). These are the deepest roots in the lexicon.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>ESCHATOLOGY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> —\n<b>Spell it.</b> E · S · C · H · A · T · O · L · O · G · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> —\n<b>Syllables.</b> e · s · c · h · a · t · o · l · o · g · y\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [es=ES] [kuh=CHA] [TOL=TOL] [uh=O] [jee=GY]\n<b>Exception.</b> Greek eskhatos = last + -logy = study; -ch- = /k/ Greek signal; study of last things/end times; stress: es-kuh-TOL-uh-jee\n<b>Origin.</b> —\n<b>Root.</b> —","cards":[{"title":"Theology Roots","body":"Eschatology (eskhatos = last) = study of the end times. Teleology (telos = end/purpose) = study of purposes or final causes. Ontology (ontos = being) = study of the nature of being. Epistemology (episteme = knowledge) = study of how we know. Cosmology (kosmos = order) = study of the universe's origin and structure."},{"title":"Religious Practice Words","body":"Hagiography (hagios = holy + graphos) = writing about saints. Iconoclasm (eikon = image + klan = break) = breaking religious images. Transubstantiation = the Catholic doctrine that bread and wine become body and blood. Blasphemy (blasphemia = evil speech) = disrespect toward God — B-L-A-S-P-H-E-M-Y (-ph- Greek!)."},{"title":"Philosophical -ism Words","body":"Solipsism = only the self exists. Nihilism = nothing has meaning. Utilitarianism = the greatest good for the greatest number. Consequentialism = morality judged by outcomes. Deontology (deon = duty + -logy) = morality judged by rules, not outcomes. Phenomenology = study of conscious experience."},{"title":"Ethics Words","body":"Altruism (alter = other) = selfless concern for others. Egoism = concern only for the self. Hedonism (hedone = pleasure) = pleasure as the highest good. Asceticism (asketes = monk) = severe self-discipline. Stoicism = endurance without complaint. Epicureanism (from Epicurus) = pleasure through simple living."},{"title":"Spelling Philosophical Words","body":"Eschatology = E-S-C-H-A-T-O-L-O-G-Y. Epistemology = E-P-I-S-T-E-M-O-L-O-G-Y. Transubstantiation = T-R-A-N-S-U-B-S-T-A-N-T-I-A-T-I-O-N (7 syllables!). Iconoclasm = I-C-O-N-O-C-L-A-S-M. Blasphemy = B-L-A-S-P-H-E-M-Y. Deontology = D-E-O-N-T-O-L-O-G-Y."}],"words":[{"w":"eschatology","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"teleology","def":"a philosophical doctrine that explains phenomena by the purposes or goals they serve rather than by prior causes","ex":"In philosophy class, we debated teleology — whether nature has built-in purposes, like how eyes seem perfectly designed for seeing.","say":"TEE-lee-aw-luh-jee","hook":"TELE-OLOGY — studying the TELOS (end goal) of everything"},{"w":"ontology","def":"(computer science) a rigorous and exhaustive organization of some knowledge domain that is usually hierarchical and contains all the relevant entities and their relations","ex":"The philosopher spent years studying ontology to understand the fundamental nature of existence.","say":"ah-NTAH-luh-jee","hook":"ONTOlogy: to study what IS, you must grab ONTO the essence of being."},{"w":"epistemology","def":"the philosophical theory of knowledge","ex":"In philosophy class, students debated an epistemology question: how do we actually know that anything is real?","say":"eh-pih-stuh-MAH-luh-jee","hook":"EPISTEMOLOGY: the STUDY (-logy) of what SEEMS (-steme) to be KNOWN — don't drop the O before -logy."},{"w":"cosmology","def":"the metaphysical study of the origin and nature of the universe","ex":"Her fascination with cosmology led her to spend countless nights studying the formation of galaxies.","say":"kaw-ZMAW-luh-jee","hook":"Cosmology is the LOGY of the COSMO — study the universe by studying the word itself."},{"w":"hagiography","def":"a biography that idealizes or idolizes the person (especially a person who is a saint)","ex":"The book was criticized as pure hagiography because it never mentioned any of the leader's flaws.","say":"ha-gee-AH-gruh-fee","hook":"Holy saints need HAGIO-GRAPHY — a HAGIO (holy) GRAPH (written) story that paints them perfectly."},{"w":"iconoclasm","def":"the orientation of an iconoclast","ex":"The young artist's iconoclasm shocked the critics, who had never seen anyone so boldly reject every traditional technique.","say":"eye-KAH-nuh-kla-zuhm","hook":"ICONOCLASM — icons get a CLASM (clash/spasm of breaking): I-C-O-N-O-C-L-A-S-M."},{"w":"transubstantiation","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"blasphemy","def":"blasphemous language (expressing disrespect for God or for something sacred)","ex":"desecration of the Holy Sabbath","say":"BLA-sfuh-mee","hook":"BLASPHEMY has 'phemy' not 'phamy' — think 'phemy' sounds like 'fame', and saying bad things ruins God's fame."},{"w":"solipsism","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"nihilism","def":"a revolutionary doctrine that advocates destruction of the social system for its own sake; the belief that nothing has meaning or value","ex":"The villain's nihilism made him truly frightening — he believed nothing mattered and acted accordingly.","say":"n-AY-uh-l-ih-z-uh-m","hook":"NIHILism — NIHIL means NOTHING in Latin; nihilism = the belief in nothing"},{"w":"utilitarianism","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"deontology","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""},{"w":"phenomenology","def":"a philosophical doctrine proposed by Edmund Husserl based on the study of human experience in which considerations of objective reality are not taken into account","ex":"Her philosophy paper explored phenomenology and how personal experience shapes the way we understand the world.","say":"fuh-NAH-muh-nah-lah-gee","hook":"PHENOMENOLOGY is the study (-LOGY) of phenomena — drop the A, it's PHENOMEN-O-LOGY."},{"w":"altruism","def":"the quality of unselfish concern for the welfare of others","ex":"Her altruism was evident when she donated her entire birthday money to help families affected by the flood.","say":"A-ltroo-ih-zuhm","hook":"ALTRUism puts ALTeR-ego first — think of the 'other' (alter) before yourself: A-L-T-R-U-I-S-M."},{"w":"hedonism","def":"the pursuit of pleasure as a matter of ethical principle","ex":"The philosopher argued that a life devoted entirely to hedonism would ultimately feel hollow and meaningless without deeper purpose.","say":"HEE-duh-nih-zuhm","hook":"HEDonism: HE Does Only Nice indulgences — seeking maximum pleasure."},{"w":"asceticism","def":"","ex":"","say":"","hook":""}]},{"title":"Championship Loanword Patterns — Rare Languages","category":"Championship Level","difficulty":"hard","concept":"Championship rounds include words from Hebrew, Malay, Swahili, Welsh, and other less-common source languages. These have distinctive patterns that cannot be decoded from Latin or Greek knowledge alone.","method":"<div class='trick'><b>SERENDIPITY</b></div>\n<b>Say it.</b> s-eh-r-uh-n-d-IH-p-ih-t-ee\n<b>Spell it.</b> S · E · R · E · N · D · I · P · I · T · Y\n<b>Say it again.</b> s-eh-r-uh-n-d-IH-p-ih-t-ee\n<b>Syllables.</b> s · e · r · e · n · d · i · p · i · t · y\n<b>Sounds → Letters.</b> [ser=SER] [en=EN] [DIP=DIP] [ih=I] [tee=TY]\n<b>Exception.</b> Coined by Horace Walpole from Serendip = old Arabic name for Sri Lanka; stress: ser-en-DIP-ih-tee\n<b>Origin.</b> French\n<b>Root.</b> Persian Serendip = old name for Sri Lanka","cards":[{"title":"Hebrew Loanwords","body":"Jubilee (yobhel = ram's horn = the year of the horn blast = a 50-year celebration). Amen = so be it. Cherub (kerubh) = a type of angel. Leviathan (liwyathan = sea monster). Sabbath (shabbat = rest). Messiah (mashiach = anointed one). Hebrew words often have doubled letters from the original consonantal script."},{"title":"Malay Loanwords","body":"Amok (amuk = furious attack) = \"running amok.\" Orangutan (orang = person + hutan = forest) = \"person of the forest\" — O-R-A-N-G-U-T-A-N. Bamboo (mambu). Rattan (rotan). Gong (gong). Malay loanwords came to English through trade in Southeast Asia — they follow CV syllable patterns similar to Japanese."},{"title":"Welsh Loanwords","body":"Corgi (cor = dwarf + gi = dog) = dwarf dog. Flannel (Welsh gwlanen = wool). Penguin (possibly Welsh pen gwyn = white head). Cwtch (a Welsh hiding place or cuddle). Welsh has unusual consonant patterns — ll = a lateral fricative, ch = /kh/. In English, these are simplified."},{"title":"Afrikaans/Dutch Loanwords","body":"Aardvark (aarde = earth + vark = pig) = earth pig. Apartheid (apart = separate + -heid = -hood = separateness). Wildebeest (wilde = wild + beest = beast). Springbok (spring = jump + bok = deer). These keep Dutch/Afrikaans spelling and can be decoded by recognizing their compound structure."},{"title":"Bee Strategy for Rare Languages","body":"When nothing from Latin, Greek, French, or German applies — ask for language of origin AND a definition AND a sentence. The combination of all three clues usually reveals the pattern. For truly unknown languages: try to spell what you hear phonetically. Many rare-language loanwords are more phonetic than Latin or Greek words."}],"words":[{"w":"serendipity","def":"means good fortune or luck","ex":"By pure serendipity, she found the missing puzzle piece tucked inside an old library book.","say":"s-eh-r-uh-n-d-IH-p-ih-t-ee","hook":"Serendip-ITY: a happy DIP into the lucky city of ITY — stumbling onto gold!"},{"w":"jubilee","def":"a special anniversary (or the celebration of it)","ex":"The whole town gathered in the square to celebrate the school's golden jubilee.","say":"JOO-buh-lee","hook":"A jubilEE has a double E at the end — two E's cheering side by side at the celebration."},{"w":"leviathan","def":"the largest or most massive thing of its kind","ex":"The cargo ship was a leviathan of the sea, so enormous it blocked the entire view of the harbor entrance.","say":"luh-VEYE-uh-thuhn","hook":"LEVIathan — think of a LEVEE that holds back a TITAN wave: massive and powerful."},{"w":"sabbath","def":"a day of rest and worship: Sunday for most Christians; Saturday for the Jews and a few Christians; Friday for Muslims","ex":"The family observed the Sabbath by resting, attending services, and sharing a big meal together.","say":"SA-buhth","hook":"SABBATH has double-B and ends in -ATH — think 'rest on a BATH day,' with two B's for the double rest."},{"w":"amok","def":"frenzied as if possessed by a demon","ex":"the soldier was completely amuck","say":"uh-MUHK","hook":"Run AMOK — short and fierce, just four letters A-M-O-K, like a quick frenzied dash."},{"w":"orangutan","def":"A large, long-armed great ape native to the rainforests of Borneo and Sumatra, known for its reddish-brown fur and highly intelligent, tree-dwelling lifestyle; from Malay meaning 'person of the forest.'","ex":"The orang-utan swung gracefully through the rainforest canopy using its incredibly long arms.","say":"aw-RA-nguh-ta-n","hook":"Orang-utan has a HYPHEN in the middle — think of the hyphen as a vine it swings on."},{"w":"bamboo","def":"the hard woody stems of bamboo plants; used in construction and crafts and fishing poles","ex":"The giant panda lazily chewed through a thick stalk of bamboo while tourists snapped photos from behind the glass.","say":"ba-MBOO","hook":"BAMBOO has a double 'o' — like the two hollow tubes of a bamboo stalk: bam-BOO!"},{"w":"corgi","def":"either of two Welsh breeds of long-bodied short-legged dogs with erect ears and a fox-like head","ex":"The queen's corgi trotted loyally beside her down the long palace corridor, its ears perked with alertness.","say":"KAW-rgee","hook":"CORGI ends in just -I, no E — a tiny dwarf dog keeps a tiny ending: C-O-R-G-I, five short letters for a short dog."},{"w":"flannel","def":"a soft light woolen fabric; used for clothing","ex":"Every winter, Marcus wrapped himself in his grandfather's old flannel shirt, which smelled faintly of pine and woodsmoke.","say":"FLA-nuhl","hook":"Double N in the middle keeps you WARM like the fabric itself"},{"w":"aardvark","def":"A large, nocturnal African mammal with a long snout and sticky tongue that feeds almost entirely on ants and termites.","ex":"Under the beam of the ranger's flashlight, the aardvark pressed its long snout deep into the termite mound and lapped up thousands of insects.","say":"AH-rdvahrk","hook":"Aard = earth, vark = pig: the 'earth pig' that digs for dinner."},{"w":"apartheid","def":"a rigid policy of segregation in South Africa","ex":"Nelson Mandela spent decades fighting against apartheid before becoming South Africa's first democratically elected president.","say":"uh-p-AH-r-t-ay-t","hook":"APART-HEID kept people APART — the 'heid' sounds like 'hate,' a reminder of the hatred behind separation."},{"w":"wildebeest","def":"large African antelope having a head with horns like an ox and a long tufted tail","ex":"The wildebeest herd stretched across the savanna for miles as the animals migrated in search of fresh grass.","say":"WIL-duh-beest","hook":"WILDE (wild) + BEEST (beast): a WILD BEAST of the African plains."},{"w":"springbok","def":"a South African gazelle noted for springing lightly into the air","ex":"The springbok leaped gracefully over the dry African scrubland, its white rump flashing in the sunlight.","say":"SPRING-bok","hook":"A SPRING-ing BUCK — it springs like a spring and is a type of buck (male deer/antelope)."},{"w":"rattan","def":"climbing palm of Sri Lanka and southern India remarkable for the great length of the stems which are used for malacca canes","ex":"The porch was furnished with a comfortable rattan chair that creaked pleasantly when you sat down.","say":"ra-TAN","hook":"RATTAN has two T's and two A's—the long, doubled cane deserves doubled letters."},{"w":"gong","def":"a percussion instrument consisting of a metal plate that is struck with a softheaded drumstick","ex":"The deep boom of the gong signaled the start of the martial arts ceremony.","say":"GAWNG","hook":"A GONG goes BONG — both rhyme and both have just four letters."},{"w":"messiah","def":"any expected deliverer","ex":"Many in the crowd believed the young leader was a messiah who would finally bring peace to their troubled land.","say":"muh-SEYE-uh","hook":"MESSiah has a double-S like MESS — the world was a MESS before the Messiah came."}]}]};
